<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  12/03/96 -- Hawaii Judge OK's Marriage for Three
Lesbian and Gay Couples</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>Hawaii Judge OK's Marriage for Three Lesbian and Gay Couples</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Tuesday, December 3, 1996</B></P>
<P>HONOLULU -- In a closely watched lesbian and gay civil rights case that has
spurred legislative action in more than 30 states and Congress, a Hawaii judge
today paved the way for three lesbian and gay couples to marry, ruling that the
state's denial of marriage licenses violates Hawaii's Constitution. </P>
<P>Circuit Judge Kevin S. C. Chang wrote in his <A HREF="/court/baehr.html">46
page ruling</A> that the state had &quot;failed to present sufficient credible
evidence . . . that the public interest in the well-being of children and
families, or the optimal development of children would be adversely affected by
same-sex marriages.&quot;</P>
<P>The American Civil Liberties Union said the ruling is a historic step toward
giving lesbians and gay men in committed relationships the equal benefits and
responsibilities currently enjoyed by other couples.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;This decision is the first major step toward recognizing that it's
fundamentally unfair to exclude lesbians and gay men from marriage,&quot; said
Matt Coles, director of the ACLU's Lesbian and Gay Rights Project.  &quot;Since
we insist that couples marry to protect their most important relationship -- or
risk losing their homes, inheritances, even contact with their partners during
medical emergencies -- it is simply wrong to deny lesbians and gay couples the
basic right to marry.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;This is a ruling that respects the rights of all people in Hawaii to
marry the person they love,&quot; Coles added.  &quot;As this court recognized,
the freedom to marry is a basic human right that belongs to each individual --
not the state.  The government should not be in the position of arranging our
marriages.  Marriage is a personal decision that belongs to the two consenting
adults in a relationship.&quot; </P>
<P>According to Coles, the case has sparked national interest because marriages
performed in one state are typically recognized by the other 49, or have been
since the U.S. Supreme Court struck down miscegenation laws in 1967.  During the
previous state legislative session, bills barring same-sex marriages were
introduced in some 35 states.  To date, 20 states rejected the anti-gay
marriages bills, while 16 states passed such measures.</P>
<P>Congress and the President also entered the fray during the 104th term,
approving the so-called &quot;Defense of Marriage Act&quot; designed to exclude
lesbian and gay couples under federal programs and allow states to deny
recognition of same-sex marriages performed in other states.  The ACLU, which
says the law is unconstitutional, has vowed to ultimately challenge it in court.
</P>
<P>But today's ruling, Coles said, is unlikely to have any immediate impact
outside Hawaii.  &quot;People shouldn't plan on hopping over to Honolulu for the
honeymoon just yet,&quot; he advised.  &quot;The state is almost sure to appeal
the case to the Hawaii Supreme Court, and this decision is likely to be stayed
while the appeal goes forward.&quot;</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;That means lesbians and gay men won't be able to marry unless and
until the state's highest court makes a final decision affirming this ruling,&quot;
Coles continued.  &quot;The question of whether other states will recognize
Hawaii gay marriages won't arise until then either.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Today's ruling came in response to a case brought in 1991 by two lesbian
couples and one gay male couple after they were denied their applications for
marriage licenses.  </P>
<P>Their case eventually led to a landmark decision by the Hawaii Supreme
Court, which ruled in May 1993 that the state's refusal to issue those licenses
appeared to violate the equal protection guarantee of the Hawaii Constitution. 
The court reasoned that since the plaintiffs would have been allowed to marry
people of the opposite sex, the state's bias against same-sex couples may amount
to unconstitutional discrimination based on sex.</P>
<P>The Hawaii Supreme Court then returned the case to the trial court to
determine whether the state could show a &quot;compelling&quot; reason for
denying the three couples their marriage licenses.   After presiding over eight
days of testimony in September, Chang today concluded that the interests offered
by the state failed to justify the discrimination.</P>
<P>&quot;The state of Hawaii failed to put forth any compelling reason to
persuade the judge not to grant marriage licenses to these three lesbian and gay
couples,&quot; said Vanessa Chong, executive director of the ACLU of Hawaii.  &quot;Absent
any convincing  argument, Judge Chang correctly concluded that lesbian and gay
couples should be given the same freedom to marry that other people in Hawaii
are granted.&quot; </P>
<P>Coles offered a historical outlook on today's ruling: &quot;At one time,
people of different races and people who had been previously married were denied
the right to marry in most of America.  In time, we recognized as a society that
those laws, which were defended as simply preserving 'traditional marriage,'
were unfair.  Laws that don't allow lesbians and gay men to marry are just as
unfair.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
