<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  09/06/96 -- Non-Bias Job Law for Gays Scheduled
for Free-Standing Senate Vote on Tuesday</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>Non-Bias Job Law for Gays Scheduled for Free-Standing Senate Vote on
Tuesday</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Friday, September 6, 1996</B></P>
<P>WASHINGTON -- In an unexpected turn of events, Senate leaders announced
Thursday evening that the Employment Non-Discrimination Law will come up for a
floor vote as a free-standing measure next Tuesday, Sept. 10.  The American
Civil Liberties Union, which has been lobbying support for the bill, called the
vote an important step towards ensuring fairness.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;We are on the verge of passing legislation that will finally ensure
fairness for all American workers, regardless of sexual orientation,&quot; said
Matt Coles, director of the ACLU's Lesbian and Gay Rights Project.  &quot;While
we have a lot of work ahead of us in the coming days, the momentum is clearly on
our side.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Majority Leader Trent Lott announced that the bill, known as ENDA, will come
to a  vote on the same day as the ill-named &quot;Defense of Marriage Act,&quot;
a measure that would deny Federal recognition of gay marriages, and allow states
to ignore such marriages performed in other states.  The ACLU and other gay
rights advocates have condemned the bill as unconstitutional, discriminatory,
and election-year gay-bashing.</P>
<P>ENDA, first introduced in 1994, would outlaw employment discrimination based
on sexual orientation, in much the same way that Title VII of the Civil Rights
Act of 1964 outlawed discrimination on the basis of race, religion and gender.</P>
<P>The ACLU said ENDA would offer basic civil rights protections for lesbian
and gay Americans, who are currently afforded such protections in only nine
states.  In the other 41 states, it is perfectly legal to fire someone solely
because of their sexual orientation.  The ACLU also answered critics of the
measure, who have sought to distort and exaggerate the bill's impact if it
became Federal law.</P>
<P>&quot;When Congress debated the first post-Civil War civil rights bill in
the 1860s, it was attacked as 'special rights',&quot; Coles said.  &quot;When
Congress took up the Civil Rights Act of 1964, opponents said it would destroy

American business and individual freedom of choice.&quot;  </P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;The truth is that both of those laws were about simple fairness, and
they have made this country a far better place,&quot; added Coles.  &quot;ENDA
is about fairness as well, and when it passes, it too will make this country a
better place.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A
HREF="http://www.aclu.org/cgi-bin/take_action.pl?GetDoc=112&dir=aclu&redirect=http//www.aclu.org/issues/gay/thanks.html">Fax
Your Senator to Support Job Bias Protections for Gay Americans</A></P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
