<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  09/01/96 -- ACLU Marks Labor Day With Workplace
Rights Video and Report</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>ACLU Marks Labor Day With Workplace Rights Video and Report</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>September 1, 1996</B></P>
<P>Redoubling its efforts to protect the rights of employees in the workplace,
the American Civil Liberties Union today launched its &quot;<A
HREF="/issues/worker/campaign.html">Campaign for Fairness in the Workplace</A>&quot;
with the release of a 12-minute video and a white paper report that documents

how employees are being increasingly spied upon and monitored at work.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;The daily abuse of civil liberties in the workplace is a national
disgrace,&quot; said Lewis Maltby, director of the ACLU's Workplace Rights
Project.  &quot;Despite a dramatic increase in workplace surveillance, most
Americans aren't even aware that they are being monitored, let alone that there
are virtually no laws in place to protect them.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The ACLU plans to distribute the video and report to hundreds of labor
unions, lawmakers, and workplace rights activists in order to drum up support
for legislative solutions to the problem.  The first challenge, says the ACLU,
is to make people aware that the problem even exists.</P>
<P>The educational video, &quot;Through the Keyhole: Privacy in the Workplace
-- An Endangered Right,&quot; documents several stories, including a machinist
fired for drinking a beer on his own time, a file clerk who was forced to strip
and take a urine drug test -- only to be fired on the basis of a &quot;false
positive&quot; for marijuana use, and a hotel worker who was secretly videotaped
while dressing and undressing in the men's locker room.</P>
<P>The video suggests strategies for effecting legislation, and includes a
resource booklet with guidelines for drafting model statutes, lobbying
lawmakers, and educating co-workers.</P>
<P>The accompanying report -- an update on the ACLU's &quot;A State of
Emergency in the American Workplace&quot; originally published in 1990 --
documents a significant increase in electronic surveillance, telephone and
computer monitoring, and urine drug testing.  It also warns of a new and
potentially devastating threat to employee privacy: genetic testing.</P>
<P>Among the key findings of the update:</P>
<UL>
<LI>The number of people subject to <B>electronic surveillance</B> at work has
increased from approximately 8 million six years ago to more than 30 million
today.</LI>
<LI>Employers eavesdrop on an estimated 400 million <B>telephone conversations</B>
every year, or more than 750 calls every minute.</LI>
<LI>The percentage of major companies which subject employees to <B>urine drug
tests</B> has climbed from 38 percent six years ago to more than 70 percent
today. </LI>
<LI>Despite strong economic incentives for companies to subject job applicants
to <B>genetic tests</B>, only six states have enacted laws proscribing such
practices.</LI></UL>
<P>The ACLU will be making the report available to the general public through
its World Wide Web site (http://www.aclu.org), where Internet users can also
view a 20-second excerpt of the video.  </P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;Our nation's workplaces have become a fertile ground for prying eyes
and ears,&quot; Maltby said.  &quot;It's time for people to stand up and demand
that their right to personal privacy be respected.  Employees do not discard
their civil liberties when they punch-in for work.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
