<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  06/13/96: ACLU Criticizes Supreme Court's
Continued Assault on Voting Rights Act</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>ACLU Criticizes Supreme Court's Continued Assault on Voting Rights Act</H2></CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Thursday, June 13, 1996</B></P>
<P>WASHINGTON -- The American Civil Liberties Union today criticized the
Supreme Court's two decisions this morning striking down majority-minority
districts, saying that the Court's continued assault on the Voting Rights Act
will have a crippling effect on civil rights. </P>
<P>The Court's 5-4 decisions in Shaw v. Hunt and Bush v. Vera strike down four
more majority- minority congressional districts, three in Texas and one in North
Carolina.  In total, eight majority- minority congressional districts have been
lost since 1993.</P>
<P>&quot;The inevitable consequence of the Court's action will be to produce a
Congress that is increasingly white at a time that the nation is becomingly
increasingly diverse,&quot; according to Laughlin McDonald, director of the
ACLU's Southern Regional Office in Atlanta.</P>
<P>&quot;The Court's continued attack on the Justice Department's enforcement
of the Voting Rights Act will further cripple one of the most effective pieces
of civil rights legislation that this country has ever enacted,&quot;  McDonald
said.</P>
<P>In last year's redistricting case from Georgia, the Court held that the
state faces a heavy burden of justification whenever race is the &quot;predominant&quot;
factor in redistricting.  Today's decisions invite even more reverse
discrimination claims by making it easier to trigger judicial strict scrutiny
and harder to satisfy it.</P>
<P>The decision from Texas, where incumbency also played an important role in
how the district lines were drawn, indicates that the Court will be quick to
find evidence of racial gerrymandering even in &quot;mixed motive&quot; cases. 
Today's decision from North Carolina indicates that &quot;bizarrely&quot; shaped
districts will rarely be upheld under a strict scrutiny test that was originally
developed to deal with invidious racial discrimination but that now is applied
to legislative efforts to remedy that discrimination.</P>
<P>&quot;In the name of racial neutrality, today's rulings perpetuate an
unfortunate double standard,&quot; said Steven R. Shapiro, the ACLU's national
legal director.  &quot;Minority districts that are not drawn with geographical
precision are likely to be struck down.  White districts that are just as oddly
shaped are tolerated as nothing more than politics as usual.  That result
promotes neither justice nor equality,&quot; he added.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
