<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN">
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>06/02/96: Visions of Liberty, #1</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><BLOCKQUOTE><IMG
SRC="/graphics/vision.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P><I>by Ira Glasser, ACLU Executive Director</I></P>
<P>NEW YORK: June 2, 1996 -- Today, we inaugurate a regular, weekly cyberspace
column focusing on civil liberties in America.  Why a column, why now, why here?
 	</P>
<P>The answer to &quot;why a column&quot; can be found in its title, &quot;Visions
of Liberty.&quot;  The title comes from a book of the same name that I wrote in
1991 to commemorate the 200th anniversary of the Bill of Rights.  In it, I tried
to tell the story of liberty: how and why the Bill of Rights was invented; how
the courts acquired the independence and power to interpret the Bill of Rights
and apply it in a way that keeps most of us free; and how the Bill of Rights was
expanded, both by subsequent constitutional amendments and Supreme Court
decisions, to include those who were at first left out.  	</P>
<P>But the story of liberty is not just about courts and lawsuits; it is also
and primarily a story of individual people, many stories actually, full of
conflict and drama and excitement, of individuals who claimed their rights,
often at great personal risk, and who were at first denied and sometimes
punished; who nonetheless fought on -- sometimes, it seemed, unreasonably -- but
whose persistence and stamina helped establish many of the rights that protect
us all today.    	</P>
<P>People like Benjamin Bache, the grandson of Benjamin Franklin, who risked
arrest and government-incited mob reprisals for exercising freedom of the press
during America's infancy; Dred Scott, a runaway slave whose case first tested --
unsuccessfully - the constitutionality of slavery; Myra Bradwell, who in 1873
dared to challenge a ban on women practicing law; Homer Plessy, a man with one
black great grandparent who challenged racial segregation on America's railroads
in 1896; John Scopes, tried as a criminal in 1925 for teaching the theory of
evolution in a Tennessee classroom; Fred Korematsu, jailed in his own country
during World War II because his ancestors were Japanese; Rosa Parks, who sat
down in 1955 in a white-only seat on a public bus; and Oliver Brown, who, with
his 7-year old daughter Linda, challenged racial segregation in public schools
in the early 1950s.  	</P>
<P>End of story?  Not hardly.  Today, and every day, we find similar stories: a
man in Colorado who challenges that state's attempt to cut off rights for gay
people; a couple in Mississippi who resist the majority's attempt to force
unwelcome religious beliefs on their small children in public school; a pregnant
teenager and her parents in Nebraska fighting against the state's intrusion into
their family's right to decide whether she should bear a child; and a variety of
people challenging a new federal law imposing censorship here on the Internet.  
 	</P>
<P>All of these cases involve efforts by individuals to assert their rights
against the majority.  For	liberty means that, even in a democracy, the majority
cannot be allowed to rule everything, that people have certain rights -- are
born with rights -- that no majority should be able to take away.  	</P>
<P>But because the majority is powerful -- especially in a democracy -- rights
are usually vulnerable and fragile, a tenuous road hacked through a jungle of
power, which, left unattended, always retakes the road.  This column, I hope,
will help illuminate the pathways to liberty through that ever-encroaching
jungle.  	</P>
<P>As to &quot;why here&quot;: whether you're reading this column on a World
Wide Web page, or in America Online, or from a sheet of recycled paper printed
with laser-jet ink, the answer lies in the myriad technological advances that
enable me to reach you through this new medium.  For if the Internet is like a
new printing press, then we have the opportunity to reach each other without
owning a newspaper or a television station.  	</P>
<P>Why now?  Because we are living through a period of rapid and fundamental
economic, technological and social change.  And we know from other, similar
historical periods, that such changes often create fear and anxiety.  When
people are afraid and anxious, they are especially vulnerable to scapegoating. 
They read in the papers or hear on the radio about the crime rate, unemployment,
and inflation and they say it's those immigrants, it's those gay people, it's
those women, it's those blacks, it's those flag-burners, it's those teenagers.</P>
<P>The problems that worry people require long-term solutions, but politicians
are reluctant to talk about long-term solutions because they don't operate in
the long-term.  They worry about next November and how to get elected.  So
they're always looking for short-term solutions, and sometimes not even that. 
They're looking for quick fixes that make them appear responsive to the anger
and the fear and if they have to scapegoat whole categories of people and sell
out everyone's civil liberties, well, that's what they'll do.  	</P>
<P>And that's &quot;why now.&quot;  This column will be devoted to connecting
the dots between the older stories of liberty and those taking place today, to
illustrating the visions of liberty that lead to rights we too often take for
granted, to linking our own rights with those who have exercised them a bit
earlier than the rest of us.  Their struggle, as always, is our struggle, even
though we don't always realize it.</P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A><H6><I>Copyright
1996, The American Civil Liberties Union<BR>Photo by Bob Adelman</I></H6></CENTER></BLOCKQUOTE></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
