</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN"><HTML><HEAD><TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  05/22/96: ACLU Says That Clinton Panders to Bigotry With Announcement That He Will Sign Ban on Same-Sex Marriage</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><BLOCKQUOTE>&nbsp;<IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif"><CENTER>         </CENTER><H2>ACLU Says That Clinton Panders to Bigotry With Announcement That He Will Sign Ban on Same-Sex Marriage</H2><P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Wednesday, May 22, 1996</B><P>WASHINGTON -- The American Civil Liberties Union today urgently requestedthat the  Clinton Administration rethink its support for legislation thatwould ban same-sex marriages.<P>  The ACLU's request came after White House Press Secretary Michael McCurrytold reporters that President Clinton would sign the legislation if it ispassed by Congress. Previously, the Administration had said that althoughthe President opposed same-sex marriage, he  had not yet decided what actionto take on the legislation introduced by Republicans in Congress.<P>  "It is particularly ironic that the Clinton Administration would makethis announcement only days after the U.S. Supreme Court made the promiseof the Constitution real for lesbian, gay and bisexual Americans," said MatthewColes, Director of the ACLU's National Lesbian and Gay Rights Project. "OnMonday, the Supreme Court ruled that laws that single out lesbians and gayAmericans for second-class status --  like the so-called Defense of MarriageAct --  violate the basic guarantees of our Constitution."<P>  Last week, the ACLU submitted a statement before a House subcommitteehearing on the legislation, calling the bill a "deplorable act of hostilityunworthy of the United States Congress."<P>  The Constitution Subcommittee of the House Judiciary Committee heldhearings last Wednesday to consider the bill, which would deny recognitionof future marriages between same-sex couples by redefining marriage in Federallaw as a "legal union between one man and one woman."  That would have theeffect of treating legally married gay couples as strangers under all Federallaws and programs, from Medicaid through the tax code.<P>  A second provision of the bill would attempt to carve a "gay exception"to the Constitution's Full Faith and Credit Clause by allowing states toignore same-sex marriages performed in any other state.  That clause guaranteesthat the rights of people in one state will be honored by the other states. Congress has invoked its power to say what effect other state laws haveon only four occasions -- and only when it sought to promote uniformity amongthe states.  <P>  "This legislation would, like the now discredited Colorado amendment,treat lesbians and gay men differently simply out of hostility or fear,"said Laura W. Murphy, Director of the ACLU's Washington National Office.</BLOCKQUOTE><P><CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMGSRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A></CENTER><P><CENTER></CENTER><H6><CENTER><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil LibertiesUnion</I></CENTER></H6></BODY></HTML>
