<CENTER>
         </CENTER><H2>ACLU Testifies at Congressional Black Caucus Braintrust on Youth Violence:<BR>
What Ever Happened to Prevention</H2><P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Monday, May 13, 1996</B><P>WASHINGTON -- The American Civil Liberties Union, leading criminologists,community activists and others will present testimony tomorrow (Tuesday,May 14th) at the Congressional Black Caucus Braintrust on Youth Violence,a day-long hearing that will examine the overlooked solution to juvenilecrime: prevention.<P>"We are at a critical juncture in this country on how we address juvenilecrime," said Laura W. Murphy, Director of the ACLU's Washington NationalOffice, who will present testimony on seizing the issue back from "lock em up" politicians.  "In this election year, the crime scapegoat is backand this time the focus is on our children."<P>The CBC Braintrust hearing -- sponsored by Rep. John Conyers (D-Mich.),Rep. Maxine Waters (D-Calif.), and Rep. Robert C. "Bobby" Scott (D-Va.) --will begin at 9:00 a.m. in Room 2237 in the Rayburn House Office Building.<P>What: ACLU and others testify at Congressional Black Caucus Braintruston Youth Violence to examine prevention strategies to address juvenile crime.<P>Who: More than 25 leading criminal justice advocates including:<UL><LI>Laura Murphy (Director of the ACLU's Washington National Office)<LI>LeAlan Jones (student at Martin Luther King High School in Chicago whoproduced an award-winning segment on juvenile crime for National Public Radio)<LI>James Fox (criminologist at Northeastern University)<LI>Mark Mauer (Sentencing Project)<LI>Marc Bell (Center on Juvenile and Criminal Justice)</UL><P>Where: Rayburn House Office Building -- Room 2237<P>When: Tuesday, May 15, 1996 from 9:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m. </BLOCKQUOTE><P><CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A></CENTER><P><CENTER>
