<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  05/09/96 -- ACLU Director Authors &quot;Do-It-Yourself&quot;
Guidebook for New Era in Gay Rights Struggle</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>ACLU Director Authors &quot;Do-It-Yourself&quot; Guidebook for New Era in
Gay Rights Struggle</H2></CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>May 9, 1996</B></P>
<P>Fed up with being treated as a second-class citizen?  Do you want your town
to outlaw sexual orientation discrimination?  Want your town to recognize
domestic partnerships? Matt Coles, Director of the ACLU's Lesbian and Gay Rights
Project, has the answers in a new book: Try This At Home! </P>
<P>Written in response to the hundreds of requests for assistance, Try This At
Home! is a practical, no- nonsense guide for winning civil rights and domestic
partnerships for lesbians, gay men, and bisexuals. <I>TRY
<A HREF="/issues/gay/trybook.html">THIS AT HOME!</A>: A Do-It-Yourself Guide to
Winning Lesbian and Gay Civil Rights (ISBN#1-56584-309- 6/Paperback
Original/$14.95/1996/The New Press/Distributed by W.W. Norton.)</I></P>
<P><I> </I> Coles draws on the experiences of more than 50 other activists to

fashion a unique step-by-step guide that covers everything from lobbying
legislatures and boards of directors, to dressing for media interviews, to
figuring out how laws and policies are made.</P>
<P>Try This At Home! is also filled with real-life examples of successful and
unsuccessful tactics.  It is designed to work at all levels of government, as
well as in colleges, corporations, banks, and social service organizations. 
Internet users will also be able to read <A HREF="/issues/gay/trybook.html">excerpts</A>
of the book and purchase copies on the ACLU's web site.</P>
<P>Coles has been a leader in the lesbian and gay civil rights movement for
more than 20 years.  He wrote and led the campaigns to pass many gay rights
laws, including the first domestic partnership ordinance in the nation
(Berkeley, Calif. in 1985), the first lesbian and gay civil rights law in
California (San Francisco in 1977), and California's statewide law barring
sexual orientation discrimination (passed in 1992).  The model legislation he
has written have been adopted by dozens of cities and states across the country.
</P>
<P>He is a main  architect of the challenge to Colorado's anti-gay Amendment 2,
which the U.S. Supreme Court struck down in late June, and he recently argued
two cases challenging the military's &quot;Don't Ask, Don't Tell&quot; policy in
the Federal appeals courts.  Coles is also a frequent spokesperson on gay and
AIDS issues, and has given numerous media interviews.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
