<body bgcolor=#ffffff><blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">

<CENTER><H2>Mississippi Mother's School Prayer Challenge Goes to Trial</H2></CENTER>
<p>

<STRONG>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>
March 4, 1996</STRONG>
<p>
Oxford, Mississippi -- Trial begins today in a major school prayer case
brought by a Mississippi mother seeking to stop unconstitutional and coercive
religious practices in her children's public school.  U.S. District Court
Judge Neal B. Biggers, Jr. will preside over the trial.  
<p>
The lawsuit, filed on December 20, 1994 by People For the American Way and
the American Civil Liberties Union of Mississippi, asks the federal court to
halt the unconstitutional practices of the Pontotoc County public schools,
which have included spoken prayers broadcast over the school intercom and in
classrooms and religious Bible studies classes for grades K through 12.
<p>
"If religious liberty means anything, it means that public schools can not
preach religion and indoctrinate students," said David Ingebretsen, executive
director of the American Civil Liberties Union of Mississippi.  "This case is
not about keeping religion away from students, but ensuring that no student
is forced to practice a particular religion against his or her will."
<p>
"This case is about religious freedom, plain and simple," said People For the
American Way President Tom Andrews.  "This nation was founded by people
seeking the right to practice their religion not according to the dictates of
the state but according to the dictates of their own conscience. Today we
will be in the courtroom with Lisa Herdahl and her family because we firmly
believe that the Constitution is on the side of religious liberty.  And we
will be outside the courtroom as well, making the case for religious freedom
to the citizens of this community and to citizens all across the country."
<p>
The plaintiff in the case, Lisa Herdahl, brought suit after school officials
rejected her request to discontinue the unconstitutional practices and her
five children in the Pontotoc County schools, ages 5 to 15 , became the
subject of ridicule and harassment for not attending Bible classes or
participating in classroom prayers.
<p>
Her 7-year-old son, Jason, has been taunted by other students ever since his
second-grade teacher put headphones over his ears to block out the prayers
recited over the school intercom.  Her son David, 11, was branded an
"atheist" and "devil worshipper" by fellow students after a teacher told the
class that David didn't participate in Bible class because he doesn't believe
in God.
<p>
On April 18, 1995, Judge Biggers issued a preliminary injunction ordering
school officials to halt vocal prayers and Bible readings over the school
intercom and vocal prayers in classrooms during the school day.  
<p>
On February 22, 1996, Judge Biggers rejected the school district's assertions
that Mrs. Herdahl had no standing to challenge the religious Bible classes
being taught in the county schools.  Mrs. Herdahl's attorneys documented
during the discovery process that the Bible class teachers, who are selected
and paid by a group of local Protestant churches, are chosen in part for
their personal "salvation experience" and have reported to the church
committee on the number of students "saved" during the classes.
<p>
Mrs. Herdahl and her family have been subjected to harassment and
vilification -- both locally and from national leaders such as U.S. Speaker
of the House Newt Gingrich -- since she asked school officials to put an end
to the unconstitutional practices.
<p>
"My kids and I have been harassed for standing up for our religious freedom,"
said Mrs. Herdahl, who is a Christian.  "I've never tried to stop anyone
else's children from praying or reading the Bible in school or anywhere else.
But I don't believe that any students should be forced to choose between
going along with some official prayer or having to stand out and be
ostracized. That's not what public schools should be about in America."
<p>
People For the American Way and the ACLU of Mississippi are both nonpartisan
organizations dedicated to protecting constitutional liberties and defending
the separation of church and state.

</p>




</blockquote>




<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
