<html><head><title>ACLU Press Release </title></head><body bgcolor=#ffffff><blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif"><center><h2>Mother's Challenge to Mississippi School Prayer 
Goes to Trial Before U.S. Judge on Monday, March 4th
</h2>
</center>
<b>
<p>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
Thursday, February 29, 1996</b>
<p>
OXFORD, Miss. -- A major school prayer challenge, brought by a Mississippi
mother on behalf of her five school children,  will go to trial on Monday,
March 4th before a federal judge in Oxford, Miss.  The mother and her
attorneys will hold a news briefing at 7:30 that morning to provide reporters
background information on the case. 
<p>
The plaintiff in the case, Lisa Herdahl, seeks to prevent the Pontotoc County
School District in northern Mississippi from authorizing school prayers over
the intercom and in classrooms, as well holding Bible study classes for
grades K through 8.
<p>
The federal lawsuit, brought by the American Civil Liberties Union of
Mississippi and People for the American Way, contends that the school board's
coercive religious practices clearly violate the separation of church and
state set forth under the First Amendment to the Constitution. 
<p>
<hr>
<p>
WHAT: News briefing to kick off four-day trial in losely-watched school
prayer case.
<p>
WHO: Lisa Herdahl, mother with five children who is plaintiff in the case;
David Ingebretsen, Executive Director of the ACLU of Mississippi; Robert
McDuff,  ACLU cooperating attorney who will be making opening statements; and
attorneys from People for the American Way.
<p>
WHERE: The Jefferson Room at the Holiday Inn of Oxford, Miss., located at 400
North Lamar. (U.S. District Courthouse located on Jackson Avenue in Oxford.) 
<p>
WHEN: Monday, March 4, 1996 at 8:00 a.m.  (Trial scheduled to begin at 9:30
a.m.)
</p>
</blockquote>
