<html><head><title>ACLU Press Release </title></head><body bgcolor=#ffffff><blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif"><center><h2>
ACLU Expresses Concerns on TV Rating Scheme;
Says "Voluntary" System is Government-Backed Censorship 
</h2>
</center>
<b>
<p>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
Thursday, February 29, 1996</b>
<p>
WASHINGTON -- The American Civil Liberties Union today expressed serious
concerns about the federal government's heavy-handed attempt to force a
content rating scheme on the television industry.  
<p>
Both President Clinton and Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich met with
broadcast executives today to discuss implementation of a "voluntary"
television content rating system.  
<p>
However, the ACLU said that any content rating system adopted would not be
voluntary at all in light of the recently passed V-chip law and the
high-profile White House and Congressional "requests" for meeting with
television executives.  The ratings system endorsed today by the television
industry would be used in conjunction with the V-Chip, automatically blocking
programs that receive certain, adverse ratings.
<p>
"Today's activity will only undermine the ability of parents to exercise
control over their children's viewing," said Daniel E. Katz, ACLU Legislative
Counsel. "Rather than support the development of independent private rating
systems and technology, the President and Congress will force the
broadcasters to comply with a singular, federally-controlled rating system."
<p>
Marjorie Heins, director of the ACLU's Arts Censorship Project, said that
"the ACLU is collecting information and talking with producers, writers and
directors who will be harmed by the V-Chip legislation."
<p>
The ACLU opposed the V-Chip provision of the Telecommunications Act when it
was before Congress, arguing that -- contrary to what the legislation's
backers claimed -- it would actually shut out families from the process of
deciding what television programming is acceptable for their children.
Rather, the ACLU said, the V-Chip would empower bureaucrats and television
executives to make decisions for parents.
<p>
"Would the V-chip's automatic censors block out such 'violent' dramas as
'Schindler's List,' 'Roots,' or 'Gone With theWind?'" Katz said. "Would
producers make a television mini-series about the bloody Civil War, which
very likely would be blocked as too violent, or pass on such a project for
fear of censorship?"
</p>
</blockquote>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
