<html><head><title>ACLU Press Release </title></head><body bgcolor=#ffffff><blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif"><center><h2>
ACLU Says Immigration Bill Is Unconstitutional, 
                       Unwise and Un-American
</h2>
</center>
<b>
 Statement of Gregory T. Nojeim,  Legislative Counsel <br>
ACLU Washington National Office 
<p>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
Tuesday, February 27, 1996
</b>
<p>  
WASHINGTON -- The House and Senate are scheduled to vote shortly on the most
wide-ranging set of immigration proposals in decades.  Much of the attention
has focused on the provisions that would reduce the number of newcomers
allowed to enter the country each year.  The most dangerous and troubling
aspects of the bills, however, evaded scrutiny : their dire effect on civil
liberties.
<p>  
    The immigration bills are unconstitutional, unwise and un-American.
 First, the bill would threaten the privacy rights of all Americans.
 Embedded in the legislation are provisions that would establish a single
federal computer registry to create a file of every single worker in the
United States. Every hiring decision would have to be cleared by this
government computer. This will not only lead to a serious infringement on our
privacy rights, but will cost taxpayers millions or billions of dollars, as
well as cause many Americans to be denied jobs improperly because of
data-entry errors.  For example, even a 1 percent error rate in the system
will cause 650,000 Americans to be categorized as unauthorized to work in
their own country.
<p>  
    The bill would also dangerously expand the government's power to listen
to our private conversations by dramatically expanding the list of federal
offenses used to authorize wiretaps. In 1994 alone, approximately two million
innocent conversations were intercepted through electronic surveillance.
 Congress should be working to minimize wiretaps, not the other way around.
<p>  
    Secondly, the House bill would visit a vestige of the McCarthy era on all
Americans. It would allow the government to deport aliens on the basis of
secret evidence. This provision is unconstitutional. Like citizens, aliens
have the right to see the evidence offered by the government against them.
Under the House bill, Americans would be barred from bring to the U.S.
speakers from abroad if they belonged to  an group that the government has
branded as "terrorist." This is a blatant attempt at governmental control of
the "marketplace of ideas" in the United States.
<p>  
    Third, the bill would violate due process.  The bill contains numerous
provisions that would eliminate some of the most basic protections of
judicial review and access to legal counsel guaranteed by the Fifth
Amendment's Due Process clause.  By imposing unreasonable time limits and
summary procedures, the bill would make it virtually impossible for someone
fleeing persecution to apply for asylum.  
<p>  
    If enacted, the bill would create two separate standards of due process:
one for citizens, another for non-citizens.  We should remind the sponsors of
this legislation that the Bill of Rights guarantees due process to all
"persons," and not just "citizens."
<p>  
    Fifth, if the Senate bill becomes law, local police untrained in
immigration enforcement would carry out the duties of the Border Patrol in
"immigration emergencies" involving a "mass influx" of aliens. This would
almost certainly result in more claims of abuse of constitutional rights
along the border. Untrained police would be even more likely than the Border
Patrol to detain Americans and authorized aliens based on their accents or
because they "look foreign."
<p>  
    The Senate bill would unnecessarily erect barriers to claims of
immigration-related employment discrimination. It would encourage the
practice of some employers to demand documents such as a "green card" from
their workers -- including U.S. citizens in some cases -- as evidence of
employment authorization.
<p>  
     Finally, both bills would tear apart American families and punish
hardworking immigrants.  The bill would shut the doors to 2.4 million people
who are the family members of Americans -- the parents, siblings and children
of U.S. citizens and residents.   In addition, the proposed legislation would
bar immigrant families, even those who have lived and worked in this country
for years, from receiving Social Security, Food Stamps and other benefits.
 Will children of immigrant parents be denied inoculations?    What does this
mean for elderly people currently receiving Social Security?  And what does
this bill mean for pregnant mothers who need health care assistance?
<p>  
    These proposals are based on fear and misunderstanding, not on the best
interest of the United States or the principles contained in our
Constitution.  They violate our country's history, and the history of
immigrants who have enabled America to grow and prosper.  We urge Congress to
honor our tradition and values, and vote against this bill.
</p>
</blockquote>
