<html><head><title>ACLU Press Release </title></head><body bgcolor=#ffffff><blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif"><center><h2>
"ACLU Argues Against State Funding of Religious Schools"
</h2>
</center>
<b>
<p>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
Monday, February 26, 1996
</b>
<p>  
MADISON -- On Tuesday, February 27, 1996 beginning at 1:30 p.m. the Wisconsin
Supreme Court in Madison will hear arguments for and against religious school
choice in a case that has national importance. 
<p>  
After the Wisconsin Legislature and Governor Tommy G. Thompson approved a
provision in the state budget bill that will  provide taxpayer dollars to
religious schools who accept qualified low income children, the American
Civil Liberties Union of Wisconsin Foundation, with the assistance of the
national ACLU and Americans United for Separation of Church and State filed a
legal challenge.  The challenge was brought on behalf of 14 parents and
clergy who seek to defend religious liberty.
<p>  
The Governor with special counsel Ken Starr is defending the proposal.   The
Wisconsin Supreme Court accepted the case as an original action, bypassing
lower state courts, in August.  The Court granted the ACLU's motion for a
preliminary injunction later in August.  The proposal has been on hold since
then. 
<p>  
At  oral arguments, the ACLU's lead attorney Jeffrey Kassel will tell the
Court that the proposed funding scheme violates the Wisconsin State
Constitution and the First Amendment to the U.S. Constitution.  The proposed
funding scheme would send taxpayer funds directly to religious schools which
have admitted their religious purpose.  In many instances religious schools
could receive more state funds per choice pupil than the school actually
charges for tuition.   National ACLU legal director Steven R. Shapiro,
ACLU/WIF's legal director Peter M. Koneazny and volunteer attorney Melanie
Cohen,  and Americans United's legal director Steven G. Green are assisting
in the representation of the ACLU's parent and clergy clients. 
</p>
<a href="/court/jackson.html">ACLU Brief</a>
</blockquote>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
