<html><head><title>ACLU Press Release </title></head><body bgcolor=#ffffff><blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif"><center><h2>
 ACLU Says Court Case Exposes America's Dirty Little Secret:
          The Criminal Justice System is Racially Biased
</h2>
</center>
<b>
<p>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
Monday, February 26, 1996
</b>
<p>  
     WASHINGTON -- The United States Supreme Court case United States v.
Armstrong, being argued here today, may provide the critical first step in
identifying a major source of racial discrimination in the nation's criminal
justice system -- the selective prosecution of African Americans.
<p>  
     The case comes not a moment too soon. The time has come for America to
admit to its "dirty little secret" that has so contaminated the nation's
criminal justice system. Ours is a racially biased, two-tiered system; one
for blacks and one for whites.
<p>  
     Beginning with the street level enforcement of state and federal
criminal laws, and ending with the meting out of the death penalty, African
Americans are disproportionately targeted, stopped, arrested, prosecuted,
sentenced to long mandatory prison terms and executed.  Indeed, in the nearly
30 years since the Kerner Commission warned that America was moving toward
"two societies, one black, one white - separate and unequal," our nation's
criminal justice system has made it a tragic reality.
<p>  
     Although the Armstrong case presents the narrow legal issue of whether
federal prosecutors in Los Angeles must disclose their charging criteria in
crack cocaine cases, the broader implications for the criminal justice system
are compelling:  whether federal prosecutors engage in a racially biased
decision-making process that results in selectively prosecuting African
Americans more harshly than whites.
<p>  
     The raw statistics cited in the Armstrong case that involve prosecutions
in Los Angeles are troubling indeed:
<p>  
-- The federal public defender's office in Los Angeles discovered that of the
24 crack cocaine cases closed out in 1991, all of the defendant's were
African American.
<p>  
--  Moreover, between 1991 and 1993 the federal public defender represented
53 defendants in crack cocaine cases, none were white.
<p>  
-- In contrast, from 1990 to 1992, 222 white defendants charged with crack
cocaine offenses were prosecuted in state court; thus, effectively avoiding
the harsh sentences required under the federal sentencing guidelines. 
<p>  
     The statistics alone certainly suggest that racial discrimination runs
rampant in the Los Angeles criminal justice system.  Although identifying
racial discrimination patterns is important, it alone does not solve the
problem.  To effectively purge the criminal justice system of racial bias, it
is critical to first expose the sources that foster racial discrimination.
 The Armstrong case may  provide the procedural vehicle for identifying these
sources.
<p>
       Indeed, the Court's decision in Armstrong may be the pivotal first step
in the attempt to eliminate racial bias in the criminal justice system.
 Requiring federal prosecutors to disclose their charging criteria for
bringing crack cocaine cases in federal court will likely resolve whether
prosecutors engage in a race-based decision-making charging process that has
a disparate impact on African Americans.  The Court must not avoid this
unique opportunity to strike a blow against racial discrimination in the
criminal justice system.  In a friend of the court brief filed with the NAACP
Legal Defense and Education Fund, the ACLU has strongly urged the Supreme
Court to affirm the lower court judgment ordering the federal prosecutor in
Los Angeles to disclose the criteria for prosecuting crack cocaine cases in
federal court versus state court.
<p>  
     It would be remiss, however, to simply discuss the Armstrong case
without acknowledging the other factors that contribute to racial bias in the
criminal justice system.  Nothing has contributed more significantly to the
racial disparity in the nation's criminal justice system than the so-called
"War on Drugs."
<p>  
     In the name of fighting this "war," our nation has increasingly employed
an ineffective militaristic approach to addressing the social problem of
illicit drug use.  As this failed "war" escalates, civil liberties crumble in
a misguided mission to conquer the perceived enemy--primarily people of color
and the poor. 
<p>  
     The results are disturbing, but not unexpected:  racial sentencing
disparity where Blacks and Hispanics are charged with and receive sentences
at or above the mandatory minimum more often than Whites arrested on the same
charges as is seen in the Armstrong case; unwarranted uniformity in
sentencing, ironically resulting in low level participants receiving more
time than so called "drug kingpins"; and an exploding prison population,
overwhelming minority, due to the proliferation of mandatory minimum
sentencing schemes.
<p>  
     These factors have produced these troubling statistics:
<p>  
     -- African Americans comprise 13 percent of the monthly drug users in
the U.S., but 39 percent of those arrested for drug offenses.
<p>  
     -- On any given day, almost one in three black men between the ages of
20-29 are in prison or jail, on probation or parole.
<p>  
     -- Although 13 percent of the U.S. population is African American, more
than 90 percent of all defendants prosecuted in federal court are African
American.
<p>  
     -- African Americans receive harsh prison sentences; whites convicted of
 similar offenses receive misdemeanor probation.
<p>  
     -- Over 60 percent of federal prisoners are drug offenders.
<p>  
     A significant contributing factor to the racial disparity can be traced
to the racial bias associated with drug sentencing.  Racial bias in drug
sentencing is most profoundly demonstrated in the irrational and unwarranted
disparity in federal cocaine law sentencing.  Under current federal
sentencing guidelines, persons convicted of crack cocaine offenses are
punished 100 times more severely than those convicted of powder cocaine
offenses.  For example, simple possession of more than five grams of crack is
a felony with a mandatory minimum sentence of five years for a first time
offender, while possession of the same amount of powder cocaine is a
misdemeanor requiring no jail time.
<p>  
     The Armstrong case provides another example of the actual impact of this
is unwarranted disparity.  In federal court under the sentencing guidelines,
one of the defendants, if convicted, could receive a sentence of 35 years to
life in prison. Conversely, if convicted in state court for the same crack
cocaine offense, the same defendant would face three to 10 years.  Given the
obvious and significant differences between federal and state sentences for
crack cocaine offenses, it strains credulity to suggest that it was pure
coincidence that all 24 crack cocaine cases that the federal prosecutors
brought in federal court involved black defendants.
<p>  
     The disparate and devastating impact of the current federal sentencing
scheme on the African American community is well documented.  Nationwide
statistics compiled by the U.S. Sentencing Commission confirm the disparity:
 in 1993, 88 percent of those sentenced federally for crack cocaine
distribution were African American, while only 4.1 percent of the defendants
were white.  It is also worth noting that a majority of the nation's reported
crack cocaine users are White, but the "war on drugs" has been
disproportionately targeted at inner city Black communities.
<p>  
     In 1995, the United States Sentencing Commission arrived at the same
opinion and stated that the "federal sentencing data leads to the inescapable
conclusion the Blacks comprise the largest percentage of those affected by
the penalties associate with crack cocaine."  Acknowledging the overwhelming
evidence against maintaining the irrational federal cocaine sentencing
guidelines, the Sentencing Commission recommended amending its guidelines to
reflect a one-to-one ratio at the current levels set for powder cocaine.
 Unfortunately, for the first time in the Commission's history, the Congress
and the President rejected the Sentencing Commission's recommendation and
reinstated the illogical sentencing structure--a structure that places
African American's in a class that is separate, but unequal.   
<p>  
     Mandatory minimum sentencing schemes in addition to the federal
sentencing guidelines targeted at drug offenses have also had a disparate
impact on minorities.  As a result, our nation's prison population is
exploding--mostly with minorities.  Black and Hispanics combined now
represent nearly 90 percent of all offenders sentenced to state prison for
drug offenses.  The root of this problem lies in the fact that mandatory
minimum sentences are disproportionately applied to minorities.  A 1992 study
of federal court cases found that, where a mandatory minimum could apply
black offenders were 21 percent more likely and Hispanic offenders 28 percent
more likely than whites to receive at least the mandatory minimum prison
sentence.  Given these striking statistics  impacting exclusively on
minorities, it is difficult not to wonder whether the "war on drugs" has
driven the nation back to the ugly days of Dred Scott.
<p>  
     The incendiary issue of racial bias in the criminal justice system
cannot be not be ignored and must be addressed head-on.  The Armstrong case
represents a critical opportunity for the Supreme Court to establish the
procedural mechanism by which one can seek to identify the sources
contributing to racial disparity.  The Court must not be inhibited in this
endeavor due to the potential for discovering that federal prosecutors
contribute to racial disparity in the criminal justice system by engaging in
selective prosecution tactics in crack cocaine cases the disproportionately
target African Americans.  Justice Louis Brandeis' words in Olmstead v.
United States should provided the Court some resolve:  "Our Government is the
potent, the omnipresent teacher . . . If the Government becomes a lawbreaker,
it breeds contempt for the law."
</p>
</blockquote>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
