http://www.aclu.org:80/news/n022696b.html 204.243.96.55 19970213143137 text/html 8041
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 13-Feb-97 14:30:20 GMT
Last-modified: Monday, 26-Feb-96 21:58:15 GMT
Content-length: 7856
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>ACLU Press Release </title></head><body bgcolor=#ffffff><blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif"><center><h2>
Litigation Analysis:
United States v. Armstrong
<p>
ACLU Urges Court to Purge Criminal Justice System of Racial Bias
</h2>
</center>
<b>
<p>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
February 26, 1996
</b>
<p>
     WASHINGTON -- In a strictly legal sense, the case of U.S. v. Armstrong,
argued today before the U.S. Supreme Court, appears to involve a  narrow
procedural issue:  under what circumstances must a federal prosecutor reveal
to the defense her reasons for bringing a prosecution. But in a larger sense,
this case presents the Court with the opportunity to address one of this
country's most troubling and insidious problems: pervasive racial bias in the
administration of our criminal justice system.
<p>
     The overrepresentation of young African American males in the jails and
prisons of the United States has been the subject of continuing media
coverage.  As has been widely reported, on any given day, almost one in three
black men between the ages of 20-29 are in prison or jail or on probation or
parole. The statistics in California, where the Armstrong prosecution arose,
are even more disturbing. Earlier this month, a study by the Center on
Juvenile and Criminal Justice found that nearly 40 percent of African
American men in their twenties in California are under some from of criminal
justice control. This compares to only 5 percent among white males of the
same age.
<p>
     Charges of racial bias by civil rights advocates, criminal defense
attorneys and social scientists are typically met with strong denials from
law enforcement officials and prosecutors, who argue that these disparities
are the unfortunate but inevitable function not of discrimination, but of the
higher crime rate in the inner cities. The importance of the Armstrong
litigation is that it may, depending on the Supreme Court's ruling, provide
some answers to this long-simmering debate by opening up to public scrutiny a
critical stage of the criminal justice process -- the charging stage.
Prosecutors have enormous discretion in deciding whom to prosecute. If the
race of a suspect, in fact, influences the charging decision, then the whole
process is vulnerable to constitutional attack. 
<p>
     A federal prosecutor's decision to prosecute a crack cocaine offense --
the offense involved in Armstrong -- is especially consequential because of
the harshness of federal penalties compared to state penalties.   If
Armstrong were convicted under federal law, he would face a 10-year mandatory
sentence. If prosecuted under state law, the same defendant could receive as
little as jail time and probation.  
<p>
     The raw statistics upon which the Armstrong case is based suggest a
pattern of selective prosecution based on race:
<p>
-- In Los Angeles, where the Armstrong litigation arose, not a single white
offender has been      convicted of a crack cocaine offense in the federal
courts since 1986, when Congress      enacted stiff new penalties.  
<p>
-- Between 1990 and 1992, over 200 white crack dealers were prosecuted by the
state      authorities in Los Angeles, a period during which the federal
authorities prosecuted not      one white defendant for crack.
<p>
-- Between 1991 and 1993, of the 53 defendants represented by the federal
public defender's      office, none were white.
<p>
Moreover, this pattern is not confined to the Los Angeles area.  According to
a 1992 survey by the U.S. Sentencing Commission, only minorities were
federally prosecuted for crack in seventeen states and many cities, including
Boston, Denver, Chicago, Miami, and Dallas.  In New York, the state most
heavily hit by the crack epidemic, only three whites were convicted in
federal court for crack distribution.  Nationwide, about 96% of crack
defendants in federal court are nonwhite.  
<p>
WHAT IS THE GOVERNMENT HIDING IN ARMSTRONG?
<p>
     The defendants in Armstrong are minorities who have been charged by the
U.S. Attorneys Office in Los Angeles  with crack distribution.   When their
attorneys filed a motion for discovery suggesting that race was a significant
charging factor, the federal trial judge was moved by the strength of the
statistical evidence and expressed concern that the "government hasn't
offered any explanation at all as to why persons being brought to Federal
court for these drug offenses all are black."   When the government could not
explain the statistical disparity, the judge ordered the government to reveal
the criteria it used "in deciding which of these cases will be filed in state
court versus Federal court."   The government then offered some of its
criteria, but the court still found its explanation wanting, and concluded
that the government had failed to make clear, "if there is any criteria for
bringing this case and others like it in Federal court." 
<p>
     Armstrong is now before the U.S. Supreme Court because the government
continues to resist divulging its criteria for charging these defendants
under federal law.
<p>
     The American public has the right to know whether blacks and other
minorities are being selectively and unconstitutionally subjected to federal,
rather than state, charges in crack prosecutions.   As the NAACP Legal
Defense and Education Fund and the American Civil Liberties Union, reminded
the Court in an amicus brief filed on behalf of the defendants:
<p>
     "This case once again brings the issue of racial discrimination in the
criminal justice system      to the forefront.  As this Court has previously
recognized, even the appearance of      discrimination has a corrosive effect
on public confidence in the administration of justice.       The actual
existence of discrimination is obviously incompatible with our most basic
     notions of due process and equal protection."
<p>
BEYOND ARMSTRONG
<p>
       During the past decade, numerous state and federal courts established
task forces charged with evaluating the treatment of racial and ethnic
minorities in the courts.  Each of the task forces concluded that racial
bias, both overt and unconscious, continues to cause not only prosecutors,
but also police and judges, to treat minorities differently and more harshly
than their white counterparts.  This occurs at every point that discretion is
exercised, whether it be at the arrest, charging, bail, jury selection or
sentencing stage.  The conclusion of the Florida Supreme Court Racial and
Ethnic Bias Study Commission is typical: 
<p>
     "In short, the reality is that African-Americans are being treated
differently at several      stages of the justice system.  When the object is
punishment -- detention, formal      adjudication, or commitment --
minorities get more; when what is being handed out is      informal
processing or diversion, minorities get less  This differential treatment
results, at      least in part, from racial and ethnic bias on the part of
enough individual police officers,      prosecutors, and judges to make the
system operate as if it intended to discriminate      against non-whites."
<p>
     It is critical that immediate steps be taken to eradicate racial bias
from our criminal justice system.  But we will not be able to rise to this
challenge if the government withholds from us the information necessary to
determine whether or not discretion is being exercised fairly. We hope the
Supreme Court will agree.
</p>

</blockquote>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
