<html><head><title>ACLU Press Release </title></head><body bgcolor=#ffffff><blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif"><center><h2>
             ACLU Names Two New Legislative Counsels
</h2>
</center>
<b>
<p>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
Friday, February 23, 1996
</b>
<p>
     WASHINGTON -- The American Civil Liberties Union has appointed two new
legislative counsels in its Washington National Office. Joining the staff are
Mark Kappelhoff, who will work on criminal justice issues, and Daniel E.
Katz, who will be responsible for covering several First Amendment issues.
<p>
     The appointments, announced by Laura W. Murphy, Director of the
Washington National Office, maintain the ACLU's primacy in these key areas of
civil liberties advocacy.
<p>
     "Beneath the rhetorical facade of the Contract with America, and the
Presidential campaign debate, are proposals to fundamentally alter the
liberties protected by the Bill of Rights," Murphy said. "I am glad we have
two more talented and committed individuals to fight the erosion of these
rights."
<p>
     Prior to joining the ACLU, Mr. Kappelhoff served as a Visiting Assistant
Professor of Law at the American University, Washington College of Law. He
taught in the nationally recognized clinical law program in which law
students represent indigent adult and juvenile clients before courts in
Maryland, Virginia and the District of Columbia.
<p>
     Mr. Kappelhoff's primary legislative responsibilities at the ACLU will
include issues involving criminal justice and civil rights such as the
omnibus crime bills, race-based sentencing disparities, civil asset
forfeiture, police brutality, prisoner rights; mandatory minimum sentencing,
search and seizure, drug testing and juvenile justice.
<p>
     Mr. Katz, although new to the legislative counsel position, is quite
familar with the ACLU Washington office. Prior to his appointment, he served
as a legal fellow working on First Amendment issues. Before that, he was a
legal fellow at the Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press in
Arlington, VA., where he monitored developments in news media law and advised
reporters about their First Amendment rights.
<p>
     Among the specific issues Mr. Katz will be watching are school prayer,
television violence, school vouchers, flag desecration, political advocacy
restrictions on nonprofit organizations and government funding of religious
organizations.
<p>
     Mr. Katz received his Juris Doctor degree from the University of Florida
College of Law, where he was a member of the Florida Law Review. An article
he authored, "Speak No Evil, Think No Evil: The Florida Hate Crime Law," was
published in the law review.
<p>
     Mr. Kappelhoff received his Bachelor of Science degree from St. John's
University in Minnesota and his Juris Doctor degree from American
University's Washington College of Law. While attending law school he was a
member of the American University Law Review and authored an article titled
"Is there a Right to Privacy?"
<p>
     Prior to becoming an attorney, Mr. Kappelhoff spent several years on the
legislative staff of Representative Gerry Sikorski. He began his legal career
as an Association in the D.C. law office of Kutak, Rock & Campbell. A strong
advocate of public interest law, he worked for several years as an Assistant
Public Defender in Montgomery County, Maryland.
</p>

</blockquote>
