<html><head><title>ACLU Press Release </title></head><body bgcolor=#ffffff><blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif"><center><h2>
ACLU Background Briefing:
     Supreme Court to Review ACLU Challenge 
to Censorship Provisions of the 1992 Cable Act</h2>
</center>
<b>
<p>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
Thursday, February 15, 1996
</b>
<p>
	WASHINGTON, D.C.--Next Wednesday, February 21, the Supreme 
Court will hear arguments in the consolidated cases of  Denver Area 
Educational Telecommunications Consortium, Inc. (DAETC) and 
American Civil Liberties Union  v. FCC and the United States, and 
Alliance for Community Media v. FCC and the United States. 
<p>
	Counsel for the ACLU and the other petitioners will argue 
that Section 10 of the 1992 Cable Act, implemented by the FCC and 
the United States, violates First Amendment freedoms because it 
authorizes and requires censorship of so-called "indecency" on 
cable television access channels under vague standards and lacks 
essential procedural safeguards against incursions on free speech.  
<p> 
	The case arises from a hastily tacked-on  amendment to the 
1992 Cable Act known as Section 10, in which Congress, led by 
Senator Jesse Helms, authorized cable operators to
prohibit programming they "reasonably believe" to be indecent, or 
to place such programming on segregated channels that must be 
blocked until the subscriber requests access in writing.  Section 
10 also authorized cable operators to prohibit programming on 
public, educational and governmental (PEG) access channels that is 
"sexually explicit" or "solicits or promotes unlawful conduct."
<p>
	This case is of particular interest in light of the ACLU's 
week-old challenge to the indecency provisions of the 
Telecommunications Act of 1996.   While it is not possible to 
predict precisely how the outcome of  ACLU and DAETC v. FCC  will 
affect the litigation against government efforts to censor the 
Internet, it is certain that this case is an important milestone in 
the ongoing struggle to preserve freedom of speech in all forms of 
electronic communication.
<p>	
<b>	Prior Proceedings</b>
<p>
	This case began during the rulemaking period following the 
passage of the 1992 Cable Act, when the ACLU, DAETC, the Alliance, 
and other civil liberties groups submitted detailed comments to the 
FCC arguing that Section 10 could not be implemented in a manner 
consistent with the Constitution. The FCC rejected the arguments 
and issued regulations implementing the law.  
<p>
	The ACLU and DAETC petitioned the Court of Appeals for the 
District of Columbia Circuit for review, with the Commission and 
the United States as respondents.  The government conceded in oral 
argument that if Sections 10(a) and 10(b) were found to involve 
"state action," they would violate the First Amendment.  A panel of 
the court unanimously struck down Sections 10(a) and (c) of the 
law, and found serious constitutional questions regarding Section 
10(b).  (Note: The provisions of Section 10 are described further 
below as well as in the text of the brief.) 
<p>
	However, the full D.C. Circuit vacated the panel's judgment, 
reheard the case en banc and sustained Section 10 and the 
regulations over the dissent in whole or in part of four of the 
court's eleven judges. The majority concluded -- in an 
unprecedented holding -- that the court could avoid addressing a 
constitutional challenge to a content-based statute regulating 
protected speech because the regulations only authorize, rather 
than command, censorship by private cable operators, and because 
these private acts cannot be attributed to government. 
<p>
	In her dissenting opinion joined in full by Judge Tatel, 
Judge Wald pointed out that Sections 10(a) and 10(b) must be 
considered together as part of one scheme regulating leased access 
programming, which, rather than "restore" editorial control to 
cable operators, requires them either to ban or block "indecent 
programming" and as such is clearly subject to First Amendment 
scrutiny.  Judge Wald concluded, joined also by Judge Rogers, that 
Sections 10(a) and 10(b) unconstitutionally cause a deprivation of 
First Amendment rights because of the undue burden on both speakers 
and listeners.  The regulations are clearly not the least 
restrictive means of achieving the asserted compelling interest, 
Judge Wald found, because of the ready availability of less 
restrictive means, such as the existing lockbox requirement.
<p>
	Additionally, Judge Wald found that 10(c), with its 
governmentally imposed definitions of disfavored speech and its 
erection of a separate scheme to regulate such speech, clearly 
constitutes governmental action and is not the least restrictive 
means of achieving the asserted compelling interest.
<p>
	The Supreme Court agreed to review the case, to address the 
questions whether a law can evade constitutional scrutiny by 
delegating censorship of a specified category of expression to 
private companies; and whether the "indecency" standard is too 
vague and subjective for a law regulating constitutionally 
protected speech.  
<p>
<b>	The Petitioner: Denver Area Educational Telecommunications 
Consortium (DAETC)</b>
<p>
	Since 1989, DAETC has operated a cable TV programming 
service, formerly known as the 90's Channel, now known as Free 
Speech TV, which has offered programming with strong political and 
social themes.   Free Speech TV currently reaches more than 4 
million cable homes on leased access and other channels.  Its 
programming is often controversial and otherwise unavailable, and 
discusses topics including the Persian Gulf war, environmental 
contamination, AIDS, racism, U.S.-Cuba relations, art censorship, 
union organizing, the status of recent immigrants, gay rights, 
feminism, the Palestinian uprising, issues of concern to Native 
Americans, prostitution, and prison conditions.
<p>
	An important part of DAETC's programming on certain of these 
topics inextricably deals with sexuality, such as a program segment 
about an organization that seeks to demystify gynecology by showing 
women how to perform their own pelvic exams, the controversy 
surrounding a Robert Mapplethorpe photography exhibit, and 
documentary-style footage from a lesbian and gay pride parade.  
<p>
	Some of DAETC's socially useful programming would be swept up 
in Section 10's broad definition of "indecency."   If Section 10 
stands, the very concept of leased and public access will crumble, 
because for the first time cable operators will have the power to 
censor these formerly independent access channels, and viewers will 
be denied access to the independent voices that can be heard on 
diverse programming such as Free Speech TV. (Note:  DAETC has 
produced a 7-minute tape illustrating Free Speech TV's programming, 
available in VHS or 3/4 format.  See below for information on how 
to obtain a copy.)  
<p>	

<b>	Section 10 of the 1992 Cable Act: Background</b>
<p>
	In 1984, to "assure that cable communications provide...the 
widest possible diversity of information sources and services to 
the public," Congress passed the Cable Communication Policy Act.  
This Act required cable operators to set aside channels for leased 
access programming that they were forbidden to censor.  
<p>
	The Act also recognized that public access or PEG channels 
were required by many local cable franchise agreements, and 
prohibited cable operators from interfering with the editorial 
content of public access programming.  In essence, cable operators 
were not First Amendment "speakers" but simply conduits for free 
speech by citizens on public and leased access channels.
The 1984 Act also required operators to provide lockboxes that 
enable a subscriber to block any cable channel during selected 
periods.  This provision remains in effect.
<p>
	In 1992, Congress once again focused on the cable industry, 
this time primarily to promote diversity through temporary rate 
re-regulation, to address customer service practices, and to 
implement "must-carry" rules requiring cable transmission of 
broadcast television.
<p>
	On the last legislative day before the Senate approved this 
bill, Senator Jesse Helms and then-Senator Wynche Fowler offered 
two floor amendments that collectively became Section 10, entitled 
"Children's Protection from Indecent Programming on Leased Access 
Channels."  
<p>
<b>	Section 10: The Details:</b>
<p>
	Section 10, which was never sent to a committee and was never 
the subject of any hearings or findings, established a censorship 
scheme with four interlocking parts:
<p>
	 	Section 10(a) authorized cable operators to ban what 
they "reasonably believe describes or depicts sexual or excretory 
activities or organs in a patently offensive manner as measured by 
contemporary community standards."
<p>
	 	Section 10(b) required the FCC to prescribe rules 
requiring cable operators that have not voluntarily prohibited 
programming under 10(a) to segregate all "indecent" leased access 
programming on channels that must remain blocked until 30 days 
after a subscriber requests access in writing.  Programmers must 
"certify in writing whether their shows are "indecent."
<p>
	 	Section 10(c) applies to public, educational and 
government (PEG) access channels and authorizes cable operators to 
ban "any programming which contains obscene materials, sexually 
explicit conduct" or "material that solicits or promotes unlawful 
conduct."   If  the operator does not ban PEG programming, it may 
cablecast the programming without blocking.
<p>
	 	Section 10(d) eliminates cable operators' immunity from 
liability for access programming that "involves obscene material."  
Taken together with the other provisions, it virtually compels 
cable operators to censor any access programming that might 
approach the definition of obscenity (a much narrower concept than 
"indecency.")  Given that many cable operators, such as Time 
Warner, will not want to risk prosecution, and in any event have no 
fondness for access channels, the end result will be a massive 
amount of censorship by cable operators and the loss of independent 
and innovative programming.  
<p>
	Before Section 10's enactment, federal law and many state and 
local laws prohibited cable operators from interfering in any 
manner with programming on access channels, regardless of content, 
because access channels' very raison d'etre is to establish a forum 
in which persons other than large media companies can speak to the 
public in one of the nation's most important forms of 
communication.  
<p>
<b>	Section 10 is Unconstitutional</b>
<p>
	Senator Helms attempted, through Section 10, to craft 
anti-"indecency" laws that would escape First Amendment scrutiny by 
placing censorship authority largely in the hands of the cable 
operators and imposing stiff penalties for failure to censor 
"indecent" programming.  But such a joint enterprise between 
government and private actors is subject to constitutional 
scrutiny.  And when subjected to well-settled First Amendment 
standards, Section 10 fails.  
<p>

<b>	 	Section 10 Encourages Content-Based Censorship and 
Therefore  is Subject to Constitutional Review </b>
<p>
		Congress cannot authorize cable operators to censor 
"indecent" speech on access channels any more than it can authorize 
cable operators to censor speech by African Americans or socialists 
or speech opposing reduction of welfare grants.  The fact that 
cable operators are private companies does change the 
constitutional standard because the companies may censor only under 
the authority of Congress.  All statutes are subject to 
constitutional review. 
<p>

<b>	 	Section 10 is not the least restrictive means of 
screening minors from "indecent" material</b>
<p>
		Congress' existing requirement of lockboxes already 
satisfies the government's asserted interest in protecting children 
from "indecency," particularly in light of cable's status as an 
invitee in the home for which the user pays a monthly fee. In the 
brief hours that the amendment was considered, Senator Helms failed 
to present evidence that lockboxes are no longer a sufficient means 
of facilitating parental protection of children, or to consider any 
other less restrictive alternatives, such as blocking programming 
on subscriber request.
<p>

<b>	 	Cable programmers are entitled to free speech 
protections </b>
<p>
		Section 10 requires programmers to certify that they 
will identify "any programming that is indecent" on pain of a 
draconian array of sanctions that include financial penalties and 
disqualification from access programming in the future.  Cable 
programmers engage in and transmit speech, and as such are entitled 
to the protections of the speech and press provisions of the First 
Amendment.  The levying of fines and other penalties, not to 
mention the direct censorship by cable operators, will undoubtedly 
have a chilling effect on free speech.  
<p>

<b>	 	The law authorizes censorship under impermissibly vague 
standards  </b>
<p>

		Given Section 10's extraordinarily sweeping definition 
of "indecency," the law imperils speech of substantial artistic, 
literary, scientific, medical, educational and social importance: 
speech that is protected not only for adults but for teenagers as 
well.  Cable operators, faced with fines and other penalties, will 
be strongly inclined to censor any speech that they might 
"reasonably believe" to be "patently offensive," according to 
"community standards." 
<p>

<b>	 	The law is impermissibly underinclusive, because it 
blocks only speech by leased access programmers.  </b>
<p>
		Irrationally, even though a cable operator is required 
to block a purportedly "indecent" leased access program, the 
operator is entirely free to cablecast that same program on one of 
its own cable channels.
<p>
<b>	Conclusion</b>
<p>
	The leased access cable medium represents a vital and unique 
environment for protected speech that is seriously endangered by 
the unconstitutional provisions of the 1992 Cable Act.   
Just as government-sanctioned clearcutting of forest lands  has 
contributed to soil erosion and endangered wildlife habitats, the 
recent concentration of the broadcast and cable mediums (through 
so-called deregulation), coupled with broad censorship schemes, is 
eroding the public's access to a diversity of information sources 
and putting constitutionally protected speech in jeopardy.  
<p>
	The indecency standard is so impossibly vague and undefinable 
that it will undoubtedly create an environment in which any 
"questionable" programming will be axed.  Whether acting  through 
direct legislation or in partnership with private industry, 
government does not have the right to cut down the Constitution.  
<p>
	###
<p>
Web pages of the two client organizations:<br>
<a href="http://www.freespeech.org/">Free Speech TV </a><br>
<a href=" http://153.18.60.51/acm.html">Alliance for Community Media</a>	
<p>
###
<p>
Counsel for ACLU and DAETC:<br>
Charles S. Sims <br>
Proskauer Rose Goetz & Mendelsohn LLP, New York City 
<p>
Marjorie Heins <br>
