<head>
<title>
December 19, 1995; Civil Rights Groups File Suit Against Santa Monica And LA Police For Widespread Violation of Miranda Rule
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff><blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif"><center><h2>
Civil Rights Groups File Suit Against Santa Monica And LA Police For Widespread Violation of Miranda Rule</h2>
</center>
<b>
<p>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
December 19, 1995<p></b>

     The ACLU Foundation of Southern California, on behalf of California
Attorneys for Criminal Justice, Criminal Courts Bar Association and two
individuals, filed a major lawsuit [California Attorneys for Criminal Justice
v. Butts 95-8634 IH] in U. S. District Court today, charging the Santa Monica
and Los Angeles police departments with extensive violation of the Miranda
rule which says police must not question suspects in their custody after they
have invoked their right to legal counsel.
<p>
     "Los Angeles and Santa Monica police departments treat the Miranda
warning with a wink and a grin," said Mark Rosenbaum, legal director of the
ACLU Foundation of Southern California. "This is the Dirty Harry school of
interrogation."
<p>
     In its 1966 decision in Miranda vs. Arizona, the U.S. Supreme Court said
that in-custody interrogation of criminal suspects "exacts a heavy toll on
individual liberty and trades on the weakness of individuals."  As a result,
officers must give the familiar Miranda warning before questioning.  If a
person asks to see a lawyer, all questioning must cease.  Officers are
violating Miranda by continuing to question after a suspect asks for a
lawyer.  
<p>
     Last November, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled, for the third time in three
years, that police may not ignore the right of an in-custody suspect to
remain silent and seek legal counsel, reversing a tendency of the high court
to favor police and prosecutors.
<p>
     The lawsuit seeks to enjoin the Los Angeles and Santa Monica Police
departments from the unlawful policy and practice of evading Miranda, by
continuing to question suspects after they have requested counsel and the
right to remain silent.  The suit charges that not only have police in these
departments violated the Miranda rule, but they have done so with the full
knowledge and consent of department leadership.
<p>
     "The invocation of Miranda is a clear and unambiguous signal for the
police to cease any and all interrogation," said Vicki Podberesky,a member of
the Board of Governors of California Attorneys for Criminal Justice. "There
is evidence to suggest that police improperly cajole individuals to answer
questions, by misinforming them that answers made outside Miranda will not be
used  against them in court when the contrary is true."
<p>
     The complaint, filed in federal court, quotes a defendant officer
telling a suspect, "I don't trust anything that anybody tells me after
they've talked to an attorney...As far as I'm concerned, they really mess up
the system."
<p>
     Criminal Courts Bar Association President Rickard Santwier said, "We are
asking the court to require those who have sworn to enforce the laws to at
least follow the law."
<p>
     Attorneys said that police must be trained to uphold Miranda, and
disciplined if they violate the rule.  Because Miranda violations are
widespread, attorneys said that results of this lawsuit will influence police
policy and practice nationally.
</blockquote>

<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
