<HEAD>
<TITLE>August 1, 1995; ACLU Challenges Public Funding of Religious Schools in Wisconsin;
        Suit Seeks to Stop Vouchers Before School Year</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>
ACLU Challenges Public Funding of Religious Schools in Wisconsin;
        Suit Seeks to Stop Vouchers Before School Year
</h2>
</center>
<br>
<b>
<P>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
August 1, 1995</b>
<P>
     MADISON, WI -- Acting on behalf of parents and religious groups, the
American Civil Liberties Union today filed suit in Dane County Circuit Court
challenging Wisconsin's school vouchers law, which would, if upheld, provide
public funding to parochial schools. 
<P>
     Today's lawsuit challenges a law signed on July 26 by Gov. Tommy
Thompson that would expand  the state's "Schools Choice" program to include
religious schools. The law would provide direct state aid to religious
schools -- including grades kindergarten through 12th -- who would then use
that state taxpayer money to support religious education. The ACLU lawsuit
marks the first legal challenge to a state school vouchers program brought in
the continental United States.
<P>
     "This law crosses the line the U.S. Supreme Court has drawn limiting
government assistance to religious education," said Peter Koneazny, Legal
Director of the ACLU of Wisconsin.  "We are seeking to block this law because
we believe in religious freedom, as provided by the U.S. and the Wisconsin
state constitutions."
<P>
     In the lawsuit, the ACLU cited a section of the Wisconsin Constitution
that promises that tax money will not be used to fund religious schools and
that no person "shall be compelled to support any place of worship, or to
maintain any ministry without consent."
<P>
     "In drafting this country's constitution, the founders understood that
religious freedom is guaranteed by keeping government out of religion," said
Steven R. Shapiro, Legal Director of the American Civil Liberties Union.
<P>
     Chris Ahmuty, Executive Director of the ACLU of Wisconsin Foundation,
said he hopes the court will rule on the injunction before school is set to
begin.
<P>
     "It is unfortunate that a program with such serious constitutional
problems was rushed through the legislature and signed so hastily," Ahmuty
said. "The governor knew this program would instantly be challenged in court,
yet he seemed to have given little thought to the inconvenience and
disruption this may cause Wisconsin parents and children."
<P>
     The action was brought today by 12 individual taxpayers, including
parents and religious leaders, who oppose the program on religious freedom
grounds.  The plaintiffs will also file a motion asking the court to issue an
injunction delaying any payments to religious schools until the courts can
rule on the constitutional issues.
<P>
     In a similar challenge last year, the Puerto Rican Supreme Court struck
down a school voucher program that provided any family with an annual income
of less than $18,000 to a $1,500 voucher that could be used to subsidize the
cost of private school tuition, including parochial school. In its decision
on November 30, 1994, the Court held that the program violated a provision of
the Puerto Rican Constitution that prohibits the use of public funds to
support private schools.  While the Court did not explicitly address the
federal constitution's Establishment Clause, it found that a voucher program
is a form of government support.
<P>
     The plaintiffs in today's challenge are represented by the Peter
Koneazny of the ACLU of Wisconsin; Steven R. Shapiro, Legal Director of the
national American Civil Liberties Union, and Steven Green, Legal Director of
Americans United for Separation of Church and State.  Lead counsel on the
case are attorneys Jeffrey Kassel and Melanie Cohen of the Madison law firm
of LaFollette & Synykin.
<P>
</blockquote>


<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
