<HEAD>
<TITLE>August 1, 1995; ACLU Asks Congress to Create a National Commission
To Review Federal Law Enforcement Policies and Practices</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>ACLU Asks Congress to Create a National Commission
To Review Federal Law Enforcement Policies and Practices
</h2>
</center>
<br>
<b>
<P>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
August 1, 1995</b>
<P>
      WASHINGTON -- In written testimony submitted to the two House
subcommittees holding Waco hearings, the American Civil Liberties Union has
asked Congress to create a national commission to comprehensively review
federal law enforcement policies and practices.
<P>
     "There has been an enormous growth of federal law enforcement over the
years so that federal police now comprise close to 10 percent of the nation's
law enforcement," the ACLU testimony said. "These federal officers work in 53
separate federal agencies in which law enforcement officers have the
authority to carry firearms and make arrests.
<P>
     "This represents an enormous expansion in recent years," the ACLU said,
"of both personnel and jurisdiction. What is lacking, however, is systematic
oversight and review of federal law enforcement practices."
<P>
      The ACLU and nine other organizations had requested creation of a
national commission in a January 1994 letter to President Clinton. Among the
issues the ACLU suggests need review by a commission are:
<P>
       -- The appropriate use of para-military and strike force units or
tactics.
       -- The use of "no knock" and "dynamic entry" tactics
       -- The use of unreliable informants and the process of verifying their
allegations.
       -- Apparent presentation of misleading and inaccurate information by
federal agents in an effort to obtain a warrant.
       -- Inadequate process for investigating complaints of misconduct and
apparent failure to appropriately discipline federal agents who have acted
improperly.
<P>
      According to the ACLU, the new commission would be similar to the
Wickersham Commission appointed by President Hoover in 1929. The Wickersham
Commission report stimulated major law enforcement reforms, including curbing
the use of the "third degree" to extract confessions. Another model cited by
the ACLU is the Citizens Advisory Panel recently created by Immigration and
Naturalization Service Commissioner Doris Meissner to advise her regarding
the problem of abuse by Border Patrol agents.
<P>
      The ACLU concluded that the Waco hearing and other hearings "have been
useful in highlighting ongoing questions about federal law enforcement
practices."
<P>
       "The next step," the ACLU said, "should be creation of a mechanism
that could begin to review these practices at issue here in a systematic
way."
<P>
(The text of the ACLU's testimony is attached to this document for
downloading.)
<P>
</blockquote>


<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
