<HEAD>
<TITLE>July 26, 1995; Jane Doe Discontinues Suit Over Peters Township
              School District's Graduation Prayers</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>
        Jane Doe Discontinues Suit Over Peters Township
              School District's Graduation Prayers
</h2>
</center>
<br>
<b>
<P>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
July 26, 1995</b>
<P>
       PITTSBURGH --  Jane Doe, who in early June sued the Peters Township
School District to stop planned graduation prayers, said today that she has
decided to discontinue the case.
<P>
      The suit resulted in an agreement on the eve of graduation that the
school district would cancel a planned invocation and benediction.  At the
graduation, however, four students read the planned invocation, a sectarian
prayer, raising public controversy.
<P>
     In her statement, Jane Doe expressed the hope that the district will
continue to recognize, as it did in the court-approved agreement, "that
scheduled student prayer [is] not appropriate at "high school commencement
ceremon[ies] . . . and other school ceremonies."  In explaining why she
decided to discontinue the suit, Ms. Doe said: 
<P>
          "To pursue this issue further would require lengthy legal dealings.
I           do not wish to involve the four student speakers any more, as
they           are all starting new lives in college.  It is my hope that as
they           continue their education, they will encounter persons of
diverse           viewpoints --  religious and otherwise -- which may give
them a new           perspective on the issue."
<P>
     The American Civil Liberties Union, which has been representing Ms. Doe
and her daughter, expressed support for the decision.  Witold Walczak, the
ACLU-Pittsburgh's Executive Director, called Ms. Doe a "very courageous woman
who stood tall for an important constitutional principle in the face of
tremendous opposition."  Walczak cautioned, however, that the discontinuance
should not be misinterpreted by school districts as a retreat by the ACLU on
the issue of graduation school prayer: "The Pittsburgh Chapter of the ACLU
has sued school districts successfully in each of the past three years to
stop student-led graduation prayers, and, if necessary, we will continue to
file similar suits in the future to stop this unconstitutional practice."   
<P>
     In response to the school district's claim that the students were only
exercising their free speech rights, Walczak replied: "Commencement exercises
are not platforms for free speech -- school districts routinely prohibit and
censor hate speech, comments critical of the school, vulgarity and anything
else that may be an embarrassment at graduation.  Peters is no different:
freedom of speech is not a quality normally encouraged at Peters Township
commencements, where student speeches are carefully scrutinized ahead of time
and proper behavior and dress are defined and monitored to an extreme degree.
Under these circumstances, permitting prayer is giving preferential treatment
to religious speech, which is a violation of the constitutional ban on
promoting religion."  
<P>
     Walczak said he hopes to have another opportunity in the near future to
litigate the tension between free speech and separation of church and state:
"Student speakers, properly placed on the program for secular reasons, may
make personal expressions of faith.  They may not, in the name of free
speech, engage the audience in a group religious exercise, such as prayer."
<P>
       Jane Doe:Statement Closing The School Prayer Case.
<P>
     Peters Township School District, in signing the original
     agreement, agreed that scheduled student prayer was not
     appropriate at the school commencement ceremony.
<P>
     We assume that having recognized this fact this year, district
     officials will continue to recognize it in future commencements
     and other school ceremonies.  The school districts surrounding
     Peters Township showed this spring that commencements can
     feature meaningful welcomes, farewells and advice to graduates
     without prayers.  These included such school districts as Upper
     St. Clair, Mt. Lebanon, Canon-McMillan, Bethel Park and
     Washington.
<P>
     As a result of this legal action, important issues have been raised
     and will continue to be discussed in this community. 
     Consciousness has certainly been heightened about the proper
     respect for all persons' religious beliefs.  We look to the
     Ministerium and the school district to continue the discussion in
     the coming year of an appreciation of diversity.
<P>
</blockquote>


<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
