<HEAD>
<TITLE>July 25, 1995; ACLU Plans to Appeal Reversal of Juvenile Hall Lawsuit </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>
       ACLU Plans to Appeal Reversal of Juvenile Hall Lawsuit
</h2>
</center>
<br>
<b>
<P>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
July 25, 1995</b>
<P>
     SAN DIEGO -- Saying that it was profoundly disappointed, the ACLU of San
Diego and Imperial County today said the Fourth Distrcit California Court of
Appeals has overturned a 1992 San Diego Superior Court ruling ordering San
Diego County to improve conditions at its Juvenile Hall.
<P>
      The ACLU said that even though the Appellate District three-judge panel
agreed that the conditions at the jail were harmful, it unanimously sided
with the County Board of Supervisors who challenged the Superior Court's
authority to order improvements at the Juvenile Hall facility.
<P>
      The ACLU and the San Diego Volunteer Lawyer Program, which had filed a
lawsuit in 1990 asking the court to require the country to limit the
population of the facility and to improve conditions there, said today that
they would soon file a motion for a rehearing with the appellate court. If
that motion is denied, they said, they will appeal the case to the California
Supreme Court.
<P>
       "This appellate decision is a profound disappointment with untold
ramifications for the thousands of children, most not convicted of any crime,
detained at Juvenile Hall," said Linda Hills, Executive Director of the ACLU
of San Diego and Imperial Counties.
<P>
       In its decision, the State Appeal Court found that "...the trial
court's statement of decision accurately portrays conditions at juvenile hall
as they existed at the time of trial. The appeals court also agreed that
every day the community "...loses valuable opportunities to protect itself
from future harm because ... we have not devoted more resources to the
services provided at juvenile hall." 
<P>
        Nevertheless, the panel said its only disagreement with the Superior
Court decision was its conclusion that courts are competent to provide a
remedy for such lost opportunities. "We," the appeal court said, "are not." 
<P>
         Jordan Budd, staff counsel of the ACLU of San Diego and Imperial
Counties, said the appeal court "has abdicated its responsibility to
safeguard the constitutional interests of the young people of San Diego
County."
<P>
          "We disagree that the courts have no role to play in correcting the
situation at Juvenile Hall," Budd said. "We will appeal the decision and hope
a higher court will breathe life back into the constitutional rights at
stake.
<P>
          "The decision renders the Constitution a dead letter with regard to
these young people,' Budd added. "It is wrong and it is tragic."
<P>
           Timothy Taylor of the San Diego Volunteer Lawyer Program said that
"legal standards of review require that appellate courts must defer to
factual findings of the trial court. It is disappointing that the appeal
court based its ruling on how Judge O'Neill expressed himself rather than on
evidence of unconstitutional violations of the rights of children whose last
refuge is the courts."
<P>
        Superior Court Judge O'Neill ruled in October 1992 that the county
must take affirmative steps to improve Juvenile Hall, including:
<P>
        -- a population cap of 395 in the facility and caps on the number of
children per room.
<P>
        -- mandatory ratios of staff to residents.
<P>
        -- improved screening and evalution of suspected mental illness.
<P>
        -- a maximum of 15-day period in which minors may be held before
beginning court ordered treatment.
<P>
        In addition, the court ordered the county to begin long-term plans
for structural and funding measures to bring about the improvements.
<P>
</blockquote>


<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
