<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>July 5, 1995; "ACLU To Sue To Block State Funding of Religious Schools"</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>
"ACLU To Sue To Block State Funding of Religious Schools"
</h2>
</center>
<br>
<b>
<P>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
July 5, 1995</b>
<P>
MILWAUKEE -- The American Civil Liberties Union of Wisconsin (ACLU/WI) and
the national ACLU today announced that they will challenge the expansion of
the current Milwaukee private school choice program to include religious day
schools.  The ACLU seeks to defend religious liberty by preventing a
violation of the principle of separation of church and state. 
<P>
The state budget soon to be signed by Wisconsin Governor Tommy Thompson would
provide direct aid to K-12 religious schools who would then use taxpayer
dollars to fund their mission of religious education.  The budget removes the
prohibition against religious schools participating in the current
non-sectarian private school choice program. 
<P>
Under the new plan, which is to be implemented in the 1995-96 school year,
approximately 7,000 students could attend religious schools in Milwaukee at
taxpayer expense.  The amount of their subsidy would equal the amount spent
per pupil by the Milwaukee Public Schools.  Students currently attending MPS,
a current choice school, or, if in grades K-3, a religious school in the City
of Milwaukee, will be allowed apply to religious schools for admission.  
<P>
The ACLU/WI will sue on behalf of a group of Milwaukee plaintiffs who object
to the proposed subsidy because any violation of the principle of separation
of church and state is offensive to religious liberty.
<P>
     The lead counsels in the case will be ACLU/WI Foundation volunteer
attorneys Jeffrey Kassel and Melanie Cohen from the Madison law firm of
LaFollette & Sinykin.  Also, representing the plaintiffs will be ACLU/WIF
legal director Peter M. Koneazny and national ACLU legal director Steven R.
Shapiro.  
<P>
"This case is about religious liberty," said Chris Ahmuty, Executive Director
of the ACLU of Wisconsin Foundation, "It is a mistake to characterize this as
a debate about anything else.  As a supporter of quality education for all
children, the ACLU objects to funding religious schools with taxpayer dollars
period.  We cannot sacrifice religious liberty on the altar of an unproven
experiment that confers a direct benefit on any religious faith, sect or
cult." 
<P>
     The ACLU anticipates filing the case shortly after Governor Thompson
signs the budget, and the July 15 deadline for religious schools to indicate
their intention to participation in the program. 
<P>
     In another development the ACLU/WIF is also filing an amicus brief in a
case pending at the United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit in
which the plaintiffs have challenged the current non-sectarian private school
choice program because it does not allow for the participation of religious
schools.  On March 14, 1995 federal district judge John W. Reynolds decided
that, "The present state of First Amendment law compels this court to hold
that the plaintiffs's request to expand the current Choice Program to make
tuition reimbursements directly payable to religious private schools who
admit eligible Choice Program schoolchildren would violate the Establishment
Clause."  The ACLU/WI maintains that there is no significant difference
between the plaintiffs' request in the pending case on appeal and the
proposal in the state budget.
<P>
</blockquote>


<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
