<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>June 6, 1995; ACLU of VA Warns Schools About Prayers at Graduation Ceremonies
Says It Will Sue Those That Do Not Follow The Law </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>
ACLU of VA Warns Schools About Prayers at Graduation Ceremonies
Says It Will Sue Those That Do Not Follow The Law</h2>
</center>
<br>
<b>
<P>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>
June 6, 1995</b>
<P>
     RICHMOND, VA -- The ACLU of Virginia is sending letters today to every
public school superintendent in Virginia, advising them not to allow
organized prayers at their upcoming graduation ceremonies.
<P>
     The ACLU said it is particularly concerned that without other guidance,
schools will follow the advice contained in the Preliminary Guidelines on
Religious Activity in Public Schools, a document that was distributed by the
State Board of Education this spring.
<P>
      Although these guidelines have not yet been officially adopted, they
contain erroneous advice on so-called class-initiated prayers and
individually initiated prayers at graduation ceremonies that could be
followed by graduation planners.
<P>
      In the case of class-initiated prayers, the ACLU says it will sue any
school that violates Gearon v. Loudoun County, the 1994 decision from the
Alexandria Federal District Court banning all formal prayers at graduation
programs, whether organized by students or school administrators. The
Preliminary Guidelines ignore Gearon and advise schools that formal prayers
are acceptable on graduation programs when the senior class votes to have
them and the prayers are delivered by students.
<P>
      Individually initiated prayers by a student speaker may be permissible,
the ACLU said, but only in instances where the school has completely
relinquished control over the student's speech. The ACLU warns schools not to
edit, approve or even review such speeches in advance because of the danger
of the appearance of endorsement of any prayer which may be part of them. If
a school wishes to maintain its traditional role in determining the content
of student speeches, it must not allow prayers to be part of the speech.
<P>
(The text of the two-page letter to superintendents will be available in
Constitution Hall soon.)
<P>
</blockquote>


<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
