<HEAD>
<TITLE>May 25, 1995; ACLU Buckhannon</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>
ACLU Buckhannon</h2>
</center>
<br>
<b>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
May 25, 1995</b>
<P>
BUCKHANNON, WV -- The West Virginia Civil Liberties Union goes to court on
Tuesday, May 30, in Clarksburg to argue that schools should not be used as a
site for local merchants to distribute bibles.
<P>
The Upshur County school board decided in February to allow local religious
groups to set up tables in all the county's schools to distribute Bibles.
Several parents and students complained to the West Virginia Civil Liberties
Union, said Hilary Chiz, Executive Director of the statewide affiliate of the
national ACLU.
<P>
U.S. District Court Judge Irene Keeley ruled in favor of the students and
parents, granting a preliminary injunction to halt the distribution plan on
February 24. A hearing on the case is scheduled for Tuesday, May 30.
<P>
"We don't have a problem with Bibles being distributed on private property,
or even in the Kroger parking lot," said Chiz. "But once anyone crosses that
threshhold and tries to use the schools, they violate the Establishment
Clause of the First Amendment of the U.S. Constitution.
<P>
"There is no reason to bring stacks of Bibles into the schools," Chiz said.
"The school libraries already have copies that are made available to anyone.
This plan is clearly just another way to get to students, who are easy
targets for religious extremists because they are all in one place --
school."
<P>
The West Virginia Civil Liberties hopes the ruling will permanently halt the
Bible distribution plan. The students and parents are represented by WVCLU
cooperating attorneys Bob Bastress and Allan Karlin of Morgantown.
<P>
</blockquote>


<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
