<HEAD>
<TITLE>May 16, 1995; First International Survey of Prayer in Schools Finds That World's Major Countries Reject State- Sanctioned School Prayer </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>First International Survey of Prayer in Schools Finds That World's Major Countries Reject State- Sanctioned School Prayer</h2>
</center>
<p>
<br>
<b>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
May 16, 1995<P></b>

    LOS ANGELES -- A school prayer amendment to the U.S. Constitution being
pushed by conservative groups and Republicans would put the United States
squarely at odds with most of the world's nations, according to an
international survey issued today by the ACLU of Southern California.
<P>
     Only two of 72 countries surveyed currently have school prayer policies
such as those proposed by conservative religious groups and political leaders
in Washington, the ACLU researchers found in what is believed to be the first
international survey ever conducted.
<P>
     Moreover, the proposal to reinstate state-sanctioned prayer in American
public schools contradicts an international trend toward greater separation
of religion and public education. The plan to amend the Constitution to
permit state-sanctioned prayer is expected to advance this week with release
of a legislative proposal by the conservative Christian Coalition.
<P>
     The ACLU study also noted that the traditional American insistence on
strict guarantees of freedom to choose one's religious beliefs without
government interference has resulted in the United States having the highest
levels of professed religious faith of any industrialized nation.
<P>
      "Our nation's spiritual health is founded on the right of both persons
and groups to practice and worship as they see fit," said the Reverend James
Lawson of the Holman United Methodist Church. "To mandate how people may
invoke the deity is inherently un-American. Attempts to force students to
pray are wrong. People of faith must unite in opposing attempts to force one
religious point of view in our public classrooms."
<P>
     Rabbi Allen Freehling of University Synagogue said: "Attempts to
Christianize the American public classroom ostracizes not only non-Christian
children, but Christian children with different religious customs and
beliefs. There is no such thing as completely ecumenical prayer or meditation
because of the different ways that people approach God. State-mandated school
prayer excludes and divides students. Those who profess freedom of religion
cannot support prayer in schools."
<P>
      The proposal by the Christian Coalition and Republican congressional
leadership is in stark contrast with recent actions in other countries to
separate church and state. For example, the ACLU survey found that Colombia
and South Africa have both moved forcefully to end state-mandated school
prayer since 1991. Colombia changed its constitution in 1991 to favor strict
separation of church and state, although the issue remains the subject of
divisive internal controversy.
<P>
     In South Africa, the new racially integrated government of President
Nelson Mandela has moved quickly to abolish mandatory school prayer and Bible
readings. Meanwhile, Mexico and Venezuela -- both strongly Roman Catholic
nations -- have continued to hold firmly against pressures to dilute
guarantees against imposing religion on school children through
state-sanctioned prayer.
<P>
     "There is a very strong message here that the American system works and
that it permits a strong, vibrant religious life in this country that could
not continue if the government meddles in this most personal of all issues,"
said Allan Parachinin, the ACLU of Southern California's public affairs
director who conducted the new survey.
<P>
     "Our findings about international practices governing state-sanctioned
school prayer show that even many countries with state religions or
fundamentalist governments do not go as far as to impose state-sanctioned
prayer on school children."
<P>
     Of 72 countries surveyed by the ACLU in December 1994 and January 1995,
only 11 nations retain any practice of state-sanctioned school prayer.
However, nine of those countries -- Finland, Greece, Libya, Nepal, Pakistan,
Saudi Arabia, Romania and Thailand -- either have state religions or
populations that are virtually homogeneous in terms of religious preference.
<P>
      Only two countries with any semblance of religious or racial
diversity--Great Britain and Sweden--permit state-sanctioned school prayer.
And in Great Britain, the practice has recently become controversial as
conservatives have sought to reinvigorate the status of the Church of England
as the country's official religion.
<P>
       Indeed, many countries where single religions dominate national life
have steered a careful course around imposing prayer in the schools. These
nations include Iran, Italy and Israel.
<P>
       Among other countries that reject state-sanctioned school prayer are
Egypt, Bahrain, Argentina, France, Germany, Hong Kong, Iraq, Japan, Lebanon,
Kuwait, Morocco, the Netherlands, Oman, Poland, Singapore, South Korea, Syria
and the United Arab Emirates.
<P>
       The survey also found that the six most diverse provinces of Canada,
including all portions of the country that enjoy signficant racial diversity,
reject state-sanctioned school prayer. Two Canadian provinces, Saskatchewan
and Newfoundland, permit school prayer but under circumstances that stop
short of expecting all children to participate in recitation of a single
prayer each day.
<P>
      "The vast majority of the major countries of the world, including
Western Europe, Central America and Asia, have rejected state-sponsored
prayer in their public school systems," the ACLU study concluded. "For
advocates of religious faith, the record of the United States speaks for
itself.
<P>
      "America chose a very different approach to religion, with the Founders
recognizing that, for religion to flourish here as they indended, the state
would have to stay out of it. Other countries have not chosen this path, but
still the vast majority of them have overwhelmingly endorsed the idea that
the public schools should not become houses of worship or put the stamp of
government approval on particular forms of worship."
<P>


<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
