<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>May 15, 1995; Letter to President </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>ACLU Launches
<P>Letter to President<p></h2>
</center>
<p>
<br>
<b>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
May 15, 1995<p></b>
     This week, the Christian Coalition is expected to unveil a
set of legislative proposals marketed as a "Contract with the
American Family."  Its centerpiece is reported to be a proposed
constitutional amendment to protect "religious expression" in the
public schools.
<P>
     The American Civil Liberties Union urges you to reject this
proposal to tamper with the Constitution -- America's original
contract with the American family.
<P>
     The First Amendment has protected both religion and
religious liberty for 204 years.  It has permitted religion to
flourish in America as nowhere else.  Americans are among the
most religious people in the world.  In terms of per capita time
spent on religious devotion, money contributed and church
attendance, the United States ranks higher than any advanced
industrial nation.  According to a recent public opinion poll,
the United States ranked as one of the two highest nations in the
percentage of its population that believed in God.  The notion
that religion is failing in America, and needs the government's
assistance, is demonstrably false.
<P>
     Moreover, the United States enjoys a wide degree of
religious diversity with comparatively little religious
divisiveness.  The reason for this is the First Amendment, which
reflects the wisdom of keeping religion and politics separate. 
Without such separation, people of different religious beliefs
inevitably end up competing for government assistance and
support.  The mixture is inflammable.
<P>
     More than two hundred years ago, Thomas Jefferson
demonstrated how the government's intervention into the private
sphere of religious belief would, as he put it, be harmful to
both religion and religious freedom.  In a speech to the Virginia
House of Delegates, he declared that religion and religious
liberty would only flourish if the state had no authority to
adopt an official opinion in matters of religion.  Two centuries
of history has proved him right.
<P>
     Now comes an extreme proposal from the Christian Coalition
to overturn what has worked so well for so long.  We must resist
their radical overtures and renew our faith in the First
Amendment, which has served us so well.  True conservatives ought
to be conserving this 18th-century principle, instead of
radically transforming it.  If we move in the direction urged by
the Christian Coalition, we will likely plunge this country into
the kind of religious/political disputes that have so often
racked other countries.
<P>
     We urge you to keep several points in mind as you consider
this proposal:
<P>
     1.  Religious expression in public schools is already
protected by the First Amendment.
<P>
     If a child in public school wishes to say grace before
eating a meal in the school cafeteria, or carry a bible to school
to read in between classes, she has the right now under the First
Amendment to do so.  That is religious freedom.
<P>
     But if the school conducts an official grace before meals so
that every student in the cafeteria is subjected to it whether
she believes in it or not, that is not permitted by the First
Amendment because it reflects official government endorsement or
sponsorship of religion, and imposes religious beliefs on
children whose families may not share them.  This is true even if
the grace ceremony is "student initiated."  Individual rights
means that any student can say grace, but no student can be
subjected to a religious ceremony because the majority outvotes
her.  That is not religious freedom.  
<P>
     The Christian Coalition says it wants to protect "religious
expression" for individual students.  If so, no constitutional
amendment is needed because the First Amendment already protects
such individual expression.  A constitutional amendment is
required only if one wishes to overturn Supreme Court decisions
that have prevented the government, through its schools, from
imposing religious beliefs and ceremonies upon all students. 
That is the Christian Coalition's real agenda, as Pat Robertson's
writings make plain.  When the Christian Coalition says it only
wishes to protect individual religious expression, it is not
telling the truth.
<P>
     Individual students may express their religious beliefs now. 
But the public schools may not be turned into a church for a few
minutes each day so that the government, or a majority of
students, can impose religious ceremonies on all students.  That
is the right line to draw, and it is a line that the Christian
Coalition wants to erase.
<P>
     2.  Whose prayer will be said?
<P>
     If the Christian Coalition has its way, and school-wide
ceremonies are allowed to be conducted in public schools, whose
prayers will be dominant, and who will decide?
<P>
     Will Jewish children be required to submit to Christian
ceremonies?
<P>
     Will Moslem children be made to listen to Catholic rituals?
<P>
<P>
     Will Baptist parents be pleased if their children are
required to sit through Muslim ceremonies?
<P>
     Or will children of minority religions in any given school
be separated from their peers in order to permit the majority to
have its way?
<P>
     And whose forms of prayer will predominate?
<P>
     Muslims bow to Mecca several times a day.
<P>
     Pentecostals stand when praying.
<P>
     Catholics and Episcopalians kneel.
<P>
     Bahai refuse to bow their heads.
<P>
     Presbyterians bow their heads.
<P>
     Getting the government involved in making these choices is a
prescription for conflict.  Either religion will be drained of
all meaning in an attempt to avoid conflict or divisiveness will
be inevitable.  Either way, as Jefferson knew, it will be bad for
religion and bad for religious freedom.
<P>
     Most Americans who favor prayer in public schools imagine
their own form of prayer.  But will they be happy if their
children are forced to submit to forms of prayer that are not
their own?  
<P>
     3.  Getting the government off our backs.
<P>
     If there is any arena of the American family's life that
should be immunized from government interference it is religion
and the religious upbringing of children.  That is exclusively a
parental right.  Traditional family values require that the
government stay out of such parental prerogatives, and not use
the public schools to erode them.  Yet the Christian Coalition
proposes to amend the Constitution to allow the government to
tell American families how, when, where, whether and with whom
their children should pray?  What could be more inappropriate,
more radically intrusive?  That is why the Christian Coalition's
proposals are anything but conservative; they represent nothing
less than a radical intrusion of big brother government into the
American family's religious life.  
<P>
     The Christian Coalition calls its proposal a "Contract with
the American Family."  It should more accurately be called "The
Government Knows Best Act of 1995."
<P>
     Prayer should remain in the private domain.  As the apostle
Matthew wrote:
<P>
               And when thou prayest, thou shalt
               not be as the hypocrites are: for
               they love to pray ... in the
               streets, that they may be seen ... 
               But, thou, when thou prayest, pray
               to thy Father, which is in private
               ...
<P>
     The rights of individual students to freedom of religious
expression is already protected by the First Amendment.  What the
Christian Coalition wants is government-assisted prayer,
government-endorsed religion.  But the government that is given
the power to assist religion, also acquires the power to destroy
it.  And the government that assists one citizen's religion
hinders another citizen's religion.
<P>
     The Christian Coalition's proposal is dangerous and radical,
and diverts us from real problems the government should address.  
<P>
     We urge you to reject it.
<P>
     We urge you to conserve the First Amendment.
<P>
     We urge you to go about the proper business of government. 
Certainly we have enough real problems without manufacturing new
ones.
<p>
Sincerley
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Ira Glesser
<P>


<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
