<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>April 19, 1995; ACLU of Texas Files Lawsuit Defending Religious Freedom for Prisoners </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>
ACLU of Texas Files Lawsuit Defending Religious Freedom for Prisoners</h2>
</center>
<P>
<br>
<b>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
April 19, 1995</b>
<P>
      AUSTIN -- The American Civil Liberties Union of Texas announced today
that it was filing a lawsuit on behalf of 13 prisoners whose religious
freedom have been violated by the Texas Department of Criminal Justice.
<P>
     "All people everywhere have a fundamental right to spiritual sustenance
and guidance," said ACLU cooperating attorney J. Patrick Wiseman, who is
handling the lawsuit. "It is a freedom no government ought to deny. But those
in prison have particular needs, and it is particularly distressing that, in
our free society, the State of Texas is denying these plaintiffs the freedom
of conscience we all hold so dear."
<P>
     The plaintiffs in the ACLU lawsuit practice various religions, including
Native American religion, Wiccan and Muslim. The suit alleges that the Texas
Department of Criminal Justice has deprived the plaintiffs of their religious
freedom guaranteed by the free speech and free exercise clauses of the First
Amendment and the Religious Freedom Restoration Act.
<P>
     Each plaintiff has been denied access to various religious materials,
many have had religious literature and articles destroyed or confiscated.
Some have been denied the right to perform religious rituals -- the Muslims
have been denied the right to attend Islamic services, the Native Americans
have been denied the right to grow their hair long, including the placing of
a plaintiff, Iron Thunderhorse, in solitary confinement and confiscating his
typewriter for his refusal to cut his hair.
<P>
     Plaintiff Ruby Mathews has been denied the right to study Wiccan redes,
religious literature written in runes, letters of the Ancient Germanic
alphabet, as well as other Wiccan religious literature.
<P>
      "Religious freedom, the ability to choose one's own spiritual path, is
at the core of our basic American liberties," said Jay Jacobson, the
Executive Director of the ACLU of Texas. "The history of mankind is so filed
with evidence of the evil caused by religious oppression and intolerance that
we could not turn away from this case.
<P>
      "As James Madison stated," Jacobson continued, "'The religion then of
every man must be left to the conviction and conscience of every man; and it
is the right of every man to exercise it as these may dictate. This right is
in its nature an unalienable right. We maintain therefore that in matters of
Religion, no man's right is abridged by the institution of Civil Society and
that Religion is wholly exempt from its cognizance.'"
<P>
      The suit, filed in U.S. District Court for the Western District, Austin
Division, names the Texas Department of Criminal Justice, the Texas Board of
Corrections and Institutional Division Director Wayne Scott as defendants and
Louis Armijo, David Davis, Larry Gagniere, Alvin Goodwin, Alvin Harrison,
Keith Jones, Noah Martinez, Ruby Mathews, Alex Montana, Dewayne Thomas, Iron
Thunderhorse, Patric Warner, and Charles Watkins as plaintiffs. Plaintiffs
come from institutions in Amarillo, Huntsville, Midway, Gatesville, Tennessee
Colony, Lockhard, Beeville, Brazoria and Beaumont.
<P>
</blockquote>


<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
