<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>April 4, 1995; ACLU of Texas Files A Complaint Against Santa Fe ISD</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>ACLU of Texas Files A Complaint Against Santa Fe ISD</h2></center>
<p>
<br>
<b>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</br>
April 4, 1995</b>
<p>
HOUSTON -- The ACLU of Texas, acting on behalf of parents and students in
Santa Fe, today filed a complaint against Santa Fe ISD for numerous
violations of the First Amendment's prohibition against government
establishment of religion.
<P>
The complaint, filed in Federal Court in Galveston, Texas, alleges that the
School District permitted, supervised or condoned the following activities:
<P>
1. Denominational prayer at school graduation.
2. Distribution of Bibles at the schools by the Gideons.
3. Grade school teacher-led prayers.
4. A teacher's belittling of a student's religion during a history class.
5. A teacher's distribution of flyers to students announcing a Baptist
Revival.
6. Junior High School Christian Club meetings during school hours and teacher
sponsorship.
7. Teacher-led religious songs during class time (a third grade student,
whose parents did not wish him to participate, was put outside the classroom
and left unattended).
8. Baccalaureate services at the High School gym, conducted by a Minister
selected by the school administration.
9. Prayers conducted at school sports events.
<P>
All of these activities, the ACLU said, have the primary effect of advancing
Christianity by Santa Fe ISD, in violation of the First Amendment. Plaintiffs
are seeking injunctive relief prohibiting the defendants from continuing to
sponsor and endorse religious practices at Santa Fe schools. Plaintiffs also
seek monetary damages and injunctive relief protecting them from retaliation
by the defendants.
<P>
Transmitted: 95-04-20 17:06:33 EDT (n040495)


<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
