<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>March 31, 1995; The American Civil Liberties Union of Alabma</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>
The American Civil Liberties Union of Alabma</h2>
</center>
<br>
<b>
<P>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
March 31, 1995</b>
<P>
JUDGE LED PRAYER CALLED UNCONSTITUTIONAL
<P>
The American Civil Liberties Union of Alabama today filed a lawsuit to
stop religious practices led or initiated by judges in Alabama's
courtrooms. Filed against Etowah County Circuit Court Judge Roy S. Moore,
the suit calls his penchant for displaying religious symbols and inviting
clergy to lead the court in prayer a constitutionally forbidden violation
of the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the US Constitution, as well as
Alabama's own constitution. 
<P>
"The Plaintiffs are asking for a courtroom that is open to all citizens,"
said Joel L. Sogol , ACLU of Alabama Co-operating Attorney.  "No one
should have to pass a religious test to receive justice in a courtroom." 
The suit is being brought in the name of the Alabama Freethought
Association and other individuals whose reside in Moore's circuit. The
suit was filed in the US District Court for the Northern District of
Alabama.  Judge Moore regularly opens his court with prayer, led by either
a member of the clergy or a layperson. The prayers are explicitly
Christian. 
<P>
In addition, Moore prominently displays a wood carving of the Biblical Ten
Commandments in his courtroom.  Following complaints about judge-led
prayer in Alabama's courtrooms, Alabama Supreme Court Chief Justice Sonny
Hornsby's office advised the judges under his jurisdiction of the problems
of the practice and let each judge decide what he or she would do. Judge
Moore is one of several judges who chose to continue sponsoring prayer in
his courtroom. 
<P>
 "Such practices have been ruled unconstitutional endorsements of religion
by the US Supreme Court and recently in the 4th and 11th Federal Circuits
in cases from North Carolina and Georgia." said Sogol.  "The Judge is a
representative of government authority acting upon a captive audience,
forcing them to participate in, or sit through, his particular form of
religious worship. Prosecutors, defendants, juries, witnesses and
spectators are all powerless to object for fear of prejudicing the Judge
against them. This is clearly a violation of both religious endorsement
and religious liberty." 
<P>
The suit asks for a removal of the religious symbols from the courtroom
and a permanent order enjoining Judge Moore from "leading, conducting or
promoting the recitation of prayers in the courtroom."  "We expect a
favorable decision," said Sogol, "and we hope both the Judge and the
Governor will abide by the law." 
<P>
Representing the ACLU in this lawsuit are James Tucker of the ACLU of
Alabama, Joel Sogol of Tuscaloosa , and Robert Skitol of Drinker Biddle
and Reath in Washington, DC. 
<P>
###
<P>
ATTACHMENT The following cites are mentioned in the body of the release,
and are included for your information:  Harvey v. Cobb County, GA (811 F.
Supp 669, 678 ND GA 1993) Affirmed without opinion, cert. denied
<P>
In reference to the Ten Commandment:  The Court concludes that the panel,
when considered in its context, has the effect of endorsing religion in
general and Christianity in particular and therefore violates the
Establishment Clause.  North Carolina Civil Liberties Union v Constangy
(947 F. 2d 1145, 1152 4th Cir. 1991), cert. denied
<P>


</blockquote>
