<HEAD>
<TITLE>March 30, 1995; Federal Judge Strikes Down "Don't Ask, Don't Tell"
 Six Lesbian and Gay Servicemembers Win Lawsuit </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>
Federal Judge Strikes Down "Don't Ask, Don't Tell"
 Six Lesbian and Gay Servicemembers Win Lawsuit</h2>
</center>
<br>
<b>
<P>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
March 30, 1995</b>
<P>
       (NEW YORK, March 30) -- In a major blow to the current law barring
open lesbians and gay men from serving in the armed forces, a federal
judge today ruled in favor of six servicemembers who sued the federal
government in the first direct constitutional challenge to the so-called
"Don't Ask, Don't Tell" law. 
<P>
       "Our victory today is enormously gratifying," said Matthew Coles,
director of the ACLU's national Lesbian and Gay Rights Project. "But in no
way is it the end of this story. We will not stop this fight until we have
finally struck down this law that denies freedom of speech and equal
protection to lesbian and gay servicemembers." 
<P>
        "Today's ruling is a decisive setback to a policy that is based
solely on prejudice and antipathy towards gays," said Beatrice Dohrn,
legal director at Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund. "This ruling
underscores what we already know. Open lesbians and gay men serve our
nation's defense well, and they do so without harming military
capability." 
<P>
       Judge Eugene Nickerson of the federal district court for the
Eastern District of New York, ruled that, "The Supreme Court has held that
the First Amendment will not countenance the proscription if the
expression of an idea because others find that idea repugnant." 
<P>
       "This principle applies with particular force where, as here,
heterosexuals find the mere idea of homosexual orientation disagreeable
based largely on irrational stereotypes." 
<P>
      "It [is] demeaning and unworthy of a great nation to base a policy
on pretense rather than truth," he said. 
<P>
       The case, Able v. U.S.A., was filed jointly by Lambda Legal
Defense and Education Fund and the American Civil Liberties Union on
behalf of six lesbian and gay servicemembers. The lawsuit contended that
the legislation adopted by Congress and signed into law by President
Clinton in 1993 is discriminatory, based on prejudice, and in violation of
the free speech and equal protection rights of the plaintiffs. 
<P>
       The current law, which subjects lesbians and gay servicemembers to
discharge if they say or do anything that reflects their sexual
orientation, marked the first time the military's discriminatory policy
was codified by Congress into law.  Enacted in November 1993 as a
political "compromise," the policy sought to modify the previous
guidelines, issued in 1981, under which nearly 17,000 servicemembers were
discharged, at a cost of $500 million to tax payers. 
<P>
       But the current law, according to military observers, does little
to change the Pentagon's longstanding policy to discharge lesbian and gay
servicemembers. In fact, the language remains largely unchanged. Rather
than a policy based on the belief that "homosexuality is incompatible with
military service," the current law holds that open lesbians and gay men
pose an "unacceptable risk to the high standards of morale, good order and
discipline, and unit cohesion that are the essence of military
capability." 
<P>
       The lawsuit was filed on behalf of two active servicemembers and
four reservists who come from a variety of ranks across military branches:
U.S. Army Reserves Colonel Jane Able (a pseudonym), U.S. Coast Guard Petty
Officer Robert Heigl, U.S. Army Reserves Captain Kenneth Osborn, U.S. Army
Reserves Sergeant Steven Spency, U.S. Navy Lieutenant Commander Richard
von Wohld, and U.S. Navy Seaman Werner Zehr. In addition to the ACLU and
Lambda, the plaintiffs were assisted by cooperating attorneys from the New
York-based law firm of Sullivan and Cromwell. 
<P>
       During the four-day trial that began on March 13, 1995, the
plaintiffs presented six witnesses including Laurence J. Korb, former
Assistant Secretary of Defense for the Reagan Administration; Retired
Major General Vance Coleman, who served from 1942 to 1989; and Retired
Brigadier General Evelyn P. Foote, who served nearly 30 years.  The
witnesses testified in support of plaintiffs' claim that the policy's
rationale is "utterly lacking in empirical fact or reasonable data ," but
is instead based solely on prejudice. The government did not produce any
witnesses to defend the military's policy. 
<P>
      "We are prepared for the government's probable appeal," said the
ACLU's Coles. "We are confident that a higher court will uphold the rights
of lesbians and gay men to serve openly in our nation's armed forces." 
<P>
      "The decision will hold up on appeal because laws based on
prejudice are never constitutional," said Lambda's Dohrn. "We will
continue to fight the military's ban on lesbian and gay servicemembers
until the policy is overturned."
<P>


</blockquote>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
