<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>March 12, 1995;  Ban on Gays in the Military Goes On Trial;
       `Don't Ask, Don't Tell' Faces Challenge in Brooklyn</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>
           Ban on Gays in the Military Goes On Trial;
       `Don't Ask, Don't Tell' Faces Challenge in Brooklyn</h2>
</center>
<br>
<b>
<P>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
March 12, 1995</b>
<P>
     (NEW YORK, March 12, 1995) -- The trial in Able et al v.
U.S.A., the first and only direct constitutional challenge to the
government's current law barring lesbians and gay men from openly
serving in the military, will begin Monday, March 13, in federal
District Court in Brooklyn. Opening statement will begin at 9
a.m., followed by the testimony of expert witnesses, which will
continue through Wednesday. Closing arguments are scheduled for
Thursday.
<P>
     The lawsuit, filed jointly by the American Civil Liberties
Union and Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund on behalf of
six servicemembers, contends that the legislation adopted by
Congress and signed into law by President Clinton in 1993, is
discriminatory, based on prejudice and in violation of the free
speech and equal protection rights of the plaintiffs.
<P>
     "The new ban is a shocking example of the government's
willingness to cave in to anti-gay antipathy," said Beatrice
Dohrn, Lambda's Legal Director. "This policy relies solely on
prejudice. Lesbians and gay men have made, and always will make,
an invaluable contribution to our nation's defense. Our
plaintiffs should be allowed to serve our country openly and
honestly."
<P>
     "This is the last bastion of officially sanctioned
government prejudice in America," said Matthew Coles, Director of
the American Civil Liberties Union's national Lesbian and Gay
Rights Project. "It violates our clients' constitutional rights
and must be struck down."
<P>
     The current ban, known misleadingly as "Don't Ask, Don't
Tell," marked the first time the military's discriminatory policy
was codified by Congress into law. Enacted in November 1993 as a
"political compromise," the policy bars lesbians and gay men from
service if they say or do anything that reflect their sexual
orientation. Although the government now admits that gays are as
capable as heterosexuals, the policy holds that open gay men and
lesbians pose "an unacceptable risk to the high standards of
morale, good order and discipline, and unit cohesion that are the
essence of military capability."
<P>
     But the current policy, which took effect on February 28,
1994, merely continued the military's longstanding policy to
discharge lesbian and gay servicemembers. Under the previous
guidelines, issued in 1981, the Pentagon held that homosexuality
was "incompatible with military service." Nearly 17,000
servicemembers were discharged under those rules.
<P>
     The lawsuit is filed on behalf of six lesbian and gay
servicemembers, two active and four reservist, who come from a
variety of ranks across the different branches of the military.
They are: Colonel Jane Able, Petty Officer Robert Heigl, First
Lieutenant Kenneth Osborn, Sergeant Steven Spencer, Lieutenant
Richard von Wohld and Seaman Werner Zehr.
<P>
     Since it is known that they are gay men or lesbians, the six
plaintiffs will face immediate discharge proceedings if the law
is upheld. A federal appeals court has ordered that the
preliminary injunction, blocking the government from proceeding
to discharge the plaintiffs, will expire on March 31, 1995, and
that Judge Eugene Nickerson should issue his final ruling in the
case before that date.
<P>
     At trial, attorneys for Lambda and the ACLU -- along with
cooperating attorneys from the law firm of Sullivan and Cromwell
-- will argue that the current statute and regulations create an
elaborate system under which all lesbian and gay servicemembers
are not judged by their fitness and ability to serve, but are
instead subject to discriminatory treatment because of the
perceived prejudices of others.
<P>
     The plaintiffs will show that the policy's rationale is
"utterly lacking in empirical fact or reasonable data," and that
Congress ignored government-sponsored studies that prove that
allowing open lesbians and  gay men to serve would not hurt
military effectiveness. They will also show that the
Congressional record was edited to disguise the fact that the
only basis for the military's ban is antipathy and prejudice
toward  lesbians and gay men.
<P>
     Expert witnesses for the plaintiffs include:
<P>
     -- Dr. Lawrence J. Korb, the former Pentagon official under
the Reagan Administration, will testify that he was directed to
implement the 1981 version of the ban despite his view that it
was unjustified.
<P>
     -- Dr. Robert MacCoun, the author of Rand Corporation's
government-commissioned report on gays in the military, will
testify that sexual orientation has no impact on unit cohesion or
military effectiveness.
<P>
     -- Major General Vance Coleman will testify about the
parallels between the arguments made in support of the current
statute, and the arguments made a generation ago to oppose racial
integration of the armed services.
<P>
<P>
     -- Dr. Pepper Schwartz, a Professor of Sociology at the
University of Washington and an expert on human sexuality, will
address the common stereotypes of lesbian and gay sexuality, and
the relationship between sexual orientation and military
effectiveness.
<P>
     -- Brigadier General Evelyn P. Foote will testify about
military discipline, chain of command,  and unit cohesion, and
how they all serve to temper bias and prejudice.
<P>
The trial is scheduled to begin Monday, March 13 at the federal
courthouse in Brooklyn, 225 Cadman Plaza East, at 9:00 A.M. in
the chambers of Judge Eugene Nickerson. (Able et al v. USA, U.S.
District Court for the Eastern District of New York, CV 94-0974.)
<P>


</blockquote>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
