<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>March 12, 1995;  Statement of Matthew Coles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>
              Statement of Matthew Coles, Director,
          ACLU National Lesbian and Gay Rights Project
   On the Challenge to "Don't Ask, Don't Tell" in Able v. USA</h2>
</center>
<br>
<b>
<P>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
March 12, 1995</b>
<P>
     "Tomorrow we will go to court on behalf of six ordinary,
capable people who wish only to serve their country.  But because
of officially sanctioned government prejudice, they cannot be here
today. The law we are challenging prohibits them from saying or
doing anything that shows they are gay. These aren't people who
seek the limelight. They have brought this case because federal law
says they can't tell their closest friends they had a date to see
a movie the night before.  Starting tomorrow, we will begin a trial
before a U.S. District Court Judge to strike down this law that
denies freedom of speech and equal protection to our clients.
<P>
     "The armed services are the largest employer in America.  This
policy denies people who are able and willing to serve their
country the opportunity to do so -- not on the basis of merit or
ability, but because others might be uncomfortable by their
presence. The most shocking thing about this case is that the
government admits this.  It admits that lesbians and gay men are
just as good as soldiers and sailors and it admits that the only
reason for the policy is that some heterosexuals are uneasy. That
is pure and simple prejudice. It cannot be the basis for law in the
United States of America, where we value fairness and merit above
all.
<P>
     "The Constitution protects all Americans.  All Americans have
the right to freedom of speech provided by the First Amendment and
to equal protection under the law as guaranteed by the Fourteenth
Amendment. The policy must be struck down because it defies the
very principles of fairness upon which this country was founded."
<P>


</blockquote>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
