<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>March 12, 1995;  Statement of Beatrice Dohrn, Legal Director
             Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>
          Statement of Beatrice Dohrn, Legal Director
             Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund</h2>
</center>
<p>
<br>
<b>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
March 12, 1995</b>
<P>
Americans should be judged by what they do, not who they are. 
Able v. USA challenges one of the most sweeping, basic,
government sponsored affronts to that principal.  This process
began with the intention of eliminating discrimination based on
sexual orientation.  It ended in the enactment of a law that
could not be clearer in its differential and unfair treatment of
lesbian and gay servicemembers.  
<P>
Let's be clear about the terms of the Act and regulations we are
challenging:  they do not punish particular acts or behavior
fairly and even-handedly.  Rather, they take aim at lesbian and
gay sexual orientation, and subject to discharge those who say or
do anything that indicates that they are gay.  
<P>
This policy works in very ironic ways.  For instance, those who
are NOT lesbian or gay are granted the freedom to participate in
activities that if undertaken by our clients, would result in
their discharge. We're talking about anything from frequenting
gay social events, reading gay literature,  putting your arm
around your football buddy, or dancing with your college
roommate, to private, non-criminal off-base, off duty sex. 
Heterosexuals are free to do these things, as well as to proclaim
their sexual orientation and even to brag about their sexual
exploits to anyone they wish.  
<P>
We intend, in this lawsuit, to demonstrate for once and for all
that every justification offered in support of this or any other
ban boil down to one thing -- antipathy toward lesbians and gay
men. Lesbians and gay men have made and always will make an
invaluable contribution to our nation's defense.  The time has
come to allow lesbians and gay men to serve openly and honestly. 
They should not be forced to hide.
<P>
At trial, we will show that tried and true principals of military
leadership would make fast work of dealing with the so-called
"disruption to good order and discipline" which the government
alleges would result, if the ban were lifted.  As Dr. Lawrence
Korb pointed out in his deposition in this case: "Military people
are wonderful about following orders.  Give an order.  They'll
make it work."  We look forward to the court giving that order.
<P>


<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
