<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>January 20, 1995; Federal Appeals Court to Hear Challenge to NJ Ban on Graduation Praye</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<center>
<h2>
Federal Appeals Court to Hear Challenge to NJ Ban on Graduation Prayer</h2>
</center>
<P>
<br>
<b>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
January 20, 1995</b>
<P>
     The Black Horse Pike School District's appeal of an injunction
against any form of prayer at its graduation ceremonies, secured by the
American Civil Liberties Union of New Jersey on behalf of a 1993
graduating student, will be heard on Monday, January 23, by the federal
Third Circuit Court of Appeals in Philadelphia. 
<P>
     The case began when the Black Horse Pick school district permitted
the senior class to vote on whether it wanted a prayer delivered during
the commencement ceremonies. The class was also allowed to vote on whether
the prayer would be delivered by a student or a clergy person. 
<P>
     In granting a preliminary injunction against that activity, the Third
Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that schools could no sooner delegate the
function of presenting prayer to students than present prayer by selecting
a clergy person. Both activites, the court ruled, amount to public-school
sponsorship of prayer at a school-sponsored event; both have the same
effect on students who do not share the same or any religious beliefs. 
<P>
     A permanent injunction against organized graduation prayers in the
district was issued in March 1994 by District Court Judge Joseph E.
Irenas. The school district appealed to the Third Circuit. 
<P>
     "This case involves issues that go to the very heart of the First
Amendment," said James Katz, the ACLU's volunteer attorney who will argue
the case for the plaintiffs. 
<P>
     "Courts have long ago held that the First Amendment requires strict
neutrality of public institutions in regard to religion," added Mr. Katz,
of the Haddonfield firm of Tomar, Simonoff, Adourian & O'Brien. 
<P>
"This requirement cannot be abrogated by having students sponsor prayer at
a school-sponsored graduation or by having a student lead the prayer as
the school officials have proposed. 
<P>
     "The fundamental rights of religious freedom were never intended to
be submitted to a majority vote," Katz said.
<P>


</blockquote>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
