<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Model Letter on Late Term Abortion</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/graphics/repro.gif"></P>

<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">MODEL LETTER TO STATE OR FEDERAL LEGISLATOR </H2>
<P><I><FONT SIZE="+1">Use your browser's copy function to paste this letter
into an e-mail to your member of congress, or paste it into a word processing
application and fax or mail to your federal or state representatives.</FONT></I></P>
<HR>
<P>Dear [legislator]:</P>
<P>As your constituent, I am writing to urge you to oppose any bans on
so-called &quot;partial-birth abortions.&quot;  This term is unrecognized by the
medical community and wholly invented by abortion opponents to mislead the
public.  The actual abortion procedure they appear to have in mind is known to
the medical community as &quot;dilation and extraction&quot; (D&amp;X) or &quot;intact
dilation and evacuation&quot; (IDE).</P>
<P>Women confronting catastrophic pregnancies must have all safe options
available, including D&amp;X, a procedure that is safest for some women in some
circumstances.  Many women have come forward to explain why D&amp;X was the
safest way to resolve their tragedies.  Vikki Stella, whose fetus was fatally
impaired, explained to Congress, &quot;As a diabetic . . . this surgery was . .
.  safer for me than induced labor or a c-section, since I don't heal as well as
other people.&quot;  Because the surgery preserved her fertility, she was able
to bear another child.  An arbitrary ban on one surgical technique is senseless
and dangerous: its only consequence would be to channel women from safer to
riskier abortion procedures.    </P>
<P>Legislators should not regulate medicine in a way that will undermine the
safety of patients.  Decisions about the best surgical techniques for abortion
are best left in the hands of doctors, patients, and their families.</P>
<P>Nearly 90 percent of all abortions in this country occur within the first 12
weeks of pregnancy.  Instead of banning procedures that protect those women who
do need abortions later in pregnancy, we should work to ensure that women
seeking abortions can get them quickly without being delayed by legal or
financial barriers.   </P>
<P>In 1992 the United States Supreme Court reaffirmed the constitutional right
to abortion; anti-choice groups merely stepped up their attacks in response. 
Their latest tactic is the attempt to ban specific abortion procedures.  I urge
you to oppose all bans on &quot;partial-birth abortions,&quot; &quot;D&amp;X 
abortions,&quot; or any other safe abortion procedure.  Please don't turn back
the clock to the days of illegal, back-alley abortions by punishing doctors who
help women end their pregnancies safely.</P>
<P>Sincerely,</P>
<P>[Your name and address]</P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P>    
</P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER></BLOCKQUOTE></BODY></HTML>
