<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU in Congress: &quot;Partial-Birth Abortions&quot;: Criminalizing a
Necessary Medical Procedure</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/graphics/repro.gif"></P>
<P>ACLU ANSWERS</P>
<H2>&quot;Partial-Birth Abortions&quot;:  Criminalizing a Necessary Medical
Procedure</H2>
<P>January 1996</P>
<H3>BACKGROUND </H3>
<P>Since 1995, the ACLU and its pro-choice allies have fought a pitched battle
against congressional attempts to ban a particular abortion procedure. 
Anti-choice forces targeted so-called &quot;partial-birth abortions&quot; -- a
term unknown to the medical community and invented solely as a propaganda ploy
to provoke legislators and the public.  </P>
<P>The abortion procedure they appear to be referring to is known as &quot;dilation
and extraction&quot; (D&amp;X) or &quot;intact dilation and evacuation&quot;

(IDE).  Doctors perform a D&amp;X abortion when it is the safest and least
traumatic option for the patient.  In some instances, doctors recommend D&amp;X
as a lifesaving operation because of grave pregnancy complications.   Other
times, D&amp;X offers women the best chance of preserving their health,
including their future fertility.</P>
<P><I><B>Federal Efforts to Ban the Procedure</B></I></P>
<P>During the 104th Congress, anti-choice forces waged a major effort to pass
the &quot;Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 1995.&quot; The bill, which
represented Congress's first attempt ever to ban a particular medical procedure,
would have outlawed the abortion method and criminalized doctors who performed
it. </P>
<P>Representative Charles Canady (R-FL) sponsored the bill in the House and
Senator Robert Smith (R-NH) sponsored the Senate version.  Both houses of
Congress passed the bill, but President Clinton vetoed the legislation in April
1996.  Anti-choice forces spent the remainder of the term trying to override the
veto.  In the closing days of the 104th Congress, proponents of the ban garnered
the necessary two-thirds vote in the House, but the Senate failed to override by
a slim 57-to-41 margin.</P>
<P>In his veto message, the President said that he would sign the bill if it
were amended to add an exception for &quot;serious health consequences.&quot; 
Some members of Congress who opposed the measure also called for such an
exception.  Despite this focus on the lack of a health exception, the bill had a
number of other constitutional flaws.  It failed to provide an adequate life
exception, applied to both non-viable and viable fetuses, and was worded so
vaguely as to cover a broad range of other procedures.</P>
<P>The ban's supporters will try again to win its passage in the current 105th
Congress.  They have introduced S. 6 (&quot;The Partial Abortion Act of 1997&quot;),
which is very similar to the ban passed by the 104th Congress.  And some members
who previously opposed the ban have signaled an interest in pursuing a
compromise.</P>
<P><I><B>State Efforts to Ban the Procedure</B></I></P>
<P>While the federal debate raged over the &quot;Partial-Birth Abortion Ban
Act,&quot; states saw significant activity in this area as well.  Like the
federal bill, most of the state legislative proposals in 1996 sought to
criminalize the procedure.  Moreover, they had narrow life exceptions, made no
exception for health, applied to both viable and non-viable fetuses, and were
vaguely worded.</P>
<P>Overall, 17 states in recent years had proposals introduced in their
legislatures.  Three states -- Michigan, Ohio, and Utah -- enacted measures
criminalizing D&amp;X abortions.  Pro-choice groups succeeded in blocking bills
in the remaining 14 states, including: California, Georgia, Illinois, Kentucky,
Maryland, Minnesota, Mississippi, Missouri, New Jersey, New York, North
Carolina, South Carolina, Virginia, and Washington.  </P>
<P>Already, during the first weeks of the 1997 legislative sessions, &quot;partial-birth
abortion&quot; bans are under consideration in at least twenty states.</P>
<H3>TALKING POINTS</H3>
<P>Banning D&amp;X abortions would jeopardize the health and lives of women by
denying them a safe and necessary medical procedure.   Anti-choice forces have
attempted to distort D&amp;X by employing the most graphic images and terms. 
But surgery, almost by definition, is unpleasant and difficult to describe. 
</P>
<P>What is important is that D&amp;X is often the safest option available to
women undergoing second- or third-trimester abortions.</P>
<P>According to doctors who perform or have observed the procedure, D&amp;X
carries fewer health risks than alternative procedures.  D&amp;X is also less
physically stressful and less toxic than other alternative methods.  In
addition, D&amp;X is the best procedure in some circumstances for preserving a
woman's ability to bear children in the future.</P>
<P>Legislators should not regulate medicine in a way that undermines the safety
of patients.  Lawmakers are not trained to make medical decisions and should not
intrude into the practice of medicine.  They should leave decisions about the
best surgical techniques for abortion in the hands of doctors, patients, and
their families.</P>
<H3>ACLU POSITION</H3>
<P>The ACLU opposes attempts to ban so-called &quot;partial-birth abortions&quot;
as an unconstitutional threat to the lives and health of women.  As the Supreme
Court has consistently recognized, a woman seeking the abortion of a non-viable
fetus has the right to choose the safest option available.  The state cannot ask
a woman to compromise her health or life by denying her a specific medical
procedure.  Similarly, a woman seeking a post-viability abortion in order to
save her life or preserve her health must be allowed to choose the safest
available medical procedure.  </P>
<H3>FACTS &amp; QUOTES</H3>
<H4>1. Individual Women Need This Procedure</H4>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;Nineteen weeks into my pregnancy, an ultrasound indicated that there
was something wrong with our baby.... Our little baby had a very advanced,
textbook case of hydrocephalus.... My doctors, some of the best in the country,
recommended the [D&amp;X] procedure.... Because the trauma to my body was
minimized by this procedure, I was able to become pregnant again.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>(Mary-Dorothy Line, &quot;A Family Confronts a Late-Term Abortion,&quot;
op-ed in<I> The Times Union</I>, 5/20/96.  The author is a registered
Republican and a practicing Catholic who joined President Clinton when he vetoed
the bill banning so-called &quot;partial-birth abortions.&quot;)</P>
<H4>2. Bans Endanger Women's Health and Safety</H4>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;It is unconscionable for Congress to force a physician to
potentially jeopardize a patient's health and ignore his or her best medical
judgment.  A woman in tragic circumstances should have the right to make her own
decision, in consultation with her physician -- not her legislator.&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>(Allan Rosenfield, M.D., &quot;Congress Plays Doctor,&quot; op-ed in <I>The
New York Times</I>, 4/1/96.  The author is the Dean of the Columbia School of
Public Health.)</P>
<H4>3. Keep Government Out of the Operating Room</H4>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;The college finds it very disturbing that Congress would take any
action that would supersede the medical judgment of trained physicians and
criminalize medical procedures that may be necessary to save the life of a
woman.&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>(Ralph W. Hale, M.D., Executive Director of The American College of
Obstetricians and Gynecologists, in a November 1995 letter to Senator Bob Dole.)</P>
<H4>4. Abortions After the First Trimester Are Not Common</H4>
<P><I>Nearly 90 percent of all abortions in the United States occur within the
first trimester (12 weeks) of pregnancy.  Of all abortions in this country, 99
percent occur within the first 20 weeks.  Only 6/100ths of one percent take
place past 24 weeks, meaning that third-trimester abortions are extremely rare. 
There are approximately 600 or fewer third-trimester abortions performed by any
method in the United States annually.</I></P>
<P>(The Alan Guttmacher Institute, &quot;When Do Abortions Take Place,&quot;
9/25/96.)</P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P>    
</P>
