<br>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=100%><br>
<p>Brief Of Respondents Warner Jackson Et Al.
</p>

<p>Statement Of The Issues
</p>


<p>	In this brief, the Jackson Respondents address the two issues that they raised in their complaint filed in the Dane County Circuit Court:
</p>
<p>I.	Does the Milwaukee Parental Choice Program, as expanded by the 1995-96 Budget Act (&quot;the Amended Choice Program&quot;), violate Article I, sec. 18, of the Wisconsin Constitution by providing state funds to support religious education?
</p>
<p>II.	Does the use of state funds to support religious schools under the Amended Choice Program violate the Establishment Clause of the First Amendment to the United States Constitution?
</p>
<p>In addition, the Respondents address the following issue that the Court has asked the parties to discuss:
</p>
<p>III.	Does the Amended Choice Program violate Article X of the Wisconsin Constitution by establishing a competing system of publicly funded schools whose educational program includes sectarian instruction?
</p>

<h3> 	INTRODUCTION
</h3>
<p>	&quot;...nor shall any money be drawn from the treasury for the benefit of religious societies, or religious or theological seminaries.&quot;  Wis. Const. Article I, sec. 18.
</p>
<p>	With this declaration, the framers of the Wisconsin Constitution and the people of this state who ratified it sought to ensure that public funds would not be used to support religious education.  This fundamental constitutional principle reflects not a hostility to religion or religious education, but a recognition that religious liberty is threatened when the government pays for religious activities.  This same elemental principle is also reflected in the Establishment Clause of the First Amendment to the United States Constitution.
</p>
<p>	The principal issue in this case is whether the dramatically expanded Milwaukee Parental Choice Program violates Article I, sec. 18, and the First Amendment by providing state funds directly to religious schools.  The new Program effectively transfers taxpayer dollars directly from the state to Protestant, Jewish, Catholic and Muslim schools to support not just secular education but the full range of religious activities at the schools.
</p>
<p>	The Jackson Respondents are concerned citizens, parents and members of the clergy from diverse religious and ethnic backgrounds.  Many of them have children in the Milwaukee public schools.  All are taxpayers in the State of Wisconsin.  They oppose the state's use of public funds, derived in part from their taxes, to pay for religious school tuition and for education that promotes particular religious beliefs.
</p>
<p>	The Court now has received four briefs supporting the Amended Choice Program -- one from the Governor's special counsel on behalf of the State of Wisconsin, one from the Attorney General, and one each from intervenors Parents for School Choice and Marquelle Miller.  Although they differ in emphasis, the briefs share a number of themes:
</p>
<p>     -	The defenders of the Choice Program insist that the expanded Choice Program does not provide direct payments to religious schools.  That argument may charitably be described as wishful thinking.  Under the statute, parents must &quot;restrictively endorse the [Choice Program] check for the use of the private school.&quot;   Sec. 119.23(4), Stats.  When a religious school deposits the Choice Program checks that parents have endorsed for its use, funds will be transferred directly from the state treasury to the school's bank account.  As one of the amicus briefs has succinctly observed, &quot;Any suggestion that this benefit is not provided directly to religious institutions requires a deliberate suspension of disbelief.&quot; 
</p>
<p>     -	 The Program's supporters also insist that any benefits to religious schools will be attenuated and incidental.  &quot;[P]arents and families,&quot; they say, are the &quot;real beneficiaries&quot; of the Program.  Brief of Additional Parties Marquelle Miller et al. (&quot;Miller Intervenors' Brief&quot;), p. 43.  There is no question, of course, that parents and children receive a benefit under the Choice Program.  That does not mean, however, that the schools do not receive very real and substantial benefits.  If the Amended Choice Program is implemented, the participating religious schools likely will receive millions of dollars in state funds.  That is not an &quot;attenuated&quot; or &quot;incidental&quot; benefit by any stretch of the imagination.
</p>
<p>	All of the Choice Program supporters' briefs, moreover, ignore a key fact that bears directly on the question of whether participating schools receive only an &quot;incidental&quot; benefit from the Amended Choice Program.  State aid payments to participating schools under the Program are not limited to the actual tuition charged by the schools.  A majority of participating religious schools will receive more from the state than they would from the parents if the parents paid the tuition from their own funds.  See Agreed Upon Statement of Facts,  30.  Even if tuition payments could be characterized as a mere incidental benefit to a school, payments in excess of tuition indisputably provide a direct and substantial benefit to the schools and, in the case of religious schools, to the religious organizations that sponsor them.
</p>
<p>     -	The Choice proponents draw on various elements of several U.S. Supreme Court decisions to buttress their claim that the Program does not violate the Establishment Clause.  Yet not a single one of the cases on which they rely involved a program that remotely resembles the Choice Program.  At most, the state and the intervenors can offer only their prediction that the U.S. Supreme Court would overrule Committee for Public Education &amp; Religious Liberty v. Nyquist, 413 U.S. 756 (1973), and uphold the Choice Program.  Yet the Court has never questioned its holding in Nyquist and relied on it quite recently in Board of Education of Kiryas Joel Village Sch. Dist. v. Grumet, 114 S.Ct. 2481, 2487 (1994).
</p>
<p>	This case is not about the quality of education provided by the Milwaukee Public Schools or whether the Choice Program is good public policy.  Nor is it about the value of religious education.  Rather, the dispositive issue is whether state funds can be used to pay for education at religious schools.  Because the religion clauses of both the state and federal constitutions and the uniformity clause of the state constitution prohibit this massive funding of religious education, this Court should declare the Amended Choice Program unconstitutional.
</p>
<h3> 	FACTS
</h3>
<p>	For the reasons discussed in the accompanying Motion to Strike and in accordance with the Court's August 17, 1995 order directing the parties to prepare an Agreed Upon Statement of Facts, the Respondents' discussion of the facts is limited to those facts included in the Agreed Upon Statement of Facts filed with the Court and facts as to which the Court may take judicial notice.
</p>
<p>The Original Choice Program.  In the spring of 1990, the Wisconsin Legislature created the Milwaukee Parental Choice Program (the &quot;Choice Program&quot;), which is codified at section 119.23, Stats.  The Original Choice Program provided that &quot;any pupil in grades kindergarten to 12 who resides within the city [of Milwaukee] may attend, at no charge, any nonsectarian private school located in the city,&quot; as long as certain requirements were met.  See Sec. 119.23(2)(a), Stats. (1993-94) (emphasis added).
</p>
<p>	From 1990 to 1994, the Choice Program was open to 1% of the membership of the Milwaukee Public School district.  For the 1994-95 school year, that percentage was raised to 1.5% -- approximately 1,460 students.  See Sec. 119.23(2)(b)1., Stats. (1993-94); Agreed Upon Statement of Facts,  8.  To take part in the program, a student's family income cannot exceed 1.75 times the federal poverty level.  See Sec. 119.23(2)(a)1., Stats.  As originally enacted, no more than 49% of a private school's total enrollment could consist of pupils attending under the Choice Program.  See Sec. 119.23(2)(b)2., Stats. (1989-90).  That percentage was increased to 65 percent by 1993 Wis. Act 16, sec. 2300.
</p>
<p>	Under the Original Choice Program, the Superintendent paid participating private schools an amount equal to the per-pupil student aid provided to the Milwaukee public schools.  See Sec. 119.23(4), Stats. (1993-94).  For the 1994-95 school year, that amount was approximately $3,209.  See Agreed Upon Statement of Facts,  10.   The moneys disbursed under the Choice Program are appropriated from general purpose revenues, see secs. 20.005(3)(fu) and 119.23(4), Stats., which consist primarily of general taxes collected by the state.  See sec. 20.001, Stats.
</p>
<p>The Amended Choice Program.  The 1995-96 Budget Act, 1995 Wis. Act 27, which Governor Thompson signed into law July 26, 1995, substantially expanded the Choice Program.  Most significantly, the Act eliminated the prohibition on participation by religious schools in the Choice Program:
</p>
<p>		SECTION 4002.  119.23(2)(a)(intro.), 2. and 3. of the statutes are amended to read:
</p>
<p>		119.23(2)(a)(intro.) Subject to par. (b), beginning in the 1990-91 school year, any pupil in grades kindergarten to 12 who resides within the city may attend, at no charge, any nonsectarian private school located in the city if all of the following apply: ...
</p>
<p>1995 Wis. Act 27, sec. 4002, amending sec. 119.23(2)(a), Stats.
</p>
<p>	In addition, the Budget Act also enlarged the number of students who can participate in the Choice Program.  As many as 7% of the Milwaukee school district's pupil population would have been able to participate in the Program during the 1995-96 school year, and up to 15 percent of the student population will be eligible beginning in 1996-97.  See id., sec. 4003, repealing and recreating sec. 119.23(2)(b), Stats.  Based on the 1995-96 Milwaukee School District estimated pupil population of 98,370 students (see Agreed Upon Statement of Facts,  12), nearly 7,000 students could have participated in the expanded Choice Program in the 1995-96 school year, with up to 15,000 students potentially taking part in later years.  The Act also repealed the restriction in the Original Program limiting a private school's enrollment to 65 percent Choice Program students.  See 1995 Wis. Act 27, sec. 4003.
</p>
<p>	The Budget Act amended the method by which the State Superintendent pays tuition to private schools participating in the Choice Program.  Rather than making the check payable to the school as under the Original Program, the Superintendent will now make checks payable to the pupil's parent or guardian.  The checks are sent not to the parents, however, but directly to the private school.  The parents then must &quot;restrictively endorse the check for the use of the private school&quot;:
</p>
<p>		SECTION 4006m.  119.23(4) of the statutes is amended to read:
</p>
<p>		119.23 (4) Upon receipt from the pupil's parent or guardian of proof of the pupil's enrollment in the private school, the state superintendent shall pay to the private school parent or guardian, from the appropriation under s. 20.255 (2) (fu), an amount equal to the total amount to which the school district is entitled under s. 121.08 divided by the school district membership, or an amount equal to the private school's operating and debt service cost per pupil that is related to educational programming, as determined by the department, whichever is less.  The state superintendent shall pay 25% of the total amount in September, 25% in November, 25% in February and 25% in May.  The department shall send the check to the private school.  The parent or guardian shall restrictively endorse the check for the use of the private school.
</p>
<p>1995 Wis. Act 27, sec. 4006m, amending sec. 119.23(4), Stats.
</p>
<p>	There are no limitations on how private schools, including religious schools, may use the funds they receive under the Choice Program.  The funds may be used to support all of the educational functions of the school, including religious education, and they may be used to maintain, repair or construct facilities, including facilities used for religious purposes.  See Agreed Upon Statement of Facts,  28.  As under the Original program, funds paid to schools under the Amended Choice Program are drawn from general purpose revenues.  See sec. 119.23(4), Stats., as amended by 1995 Wis. Act 27, sec. 4006m.
</p>
<p>	The amount of money a school will receive under the Amended Choice Program is not predetermined.  Participating schools will receive the lesser of the amount of per-pupil state aid to the Milwaukee public schools under sec. 121.08, Stats., or &quot;an amount equal to the private school's operating and debt service cost per pupil that is related to educational programming, as determined by the department.&quot;  Id.  The per-pupil state aid provided to MPS under sec. 121.08 for the 1995-96 school year is approximately $3,667.  See Agreed Upon Statement of Facts,  29.
</p>
<p>	Under the Amended Choice Program, participating schools must allow students to opt-out of &quot;religious activities.&quot;  The amended statute provides that:
</p>
<p>	A private school may not require a pupil attending the private school under this section to participate in any religious activity if the pupil's parent or guardian submits to the pupil's teacher or the private school's principal a written request that the pupil be exempt from such activities.
</p>
<p>Sec. 119.23(7)(c), Stats., created by 1995 Act 27, sec. 4008.  Students attending a religious school under the Choice Program who have not opted-out may participate, at state expense, in the full-range of religious activities offered by the school.
</p>
<p>The Participating Schools.  There are 122 private schools in the city of Milwaukee that would have been eligible to participate in the Amended Choice Program during the 1995-96 school year.  See Agreed Upon Statement of Facts,  24.  Of those, 89 are sectarian and 33 are nonsectarian.  Id.,  25.  Approximately 84 percent of the pupils who attended private schools during the 1994-95 school year attended religious schools.  Id.,  26.
</p>
<p>	The parties have provided the Court, as part of the Agreed Upon Statement of Facts, the mission statements and other written materials prepared by many of the religious schools that notified the Superintendent of Public Instruction of their intent to participate in the Amended Choice Program during the 1995-96 school year.  Id.,  27, Exhibit E.  Those materials make clear that religion is a pervasive part of each student's educational experience at these schools.  The participating schools announce forthrightly that their mission is religious and that religious doctrine will be instilled in their students:
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;Oklahoma Avenue Lutheran School is an integral part of the ministry of Oklahoma Avenue Lutheran Church.&quot;  Exhibit E to Agreed Upon Statement of Facts, p. 535.
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;The mission of St. Leo and St. Rose Catholic schools is to share in the parish evangelization effort through providing quality Catholic education in grades pre-kindergarten through eight.&quot;  Id. at 720.
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;The continuing purpose of St. Matthew Ev. Lutheran Church and School is to go and tell the pure Gospel of Jesus Christ for the conversion of unbelievers and the strengthening of believers in faith and Christian living.&quot;  Id. at 750.
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;St. Paul's Lutheran School exists to:
		-assist parents in training children in God's ways,
		-teach God's Word to children, and
		-make disciples of children.&quot;  Id. at 790.
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;We believe our school exists to carry out the Savior's command to `go and make disciples&quot; (Matthew 28:19).  Consequently, our school's primary reason for existence is to be a tool for bringing young souls to faith in Jesus....&quot;  Id. at 275 (Fairview Lutheran School).
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;A prospective student whose parents are not members of a church will be considered as mission prospects.  Christ Lutheran Church/School considers it a responsibility to teach the Word of God to those who have not heard this blessed Word.&quot;  Id. at 198.
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;The objectives of the [Clara Muhammad School] are:
	1.	To foster within each student the principle of submissions to the will of Allah (God) as the essential element in achieving human excellence.&quot; Id. at 227.
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;Holy Redeemer Christian Academy is an integral part of the ministry of Holy Redeemer Church of God in Christ.&quot;  Id. at 399.
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;As a Catholic high school, [Divine Savior Holy Angels High School] is dedicated to promoting the beliefs and traditions of the Catholic Church.&quot;  Id. at 234.
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;The Yeshiva Elementary School of Milwaukee was initiated by members of the Orthodox Jewish Community with the following objectives as their goals:  
</p>
<p>	To teach elementary school children Torah and Mitzvos in accordance with the ideals and aspirations of Torah as espoused by the G'Dolei Yisroel in order to provide the excellence in Orthodox Jewish Education which will prepare our children to attend the finest seminaries, Yeshivas and institutions of Jewish higher learning.&quot;  Id. at 966.
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;The function of St. Bernadette Day School is to provide for Christian individuals opportunities for growth in faith, for formation, for development.&quot;  Id. at 614.
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;First and foremost Garden Homes Lutheran Church conducts and maintains a Christian elementary school to assist Christian parents in the training and nurturing of their children in the Word of God.&quot;  Id. at 316.
</p>
<p>	As the schools' literature emphasizes, one of the primary means by which these schools accomplish their religious missions is by integrating the religious and secular aspects of the schools' educational programs.
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;In keeping with the purpose of our school, our curriculum is taught in the setting of God's Word.  Religion is not only taught as a subject, but our teachers have been trained to integrate God's Word across the curriculum. ...  Our curriculum offerings place Christ as the focal point for all study.&quot;  Id. at 414, 417 (The Lutheran Chapel of The Cross Church and School).
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;Each class is taught by a dedicated Christian teacher who believes in Biblical concepts of salvation.  Teachers strive to build into the curriculum a philosophy of Christian living that includes moral and spiritual values.&quot;  Id. at 471 (Milwaukee Junior Academy (Seventh-day Adventist)).
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;Emmaus Lutheran Church and School is a Christian institution, NOT a private school.  The Holy Gospel is the center of our curriculum.&quot;  Id. at 259.
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;[E]verything that confronts the child in the educational program offered by St. Matthew Ev. Lutheran School will be presented in the light of His inspired, inerrant word of truth and power.&quot;  Id. at 750.
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;The children will be thoroughly trained in the fundamental subject areas needed for a successful life here on this earth.  It is our aim that these subjects be taught in accordance to Scripture and that all things related to the children's educational life be permeated with God's Word.&quot;  Id. at 792 (St. Paul's Lutheran School).
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;Christian teachings are fostered in all classes, but especially in the religion program.&quot;  Id. at 106 (All Saints Catholic Elementary School).
</p>
<p>   *	At St. Veronica Catholic Elementary School, &quot;Christian-Centered Education&quot; means &quot;Integrating Catholic faith in all academic areas.&quot;  Id. at 841.
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;The students of St. Alexander's are not only taught the basic truths of their religion; they are also exposed to the Christian attitudes and ideologies which pervade their school environment.&quot;  Id. at 553.
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;The message of Jesus is taught in religion classes and other curricular areas. ... Because of the nature of a Catholic school, religion is taught daily as part of the curriculum.  Catholic values are also incorporated into all other aspects of the curriculum.&quot;  Id. at 614, 617 (St. Bernadette School).  
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;The Bible forms the core and center upon which all instruction is based.  Each day is opened with a devotion followed by instruction in Christian doctrine and Bible study.  Our school gives due instruction in all branches of academics, which are required by the State of Wisconsin.  All subjects are taught by a Christian teacher in the light of God's Word, emphasizing God's love for all men through Jesus.&quot;  Id. at 131 (Bethlehem Lutheran School).
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;All subject areas in our school are Christ-centered.&quot;  Id. at 323 (Gospel Lutheran School).
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;We Believe...that the Christian School, where every subject is taught from the Christian point of view, related to the teachings of Christianity and permeated with the spirit of Christianity, can be more successful in leading children to a vital Christian life than any other agency, except the Christian home.&quot;  Id. at 534 (Oklahoma Avenue Lutheran School).
</p>
<p>   *	&quot;We teach all the traditional subjects, but we teach them differently--from a Christian perspective.&quot;  Id. at 526 (Mount Olive Lutheran School).
</p>
<p>	As noted above, the Amended Choice Program pays participating schools the lesser of the schools' per-pupil costs or the amount of the per-pupil state aid provided to MPS under sec. 121.08, Stats., which in the 1995-96 school year is approximately $3,667.  See Agreed Upon Statement of Facts,  29.  The tuition charged by a majority of the religious schools that have applied to participate in the Amended Choice Program, however, is less than either of those amounts.  See id.,  30.  As a result, a majority of the participating religious schools will receive more money from the state for each participating pupil than they charge in tuition.  
</p>
<p>	Holy Cross School, for example, charges tuition of $1,475, while its &quot;actual cost of education&quot; is $2,446 per student.  See id., Exhibit E, p. 388.  Emmaus Lutheran School charges $1,080 tuition to church members and $1,350 nonmembers, though its annual expenditures exceed $2,000 per pupil.  Id. at 261.  Mother of Good Counsel School reports that its tuition ($1,370 for parish members, $1,940 for nonmembers) &quot;covers just half the cost of educating MGC students.&quot;  Id. at 489, 497.  Mount Olive Lutheran School states that the tuition charged even to non-members is &quot;substantially less than our per pupil cost.&quot;  Id. at 526.
</p>
<p>	Many religious schools depend on subsidies from their sponsoring churches to make up the difference between tuition and operating expenses.  Bethlehem Lutheran School, for example, reports that &quot;Bethlehem Lutheran Church subsidizes nearly 50% of the cost per student.&quot;  Id. at 130.  Mount Olive Lutheran School states that &quot;Mount Olive Congregation provides the major support since the focus of our school is Christian education.&quot;  Id. at 526.  St. Catherine School says that it &quot;is partially subsidized by the parish at large.&quot;  Id. at 663.   Because the Amended Choice Program pays schools more than what they charge in tuition, the Program relieves the churches that sponsor the schools of at least part of the cost of subsidizing the difference between tuition received and the actual cost of education.
</p>

<h3>	ARGUMENT
</h3>
<p>I.	THE AMENDED CHOICE PROGRAM VIOLATES ARTICLE I, SECTION 18, OF THE WISCONSIN CONSTITUTION.
</p>
<p>	Long before the United States Supreme Court held that the Establishment Clause of the First Amendment is binding on the states through the Fourteenth Amendment, this Court recognized that Article I, sec. 18, of the Wisconsin Constitution prohibits &quot;the drawing of any money from the state treasury for the benefit of any religious school.&quot;  State ex rel. Weiss v. District Bd., 76 Wis. 177, 215, 44 N.W. 967 (1890).  Even after the states were required to adhere to Establishment Clause dictates, this Court continued to apply Article I, sec. 18, independently and more strictly than its federal counterpart, particularly when public funding of religious education is at issue.  Indeed, this Court need not even reach the Establishment Clause issues in this case because Article I, sec. 18, of the Wisconsin Constitution provides an independent basis for deciding the case.
</p>
<p>	Two of section 18's four clauses are at issue here.   The &quot;benefits&quot; clause (&quot;nor shall any money be drawn from the treasury for the benefit of religious societies, or religious or theological seminaries&quot;) has been discussed extensively in the Choice supporters' briefs and will be discussed first here.  The &quot;compelled support&quot; clause (&quot;nor shall any person be compelled to attend, erect or support any place of worship, or to maintain any ministry, without consent&quot;), though not addressed in any of those briefs, provides an additional ground for concluding that the Amended Choice Program violates Article I, sec. 18, of the Wisconsin Constitution. 
</p>
<h4>		A.	The Amended Choice Program violates the benefits clause of Article I, sec. 18.
</h4>
<p>	As early as its 1890 decision in Weiss, this Court determined that the framers of the Wisconsin Constitution intended Article I, sec. 18, to establish a strict separation of church and state.  In Weiss, Roman Catholic parents objected to the reading of a Protestant Bible in the Edgerton public schools.  The Court said that the history of the Wisconsin Constitution requires that Article I, sec. 18, be construed to provide a particularly rigorous separation of church and state:  &quot;Wisconsin, as one of the later states admitted into the Union, having before it the experience of others, and probably in view of its heterogeneous population, ... probably furnished a more complete bar to any preference for, or discrimination against, any religious sect, organization, or society than any other state in the Union.&quot;  76 Wis. at 207-08.  
</p>
<p>	The Weiss Court held that religious instruction in a public school rendered the school a &quot;religious seminary&quot; as that term is used in Article I, sec. 18.  Id. at 215.   Because the school district received state funds to support the school, the Court concluded that Article I, sec. 18, was violated by the use of treasury funds to benefit that &quot;religious seminary.&quot;  Id. 
</p>
<p>	The first modern case to consider whether the use of public funds to benefit religious organizations violates the Wisconsin Constitution, State ex rel. Reynolds v. Nusbaum, 17 Wis. 2d 148, 115 N.W.2d 761 (1962), is also the Wisconsin case most similar to this action.  At issue in Reynolds was a statute that required school boards to provide private school students with free transportation to and from the nearest public school.  Fifteen years earlier, in Everson v. Board of Education, 330 U.S. 1 (1947), the U.S. Supreme Court had held that a New Jersey law permitting parental reimbursement for the cost of children's bus transportation to parochial schools did not violate the Establishment Clause of the First Amendment.  Citing its earlier decision in Weiss, the Court held that Art. I, sec. 18, mandates a more rigid separation of church and state than the First Amendment, especially when the expenditure of public funds is involved.  &quot;[W]e deem that the First amendment provision, which prohibits laws `respecting an establishment of religion,' lends itself to more flexibility of interpretation than the provision contained in the last clause of sec. 18, art. I of the Wisconsin constitution.&quot;  17 Wis. 2d at 165.
</p>
<p>	The Court's analysis of the benefits clause in Reynolds establishes the framework for analyzing the constitutionality of the Amended Choice Program.  The Court first held that elementary and secondary schools operated by religious organizations are &quot;religious seminaries&quot; within the meaning of the clause:
</p>
<p>		We construe &quot;religious societies&quot; to be synonymous with religious organizations, and, under the stipulated facts, practically all of the nonpublic schools, whose pupils are to be transported under the attacked act, are operated by religious organizations.  Furthermore, at the time of the adoption of our constitution in 1848, the word &quot;seminaries&quot; was synonymous with academies or schools. ...  Therefore, inasmuch as some religious instruction is given in all of the approximately 500 nonpublic schools operated by religious organizations or sectarian groups, ... these parochial schools constitute &quot;religious seminaries&quot; within the meaning of sec. 18, art. I, Wisconsin constitution.
</p>
<p>Id. at 156.  The Court next held that providing transportation to parochial school students is a benefit to the parochial schools themselves:
</p>
<p>	[I]t is fair to assume that a considerable number of pupils attending these schools will be afforded transportation under the new act if its validity is upheld.  Those parochial schools, which now pay part or all of the cost of transportation of their pupils out of their school funds, stand to benefit financially by the operation of the new act.  Others stand to gain through increased enrollment.  Such an increase of enrollment is a benefit to these parochial schools.
</p>
<p>Id. (emphasis added).
</p>
<p>	The Court concluded that these benefits to parochial schools are impermissible under Article I, sec. 18.  It did not matter, the Court said, that parochial school pupils were provided transportation only to the nearest public school.  Id. at 163.  Nor did it matter that the legislature's declared purpose was to promote the safety and welfare of the students.  &quot;It could also be argued with equal plausibility that a direct grant in aid of public funds to parochial schools promotes the general welfare of the pupils of such schools because it aids in their education.&quot;  Id. at 160.
</p>
<p>	The Court also rejected the argument that providing transportation to parochial school students was constitutional because it &quot;entails no more expenditure of public funds than would be required if these pupils were to attend public school.&quot;  Id. at 160.
</p>
<p> 	[T]his same argument would sustain the use of public funds to pay salaries of parochial school teachers or other direct operating expenses of such schools.  Considering the objective sought by the framers of our state constitution in including the provisions of sec 18, art. I, we are certain that the determination of whether religious schools receive a benefit from public funds is not dependent on whether the overall cost to the public treasury would be less or greater by reason of the operation of such schools than would be the case if all the pupils thereof were to attend public schools.
</p>
<p>Id. at 160 (emphasis added).  
</p>
<p>	Under the Amended Choice Program, public funds will go directly to religious schools.  While the check from the state is made payable to the parent, the Superintendent of Public Instruction must, by law, send the check to the school, and the parent must, by law, &quot;restrictively endorse the check for the use of the private school.&quot;  Sec. 119.23(4), Stats., as amended by 1995 Wis. Act 27, sec. 4006m.  Once received by the school, the money may be used for any purpose, including purposes specifically forbidden by Reynolds such as teachers salaries and operating expenses.  The school also may use state funds for capital improvements such as renovating or building offices, classrooms or chapels.  See Agreed Upon Statement of Facts,  28. 
</p>
<p>	The Choice proponents assert that the Amended Choice Program provides a direct benefit only to parents and that the benefits to the religious schools are only &quot;indirect and incidental.&quot;  See, e.g., Governor's Brief at 31.  State payment of private school tuition undoubtedly does provide a significant benefit to parents.  It does not follow, however, that those payments do not also provide a direct and substantial benefit to the schools.  As Reynolds illustrates, a state program that provides direct benefits to parents and students may also provide an impermissible benefit to schools as well.  When a program will provide millions of dollars to private schools, it is difficult to understand how that program can be said to provide only an &quot;indirect and incidental&quot; benefit to those schools. 
</p>
<p>	Furthermore, state payments to participating religious schools under the Amended Choice Program are not limited to the tuition actually charged by the schools.  The parties have stipulated that the tuition charged by a majority of the religious schools is less than the amount of state payment they would receive under the Amended Choice Program.  See Agreed Upon Statement of Facts,  30.  Most religious schools participating in the Choice Program will receive more from the state under the Program than they would receive from the students' parents if the parents paid tuition from their own funds.
<p>	
	The primary beneficiaries of state payments that exceed tuition are not the parents -- payment of the tuition alone would allow their children to receive a private school education.  Every dollar paid by the state to a participating school that exceeds the actual tuition charged by that school provides a direct and substantial benefit to the school and, in the case of a religious school,  to the religious organization that sponsors it.  Even if it were possible to characterize the tuition portion of state aid as only an &quot;indirect and incidental&quot; benefit to a school, it is impossible to characterize payments in excess of tuition as anything but a direct and substantial benefit to the school.
</p>
<p>	The Choice supporters also argue that state funds will flow to religious schools only as a result of parents' decision to send their children to those schools.  See Governor's Brief at 32.  But that was also the case in Reynolds -- the religious schools there benefited from taxpayer-funded busing only as a result of parents' decisions to send their children to religious schools.  That fact had no bearing on the Court's decision that the busing program provided an impermissible benefit to the schools under Article I, sec. 18.
</p>
<p>	That rationale, moreover, would justify any state aid program to religious organizations that based the amount of aid on the number of the organization's members.  Under such a program, state aid would flow to the organization only as a result of individuals' choices to join the organization.  Yet surely the Choice proponents do not contend that the state may make per-capita grants to churches simply because funds would be provided to the churches only as a result of such individual choices.
</p>
<p>	The Governor also contends that another parental choice is interposed between the state and religious schools -- &quot;the school gets nothing,&quot; he argues, &quot;until the parent decides to endorse the check.&quot;  Governor's Brief at 21, 32.  The implication is that the parent is free to decide whether to endorse the check to the school or to use the funds for other purposes.  The Amended Choice Program gives parents no such choice.  By law, the parent &quot;shall restrictively endorse the check for the use of the private school.&quot;  Sec. 119.23(4), Stats., as amended by 1995 Wis. Act 27, sec. 4006m (emphasis added).
</p>
<p>	The fact that state funds will flow to religious schools only because parents have chosen to send their children to those schools is wholly irrelevant under Article I, sec. 18.  Under the Amended Choice Program, state treasury funds will be used to benefit religious schools in a manner that cannot reasonably be described as merely incidental.  For that reason, the Amended Choice Program violates the benefits clause of Article I, sec. 18, of the Wisconsin Constitution.
</p>
<h4>	B.	The Amended Choice Program is unconstitutional under this Court's long line of post-Reynolds cases.
</h4>
<p>	Reynolds was not this Court's last word on the benefits clause of Article I, sec. 18.  Nothing in those later cases undermines Reynolds' validity, however, or provides any basis for upholding the Amended Choice Program.
</p>
<p>	In State ex rel. Warren v. Reuter, 44 Wis. 2d 201, 170 N.W.2d 790 (1969), the Court upheld a state appropriation to the Marquette School of Medicine.  The Court found that the medical school was an independent nonsectarian institution that was no longer under the control of Marquette University.  Id. at 224-25.  The Court rejected the argument that the appropriation nevertheless violated Article I, sec. 18, because Marquette University, a Catholic institution, derived some incidental benefits through its joint programs with the medical school.  Reynolds did not prohibit such incidental benefits to religious schools, the Court said -- it prohibited legislation whose primary effect is the advancement of religion.  Id. at 226-27.  The Court contrasted the case with the private school transportation aid at issue in Reynolds, where &quot;the primary effect was a benefit to private schools....&quot;  Id. at 227.
</p>
<p>	Three years later, the Court struck down a law providing state funds to pay tuition at the Marquette University dental school.  State ex rel. Warren v. Nusbaum, 55 Wis. 2d 316, 198 N.W.2d 650 (1972) (&quot;Nusbaum I&quot;).  The Court held that the state aid violated the federal Establishment Clause because there was a possibility that the funds would be used for the university's operating costs other than those of the dental school, and that any program that violated the Establishment Clause necessarily violated Article I, sec. 18, as well.  Id. at 325, 332-33.  The Court added in dictum that a &quot;proper contract&quot; which truly restricted the use of state funds to secular dental education would not violate the benefits clause because the dental school was a wholly secular unit of the university and the university as a whole would derive only an incidental benefit from such a contract.  Id. at 333-35.
</p>
<p>	The Amended Choice Program presents an even more compelling violation of Article I, sec. 18, than the funding at issue in Nusbaum I.  The state funding in Nusbaum I was directed at a purely secular program within a religious institution, but was unconstitutional nevertheless because the funds might be used for religious purposes.  Under the Choice Program, in contrast, there is not even an attempt to direct state funds towards secular education.  To the contrary, it is undisputed that state funds will be used for religious as well as secular education.  Indeed, any attempt to limit Choice Program funds to secular education would effectively bar virtually all parochial schools from participating in the Program because their secular and religious programs are inextricably intertwined. 
</p>
<p>	In State ex rel. Warren v. Nusbaum, 64 Wis. 2d 314, 219 N.W.2d 577 (1974) (&quot;Nusbaum II&quot;), the Court upheld the constitutionality of a law that required school districts to contract with private special educational institutions to provide services to children with exceptional needs if those services were not available from public agencies.  Under that law, the governing board, faculty, student body and teachings of the private special education service could not be &quot;chosen or determined by any religious organization or for any sectarian purpose.&quot;  Id. at 321.  Given that limitation, the Court held that the primary effect of the legislation was not to benefit religious organizations.  Id. at 325-26.
</p>
<p>	The Governor contends the Amended Choice Program &quot;is even more clearly constitutional than the neutral contract approved in Nusbaum II, which involved direct aid to religious organizations.&quot;  Governor's Brief at 55.  But the Court in Nusbaum II upheld the contracts precisely because they did not involve aid to religious education.  64 Wis. 2d at 325-26.  It emphasized that under the challenged statute, &quot;the legislature has gone to great lengths to insure that the inculcation of religious tenets shall not take place.&quot;  Id. at 325.  The Court pointed out that any contract with an entity whose governing board or faculty was controlled by a religious organization would be &quot;challengeable in a later action under the statute and the constitutional amendments.&quot;  Id. at 326.  Nothing in the Amended Choice Program, in contrast, limits &quot;the inculcation of religious tenets&quot; by participating schools or excludes schools whose governing boards and faculties are &quot;chosen or determined by any religious organization or for any sectarian purpose.&quot;
</p>
<p>	The Choice supporters contend that the &quot;opt-out&quot; provision of the amended Choice Program minimizes the Program's benefit to religion.  The opt-out provision does not cure this infirmity; if anything, it makes it worse.  Newly enacted sec. 119.23(7)(c), Stats., provides that &quot;[a] private school may not require a pupil attending the private school under this section to participate in any religious activity if the pupil's parent or guardian submits ... a written request that the pupil be exempt from such activities.&quot;  The opt-out provision serves only to emphasize that students attending religious schools under the Choice Program who have not opted out of religious activities may participate in the full range of religious activities at their schools, with their tuition paid by the state. 
</p>
<p>	Nusbaum II provides a test for determining when state aid has the unconstitutional primary effect of benefitting religion for purposes of the benefits clause of Article I, sec. 18.  It is a test that none of the Choice proponents acknowledge or apply to the facts of this case:
</p>
<p>		Aid may normally be thought of as having the primary effect of advancing religion when it flows to an institution in which religion is so pervasive that a substantial portion of its functions are subsumed in the religious mission or when it funds a specifically religious activity in an otherwise substantially secular setting.
</p>
<p>Id. at 325.  In a later decision, the Court explained why elementary and secondary schools operated by religious organizations meet that test:
</p>
<p>		In contrast to the ... line of decisions involving colleges and universities, the [United States Supreme] Court has generally held that elementary and secondary schools are pervasively sectarian.  The basis of this distinction is that the very purpose of many elementary and secondary schools is to provide an integrated secular and religious education.  The schools are often devoted to the inculcation of religious values.
</p>
<p>State ex rel. Wisconsin Health Facilities Authority v. Lindner, 91 Wis. 2d 145, 156-57, 280 N.W.2d 773 (1979) (citations omitted).
</p>
<p>	The religious schools that have applied to participate in the Choice Program are &quot;institution[s] in which religion is so pervasive that a substantial portion of [their] functions are subsumed in the religious mission.&quot;  Nusbaum II, 64 Wis. 2d at 324.  Their mission statements and other literature quoted above (see supra, pp. 9-12) and reproduced in Exhibit E to the Agreed Upon Statement of Facts demonstrate beyond question that the sectarian schools participating in the Choice Program are not only religious in name, but are also pervasively religious in practice.
</p>
<p>	It is entirely appropriate, of course, for religious teachings to permeate the curriculum and activities of schools operated by religious organizations.  What is neither appropriate nor constitutional, however, is for the State of Wisconsin to provide funding for that religious education.
</p>
<h4>		C.	The Court's decision in King v. Village of Waunakee does not preclude an independent analysis of Article I, sec. 18.
</h4>
<p>	All of the Choice proponents contend that the Court's decision King v. Village of Waunakee, 185 Wis. 2d 25, 517 N.W.2d 671 (1994), marked the demise of any independent interpretation of Article I, sec. 18, by this Court.  Nothing in that case, however, altered the well-established analysis that the Court has applied to public funding issues under the benefits clause.
</p>
<p>	The issue in King was the constitutionality of a nativity scene owned by the village of Waunakee that the village displayed in a park during the holiday season.  The display cost the village about $500 a year to maintain and operate.  In a 5-2 decision, the Court held that the display did not violate the Establishment Clause or Article I, sec. 18.
</p>
<p>	The majority decision did not address the benefits clause other than to observe summarily that no money was drawn from the treasury for the benefit of any religious societies.  185 Wis. 2d at 53.  That conclusion is explained by the fact that the display was owned by the village, rather than by any religious organization.  The funds expended by the village did not relieve any religious organization of the expense of maintaining or operating the display.  The Court also characterized the village's $500 annual expenditure as de minimus.  Id. at 56.
</p>
<p>	The Choice Program, in contrast, will provide public funds to private schools operated by religious organizations.  The tens of millions of public dollars that will flow to religious schools under the Choice Program in the coming years are not de minimus by even the most generous standard.
</p>
<p>	The Choice proponents note that the Court said in King that it agreed with the court of appeals' statement that Wisconsin courts interpret Article I, sec. 18, &quot;in light of United States Supreme Court cases interpreting the Establishment Clause&quot; and that this Court had not &quot;elaborated&quot; on the statement in Reynolds that the Establishment Clause &quot;lends itself to more flexibility of interpretation&quot; than the religious benefit clause of the Wisconsin Constitution.  Id. at 55.  While this Court may not have &quot;elaborated&quot; on that statement, it twice has stated, in cases decided after Reynolds, that &quot;the additional language `nor shall any monies be drawn from the treasury for the benefit of religious societies' renders the clause more prohibitive than the First Amendment....&quot;  Lindner, 91 Wis. 2d at 163; see also Reuter, 44 Wis. 2d at 227.
</p>
<p>	In King, moreover, the Court reached its conclusion that the nativity display was constitutional &quot;even assuming that [Article I, sec. 18] may be `less flexible' than the First Amendment.&quot;  185 Wis. 2d at 54.  As the Governor's brief in opposition to the preliminary injunction motion acknowledged (at p. 30), &quot;the court's broader statements concerning the scope of the religion clauses are in some technical sense dictum.&quot;   As a recent discussion of King observed, &quot;if the court had intended to overrule Reynolds, it would not have cited Reynolds and would not have based its decision on the assumption that Reynolds continues to be valid precedent.&quot;  Gordon, &quot;How vast is King's realm?&quot;, Wisconsin Lawyer 18, 21 (Aug. 1995).
</p>
<p>	The Governor suggests that any interpretation of the benefits clause that is more prohibitive than the federal Establishment Clause &quot;would risk creating painful friction between the religious benefits clause and the federal Free Exercise Clause....&quot;  Governor's Brief at 53-54.  That fear is unfounded.  The Free Exercise Clause does not require a state to fund religious activities.  State constitutional restrictions on providing state funds to religious organizations do not conflict with any right guaranteed by the Free Exercise Clause of the federal constitution.  See infra, pp. 44-50.  
</p>
<p>	The Governor, the Attorney General and the intervenors all contend that Article I, sec. 18, of the Wisconsin Constitution means nothing more and nothing less than what the United States Supreme Court declares at any given time to be the meaning of the Establishment Clause.  This Court has a long tradition, however, of interpreting Article I, sec. 18, as a vital and independent declaration of this state's commitment to religious liberty, including the explicit prohibition on state funding of religious schools.  While this Court may &quot;look to&quot; federal Establishment Clause cases for guidance in interpreting Article I, sec. 18, this Court has never said that any state funding program that is constitutional under the Establishment Clause necessarily is constitutional under the Wisconsin Constitution.
</p>
<p>	Regardless of whether the U.S. Supreme Court in some future case might find a school voucher program constitutional under the Establishment Clause, this Court must decide whether the Choice Program is constitutional under the Wisconsin Constitution.  To give effect to the plain language of the benefits clause of Article I, sec. 18, the Court should reaffirm that that language means exactly what it says -- that state treasury funds cannot be used to support religious school education because that confers an impermissible benefit on the religious schools.
</p>
<h4>	D.	The Amended Choice Program violates the compelled support clause of Article I, sec. 18.
</h4>
<p>	The second clause of Article I, sec. 18, provides that no person &quot;shall...be compelled to attend, erect or support any place of worship, or to maintain any ministry, without consent...&quot;  The Amended Choice Program violates the compelled support clause because it compels taxpayers to support places of worship and to maintain ministries without their consent.
</p>
<p>	In State ex rel. Weiss v. District Bd., supra, this Court held that Bible readings in the public schools violated the compelled support clause as well as the benefits clause.  The Court found that reading of the Bible in public schools is &quot;worship&quot; and that, as a result, the school room in which Bible readings occurred was a &quot;place of worship&quot; within the meaning of Article I, sec. 18.   Weiss, 76 Wis. at 211-13.  It rejected the school district's argument that a &quot;place of worship should be confined to some church edifice, or place where the members of a church statedly worship.&quot;  Id. at 213.
</p>
<p>	The Bible reading violated the compelled support clause because the objecting plaintiffs, as taxpayers of the school district, were &quot;compelled to aid in the erection of the school building in question, and also to aid in the support of the school maintained therein.&quot;  Id.  &quot;Being thus compelled to aid in such erection and support, they have a legal right to object to its being used as a `place of worship.'&quot;  Id.  It did not matter, the Court said, that &quot;only a small fraction of the school hours is devoted to such worship....&quot;  Id.  That &quot;in no way justifies such use as against an objecting tax-payer.&quot;  Id.  
</p>
<p>	The Amended Choice Program similarly compels taxpayers to &quot;support [a] place of worship...without consent.&quot;  Many, if not most, of the religious schools that will participate in the Choice Program include religious worship as part of their daily activities.  See, e.g., Exhibit E to Agreed Upon Statement of Facts, pp. 106, 131, 154, 332, 353, 400, 414, 508.  If a brief daily Bible reading renders a public school classroom a &quot;place of worship&quot; under Article I, sec. 18, there can be no doubt that a parochial school operated by a religious organization, in which religious and secular instruction are intertwined and daily prayer is an integral part of the educational program, is likewise a &quot;place of worship&quot; under the state constitution.  
</p>
<p>	Nor can there be any doubt that under the Amended Choice Program, tax funds will be used to &quot;support&quot; these &quot;places of worship.&quot;  The parties have stipulated that a participating religious school may use state funds received under the Choice Program &quot;for any purpose the school deems appropriate, including, among other things, the payment of salaries and expenses of employees affiliated with the school's religious mission, the purchase of literature and other materials identified with the school's religious mission, and the maintenance and construction of facilities used for religious purposes.&quot;  Agreed Upon Statement of Facts,  28.
</p>
<p>	The Amended Choice Program also runs afoul of the compelled support clause because many, if not most, of the religious schools are viewed by their sponsoring religious organization as an integral part of the organization's religious ministry.  See supra, pp. 9-11.  As a result, Wisconsin taxpayers will be &quot;compelled to ... maintain [a] ministry&quot; without their consent when their tax dollars are used to support religious schools.
</p>
<p>	The Court in Weiss explained that one of the reasons that the Wisconsin Constitution prohibits sectarian instruction in district schools is that &quot;the child of the Jew, or Catholic, or Unitarian, or Universalist, or Quaker should not be compelled to listen to the stated reading of passages of scripture which are accepted by others as giving the lie to the religious faith and belief of their parents and themselves....&quot;  76 Wis. at 198.  As the amicus brief filed by the Wisconsin Jewish Conference and the Milwaukee Jewish Council for Community Relations poignantly illustrates, that same concern explains why taxpayers cannot be compelled under the Choice Program to support religions that are hostile to their own beliefs.  Many of the Christian religious schools that have applied to participate in the Program frankly admit that their mission is to proselytize students and their families and to convert them to their faith.  This means that state taxes paid by Jewish, Muslim and other religious minority taxpayers, as well as by taxpayers who hold no religious beliefs, will fund attempts to convert children to the Christian faith.
</p>
<p>		If the challenged legislation is implemented, Wisconsin Jews and other religious minorities will see their State tax dollars used to fund core religious programs which are antithetical -- and in some cases actively hostile -- to their own most personal religious beliefs. ...
	. . . 
		Surely, few state acts could send more disturbing tremors of dj vu throughout the American Jewish community that to force that community to watch their own State tax dollars used to fund a religious school which openly announces to the State that it will use those State funds to aggressively proselytize anyone who is not a Christian.
</p>
<p>Amicus Curiae Brief of the Milwaukee Jewish Council for Community Relations and the Wisconsin Jewish Conference in Support of a Preliminary Injunction, p. 4 (emphasis in original).
</p>
<p>	Payment of state treasury funds to religious schools under the Amended Choice Program will provide substantial benefits not only to the participating schools but to the sponsoring religious organizations for which those schools constitute a vital part of their ministry.  For that reason, the Amended Choice Program violates the compelled support clause as well as the benefits clause of Article I, sec. 18, of the Wisconsin Constitution.
</p>
<h3>II.	THE CHOICE PROGRAM VIOLATES THE ESTABLISHMENT CLAUSE OF THE FIRST AMENDMENT.
</h3>
<p>	The Establishment Clause of the First Amendment, made applicable to the states by the Fourteenth Amendment, provides that &quot;Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion....&quot;  Under that provision, the U.S. Supreme Court has struck down virtually every form of financial aid to parochial schools at the elementary and secondary level.  In addition to its state constitutional infirmities, the Choice Program violates the fundamental constitutional guarantee of separation of church and state created by the Establishment Clause.
</p>
<p>	The Supreme Court decisions prohibiting state aid to parochial schools are based on the pervasively sectarian nature of elementary and secondary religious schools.  Virtually every aspect of parochial education includes religious training of some kind.  It is impossible to isolate and then fund the secular activities of parochial schools without funding their religious mission as well.
</p>
<p>	The very purpose of many of these schools is to provide an integrated secular and religious education; the teaching process is, to a large extent, devoted to the inculcation of religious values and beliefs.  Substantial aid to the educational function of such schools, accordingly, necessarily results in aid to the sectarian school enterprise as a whole.  &quot;[T]he secular education those schools provide goes hand in hand with the religious mission that is the only reason for the schools' existence.  Within the institution, the two are inextricably intertwined.&quot;  
</p>
<p>Meek v. Pittenger, 421 U.S. 349, 366 (1975) (citations and footnote omitted), quoting Lemon v. Kurtzman, 403 U.S. 602, 657 (1971) (opinion of Brennan, J.); accord, School Dist. of Grand Rapids v. Ball, 473 U.S. 373, 384 (1985).
</p>
<p>	Accordingly, the Supreme Court consistently has invalidated aid programs that provide unrestricted benefits to religious schools or that help fund the instructional process.  Examples of aid programs found unconstitutional have included construction and repair grants for parochial schools, Committee for Public Education &amp; Religious Liberty v. Nyquist, 413 U.S. 756 (1973); tuition reimbursement for parents, Id., Sloan v. Lemon, 413 U.S. 825 (1973); salary supplements for parochial school teachers, Lemon v. Kurtzman, supra; and instructional equipment and materials that can be used for religious purposes, Wolman v. Walter, 433 U.S. 229 (1977); Meek v. Pittenger, supra.
</p>
<p>	The U.S. Supreme Court case involving an aid program most similar to the Choice Program is Nyquist.  One of the New York programs challenged in Nyquist was a tuition reimbursement program that provided unrestricted grants of $50 to $100 per child as reimbursement to low-income parents who sent their children to private schools, the great majority of which were religious schools.  The Court first observed that because there was no effective means of guaranteeing that the grants would be used exclusively for secular purposes, &quot;[t]here can be no question that these grants could not, consistently with the Establishment Clause, be given directly to the sectarian schools....&quot;  413 U.S. at 780.
</p>
<p>	The Court then held that the fact that the program provided reimbursement to the parents rather than direct payment to the schools made no difference:
</p>
<p>	[I]f the grants are offered as an incentive to parents to send their children to sectarian schools by making unrestricted cash payments to them, the Establishment Clause is violated whether or not the actual dollars given eventually find their way into the sectarian institutions.  Whether the grant is labeled a reimbursement, a reward, or a subsidy, its substantive impact is still the same.
</p>
<p>Id. at 786 (footnote omitted).
</p>
<p>	In a case decided the same day as Nyquist, the Court rejected the argument that Pennsylvania's private school tuition reimbursement law was constitutional because the law authorizes grants to all parents of children in private schools and that it cannot be assumed that the parents will spend the money on religious school tuition.
</p>
<p>		Our decision...is not dependent upon any such speculation.  Instead we look to the substance of the program, and no matter how it is characterized the effect remains the same.  The State has singled out a class of its citizens for a special economic benefit.  Whether that benefit be viewed as a simple tuition subsidy, as an incentive to parents to send their children to sectarian schools, or as a reward for having done so, at bottom its intended consequence is to preserve and support religion-oriented institutions. ...  We hold that Pennsylvania's tuition grant scheme violates the constitutional mandate against the &quot;sponsorship&quot; or &quot;financial support&quot; of religion or religious institutions.
</p>
<p>Sloan v. Lemon, 413 U.S. at 832-33.
</p>
<p>	The Choice Program is indisputably unconstitutional under Nyquist.  Both involve aid to low income students who attend private schools, whether sectarian or nonsectarian.  In both cases, the great majority of the schools that stand to benefit from the aid are sectarian.  The only significant distinctions between the Choice Program and the New York program provide additional evidence of the Choice Program's unconstitutionality -- under the Choice Program, the money does flow directly to the schools, and the amount of the payment, even after taking into account two decades of inflation, not only is much greater under the Choice Program but will in most cases exceed tuition.
</p>
<h4>	A.	Nyquist remains good law.
</h4>
<p>	The Choice proponents would have this Court consign Nyquist to the dustbin of constitutional history.  Notwithstanding their protestations, Nyquist remains the law.
</p>
<p>	The U.S. Supreme Court cited Nyquist with approval as recently as 1994.  See Board of Education of Kiryas Joel Village Sch. Dist. v. Grumet, 114 S.Ct. 2481, 2487 (1994).  Just last year, United States District Judge John Reynolds also relied on Nyquist when he held that the Establishment Clause prohibited any expansion of Wisconsin's Choice Program to include religious schools.  Miller v. Benson, 878 F. Supp. 1209 (E.D. Wis.), vacated as moot, 68 F.3d 163 (7th Cir. 1995).
</p>
<p>	In 1993, the Miller Intervenors sued the State of Wisconsin in federal court, alleging that the exclusion of religious schools from the original pre-Budget Act version of the Choice Program deprived them of their free exercise and equal protection rights.  Rejecting those arguments, Judge Reynolds observed that &quot;No case has overruled Nyquist's prohibition on tuition grants and unrestricted direct subsidies to religious schools.&quot; 878 F. Supp. at 1215. 
</p>
<p>	The Choice proponents read far more into the Supreme Court's post-Nyquist decisions -- Mueller, Witters, Zobrest and Rosenberger -- than is warranted.  In Mueller v. Allen, 463 U.S. 388 (1983), a 5-4 Court upheld a Minnesota statute that allowed state taxpayers to deduct from their state income tax expenses incurred in providing tuition, textbooks and transportation for their children attending elementary or secondary schools.  The Court found that the deduction did not have the primary effect of advancing the sectarian aims of the religious schools.  It noted that &quot;the tax deduction is available for educational expenses incurred by all parents, including those whose children attend public schools and those whose children attend nonsectarian private schools or sectarian schools.&quot;  Id. at 397.
</p>
<p>		In this respect, as well as others, this case is vitally different from the scheme struck down in Nyquist.  There, public assistance amounting to tuition grants was provided only to parents of children in non-public schools.  This fact had considerable bearing on our decision striking down the New York statute at issue; we explicitly distinguished both Allen and Everson on the grounds that &quot;[in] both cases the class of beneficiaries included all schoolchildren, those in public as well as those in private schools.&quot;
</p>
<p>Id. at 398.  
</p>
<p>	But more significantly, the Mueller Court distinguished the passive nature of the tax deduction from the tuition reimbursements in Nyquist and Sloan, which it viewed as actively subsidizing religious education.  Id. at 396 n.6, 399.  Unlike reimbursements involving the actual transfer of public funds, the tax deduction provided merely an &quot;attenuated financial benefit[]&quot; to the religious schools.  Id. at 399.  The Court reaffirmed that &quot;the direct transmission of assistance from the State to the [religious] schools themselves&quot; would be unconstitutional.  Id. 
</p>
<p>	In Witters v. Washington Dept. of Services for the Blind, 474 U.S. 481 (1986), the Court upheld the payment of vocational educational assistance funds to a blind student attending a Bible college.  The Court said that it was &quot;well settled...that the State may not grant aid to a religious school, whether cash or in kind, where the effect of the aid is that of a direct subsidy to the religious school from the State.&quot;  Id. at 487 (internal quotations omitted).  &quot;Aid may have that effect,&quot; the Court said, &quot;even though it takes the form of aid to students.&quot;  Id.
</p>
<p>	As in Mueller, the Court in Witters found the program constitutional in large part because it was available to students attending both public and private schools and is &quot;in no way skewed towards religion.&quot;  Id. at 487-88.  The Court viewed the program primarily as providing vocational assistance to the disabled student, rather than one in which &quot;any significant portion of the aid expended under the Washington program as a whole will end up flowing to religious education.&quot;  Id. at 488.  Under the Amended Choice Program, in contrast, &quot;a significant portion of the aid expended&quot; will &quot;end up flowing to religious education.&quot; 	
</p>
<p>	More recently, in Zobrest v. Catalina Foothills School Dist., 113 S.Ct. 2462 (1993), the Court held that a school district may provide a sign-language interpreter under the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA) to a student at a Roman Catholic high school.  Once again, the Court noted that the assistance was available to students attending both public and private schools.  Id. at 2467.  For that reason, the Court said, the IDEA &quot;creates no financial incentive for parents to choose a sectarian school....&quot;  Id.   Moreover, the Court observed, under the IDEA, &quot;no funds traceable to the government ever find their way into sectarian schools' coffers.&quot;  Id. at 2467-68.
</p>
<p>	The Choice Program supporters can take no comfort in Mueller, Witters or Zobrest.  Unlike the programs at issue in those cases, the Choice Program is available only to students attending private schools.  Three-fourths of those private schools are religious, and over eighty percent of the private school students in Milwaukee attend religious schools.  The great majority of the state aid under the Choice Program will flow to religious organizations.  Millions of dollars of &quot;funds traceable to the government&quot; will &quot;find their way into sectarian schools' coffers.&quot;  Zobrest, 113 S.Ct. at 2468. The express purpose of the Budget Act, moreover, was to expand the Choice Program to religious schools.  As a result, the Amended Choice Program now creates a powerful &quot;financial incentive for parents to choose a sectarian school....&quot;  Id. at 2467.
</p>
<p>	The most recent U.S. Supreme Court decision on state funding of religious activities, Rosenberger v. Rector and Visitors of the University of Virginia, 115 S.Ct. 2510 (1995), reinforces the continuing vitality of Nyquist's holding.  In Rosenberger, a 5-4 majority of the Court held that the University of Virginia would not violate the Establishment Clause if it used money from a student activities fund to pay printing bills for a Christian student group.  The Court found it significant that the funds were derived from an activity fee imposed on students, rather than a tax designed to raise revenue, and that the money was paid directly to the printer. 
</p>
<p>	Our decision, then, cannot be read as addressing an expenditure from a general tax fund.  Here, the disbursements from the [student activity] fund go to the private contractors for the cost of printing....  This is a far cry from a general public assessment designed and effected to provide financial support for a church.
</p>
<p>Id. at 2522.  Justice O'Connor, who supplied the crucial fifth vote, also observed that in light of these distinctions, the Court's decision did not &quot;signal[] the demise of the funding prohibition in Establishment Clause jurisprudence.&quot;  Id. at 2528 (O'Connor, J., concurring).
</p>
<p>	Unlike the student activity fees in Rosenberger, the funds for the Choice Program come directly from general tax revenues deposited in the state treasury.  These state funds flow directly to religious institutions where they will support religious activities.  Nothing in Rosenberger even remotely suggests that the Choice Program is constitutional.
</p>
<h4>	B.	The facial neutrality of a governmental program does not eliminate Establishment Clause concerns.
</h4>
<p>	The Choice proponents make the &quot;neutrality&quot; of the Choice Program a centerpiece of their argument.  &quot;A program that neutrally benefits sectarian and nonsectarian institutions alike,&quot; they argue, &quot;cannot have the primary effect of advancing religion.&quot;  Governor's Brief at 36.  While neutrality certainly is a factor in the Supreme Court's Establishment Clause jurisprudence, the Court has made it clear that neutrality alone does not insulate a program from constitutional infirmity.
</p>
<p>	In Bowen v. Kendrick, 487 U.S. 589 (1988), for example, the Court expressly rejected the proposition advanced by the Governor here that a program that neutrally benefits sectarian and nonsectarian institutions cannot have the primary effect of advancing religion.
</p>
<p>		Of course, even when the challenged statute appears to be neutral on its face, we have always been careful to ensure that direct governmental aid to religiously affiliated institutions does not have the primary effect of advancing religion.  One way in which direct government aid might have that effect is if the aid flows to institutions that are &quot;pervasively sectarian.&quot; ... The reason for this is that there is a risk that direct government funding, even if it is designated for specific secular purposes, may nonetheless advance the pervasively sectarian institution's &quot;religious mission.&quot;
</p>
<p>Id. at 609-10.  Similarly, in Roemer v. Board of Public Works, 426 U.S. 736 (1976), the Court said:
</p>
<p>	The Court has taken the view that a secular purpose and a facial neutrality may not be enough, if in fact the State is lending direct support to a religious activity.  The State may not, for example, pay for what is actually a religious education, even though it purports to be paying for a secular one, and even though it makes its aid available to secular and religious institutions alike.
</p>
<p>Id. at 747.
	
	Most recently, in Rosenberger, the Supreme Court once again affirmed that neutrality of a program alone does not guarantee its constitutionality.  While holding that a state university's use of student activity fees to pay a religious organization's printing bill would not violate the Establishment Clause, the Court stated that its decision cannot be read as approving a government funding scheme in which, &quot;even under a neutral program that includes nonsectarian recipients, the government is making direct money payments to an institution or group that is engaged in religious activity.&quot;  115 S.Ct. at 2523.  As Justice O'Connor observed in her concurring opinion, the Court's decision in Rosenberger &quot;neither trumpets the supremacy of the neutrality principle nor signals the demise of the funding prohibition in Establishment Clause jurisprudence.&quot;  Id. at 2528 (O'Connor, J., concurring).
</p>
<h4>	C.	Even indirect aid to religious organizations may violate the Establishment Clause.
</h4>
<p>	This Court likewise should reject the Choice proponents' argument that the expanded Choice Program  is constitutional because it provides only an indirect benefit to religious schools as a result of private decisions of individual parents.  As a factual matter, that is not correct.  Under the Program, state funds pass instantaneously through the hands of parents to the private schools.  The Choice Program payments are &quot;direct contributions which are merely routed through the parents to the schools, ... in lieu of payment by the parents.&quot;  Nyquist, 413 U.S. at 785-86.  That is no indirect or attenuated benefit to the school -- it is a direct subsidy that serves to &quot;advance [a] pervasively sectarian institution's `religious mission.'&quot;  Bowen v. Kendrick, 487 U.S. at 610.
</p>
<p>	Moreover, even if this Court were to view the Choice Program as providing only an indirect benefit to sectarian schools, the Supreme Court has never adopted the distinction between direct and indirect aid as a dispositive rule.  To the contrary, in Nyquist and Sloan, the Court found that tuition grants violated the Establishment Clause even though the funds were paid to the parents and did not flow directly to the religious schools.  As the district court stated in the contemporaneous case of Wolman v. Essex, 342 F. Supp. 399, 415-16 (S.D. Ohio), aff'd mem. 409 U.S. 808 (1972):
</p>
<p>	Payment to the parent for transmittal to the denominational school does not have a cleansing effect and somehow cause the funds to lose their identity as public funds....  Since the parents serve as mere conduits of public funds, the State retains a responsibility for insuring that the public moneys provided and which retain their public character throughout the transaction, are used for constitutionally permissible ends and continue to be so used.
</p>
<p>	In 1985 -- two years after it decided Mueller -- the Court reaffirmed the holdings in Nyquist and Sloan, explaining that the &quot;differences in form [in Nyquist and Sloan] were insufficient to save programs whose effect was indistinguishable from that of a direct subsidy to the religious school.&quot;  Ball, 473 U.S. at 394.  The Court expressly stated that an &quot;indirect subsidy&quot; will still &quot;evoke[] Establishment Clause concerns when the public funds flow to `an institution in which religion is so pervasive that a substantial portion of its functions are subsumed in the religious mission....'&quot;  Id. at 394 n.12, quoting Hunt v. McNair, 413 U.S. 734, 743 (1973).
</p>
<p>	The determinative factor in recent decisions has not been the direct or indirect nature of the aid but whether the benefit to religion is attenuated and insubstantial.  See Rosenberger, 115 S.Ct. at 2524 (&quot;Any benefit to religion is incidental&quot;); Zobrest, 113 S.Ct. at 2467-69.  As the Court reaffirmed in Witters, state aid still may have an impermissible effect &quot;even though it takes the form of aid to students or parents.&quot;  474 U.S. at 487.
</p>
<p>	The Miller Intervenors correctly recognize that the distinction between &quot;direct&quot; and &quot;indirect&quot; aid is not dispositive, in part because it is a &quot;feature easily manipulated by a state legislature.&quot;  Miller Intervenors' Brief at 46.  That is precisely what the Wisconsin legislature attempted here, when it changed the Choice Program's payment mechanism from a check payable to the school to a check payable to the parents which they must endorse over to the school.  That sort of legislative legerdemain cannot have any constitutional significance.
</p>
<p>	To the State of Wisconsin, however, this change in payment mechanism apparently makes all the difference between a constitutional program and an unconstitutional one.  In the federal court litigation in Miller v. Benson, the state argued (and persuaded the district court) that the Original Choice Program would be unconstitutional if it included religious schools:
</p>
<p>		The choice statute grants a payment of money directly from the state to the private school.  If the program included sectarian private schools, tax funds would be transferred from the state treasury to sectarian schools to directly support the teaching of religious doctrine. 
</p>
<p>Now, of course, the state (through both the Governor, who asserts that he represent the state's position here, and the Attorney General, who represented the state in Miller) contends that including religious schools in the Choice Program is not unconstitutional.  The only explanation for that abrupt about-face is that the state believes that the change in payment mechanism is dispositive.  The other elements of the amended Program that the state now finds so important -- the neutrality of the program and the fact that state funds go to the schools as a result of parental choice -- have not changed.
</p>
<p>	The U.S. Supreme Court has never accepted the general principles on which Choice proponents rely as dispositive.  It has, however, specifically and unequivocally prohibited the sort of state funding for religious education that the Choice Program provides to parochial schools in Milwaukee.  For that reason, the Amended Choice Program violates the Establishment Clause of the First Amendment in addition to violating Article I, sec. of the Wisconsin Constitution.
</p>
<h3>III.	EXCLUDING RELIGIOUS SCHOOLS FROM THE CHOICE PROGRAM DOES NOT VIOLATE THE FREE EXERCISE CLAUSE OF THE FIRST AMENDMENT.
</h3>
<p>	Alone among the Choice Program supporters, the Miller Intervenors contend that the Free Exercise Clause of the First Amendment requires that the Choice Program include religious schools.  They contend that the Original Program was (and continues to be) unconstitutional because it purposefully discriminates against religion.  State funding for private education that excludes religious schools, the Miller Intervenors claim, requires them to waive their free exercise rights as a condition of accepting the benefits of publicly funded private education.
</p>
<p>	The Miller Intervenors' free exercise arguments are without merit.   The Original Choice Program does not make any religious practice unlawful or exclude any religious (or nonreligious) parent from participating in the Program because of his or her faith.  Some parents, like those represented here by Parents for School Choice, want to send their children to religious schools for reasons other than their religious beliefs.  Other parents, like many of the Jackson Respondents, are devoutly religious people who believe that enrolling their children in public schools best conforms to their beliefs.  But regardless of how any particular individual interprets or responds to the demands of his or her religious faith, the Original Choice Program treats all parents the same.  
</p>
<p>	In Brusca v. Missouri, 332 F. Supp. 275 (E.D. Mo. 1971), aff'd, 405 U.S. 1050 (1972), the district court, in a decision summarily affirmed by the U.S. Supreme Court, rejected the argument that a state's refusal to fund religious education discriminated against parents who wished to send their children to parochial schools.
</p>
<p>	We find nothing arbitrary or unreasonable in the determination of the State to deny its funds to sectarian schools or for religious instruction....  All children of every and no religious denomination have the same right to attend free secular public schools maintained by tax funds.
</p>
<p>Id. at 279.  The Original Choice Program similarly reflects a decision by the State of Wisconsin to fund only secular education, while allowing children of all faiths or no faith to attend those schools.
</p>
<p>	The mere fact that the state funds only secular programs or limits the application of public monies to secular providers or for secular purposes does not translate into purposeful discrimination against religion.  The Original Choice Program is no different in this respect from a host of state and federal programs that prohibit the use of public funds for religious purposes while allowing all individuals, religious and nonreligious, to participate equally in the programs.  See, e.g., Bowen v. Kendrick, 487 U.S. at 609-10 (holding that funds under the federal Adolescent Family Life Act may not be used for religious purposes even though religiously affiliated entities may participate in the program); Tilton v. Richardson, 403 U.S. 672 (1971) (barring church-affiliated colleges from using federal funds for religious purposes).   If the Free Exercise Clause requires that the government allow neutrally available funds to be used for religious purposes, then every one of these programs is unconstitutional.
</p>
<p>	The Miller Intervenors rely heavily on the Supreme Court's recent decision in Rosenberger, where the Court found that a state university had discriminated against the petitioners based on the religious content of their speech.  The Rosenberger Court reaffirmed, however, the constitutionality of maintaining such distinctions with respect to the funding of religious entities.  115 S.Ct. at 2522-23.  Thus, the fact that the state funds only secular programs or limits the application of public monies to secular providers or for secular purposes does not amount to purposeful discrimination against religion.
</p>
<p>	The Miller Intervenors also have failed to show that they have suffered any substantial burden on their religious practices.  They do not allege that their religious beliefs require that they send their children to religious schools or that the state's failure to pay for a religious education somehow compels them to act contrary to their religious beliefs.   The mere failure of the state to pay for the enhancement of an individual's religious faith cannot be equated with the imposition of a substantial burden on that person's religious practice.  As the Court explained in Lyng v. Northwest Indian Cemetery Protective Ass'n, 485 U.S. 439 (1988):
</p>
<p>	[T]his Court has repeatedly held that indirect coercion or penalties on the free exercise of religion, not just outright prohibitions, are subject to scrutiny under the First Amendment.  Thus, for example, ineligibility for unemployment benefits, based solely on a refusal to violate the Sabbath, has been analogized to a fine imposed on Sabbath worship.  Sherbert [v. Verner, 374 U.S. 398, 404 (1963).]  This does not and cannot imply that incidental effects of governmental programs, which may make it more difficult to practice certain religions but which have no tendency to coerce individuals into acting contrary to their religious beliefs, require government to bring forward a compelling justification for its otherwise lawful actions.  The crucial word in the constitutional text is &quot;prohibit&quot;:  &quot;For the Free Exercise Clause is written in terms of what the government cannot do to the individual, not in terms of what the individual can exact from the government.&quot;
</p>
<p>Id. at 450-51, quoting Sherbert, 374 U.S. at 412 (Douglas, J., concurring) (emphasis added); accord, Bob Jones University v. United States, 461 U.S. 574, 603-04 (1983) (holding that a denial of benefits &quot;will inevitably have a substantial impact on the operation of private religious schools, but will not prevent those schools from observing their religious tenets.&quot;).  As the court held in Brusca:
</p>
<p>	[A] parent's right to choose a religious private school for his children may not be equated with the right to insist that the state is compelled to finance his child's non-public school education in whole or in part in order that he may obtain a religious education.
</p>
<p>332 F. Supp. at 277.
</p>
<p>	In a case raising a similar issue under the rubric of the Equal Protection clause, the Supreme Court rejected the argument that parents' constitutional right to send their children to private schools if they choose, recognized in cases such as Pierce v. Society of Sisters, 268 U.S. 510 (1925), imposes any obligation on the states to fund private schools.
</p>
<p>	In Pierce, the Court affirmed the right of private schools to exist and to operate; it said nothing of any supposed right of private or parochial schools to share with public schools in state largesse, on an equal basis or otherwise.  ...  It is one thing to say that a State may not prohibit the maintenance of private schools and quite another to say that such schools must, as a matter of equal protection, receive state aid.
</p>
<h2>Norwood v. Harrison, 413 U.S. 455, 462 (1973). 
</h2>
<p>	Because the decision not to fund sectarian education does not impose a substantial burden on the Miller Intervenors' religious practice, it cannot have the effect of imposing an unconstitutional condition -- the waiver of a free exercise right -- on the acceptance of the benefit of participating in the Original Choice Program.  &quot;A government regulation that indirectly and incidentally calls for a choice between securing a governmental benefit and adherence to religious beliefs is wholly different from governmental action or legislation that criminalizes religiously inspired activity or inescapably compels conduct that some find objectionable for religious reasons.&quot;  Bowen v. Roy, 476 U.S. 693, 706 (1986).
</p>
<p>	&quot;The fact that the government cannot exact from [a citizen] a surrender of one iota of [his] religious scruples does not, of course, mean that [he] can demand of government a sum of money, the better to exercise them.&quot;  Sherbert v. Verner, 374 U.S. at 412 (Douglas, J., concurring).  The Miller Intervenors concede that the State of Wisconsin would not have violated their free exercise rights had it limited state funding to only secular public education.  See Miller Intervenors' Brief at 14.  The restriction in the Original Choice Program limiting participation in the Program to secular schools no more impairs the Miller Intervenors' free exercise rights than would the state's decision to fund only public education.
</p>
<h3>IV.	THE AMENDED CHOICE PROGRAM VIOLATES ARTICLE X OF THE WISCONSIN CONSTITUTION.</h3>
<p>	
	In Article X of the Wisconsin Constitution, the framers required that the legislature establish a system of primary and secondary instruction that was to be free and uniform.   The comprehensive nature of the educational system established in Article X, along with the history of that provision and of education in Wisconsin, demonstrates the framers' intent that the district school system described in Article X be the state's only system of publicly-supported primary and secondary education.  The Amended Choice Program undermines this goal by creating an alternative system composed of publicly-funded private schools that competes with the public schools for students and funds -- schools that are beyond the reach of the taxpayers who support them, the Superintendent of Public Instruction and, the Choice proponents contend, the Constitution.
</p>
<h4>		A.	Davis v. Grover Is Not Dispositive.
</h4>
<p>	The Choice proponents contend that any Article X issues raised by the Choice Program were resolved definitively in Davis v. Grover, 166 Wis.2d 501, 480 N.W.2d 460 (1992), and that the Court need not re-examine them here.  Those arguments ignore the substantial differences between the Original Choice Program at issue in Davis and the Amended Choice Program now before the Court.
</p>
<p>	The Davis decision repeatedly emphasized that the Choice Program was experimental, limited in scope, and carefully monitored by the state.  See 166 Wis.2d at 512, 513, 533, 534, 539, 546.  Specifically, the Court noted that the Program was open only to one percent of the school district's membership, which amounted to no more than 1,000 students.  Id. at 515.  The Program also was limited to nonsectarian schools and participating schools could enroll no more than 49% of their total enrollment under the Program.  Id. at 514-15.
</p>
<p>	The Amended Choice Program is a drastic departure from that &quot;narrowly defined and carefully monitored&quot; Program.  Id.  It no longer is limited to nonsectarian schools.  Choice students no longer need make up a minority of a participating schools' students; under the Amended Program, 100 percent of a school's pupils may be publicly funded Choice Program students.  Nor is the Amended Program limited to one percent of the MPS pupil population; instead, up to 15 percent of the MPS membership -- nearly 15,000 students -- will be able to participate next year.  Indeed, with 15,000 students, the Choice Program will have more students than all but a handful of the state's school districts. 
</p>
<p>	The Amended Choice Program is no longer experimental.  The reporting and information gathering requirements upon which the Court relied in Davis to find the Original Program to have been experimental now have been repealed.  See 1995 Wis. Act 27, Sec. 4007m.  The expanded Choice Program will remain in effect indefinitely.
</p>
<p>	Given the limited number of students eligible to participate in the Original Program, the Court in Davis found that the Program did not constitute &quot;an abandonment of the public school system.&quot;  166 Wis. 2d at 533.  With up to 15,000 MPS students about to be diverted from public schools under the Amended Choice Program, that conclusion no longer is true.
</p>
<p>	The small-scale, experimental Choice Program considered in Davis bears little resemblance to the Program now before the Court.  The Court should take a fresh look at the Article X issues raised by the Choice Program in light of the extensive changes to the Program.
</p>
<h4>		B.	Article X prohibits public funding of primary and secondary education at private schools.
</h4>
<p>	Article X, sec. 3, is &quot;a limitation upon the broad power of the state to educate its citizens through the establishment and operation of schools.&quot;  Zweifel v. Joint Dist. No. 1, 76 Wis.2d 648, 658, 251 N.W.2d 822 (1977).  The legislature is not free to adopt whatever educational system it chooses.  &quot;The limitations are precisely stated:  District schools, uniformity, and free tuition for certain ages.&quot;  Id.
</p>
<p>	Just as the legislature may not refuse to establish district schools, it cannot disband those schools or allow them to deteriorate.  See Davis, 166 Wis. 2d at 557 (Abrahamson, J., dissenting).  Indeed, Article X, sec. 3, and the constitutional guarantee of a free education in district schools would mean little if the state could undermine public schools by paying for children to attend private schools.
</p>
<p>	One of the principle aids in interpreting the Wisconsin Constitution is a &quot;historical analysis of the constitutional debates and of what practices were in existence in 1848....&quot;  Buse v. Smith, 74 Wis. 2d 550, 568, 247 N.W.2d 141 (1976).  The history of the Wisconsin Constitution demonstrates that the framers intended that the district schools be the only system of publicly financed primary and secondary education in Wisconsin.  The adoption of Article X reflects their belief that educating the public was a core function of the state.  See Kukor v. Grover, 148 Wis.2d 469, 488, 436 N.W.2d 568 (1989).  Education, it was believed, was integral to the protection of liberty and democracy and should be provided by the state free to all of its citizens:
</p>
<p>	[A] general system of education was the only system on which we could depend for the preservation of our liberties.
</p>
<p>Id., quoting Journals and Debates, Constitutional Convention (1847-48), at 238.  The framers also believed that providing public education that was free from sectarian beliefs would foster equality, attract people of diverse religions and ethnic backgrounds, and prevent divisiveness.  See Weiss, 76 Wis. at 198.  
</p>
<p>	The creation of a single system of public education was a reaction to the &quot;patchwork&quot;  system of schools that existed when the constitution was adopted and reflected the framers' commitment to a system of district common schools.  At that time, virtually all schooling was private.  37 O.A.G. 347, 349 (1948).   Article X and the creation of a single state-supported school system represent the framers' rejection of private schools as the primary means of educating the state's citizens.  They represent as well the rejection of the mixed public and private funding of primary and secondary schools.  Davis, 166 Wis. 2d at 557 (Abrahamson, J., dissenting).
</p>
<p>	The debates over the funding of the schools also demonstrate the intent to create an exclusive system of publicly financed primary and secondary instruction.  During the constitutional convention of 1847-48, the framers hotly debated the extent to which the state should fund the schools.  Kukor, 148 Wis.2d at 488.  They decided that the best way to safeguard the quality of the schools was to fund them through taxation which, they believed, would ensure public interest in the schools.  See id. at 489.  The framers feared that apathy on the part of the public would cause the public schools to decline, with private schools rising &quot;on their ruins.&quot;  Id., quoting Journals and Debates at 335.  By giving the public a direct pecuniary interest in the public schools, the framers hoped to preserve those schools and prevent the dominance of private schools.  
</p>
<p>  	Early case law is also instructive.  In Curtis's Administrator v. Whipple, 24 Wis. 350 (1869), the Court struck down a law that authorized the Town of Jefferson to raise a tax to support a private school.  In his concurring opinion, Justice Paine explained that the educational system prescribed in the constitution was the only public instruction to be supported by taxation.
</p>
<p>	Our constitution provides for a general system of public free schools, for normal schools, incorporated academies, and a state university.  These are all to be supported largely by taxation.  And from the general and extensive character of the provisions upon this subject, I think there is some implication that this system was designed to be exclusive, and to furnish the only public instruction which was to be supported by taxation.
</p>
<p>Id. at 359-60 (Paine, J., concurring)   Justice Paine's opinion made explicit what is implicit in the Constitution: the district school system designed in Article X was meant to be the only publicly funded system of primary and secondary education in the state.
</p>
<p>	The Court's decisions in Manitowoc v. Manitowoc Rapids, 231 Wis. 94, 285 N.W. 403 (1939) and State ex rel. Warren v. Reuter, supra, do not compel a different conclusion.  In Manitowoc, the Court held that Article X, sec. 3, did not prohibit the state from providing a free education to those over the age 20 or under the age of 4.  Reuter involved state funding of a private medical school, not primary or secondary schools, and raised no Article X, sec. 3, issues.  Because those cases did not involve public funding of primary or secondary instruction, and because the schools at issue in those cases that received public funding did not duplicate services that were constitutionally mandated by Article X and provided by public primary and secondary schools, they are irrelevant to this case.  For the same reason, the Choice proponents' analogies to programs through which the state contracts with private organizations to provide specialized services to public school students also fail.
</p>
<p>	Unlike the vocational schools in Manitowoc and the medical school in Reuter, the Choice Program directly competes with the public primary and secondary schools for students and funds.  See Agreed Upon Statement of Facts, at  34.  The Program undermines the purpose of Article X by effectively replacing the public schools with competing publicly funded private schools.  The Program does not merely provide students with a &quot;choice&quot; of educational opportunities; it advances private schools at the expense of the public schools.  Moreover, it deprives the public of a voice in the operation of schools that they support with their taxes and exempts the participating schools from the accountability and oversight requirements that the framers believed essential.
</p>
<p>	While the legislature may provide educational opportunities beyond those that are constitutionally required, the means chosen to accomplish that goal may not violate the Constitution.  See Buse, 74 Wis.2d at 567-68.  The Amended Choice Program violates Article X, sec. 3, by creating a competing school system composed exclusively of private schools that supplants the system of district schools prescribed in Article X, sec. 3.
</p>
<h4>		C.	The Amended School Choice Program violates Article X, sec. 3's requirements of a uniform education free from sectarian instruction.
</h4>
<p>	Relying on Davis, the Choice proponents contend that private schools are not &quot;district&quot; schools subject to Article X, sec. 3.  In Davis, the Court rejected the argument that a private school that accepts any public money is a district school.  See 166 Wis.2d at 540.  Under the Program at issue in Davis, however, no school could receive more than half of its funds from the state.  Under the Amended Choice Program, in contrast, a private school's entire enrollment may consist of Choice students and the school may be supported entirely by state funds.  This Court need not overrule Davis to conclude that &quot;private&quot; primary and secondary schools that may receive the majority of their funds from tax dollars are &quot;district&quot; schools subject to Article X, sec. 3.
</p>
<p>	If Article X, sec. 3, does apply, it is beyond dispute that the Choice Program schools do not meet the constitutional requirements of educational uniformity and freedom from sectarian instruction.  The uniformity requirement applies to the character of instruction in the schools, which must be &quot;as uniform as practicable.&quot;  Kukor, 148 Wis.2d at 492.  While private schools are subject to certain basic curricular requirements, see sec. 118.165, Stats., those requirements fall short of the extensive obligations that public schools have under sec. 121.02, Stats.  As a result, &quot;the character of instruction and the educational training that is provided to pupils who attend the participating private schools and MPS will not necessarily be the same.&quot;  Agreed Upon Statement of Facts, at  35.
</p>
<p>	This conclusion is underscored with respect to the religious schools that will participate in the Choice Program.  The religious education that students receive through the Choice Program will be of a entirely different character than the secular education that students receive in the public schools of this state.
</p>
<p>	Expanding the Choice Program to include religious schools also violates Article X, sec. 3's prohibition on sectarian education in the district schools.  That provision, read in the context of the history and purpose of the Constitution -- including Article I, sec. 18 -- prohibits state-supported religious education, which the framers saw as divisive and incompatible with the principles of equality and religious liberty.  See Weiss, 76 Wis. at 198.  The state legislature cannot avoid the constitutional prohibition on state-supported religious instruction by paying for students to attend religious schools as an alternative to public schools. 
</p>
<p>	Article X, sec. 3, applies whenever the legislature allows primary and secondary schools to receive a majority of their support from public funds.  If the Court finds that Article X, sec. 3, permits the large-scale public funding of private primary and secondary schools provided under the Amended Choice Program, the schools participating in the Program should be held to the same standards of uniformity and freedom from sectarian instruction as all other publicly supported primary and secondary schools in the state.
</p>

<h3>	CONCLUSION
</h3>
<p>	Both the state and federal constitutions prohibit the massive state funding of religious education provided by the Amended Choice Program.  For the reasons stated above, the Court should find the Amended Choice Program unconstitutional.
</p>
<p>Dated:  January 16, 1996.
<p>
