<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Briefer: Workplace Drug Testing</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/graphics/worker.gif"></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">WORKPLACE DRUG TESTING</H1>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">AMERICAN CIVIL LIBERTIES UNION BRIEFER</H3>
<P>Today, in many industries, drug tests have become as routine as filling out
a job application &#151; even though the vast majority of the workers tested are
not suspected of drug use.</P>
<P>According to the American Management Association, the number of companies
with drug testing programs increased by more than 300 percent between 1987 and
1994. Millions of American workers are tested yearly.</P>
<P>Random drug testing is pervasive, but is it fair? Are the tests accurate? Do
they deter or prevent drug use? The ACLU's answer to all three questions is: no.
</P>
<P>Employers have the right to expect their employees not to be high, drunk or
asleep on the job. But they should not have the right to require employees who
are not suspected of using drugs, to prove their innocence by providing a urine
specimen on demand.</P>
<P>THAT IS NOT THE AMERICAN WAY.</P>
<HR>
<H3>DRUG TESTING IS AN INVASION OF THE RIGHT TO PRIVACY</H3>
<P>However routine such tests have become, a drug test is still a search &#151;
and searches raise privacy concerns. First, the specimen collection process
itself often involves direct or indirect observation to prevent tampering by the
employee. Direct observation involves the presence of a monitor during the act
of urination. One employee described her ordeal:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<TABLE
WIDTH="50%" BORDER="BORDER" ALIGN="CENTER" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" CELLPADDING="2">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><BR>&quot;I was given a container in which to urinate. I waited for the
attendant to turn her back before pulling down my pants, but she told me she had
to watch everything I did. I am a forty-year-old mother of three: nothing I have
ever done in my life equals or deserves the humiliation, degradation and
mortification I felt.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR></TABLE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Even indirect observation can be degrading. Typically, employees must remove
all outer garments, and urinate into a toilet where the water supply has been
turned off. </P>
<P>A second search takes place in the lab. Urine analysis reveals not only the
presence of illegal drug by products, but also many other physical and medical
conditions &#151; medication for hypertension, epilepsy or diabetes; a genetic
predisposition to heart disease or cancer; pregnancy. In fact, at the time of
the drug test, employees are usually required to fill out forms listing all of
the medications they are currently taking &#151;a clear invasion of privacy.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<TABLE
WIDTH="50%" BORDER="BORDER" ALIGN="CENTER" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" CELLPADDING="2">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><BR>In the late 1980s, the Washington, D.C. police department admitted that
it routinely subjected urine specimens taken for drug tests from female police
officers and other female employees to pregnancy testing as well &#151; without
the employees' knowledge or consent. </P></BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR></TABLE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>THERE IS NO WORKPLACE DRUG EPIDEMIC</H3>
<P>Claims of billions of dollars lost in productivity every year due to
employee drug use are based on media exaggeration and guesswork, not on
empirical evidence. </P>
<P>Drug abuse in the workplace affects a relatively small percentage of
workers: in 1987 &#151; the decade in which most drug testing programs were
established &#151; only eight percent of all adults (age 26 and older) reported
using drugs during the previous month. The percentage of adults who used drugs
in the workplace was much lower. </P>
<P>A 1994 National Academy of Sciences report concluded that &quot;illicit
drugs have never been used at work by a large proportion of the work force.&quot;
The report found workplace drug use &quot;ranges from a modest to a moderate
extent,&quot; and noted that much of reported drug use &quot;may be single
incidents, perhaps even at events like office parties.&quot;</P>
<H3>DRUG TESTS MAKE MISTAKES</H3>
<P>Although urine testing technology is improving, it's still faulty. Sometimes
the laboratory accidentally switches samples; sometimes the equipment is not
clean, sometimes the test itself fails to distinguish between legal and illegal
substances. Depronil, a prescription drug used to treat Parkinson's Disease,
shows up as amphetamine on the standard drug test. Over-the-counter,
anti-inflammatory drugs like Ibuprofen have shown up positive on the marijuana
test. Even the poppy seeds found in baked goods can produce a positive result &#151;
wrongly suggesting morphine, opium or heroin use.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" WIDTH="80%" ALIGN="CENTER" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0">
<TR>
<TD>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><BR>FAR FROM FOOLPROOF</P>
<P ALIGN="LEFT">Drug tests sometimes fail to distinguish between legal and
illegal substances. Ibuprofen has often shown up as marajuana -- and the poppy
seeds in baked goods have wrongly suggested morphine, opium or heroin use!</P></BLOCKQUOTE></TD>
<TD>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><BR>Even a small margin of error translates into a substantial number of
injustices. If one million tests are performed in a year (a conservative
estimate), and .05 percent of those tests yield false positive results (also a
conservative estimate), that translates into 50,000 mistakes &#151; people who
may be fired from their jobs, or not offered jobs for which they are qualified.</P></BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR></TABLE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>DRUG TESTS AREN'T WORK RELATED</H3>
<P>Random drug tests are also unfair because they're not work-related.
Urinalysis does not and cannot measure impairment on the job. Unlike a
breathelyzer test for alcohol, a positive test for, say, cocaine only reveals
that a drug was ingested at some time in the past. It doesn't show when or how
much of the drug was taken. Nor does it distinguish between occasional or
habitual use.</P>
<P>Drug testing is designed to detect and punish conduct that is usually
engaged in off-duty and off the employer's premises &#151; that is, in private.
Employers who conduct random drug tests on workers who are not suspected of
using drugs are policing private behavior that has no impact on job performance.</P>
<H3>SAFETY TESTING FOR PILOTS, TRAIN ENGINEERS AND TRUCK DRIVERS</H3>
<P>It may seem logical to test transportation workers, but it isn't. First,
employee impairment due to on-duty drug use in safety sensitive jobs is
extremely rare. Never has a commercial airline accident been traced to a pilot
under the influence of drugs. And ironically, in one of those rare cases where
an accident was related to drug impairment &#151; the fatal 1994 collision of
two Amtrak trains in Maryland &#151;  good management supervision would have
been a wiser approach than drug testing. The National Transportation Safety
Board determined the train engineer had a long and well-known history of alcohol
abuse. Had his supervisors adequately observed his behavior on the morning of
the crash, they could have removed him from service &#151; and saved 16 lives.
Obviously, drug tests after the fact cannot prevent accidents, nor do random
tests prevent accidents since they don't address the specific problem a
particular employee might have.</P>
<H3>WORKPLACE DRUG TESTING PROGRAMS DON'T DETER DRUG USE</H3>
<P>A decade of testing has failed to prove its value as a deterrent. After an
exhaustive review of the scientific literature, the National Academy of Sciences
found &quot;there is as yet no conclusive scientific evidence from properly
controlled studies that employment drug-testing programs widely discourage drug
use or encourage rehabilitation.&quot;</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<TABLE
BORDER="BORDER" WIDTH="80%" ALIGN="CENTER" CELLPADDING="2" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><BR><FONT SIZE="+3">NON-INVASIVE READINESS CHECKS</FONT></P>
<P>Computer-assisted performance tests measure impairment in hand-eye
coordination and response time. Performance tests reveal if someone is unfit for
work, whether the problem is substance abuse, fatigue or physical illness. For
years, NASA has tested astronauts and pilots with this method, but it is still
not widely used.</P>
<P>Employee assistance programs (EAPs) help employees experiencing temporary
emotional, health, financial or substance abuse problems that affect job
performance.  Company supervisors refer troubled employees to the EAP counselors
who decide what type of intervention is needed: EAP staff support, referral to
inpatient treatment, attendance at Alcoholics Anonymous or Narcotics Anonymous
meetings, etc.  In this context, counselors might recommend periodic urinalysis
with the employee's consent as one way of keeping him or her &quot;clean.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR></TABLE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>STATES THAT PROTECT EMPLOYEES FROM RANDOM DRUG TESTING</H3>
<P>Only a handful of states, Montana, Iowa, Vermont and Rhode Island, ban
testing that is not based on individualized suspicion. Minnesota, Maine and
Connecticut permit not-for-cause testing, but only of employees in
safety-sensitive positions. These laws also require confirmation testing, lab
certification and test result confidentiality. Hawaii, Louisiana, Maryland,
Nebraska, Oregon and Utah regulate drug testing in some fashion; laws in Florida
and Kansas protect government employees' rights, but not those in the private
sector. Only in California, Massachusetts and New Jersey have the highest courts
ruled against some forms of drug testing on state constitutional or statutory
grounds. However, the vast majority of U.S. workers cannot refuse a drug test
without risk of losing their jobs. </P>
<P><B>To find out the legal status of drug testing in your state, call
800-775-ACLU and request the free document &quot;Workplace Privacy Rights, state
by state.&quot; </B></P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" ALIGN="JUSTIFY" CELLPADDING="2" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><BR><FONT SIZE="+3">IS DRUG TESTING CONSTITUTIONAL?</FONT></P>
<P>Unfortunately, the courts have not always agreed with the ACLU's position
that random workplace drug testing is an unconstitutional violation of the right
to privacy. </P>
<P>In 1989, after several years of conflicting decisions in federal courts, the
U.S. Supreme Court issued its first rulings on the drug testing of government
employees. One case reviewed the post-accident testing of railway workers,
including workers not directly implicated in the accident; a second case
involved the random testing of U.S. Customs Service officers.  Although the
Court conceded that urinalysis is a search under the Fourth Amendment, it held
that because of the country's drug problem &#151; and because these particular
employees were in &quot;safety sensitive&quot; occupations &#151; the government
had a &quot;special need&quot; that outweighed employees' privacy rights.</P>
<P>Today, employees who are engaged directly in transportation work, carry a
weapon, have access to highly classified information, or hold some other &quot;
safety sensitive&quot; position, can be subject to drug testing without cause.</P>
<P>Since the Fourth Amendment doesn't apply to private companies, private
sector employees and job applicants have even less legal protection than their
public sector counterparts. Lawsuits based on state constitutions and statutes
have produced mixed results. For the most part, unless restricted by a
collective bargaining agreement, private employers have almost unlimited
authority to implement drug testing programs in their workplaces.</P></BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>The ACLU, along with other privacy advocates and many labor unions, combats
unfair workplace drug testing on many fronts &#151; in the courts, in Congress
and state legislatures, and in the arena of public opinion. This briefer is just
one of the resources we provide. Others include:</P>
<P></P>
<UL>
<LI> A model state statute regulating workplace drug testing and protects
employee rights
</LI>
<LI> A 10-minute video, Through The Keyhole: Privacy in the Workplace, An
Endangered Right
</LI>
<LI> Speakers and experts
</LI>
<LI> Relevant materials available on the ACLU's web site: http://www.aclu.org.
</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER></BLOCKQUOTE></BODY></HTML>
