HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 13-Feb-97 12:57:07 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 29-Aug-96 18:59:56 GMT
Content-length: 11215
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 + all extensions//EN" "hmpro3.dtd">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Briefer: Electronic Monitoring</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/graphics/worker.gif"></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">ELECTRONIC MONITORING</H1>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">AMERICAN CIVIL LIBERTIES UNION BRIEFER</H3>
<P>Employers love to keep tabs on their workers. A 1996 survey conducted by the
University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign showed that 67% of the Fortune 500
companies surveyed used investigative services to collect or verify personnel
information. Not all workplaces need call on the help of outside investigators
to track employees, however: stunning technological advances over the past
decade have made it affordable and effortless for companies to keep an
unblinking eye on their workers, from punch in to quitting time.</P>
<P>Workplace technology is a mixed bag. On the one hand, it is a boon that
helps workers do their jobs faster and more efficiently and an aid to management
who can strategize and allocate resources for increased productivity. But too
often, the ever-improving technology only serves to surveil, intimidate and
disempower workers, reducing them to mere task-fulfilling machines. At the same
time, technology frustrates management's goals by creating a hostile climate
that undermines the very productivity it is supposed to promote.</P>
<P>THAT IS NOT THE AMERICAN WAY.</P>
<HR>
<H3>HOW EMPLOYERS MONITOR THEIR WORKERS</H3>
<P>With the partial exception of personal oral communication, employees have no
rights to privacy at work. Employers can read workers' e-mail, videotape them,
read personal items on computers and even eavesdrop on some phone calls, without
the workers' consent &#151; or knowledge.</P>
<P>Wireless and digital <I>surveillance systems</I>  allow for secret video
and audio monitoring. <I>Keystroke monitoring</I> measures employee activity
and idle time.
<I>Headphones</I> and <I>audio monitors</I> can record every word an employee
utters: official business, side comments made to neighboring workers, or even to
oneself. <I>Data storage systems</I> on computer hard drives as well as e-mail
and voice mail can store information an employee thinks has been deleted.
Sophisticated <I>infrared technology</I> even lets companies track an
employee's whereabouts in the office.</P>
<H3>MONITORING IS LEGAL COMPANY POLICY</H3>
<P>Constitutional protections against unreasonable search and seizure apply in
government, but not private sector workplaces.  Whether employers are benevolent
and enlightened concerning workers' privacy or tyrannical and invasive is up to
them, except in those few states where legislation has been passed protecting
privacy. Whatever the policy, companies should inform their workers, through
employee handbooks or memos, of their information collecting procedures, and how
this information is used. However, under current law, a company is not required
to do so.</P>
<H3>MONITORING IS A PRIVACY ISSUE</H3>
<P>Electronic monitoring of employees is a privacy issue because it often goes
beyond legitimate management concerns and ends up undermining workers' dignity.
Recently, postal workers in New York City were horrified to discover their
employers had installed video cameras in the restroom stalls. Female workers at
a large northeastern department store discovered a hidden video camera installed
in an empty office space that was commonly used as a changing room. </P>
<P>Besides enabling such invasions of an individual's most intimate privacy,
electronic monitoring can be exerted as a means of control over employees. Quite
frequently an employee doesn't know he or she has been monitored &#151; and only
finds out during an evaluation or disciplinary proceeding. Employees typically
do not have access to the data collected electronically nor the means to correct
misleading or faulty information. They also may have no control over which third
parties, such as creditors, insurance agencies and landlords   are made privy to
their personal data by their employer.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<TABLE
BORDER="BORDER" WIDTH="65%" ALIGN="CENTER" CELLPADDING="2" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><BR>&quot;Monitoring makes stressful jobs much more stressful.  People know
everything they say, everything they do can be listened to, timed and counted&quot;</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT"><I>-- Cyndia Cameron, 9 to 5 National Association of Working
Women</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR></TABLE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Although the 1986 Electronic Communication Privacy Act (an amendment of
Title II of the 1968 Omnibus Control and Safe Streets Act) prohibits employers
from eavesdropping on employees' personal calls, there is no restriction on the
amount of time it takes to determine if the call is personal or not: within that
unspecified time, often up to five minutes,  a listener can hear a lot of
information both the employee and the other person on the line might prefer to
keep private! And there are no legal means to limit how often an employer can
listen in on a worker's phone calls.</P>
<H3>ELECTRONIC MONITORING AFFECTS ALL EMPLOYEES</H3>
<P>While electronic monitoring methods are often associated with the clerical,
service and support positions that rely heavily on computer and telephone
equipment, professionals are just as vulnerable to the unblinking eye of the
technological monitor. Because e-mail and voice mail technology allow for
indefinite data storage, an employee can not be sure private information
transmitted electronically will not fall under a supervisor's scrutiny at a
later date. </P>
<H3>MONITORING NEGATIVELY AFFECTS EMPLOYEE PRODUCTIVITY</H3>
<P>While it is difficult to calculate the extent to which employee absenteeism,
illness or job-related stress is caused by the presence of electronic workplace
monitoring, employees who already work under stressful conditions experience
diminished productivity when they feel &quot;Big Brother&quot; is watching. It
is not surprising that countries like Japan, Germany and Sweden, who do not use
secret monitoring, provide service, quality and productivity that are among the
best in the world. Many enlightened corporations in the United States who place
a premium on employee comfort and satisfaction benefit from high productivity
and low turnover rates. Unfortunately, there are many companies who do not
choose to adopt such policies. </P>
<H3>HOW EMPLOYEES CAN PROTECT THEMSELVES</H3>
<P>Given the fact that employers listen in on more than 400 million calls a
year and the sharp increase in the use of electronic surveillance equipment, it
is wise to be prudent when on company time. Some employers designate specific
telephones for personal use only, which under the 1968 Omnibus Crime Control and
Safe Streets Act cannot be monitored. However, it is sound advice for employees
to avoid writing, saying, or sending any electronic correspondence that they
would not wish to be seen or heard by their co-workers or supervisors. Legally
enforceable rights against electronic monitoring can exist only where companies
adopt a policy against electronic monitoring &#151; either by voluntary internal
decision or under the mandate of new state laws.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<TABLE
BORDER="BORDER" WIDTH="80%" ALIGN="CENTER" CELLPADDING="2" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><BR><FONT SIZE="+2">NEEDED:<BR>LEGAL PROTECTION FROM
SECRET MONITORING</FONT></P>
<P>Only a fraction of the American workforce is protected from secret
electronic monitoring.  With the exception of Connecticut, which does not allow
monitoring &quot;in areas designated for the health or personal comfort of
employees,&quot; not a single state legislature has enacted protective
legislation.  A federal bill which would have reduced monitoring abuses, The
Privacy for Consumers and Workers Act, failed to pass Congress in 1994 and has
not be reintroduced.  </P>
<P>In general, public employees have more protection against &quot;unfair&quot;
monitoring than private sector employees., especially when it comes to physical
searches of person or property.  The constitutional right to due process, which
applies only to government employees, does not prevent monitoring, but it does
confer the right to challenge dismissals, demotions or other adverse personnel
actions based on monitoring that's irrelevant to job performance, or that
targets certain workers unfairly.  According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics,
government employees, however, constituted only 16.5%   percent of the American
workforce in 1995, the last year where data was available.</P>
<P>Unionized employees may be protected from secret monitoring by their
collective bargaining agreements.  But fewer than 20 percent of the American
workforce is unionized.</P></BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR></TABLE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>LAWS HAVE HELPED IN THE PAST</H3>
<P>During the 20th century, many labor laws were enacted to ensure that workers
are treated fairly and justly. Congress passed laws  prohibiting discrimination
against women and minorities in the private sector (Title VII of the 1964 Civil
Rights Act); and requiring a minimum wage (the Fair Labor Standards Act of
1938). Legislation has also been enacted to ensure employees' right to organize
unions (The National Labor Relations Act of 1935) and to receive prior notice of
expected plant closings (the Worker Adjustment and Retraining Notification Act
of 1989). The Employee Polygraph Protection Act of 1988 placed a sweeping ban on
the use of invasive, often faulty, employee lie detector tests. </P>
<P>Today, restrictions on electronic monitoring by employers must be enacted if
employee privacy and dignity are to be protected.</P>
<HR>
<P>The ACLU's Task Force for Civil Liberties in the Workplace (also known as
the Workplace Rights Project) runs the Campaign for Fairness in the Workplace.
This Campaign undertakes to educate the public about workplace privacy issues
and lobby for workplace privacy legislation. Because Congress and the Supreme
Court have declined to rule on the several workplace privacy issues in the past,
the ACLU is focusing on legislative change at the state level. </P>
<P>The Task Force has drafted model statutes for workplace privacy which
stipulate the rights and responsibilities of both employer and employee. The
statute on electronic monitoring recommends employers notify workers of company
monitoring practices, provide employee access to the data and the means to see
and copy reports as well as rectify incorrect or misleading information.
Likewise, the model statute also requires data collection be limited to

information relevant to work performance, curtails third-party disclosure of

data and ensures a grievance procedure for employees. </P>
<P><B>For more information about workplace rights issues, call the ACLU at
1-800-775-ACLU.</B></P>
<P></P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
