HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 13-Feb-97 13:20:01 GMT
Last-modified: Saturday, 27-Jan-96 17:52:01 GMT
Content-length: 16986
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>ACLU in the Court</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">

<h1><i> Summary of Argument in ACLU amicus brief </font></i></h1>
<br>
<center>
<font color="#ff0033">Docket 94-749<br></font>
<h3><font color="3300ff">HURLEY et al<br>. v.<br> IRISH-AMERICAN GAY, LESBIAN AND BISEXUAL<br> GROUP
OF BOSTON et al.</font></h3>
<br>
</center>
<br>
<blockquote>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>

<h4>Statement of the Case</h4>
<p>This case challenges the constitutionality of an injunction
issued by the Massachusetts courts requiring the South Boston
Allied War Veterans Council ("the Council"), as sponsors of the
1993 Boston St. Patrick's Day Parade, to permit an identifiable
contingent of gay and lesbian marchers to participate in the
Parade.[1] The injunction was issued by the Superior Court,
Pet.Cert. at B1-B-29, and affirmed by the Massachusetts Supreme
Judicial Court. Id. at C1-C26. The Massachusetts courts based
their rulings on an interpretation of the state's public
accommodations law, and a finding that the injunction would not
interfere with the Council's First Amendment rights.
</p>
 <p>    Given the heated nature of this controversy, it is ironic to
note that the St. Patrick's Day Parade began in the 19th century
as a response to efforts by nativist bigots, the "Know-Nothings,"
to exclude Irish Catholics from full participation in the July
4th Independence Day Parade.[2] The celebration of St. Patrick's
Day as an Irish-American alternative to a nativist Independence
Day was aided in Boston by the practice of linking St. Patrick's
Day to Evacuation Day, the official commemoration of George
Washington's first victory over the British during the
Revolutionary War -- his tactical use of artillery to force the
evacuation of the City of Boston in 1776.[3]
</p>
 <p>    Until 1947, the Parade was jointly organized by the South
Boston Citizens Association and the City of Boston. In 1947,
however, Mayor Curley granted the Veterans Council authority to
organize the parade, which it has done ever since. Pet.Cert. at
B8-B9. The Parade has now evolved into a massive event with over
20,000 participants and 700,000 spectators that winds through the
traditional Irish ethnic strongholds of South Boston, replete
with commercial, political and ethnic displays.
</p>
 <p>    Combining St. Patrick's Day with Evacuation Day gave the
celebration an official sanction and led to broad governmental
support for the Parade ranging from proclamations by the governor
urging the citizenry to observe the day, to intense participation
by public officials in the planning and administration of the
Parade, to actual taxpayer subsidies of the event.
</p>
 <p>    The extensive nature of the city's involvement with the St.
Patrick's Day Parade is detailed in the trial court's opinion:</p>
<dl>
     <dd>     Up through the 1992 Parade, the City provided
          the use of its official seal, printing
          services, and direct funding to participants
          and sponsors. Until 1993, the City provided
          approximately twenty-five percent of the
          Parade's total costs through the Office of
          Business and Cultural Development. The City
          also identified and contacted potential
          participants and disseminated information
          regarding the Parade.
<br>
Pet.Cert. at B17 (footnote omitted).[4]
</dl>
 <p>    Beginning in 1992, the Irish-American Gay, Lesbian and Bi-
sexual Group of Boston (GLIB) has sought permission each year
from the Council to march as an identifiable contingent in the
Boston Parade. That permission has been consistently denied and
GLIB has responded with a series of lawsuits.
</p>
 <p>    This litigation involves the 1993 Parade. In ruling in favor
of GLIB, the Massachusetts courts rejected the Council's argument
that forced inclusion of identifiable gay and lesbian marchers in
the St. Patrick's Day Parade was inconsistent with the message
the Parade sponsor wished to convey. Instead, the trial court
found that the 1993 Parade was not intended to convey any
coherent message. Pet.Cert. at B25.[5] Thus, the court reasoned,
the forced inclusion of gay and lesbian marchers did not pose a
significant threat to the sponsor's First Amendment rights. Id.
In the absence of such a threat, the court held that the state
public accommodations law controlled. Because state law bans
discrimination based on sexual orientation, the Massachusetts
courts ordered the Council to admit GLIB to the 1993 Parade.[6]
</p>
  <p>   As a result of this judicial action, the 1993 Parade
included a contingent of gay and lesbian marchers. When the 1993
injunction was made permanent and similar restrictions were
placed on the 1994 Parade, however, the Parade was cancelled. In
its place, the Council organized a motorcade of over 800 cars
protesting the injunction. In 1995, the Council explicitly
characterized the St. Patrick's Day Parade, which it once again
organized, as a protest against the prior decision of the
Massachusetts courts. On this basis, the Parade's sponsors
recently persuaded a United States district judge to issue
declaratory relief forbidding the City of Boston to require the
presence of gay and lesbian marchers in the sponsor's amended
version of the 1995 Parade. South Boston Allied War Veterans
Council v. The City of Boston, No 94-11402-MLW (D.Mass. January
17, 1995).
</p>
   <h4>                    Summary of Argument</h4>

<p>     This case implicates at least four sets of potentially
conflicting legal rights. First, gays and lesbians who wish to
march openly in celebration of St. Patrick's Day Parade have an
undoubted First Amendment right to assemble publicly in order to
assert that they are integral members of the Irish community.
E.g., Hague v. CIO, 307 U.S. 496 (1939); Edwards v. South
Carolina, 372 U.S. 229 (1963); Gregory v. Chicago, 394 U.S. 111
(1969); Shuttlesworth v. Birmingham, 394 U.S. 147 (1969); Forsyth
County v. Nationalist Movement, 505 U.S. ___, 112 S.Ct. 2395
(1992).
</p>
 <p>    Second, the Parade's sponsors have an undoubted First
Amendment right to assert that homosexuals should not be viewed
as full members of the Irish community and to resist official
pressure to say otherwise. E.g., Miami Herald Publishing Co., v.
Tornillo, 418 U.S. 241 (1974); Wooley v. Maynard, 430 U.S. 705
(1977).
</p>
   <p>  Third, all parties have an undoubted First and Fourteenth
Amendment right to be treated equally by the government as
speakers regardless of their views or their sexual orientation.
E.g., Grosjean v. American Press, 297 U.S. 233 (1936); Chicago
Police Dep't v. Mosely, 408 U.S. 92 (1972).
</p>
   <p>  Finally, gays and lesbians are entitled under Boston's local
civil rights laws to nondiscriminatory access to all places of
public accommodation. Mass Gen. L. ch. 272, section 98 (1992).
</p>
   <p>  Ordinarily, the potential for conflict between and among the
parties' legal rights would be avoided by authorizing each side
to mount its own parade, with government remaining aloof except
to maintain order.[7] Here, however, separate parades and
complete governmental neutrality are evidently not practicable,
because each side vigorously maintains that inclusion in, or
exclusion from, the St. Patrick's Day celebration is essential to
its message. Since the opposing parties wish to use a unique
public forum to deliver mutually exclusive messages at the same
time, Boston has been placed in the difficult but inescapable
role of necessarily determining whose rights will prevail.
</p>
  <p>   To the extent that the Parade can appropriately be
characterized as government sponsored, the First and Fourteenth
Amendments prohibit any effort by the state to exclude marchers
because of their sexual orientation or the content of their
message. E.g., Schact v. United States, 398 U.S. 58 (1970);
Minneapolis Star & Tribune v. Minnesota Comm'r of Revenue, 460
U.S. 575 (1983); Arkansas Writers' Project, Inc. v. Ragland, 481
U.S. 221 (1987); Simon & Schuster v. New York State Crime Victims
Board, 502 U.S. ___, 112 S.Ct. 501, (1991). Furthermore, that
sponsorship may be formal or informal. For example, if Boston
elects to delegate perennial control over the Parade to the same
nominally private group, and supports that specially favored
group with significant state assistance, a state action finding
may well be appropriate. Of. Edmonson v. Leesville Concrete Co.,
500 U.S. 614 (1991); Adickes v. S.H. Kress, 398 U.S. 144 (1970);
Terry v. Adams, 345 U.S. 461 (1953).
</p>
  <p>   On the other hand, if the Parade cannot fairly be described
as a government-sponsored event, a different set of
constitutional principles apply. Under these circumstances, the
Council's use of a traditional public forum for a parade is an
expressive event whose message is necessarily determined by the
parade's sponsors and not by the government. As an expressive
event, moreover, it follows that the parade sponsors have a
constitutional right to exclude marchers whose message conflicts
with the message the sponsors desire to convey. Cf. Wooley v.
Maynard, 430 U.S. 705; Pacific Gas & Electric Co. v. Public
Utility Comm'n of California, 475 U.S. 1 (1986); West Virginia
State Board of Education v. Barnette, 319 U.S. 624 (1943).
</p>
   <p>  While Boston may respond to a given sponsor's exclusionary
behavior by granting supplemental permits to allow excluded
marchers to organize a competing parade, once a private group has
been duly authorized to sponsor a parade, the government may
neither reject nor redefine the sponsor's message, even when the
message the sponsor wishes to convey is an ugly one of bigotry
and intolerance. Cf. R.A.V. v. City of St. Paul, 504 U.S. ___,
112 S.Ct. 2538 (1992).
</p>
 <p>    Thus, the lower courts erred in applying the state's public
accommodations law and rejecting the Council's First Amendment
claim if the 1993 Parade is regarded as a privately sponsored
event, as the courts below evidently assumed.[8] At the outset,
the Supreme Judicial Court should not have deferred, using the
"clearly erroneous" standard, to the factual finding of the trial
court that the Parade lacked a message. Pet.Cert. at B24, C15.
Appellate courts must exercise de novo review over the record as
a whole when a trial court's findings are contrary to the
exercise of a First Amendment right. Bose Corp. v. Consumers
Union, 466 U.S. 485 (1984).
</p>
 <p>    More fundamentally, the First Amendment demands that the
sponsors of a parade be afforded broad deference in defining the
message of their parade. When the parade's sponsors asserted an
incompatibility between their intended message and the inclusion
of a contingent of gay and lesbian marchers, the First Amendment
rights of the sponsors were on a collision course with the wishes
of the excluded marchers. Once that collision is acknowledged,
the First Amendment requires that it be resolved in favor of the
private sponsor of the parade.
</p>
 <p>    While this Court has quite properly upheld anti-
discrimination provisions that bar large multi-purpose
organizations like eating clubs, labor unions, business groups
and service organizations from denying access to women and racial
minorities, a parade is an ephemeral association whose only
purpose is communication. As with political parties, when an
association's dominant purpose is expressive, the state may not
force its members to associate against their will, especially
when such forced association would alter the desired message. See
Tashjian v. Republican Party, 479 U.S. 208 (1986). See also
Roberts v. United States Jaycees, 468 U.S. 609, 627 (1984), id.
at 631-38 (O'Connor, J., concurring); Democratic Party of the
United States v. Wisconsin, 450 U.S. 107, 122 (1981) (freedom to
associate for the advancement of one's views "necessarily
presupposes the freedom to identify the people who constitute the
association, and to limit the association to those people only");
Eu v. San Francisco Democratic Committee, 489 U.S. 214 (1989).
</p>
  <p>   It is not clear, however, that the courts below accurately
characterized the allegedly private nature of the sponsorship of
the St. Patrick's Day Parade in Boston. Given the erroneous
assumption of the courts below that the First Amendment rights of
a private sponsor would not be violated by forcing the inclusion
of marchers bearing an unwanted message, the Massachusetts courts
were not compelled to explore the precise nature of the Parade's
sponsorship.[9] But, if this Court rules that the First Amendment
rights of a private parade sponsor would be violated by state-
mandated inclusion of marchers bearing an unwanted message,
whether or not the sponsorship is truly private becomes an issue
of critical importance.
</p>
  <p>   Throughout its history, the Boston Parade has been closely
bound up with the simultaneous celebration of a Massachusetts
civic holiday -- Evacuation Day -- commemorating George
Washington's first victory in the Revolutionary War. Indeed,
until 1992, Boston openly granted its official imprimatur to the
celebration of the combined holiday, including (but not limited
to) a significant subsidy with taxpayer funds. The Parade's
administration has been, and remains, closely tied to the Boston
City government. Finally, for the past half-century, the permit
for the Parade has been routinely allocated to the same nominally
private sponsor. See p.2, supra.
</p><p>
     Because the nature of the Parade's sponsorship was not fully
explored below, we respectfully suggest that the case be remanded
for fact-finding and an initial legal consideration of the scope
of governmental involvement in the sponsorship and administration
of Boston's St. Patrick's Day Parade. See Smith v. Allwright, 321
U.S. 649 (1944); Terry v. Adams, 345 U.S. 461; Edmonson v.
Leesville Concrete Co., 500 U.S. 614.
</p>

<h4>Footnotes:</h4>
<p>
[1] The Question Presented for review is whether petitioners can
be compelled to including "in their privately organized Parade, a
message the petitioners deemed unwarranted and antiethical."
Pet.Cert at i.</p>
<p>
[2] Much of the history discussed in this brief is derived from
Larry W. Yackle, "Parading Ourselves: Freedom of Speech at the
Feast of St. Patrick," 73 B.U. L.Rev. 791 (1993).
</p><p>
[3] The only connection between General Washington's victory and
Irish pride was the use of "St. Patrick" as the password for the
Revolutionary troops on the crucial day.
</p><p>
[4] According to the trial court, Boston apparently provides city
assistance of this sort to other parades as well. Id.
</p><p>
[5] The trial court emphasized that the Boston Parade has been
broadly inclusive and its opinion contains a long list of civic
and commercial organizations that marched in the 1992 Parade.
Pet.Cert. at 6-7. It is also undisputed, however, that the
Council has excluded from the Parade at least two other groups in
addition to GLIB: the Ku Klux Klan and ROAR, a local anti-busing
organization. Id. at B7.
</p><p>
[6] A similar order was entered with regard to the 1992 Parade.
GLIB v. City of Boston, No. 92-1518 (Suffolk County SuperCt.
