</p><p>
[7] For example, courts have imposed a shared access plan in
connection with sidewalk demonstrations in the vicinity of St.
Patrick's Cathedral in New York City during Gay Pride Week.
Opposing groups of 25 demonstrators alternate at 30 minute
intervals. Olivieri v. Ward, 801 F.2d 602, 607 (2d Cir.), cert.
denied, 480 U.S. 917 (1986).
</p><p>
[8] The reach of Massachusetts' public accommodations law is, of
course, solely an issue for the state courts. Only if the state
construction causes a violation of federal rights is the issue
before this Court. Pruneyard Shopping Center v. Robins,  447 U.S.
74 (1980).
</p><p>
[9] This Court followed a similar analytical path in Cousins v.
Wigoda, 419 U.S. 477 (1975), electing to dispose of the
substantive issue without first determining the precise status of
the parties.
</p>
