</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>ACLU in the Court</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">
<h1><i> ACLU amicus brief </i></h1>
<br>
<center>
<font color="#ff0033">Docket 94-329<br></font>
<h2><font color="3300ff">ROSENBERGER et al.<br>
 v.<br>
 RECTOR AND VISITORS<br>
 OF UNIVERSITY OF VIRGINIA et al.<br></font></h2>
<br>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
</center>
<br>
<blockquote>
<h4>STATEMENT OF THE CASE
</h4>
<p>The University of Virginia recognizes and provides facilities and services
to a wide range of student activities, known as &quot;Contracted Independent
Organizations&quot; (CIOs).  Most CIOs may also apply for student activity
funds, which are derived from an annual $14 student activity fee. 
</p>
<p>&quot;The purpose of the student activity fee is to provide financial support
for student organizations that are related to the educational purpose of
the University .... [T]he monies collected by the University of funding
student activities are public funds.  The University of Virginia
recognizes and provides facilities and services to a wide range of student
activities, known as &quot;Contracted Independent Organizations&quot; (CIOs).  Most
CIOs may also apply for student activity funds, which are derived from an
annual $14 student activity fee. hich must be administered in a manner
consistent with the educational purposes of the University as well as with
State and Federal law.&quot; 
</p>
<p>-- Rosenberger v. The Rector and Visitors of the University of Virginia,
793 F.Supp. 175, 180 (W.D.Va. 1992), aff'd, 18 F.3d 269 (3d Cir. 1994). 
</p>
<p>Pursuant to its guidelines, however, the University does not fund either
&quot;religious organizations&quot;[2] or &quot;religious activities.&quot;[3] If a student
organization is not disqualified on religious or other grounds, and its
goals are deemed generally &quot;consistent with the educational purposes of
the University,&quot; the University then examines the group more closely,
including investigation of possible discriminatory conduct, to decide if
the group should receive funding.  J.A. 71, paragraph 8. 
</p>
<p>The plaintiffs publish a student journal called &quot;Wide Awake:  A Christian
Perspective at the University of Virginia.&quot;  Although not affiliated with
any religious institution, the journal is pervasively and concededly
sectarian: its announced purpose is &quot;to challenge Christians to live, in
word and deed, according to the faith they proclaim[,] and to encourage
students to consider what a personal relationship with Jesus Christ
means,&quot;  Rosenberger, 18 F.3d at 272.  There is no dispute that &quot;Wide
Awake&quot; is a religious activity within the meaning of the University's
funding guidelines.  Id. at 273.  Accordingly, although it is a CIO with
access to University computers, printers, and other publication equipment,
id., its application for direct funding was denied.[4]
</p>
<p>Petitioners challenged the funding denial on free speech, free exercise,
and equal protection grounds.  The federal district court, ruling on the
cross motions for summary judgement, rejected all three claims.  793 F.
Supp. 175.  The court concluded that the student activity fund was a
nonpublic forum and the religious exclusion was reasonable and
viewpoint-neutral; that the funding denial did not substantially burden
petitioners' freedom of religion; and that no &quot;discriminatory intent&quot; was
shown with respect to alleged disparate funding of religious groups.  Id.
at 178-83.  Without fully addressing the Establishment Clause issue, the
district court did note that the University's refusal to fund religious
groups because of church-state concerns was &quot;reasonable.&quot;  Id. at 181. 
</p>
<p>The Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit affirmed, but gave more
scrupulous consideration to petitioners' free speech claims.  the court of
appeals concluded that the religious exclusion was a viewpoint-based
unconstitutional condition which could be upheld only if narrowly drawn
and justified by a compelling state interest.  18 F.3d at 277-83.[5] The
Fourth Circuit held that the Establishment Clause constituted such a
compelling interest because direct government funding of religious
activities like &quot;Wide Awake&quot; would violate two of the three prongs of the
test set forth by this Court in Lemon v. Kurtzman, 403 U.S. 602 (1971). 
</p>
<p>First, according to the court of appeals, funding would have a primary
effect of advancing religion because &quot;it would be difficult to view
awarding SAF monies to &quot;Wide Awake&quot; as anything but state sponsorship --
and therefore advancement -- of religious belief .... Using public funds
to support a publication so clearly engaged in the propagation of
particular religious doctrines would constitute a patent Establishment
Clause violation.&quot;  18 F.3d at 285.  Second, funding religious activities
would foster excessive government entanglement with religion, both because
of its &quot;potentially divisive political effect&quot; and because it would &quot;send
an unmistakably clear signal that the University of Virginia supports
Christian values.&quot;  Id. at 286.[6]
</p>
<p>The petition for certiorari followed.
</p>

<h4>SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT
</h4>
<p>This case presents a conflict between free speech and Establishment Clause
principles.  Under ordinary circumstances, government is barred from
requiring relinquishment of constitutional rights as a condition of access
to benefit programs.  Perry v. Sindermann, 408 U.S. 593, 597 (1972). 
</p>
<p>In addition, the Free Speech Clause requires viewpoint neutrality in the
government's distribution of subsidies or other benefits.  Regan v.
Taxation with Representation, 461 U.S. 540, 548 (1983).  thus, although
government may choose to subsidize one constitutionally protected activity
and not another, Rust v. Sullivan, 500 U.S. 173 (1991), it may not base
its decisions ont he viewpoints or ideas expressed by those seeking funds. 
This is particularly true for government programs that themselves support
free speech: universities, public fora, subsidies for scientific research
or the arts. 
</p>
<p>To the extent that religious expression is to be considered a &quot;viewpoint&quot;
for purposes of the speech clause, Lamb's Chapel, 113 S.Ct. at 2147-48,
such expression cannot ordinarily be denied government benefits, such as
access to meeting space, that are made available to other &quot;viewpoints.&quot; 
Under a viewpoint analysis, as the Fourth Circuit has held, the
University's exclusion of &quot;religious activities&quot; from funding eligibility
prima facie violates the principle of viewpoint neutrality. or under an
unconstitutional conditions analysis is presumptively defective int hat it
requires a sacrifice of expressive freedom for the sake of a government
benefit.[7]
</p>
<p>The Establishment Clause, however, prohibits direct government funding of
religion.  Bowen v. Kendrick, 487 U.S. 589 (1988); Committee for Public
Ed. and Religious Liberty v. Nyquist, 413 U.S. 756 (1973); Walz v. Tax
Comm'n, 397 U.S. 664 (1970).  Contrary to the Fourth Circuit's reasoning,
this is not because government funding necessarily implies endorsement. 
Indeed, it is a corollary of the principle of viewpoint neutrality that
government subsidies, especially in the area of free expression, no more
imply endorsement or sponsorship than does the government's maintenance of
public fora where all can speak, or public libraries where authors of
myriad viewpoints, from Marx to Madonna, are represented. 
</p>
<p>The Establishment Clause bars direct funding of religion for reasons
independent of implied endorsement.  Levying taxes to support religion was
the main abuse that the framers in drafting the Establishment Clause
sought to prevent.  The Clause is unique in recognizing that government
subsidy of religion through coercive taxation violates fundamental rights
of individual conscience.  When government funding for religion is
involved, therefore, the Establishment Clause is best understood as a
constitutionally ordained exception to the doctrines of unconstitutional
conditions and viewpoint neutrality.  Any other rule would, at the very
least, require the Court to reexamine nearly a half-century of cases
holding that the Establishment Clause forbids direct aid to parochial
education even though the state simultaneously supports a secular, public
education system.  In our view, such a drastic departure from precedent is
both unwarranted and unwise. 
</p>
<p>Petitioners argue that there is no meaningful difference between direct
funding and other benefits to which the University admits religious groups
are entitled:  meeting space, use of University facilities, even tax
exemption and credits.  But, as this Court explained in Walz, direct
payments differ materially from indirect and incidental forms of
assistance.  Indirect aid, ranging from police and fire services to tax
credits, does not require discretionary decisionmaking or the active,
affirmative transfer of government funds to church coffers.  In our
contemporary world, there is no way to sever religion from all forms of
government assistance, nor is such absolute separation constitutionally
required.  But direct subsidies are qualitatively different, and violate
the core meaning of the Establishment Clause, as the taxpayer standing
cases recognize.  See Valley Forge v. Americans United, 454 U.S. 464, 479
(1982). 
</p>
<p>A rule against direct financial support of religions activity does not
mean that no student publication or group that receives University funds
can address the question of religion, mount plays or art exhibits that
reflect religious issues, or print any articles written from a religious
viewpoint.  The Establishment Clause prohibits direct funding only of
pervasively sectarian activity, such as religious worship, training, and
proselytizing.  That the line-drawing may be difficult in some cases does
not m ean that it cannot be accomplished.  If the law were otherwise, the
Establishment and Free Exercise Clauses themselves would become
meaningless.  For every case involving either clause initially requires a
determination whether the activity in question is in fact religion. 
</p>
<center>
<hr width=60%>
</center>
<p>[1] Letters of consent to the filing of this brief have been lodged with
the Clerk of the Court pursuant to Rule 37.3. 
</p>
<p>[2] The University's guidelines define &quot;religious organization&quot; as &quot;an
organization whose purpose is to practice a devotion to an acknowledged
ultimate reality or deity.&quot;  Rosenberger, 18 F.3rd 269, 271 n.2 (3rd. Cir.
1994).  Fraternities and sororities, &quot;political&quot; organizations, and groups
with exclusionary membership policies are also ineligible for funding. 
</p>
<p>[3] The guidelines define &quot;religious activity&quot; as &quot;an activity which
primarily promotes or manifests a particular belief(s) in or about a deity
or an ultimate reality.&quot;  18 F.3rd at 271 n.2.  Other excluded
expenditures are &quot;honoraria or similar fees, . . . social entertainment
and related expenses, . . . philanthropic contributions and activities;
and . . . political activities.&quot;  Id. at 271. 
</p>
<p>[4] Because &quot;Wide Awake's&quot; funding application was denied, it was not
subjected to the post-approval process of determining how much financial
aid it should receive.  This process involves an evaluation of &quot;(1) the
size of the group; (2) the University-wide benefits conferred by the
group's activities; and (3) the group's financial self-sufficiency.&quot; 
Rosenberger 18 F.3rd at 271.  If an organization is approved for financial
aid, the University pays its cost directly after reviewing vouchers
submitted by the group and determining that the expenditures are proper. 
Id. 
</p>
<p>[5] The court did not view public forum analysis as necessary or
appropriate, given the factual context -- &quot;content-based discrimination
relating to government-generated burdens or benefits.&quot;  18 F.3rd at 287. 
</p>
<p>[6] The Fourth Circuit viewed the free exercise claim as &quot;abandoned,&quot; 18
F.3rd at 277 n.23; and disposed of the equal protection argument on the
ground that petitioners &quot;fail[ed] to argue discriminatory intent as a
matter of law.&quot;  Id at 288. 
</p>
<p>[7] Alternatively, to the extent that the religious expression in this
case is deemed excludable from University funding because of its religious
subject matter, Cornelius v, NAACP Legal Defense &amp; Educ. Fund, Inc., 473
U.S. 788, 806 (1985), the decision not to fund the expressive activity at
issue would be impermissible even in a nonpublic forum unless demonstrably
reasonable, and in a traditional public forum or its equivalent would
violate the free speech guarantee unless justified by a compelling
governmental interest.
</p>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
</blockquote>
<center>
<p>
