<html>
<head>
<title>Aclu in the Court</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">
<h1><i>Summary of Argument in ACLU amicus brief </i></h1>
<br>
<center>
<font color="#ff0033">Docket 93-7407<br></font>
<h2><font color="3300ff">O'NEAL <br>
v.<br>
 McANINCH, WARDEN<br></font></h2>
<br>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
</center>
<br>
<blockquote>
<h4>SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT
</h4>
<p>Prior to Chapman v. California, 386 U.S. 18 (1967), most courts
understood that constitutional error in a criminal case could never be
&quot;harmless&quot; and always warranted relief, either on direct review or in
federal habeas corpus.  That understanding changed after Chapman, where
the Court held that some constitutional errors at trial could be ignored
if it could be said with relative assurance that they had no effect on the
ultimate verdict. 
</p>
<p>In rationalizing this fundamental change in constitutional
jurisprudence, Chapman weighed the costs of automatic reversal against the
risks of erroneous conviction and concluded that the system could tolerate
some additional risk.  To ensure that the idea of harmless error remained
within close bounds, however, the Court held that no error could be
considered harmless unless the prosecution demonstrated, beyond a
reasonable doubt, that the error had not influenced the verdict. 
</p>
<p>The careful balance articulated in Chapman remained the governing
rule for more than two decades until last Term's decision in Brecht v.
Abrahamson, 113 S.Ct. 1710, which relaxed the standard for determining
harmless error in habeas corpus cases pursuant to 28 U.S.C. Section 2254. 
Under Brecht, constitutional trial error can be held harmless if it had no
&quot;substantial&quot; effect on the verdict within the meaning of the benchmark
harmless error case, Kotteakos v. United States, 328 U.S. 750 (1946). 
This standard, of course, created a greater risk of erroneous conviction
than the previously applicable Chapman rule. 
</p>
<p>Now, the risk of erroneous conviction has been increased still
further by the decision of the Sixth Circuit in this case to shift the
burden of proof with respect to harmless error to the prisoner.  The
circuit decision misapprehends the very nature of the decision the Court
made in Brecht and, in so doing, scrambles the doctrine worked out by the
combination of Brecht, Chapman, and Kotteakos in a way that threatens the
bedrock objectives of the criminal justice system:  accurate
determinations of guilt or innocence. 
</p>
<p>Shifting the burden of proof with respect to harmless error is out
of step with this Court's habeas decisions generally.  Those decisions
have justified various procedural barriers to the federal forum as efforts
to conserve scarce federal judicial resources and to respect legitimate
state interests.  The burden allocation the circuit court has adopted does
not streamline or expedite the processing of claims in habeas corpus, but
impedes the federal courts' ability to adjudicate properly preserved
claims on the merits. 
</p>
<p>In Brecht, this Court altered the standard by which federal habeas
corpus courts judge harmless error, but did not disturb the traditional
understanding that the burden of demonstrating that error was harmless
lies with the party who stands to benefit from an affirmative
determination:  the respondent. 
</p>
<p>As justification for this decision, the circuit court erroneously
relied on a single sentence in this Court's opinion in Brecht.  On close
examination, that sentence will not bear the weight the circuit attaches
to it.  Indeed, read as a whole, the Brecht opinion makes clear that the
Court in that case did not alter the settled norm regarding burdens of
proof. 
</p>
<p>The preservation of the burden on the respondent harmonizes the
framework for harmless error analysis in habeas corpus cases under 28
U.S.C. Section 2254 with practice under the federal harmless error
statute, 28 U.S.C. Section 2111; the relevant rule, Fed.R.Crim.P. 52(a);
and, indeed, the very decision to which Brecht looked for primary
guidance:  Kotteakos.  It also reconciles Brecht with this Court's cases
on the effects of procedural default. 
</p>
<p>The conventional allocation of the burden of proof to the state is
supported by solid, practical analysis.  It advances the accuracy of
criminal judgements, comports with ordinary expectations regarding the
allocation of burdens in constitutional litigation, and assigns
responsibility to the party with the incentive and capacity to develop the
relevant guidance and arguments. 
</p>
<p>A reallocation of the burden of proof with respect to harmless
error would complicate and confuse the determination of the merits of
claims in habeas corpus, distorting the habeas courts' understanding and
exposition of federal constitutional rights.  Those distortions would not
be offset by any practical benefits.  Both the federal courts and state
authorities would find their work more, not less, burdensome.
</p>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
</blockquote>
<center>
