<title>ACLU in the Courts</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">

<h1><i> Summary of Argument in ACLU amicus brief </font></i></h1>
<br>
<center>
<font color="#ff0033">Dockets 94-558 & 94-627<br></font>
<h3><font color="3300ff">United States, Appellant,<br>
v.<br>
Ray Hays, et al., Appellees.<br>
<br>
<br>
<p>State of Louisiana, et al.,<br>
Appellants<br>
v.<br>
Ray Hays, et al.,<br>
Appellees.
</font></h3>
<br>
</center>
<br>
<blockquote>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
<br>
<h4>                      Summary of Argument
</h4>
<p>     Affirmance of the decision below that race-conscious redistricting is
always subject to strict scrutiny without regard to bizarre shape and that
the state had no compelling interest in complying with the Voting Rights
Act or in remedying past discrimination would render constitutionally
suspect or invalidate most of the congressional, state, and local
redistricting plans in the South as well as in other parts of the nation.
A generation of litigation and administrative action under the Act would
be set aside that Congress, national administrations of both parties, and
this Court have endorsed as appropriate efforts to remedy the exclusion of
minorities from the political process. Existing majority-minority
districts would be invalidated and given the fact that minorities have
been elected almost exclusively in majority-minority districts,
legislative bodies at the national, state, and local levels would become
primarily white. 
</p>
<p>     The consideration of race in redistricting is not per se suspect and
is different from consideration of race in the allocation of scare
employment of contractual opportunities where an independent claim of
entitlement exists. Any racial groups may complain if its voting strength
has been abridged, but a non-dilutive race-conscious redistricting plan
injures no one. Congress has sanctioned the use of majority-minority
districts and has concluded that they do not isolate voters or increase
racial tension.
</p>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
</blockquote>
<center>
