<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">
<h1><i>ACLU Support Letter</i></h1>
<br>

<br>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
<blockquote>
<h4>November 9, 1995
</h4>
<h4>Re: Claims of Abraham Ahmad and Family<br> Under the Federal Tort Claims Act     
</h4>
<h4>Dear Sirs and Madams:
</h4>
<p>     This letter serves as a joint claim for damages under the Federal Tort
Claims Act filed on
behalf of Abraham Ahmad, his wife Martina Ahmad, and their minor children,
Sanna and Nesreen Ahmad.  The Ahmads' claims arise out of the actions of
various unknown employees of the United States Department of Justice, the
Federal Bureau of Investigation, the United States Custom Service, the
Immigration and Naturalization Service, and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms during the period of April 19 to 21, 1995.  Specifically, the
claims concern the detention and mistreatment of Mr. Ahmad by these employees
in the aftermath of the explosion of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building in
Oklahoma City, Oklahoma on April 19, 1995.
</p>

<p>     During the three days following the bombing, various employees of the
foregoing federal
agencies committed a number of tortious acts against Mr. Ahmad, with severe
consequences for
both Mr. Ahmad and his family.  As more fully described below, while
attempting to travel to
Jordan to visit his family, Mr. Ahmad was stopped by United States
authorities solely because of
his ethnicity.  From Wednesday through Friday he was detained by various
government officials,
first in Chicago, then in London, Virginia, and back in Oklahoma City.  He
was repeatedly
questioned, photographed, and fingerprinted.  He was deprived of food and
sleep, and denied
permission to call his family.  In London, he was strip-searched and then
paraded through a
crowded airport in handcuffs.  His luggage was unconstitutionally searched
without his permission and he was identified to the public and the media as a
suspect in the Oklahoma City bombing. During this three-day period Mr. Ahmad
was subjected to, inter alia, false arrest, false
imprisonment, abuse of process, invasion of privacy, injury to reputation,
and defamation.(1) 
Other members of the Ahmad family were also directly subjected to an invasion
of privacy.(2)
</p>

<p>     Mr. Abraham Ahmad seeks a sum certain of $1,013,350 for his personal
injuries, loss of
property, and pain and suffering as a result of this tortious conduct.  In
addition, Martina, Sanna,
and Nesreen Ahmad seek a sum certain of $305,850 each for the personal
injuries and pain and
suffering they experienced as a result of both the invasion of their privacy
and the torts committed against Abraham Ahmad.  The claimants believe that
such sums are fully justified under the circumstances; nevertheless, they are
willing to discuss settlements for different sums.  Finally, Mr. Ahmad seeks
an acknowledgment from the federal government that it is impermissible, and a
violation of the right to equal protection of the laws, to detain a person in
connection with a criminal investigation solely because of his ethnicity, and
without any evidence whatsoever of any culpability on his part.
</p>

<p>     Because of the complexity of this matter -- the number of claimants, the
number of federal
agencies involved, and the variety of causes of action -- the Ahmads are
submitting their claims
through this letter, rather than on Standard Form 95.  The remainder of this
letter details all of the information sought by Standard Form 95.
Nevertheless, upon request by any agency, claimants will be happy to
supplement the record with a completed Standard Form 95.
</p>

<h4>Federal Agencies Involved
</h4>

<p>     Tortious acts were committed against Mr. Abraham Ahmad and his family by
unknown
employees of the Federal Bureau of Investigation, the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, the United States Customs Service, the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, and the
Department of Justice.  Notice of the Ahmads' claims is being submitted to
each of these five
agencies, as well as the Department of the Treasury (as the parent agency for
the Customs Service and the BATF) and the Office of the United States
Attorney for the Western District of
Oklahoma.
</p>

<h4>Names of Claimants
</h4>

<ul>
<li>Abraham Ahmad<br>
<li>Martina Ahmad<br>
<li>Sanna Ahmad<br>
<li>Nesreen Ahmad<br></ul>
1820 Northwest 40, Oklahoma City, OK 73118
</p>

<h4>Name and Address of Claimants' Personal Representative
</h4>
<p>Louis M. Bograd<br>
American Civil Liberties Union Foundation<br>
122 Maryland Avenue, N.E. <br>
Washington, D.C. 20002<br>
</p>


<h4>Dates of Birth and Marital Status of Claimants
</h4>

<ul>
<li>Abraham Ahmad  7/15/63 Married<br>
<li>Martina Ahmad 6/25/65 Married<br>
<li>Sanna Ahmad 6/29/89 Single<br>
<li>Nesreen Ahmad 10/6/92 Single
</ul>

<h4>Dates of Tortious Conduct
</h4>
<p>April 19 - 21, 1995
</p>

<h4>Basis of Claim
</h4>

<p>     Abraham Ahmad is a naturalized American citizen who has lived in
Oklahoma since 1982. 
On April 19, 1995 he had planned to travel to Amman, Jordan to visit
relatives and to deal with a
family emergency.  He was scheduled to fly first to Chicago, then on to Rome,
and finally from
Rome to Amman.  The actions of a number of federal employees prevented him
from completing his trip.
</p>

<p>     Mr. Ahmad's flight out of Oklahoma City was scheduled to depart at 10:43
a.m.  He and
his family left their house about 9 a.m. to run a few errands before heading
to the airport.  They
arrived at the airport a little after 10 a.m.  At no point that day was Mr.
Ahmad anywhere near the
Murrah building.  In fact, to the best of his recollection, he had not been
in the vicinity of the
Murrah Building in over a year.
</p>

<p>     Mr. Ahmad brought five bags with him to the airport: two hand bags to be
carried with
him and three large suitcases to be checked.  Mr. Ahmad checked the suitcases
at the American
Airlines counter, paid an excess baggage fee, said goodbye to his family, and
left for Chicago.
</p>

<p>     Mr. Ahmad's flight arrived in Chicago at 12:30 p.m.  He was scheduled to
depart for
Rome on an Alitalia flight at 3:30 p.m.  Because Mr. Ahmad was considering an
export venture
with his brothers (whom he planned to see in Amman), he stopped by the
customs office to obtain some information about the import/export business.
He read some of the information he received, prayed, and then around 2 p.m.
headed toward the gate for his Alitalia flight.  Near the gate area he saw a
television monitor broadcasting a news report about the bombing in Oklahoma
City.  This was the first he learned of the explosion of the Murrah Building.
</p>

<p>     While Mr. Ahmad was watching the news report he was approached by two or
three
federal employees, who he believes were from the Immigration and
Naturalization Service (INS). 
On information and belief, these INS employees stopped Mr. Ahmad solely
because he was an
Arab American traveling from Oklahoma City.  They instructed him to come with
them, took him
to a small room, and began to question him.  Mr. Ahmad answered all of their
questions.
</p>

<p>     Mr. Ahmad's hand bags and papers were taken by the government employees
and
searched.  The government employees did not ask Mr. Ahmad for permission to
search his bags
and he did not offer them permission to do so.
</p>

<p>     Other federal employees came into the interview room.  Mr. Ahmad
estimates that there
were five federal employees in the room with him, from both the INS and the
United States
Customs Service (Customs).  In addition, there were guards posted outside the
door.  
</p>

<p>     Mr. Ahmad definitely perceived that he was not free to leave.  At one
point he attempted
to stand to respond to a question by one INS agent, when another officer
ordered him to sit down
and not to move.  When Mr. Ahmad told them he was afraid he was going to miss
his flight, they
told him: &quot;Don't worry about it.  We'll get you another one.&quot;  
</p>

<p>     Mr. Ahmad's questioning in this first room continued for approximately
an hour and a
half.  Then he was escorted by at least five federal employees to another
room for fingerprinting. 
Federal officers stayed with him even when he went to a bathroom to wash his
hands after
fingerprinting.  
</p>

<p>     Mr. Ahmad was then taken to another room and told to wait there.  He was
guarded by
two federal officers, one inside the room and one outside.  After waiting for
approximately thirty
minutes, two agents from the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) arrived
and took him to yet
another room for further questioning and photographing.  The FBI agents,
accompanied by two
or three other federal employees, questioned him for approximately two hours,
repeating many of the same questions he had already answered.  They again
went through his hand bags and asked him questions about their contents.  The
FBI agents seized two tubes of caulking Mr. Ahmad was carrying to repair the
sink in his father's house in Jordan.  They paid him four dollars for the
caulk and gave him a receipt.  
</p>

<p>     Finally, at around 7:00 or 8:00 p.m., after Mr. Ahmad had been detained
for five to six
hours in Chicago, the FBI agents told him they were sorry and that they were
going to get him
another ticket to Jordan.  The government agents then booked him on a British
Airways flight
from Chicago to London's Heathrow Airport and then on a Royal Jordanian
Airlines flight from
Heathrow to Amman.  The departure time for the latter flight was so soon
after the scheduled
arrival time for the British Airways flight that it would have been
impossible for Mr. Ahmad to
make the connection.  When Mr. Ahmad explained this to the government agents
they told him
not to worry about it; he could deal with any problem in London.  They then
returned his hand
bags and papers and took him to the door of his British Airways airplane.
Thus, he was
effectively in detention until at least the moment he boarded his flight.
</p>

<p>     Mr. Ahmad's mistreatment did not end with his departure from Chicago.
As he had
predicted, his flight arrived at Heathrow Airport on the morning of April 20
too late to make his
connecting flight to Amman.  He then learned that the next flight to Jordan
was not for two days. 
Because Mr. Ahmad has a brother who lives in London, he figured he could stay
with him during
the interim.  However, he never got a chance to visit his brother, because he
was detained by
British authorities and denied permission to enter the country.  On
information and belief, all of
the wrongful treatment Mr. Ahmad experienced in London -- described in the
following
paragraphs -- occurred as a result of instructions from and at the behest of
unknown employees of the United States government in the United States.  As
such, it is actionable under the Federal
Tort Claims Act.
</p>

<p>     When Mr. Ahmad attempted to pass through British immigration control, he
was forced to
wait for approximately twenty minutes.  Then approximately six or seven
British government
personnel approached him and ordered him to come with them.  They took him to
a small room
and ordered him to remove all of his clothes.  For a Muslim, appearing naked
before strangers is
sinful and offensive.  Although he was not physically touched during this
strip search, he was
ordered to bend over for a visual inspection.  After his clothes were
thoroughly searched, he was
allowed to redress.
</p>

<p>     Because Mr. Ahmad was tired, scared, and hungry, he asked for something
to eat.  This
request was denied, though he was given some coffee to drink.  He asked if he
could call his
family to let them know that he was all right and that he would not be
arriving in Jordan as
scheduled.  This request was denied.  He invoked his right as a U.S. citizen
to meet with an
American consular official, but he was not permitted to do so.  His hand bags
were taken from
him without his permission.  He would not see them again until Friday
afternoon back in the
United States.
</p>

<p>     Mr. Ahmad was not questioned by the British authorities, but he was held
for
approximately four hours.  After that time, the head of the British
authorities said to him: &quot;You
are under arrest.  You have to go back to the United States.&quot;  Mr. Ahmad was
then handcuffed to
be taken to another location.  He asked to have his jacket placed over his
hands to hide the
handcuffs, but this request was also denied.  He was then paraded through the
airport so that
other passengers could see him in handcuffs and taken to another small room
to await his flight
back to the United States and the arrival of the FBI.  He was given a notice
by British
Immigration authorities refusing him permission to enter the United Kingdom
as a transit
passenger on the grounds that his &quot;exclusion from the United Kingdom is
conducive to the public
good.&quot;  (A copy of this notice is attached to this letter.)  
</p>

<p>     After being confined in this new room for one to two hours, Mr. Ahmad
was informed
that his flight was ready.  He was again marched through the airport in
handcuffs, this time
surrounded by approximately fourteen government agents.  He boarded the plane
in handcuffs and was greeted by stares and whispers from the other
passengers.  Mr. Ahmad was guarded by one British officer and two FBI agents
the entire flight.  He was too embarrassed to use the restroom on the
airplane, knowing that he would have to walk through the plane in handcuffs
and
accompanied by a guard to get to the restroom.
</p>

<p>     The airplane landed at Dulles Airport in Virginia at 6:00 or 7:00 p.m.
on Thursday
evening, April 20.  Mr. Ahmad was instructed not to move until all the other
passengers had
disembarked.  Then, three FBI agents entered the plane to take Mr. Ahmad out.
The agents led
him to a bus right outside the plane where approximately another fifteen
agents were waiting for
him.  Mr. Ahmad was then taken to a government office at the airport, where
he was
refingerprinted and rephotographed.  Mr. Ahmad was then taken to a darkened
van and
transported approximately forty-five minutes to an unknown destination.
</p>

<p>     During the ride in the van, Mr. Ahmad was handed two pieces of paper.
The first was a
form authorizing the FBI to search his luggage.  Mr. Ahmad was reluctant to
sign the form, but
eventually agreed to sign after first appending a statement to the effect
that: &quot;The FBI in Chicago
questioned me for about six hours, and they searched my bags, found nothing
and they told me to go, because they had nothing on me.&quot;  Such an
authorization was not voluntary and, in any event, was ineffective because,
as discussed above, Mr. Ahmad's hand baggage had already been searched
improperly without his permission and, as discussed below, it also appears
that his checked luggage had already been searched prior to the time he
signed the authorization form. 
</p>

<p>     The second form handed to Mr. Ahmad was a statement of his rights.  This
form confused
Mr. Ahmad, because, despite what he had been told by British authorities,  he
had been led to
understand that he was not under arrest.  An FBI agent confirmed that Mr.
Ahmad was not under
arrest, but that he needed to know his rights and the system.  Mr. Ahmad
asked: &quot;If that is true,
why did no one tell me my rights in Chicago?&quot;
</p>

<p>     Mr. Ahmad was taken to a building at an unknown location, presumably in
Virginia.  He
was again told to wait in a room.  Shortly, two FBI agents and two agents
from the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms (BATF) entered the room, showed him their
badges, and began to question him.  They questioned Mr. Ahmad for
approximately two hours.  Many of the questions concerned the contents of his
checked luggage and the questions revealed that the government agents were
familiar with the contents of that luggage.  This clearly indicates that Mr.
Ahmad's checked baggage had been searched before the time he was asked to
sign the authorization to search in the van.(3)
</p>
<p>     The FBI and BATF agents questioned Mr. Ahmad until 11:00 or 12:00 at
night.  They
then offered to put him up in a room in the FBI building for the night.  Mr.
Ahmad said that he
would rather go home to his wife and children, but they replied that there
were no further flights
to Oklahoma City that evening and they might have more questions for him the
next day.  Feeling he had no other choice, Mr. Ahmad agreed to stay at the
FBI building.  Mr. Ahmad believes that his room was monitored by video
camera, so that he was under surveillance the entire night.  The agents
permitted him to use the telephone so that he could call his family in
Jordan; presumably this call was monitored as well.
</p>

<p>     The next day, Friday April 21, the agents returned to ask Mr. Ahmad some
further questions. 
They returned his hand bags to him and reviewed their contents with him to
make sure that he had all his stuff.  Mr. Ahmad signed a voucher for the
return of his bags.  Subsequently, Mr. Ahmad realized that three videotapes
that had been in these bags had been removed by the FBI.  He asked the FBI
agents about them and was assured that they would be returned.  To date, the
FBI has not restored the videotapes to Mr. Ahmad.
</p>

<p>     Around 3:00 p.m. Mr. Ahmad and the FBI agents left to go to National
Airport.  Two FBI
agents accompanied him on a Northwest Airlines flight to Memphis, Tennessee.
While waiting
for their connecting flight in Memphis, Mr. Ahmad overheard two men
discussing press reports
that Middle Eastern men had been arrested in Chicago and London for the
bombing of the Murrah building.  He realized that they were talking about him
and for the first time realized that the public had been given information
linking him to the bombing.
</p>

<p>     The connecting flight to Oklahoma City did not arrive until 10:00 p.m.
Friday evening. 
Mr. Ahmad and the agents traveling with him were met at the airport by two
other FBI agents. 
Mr. Ahmad was taken downstairs and questioned for approximately another
fifteen minutes by
one of the agents.  The FBI agent then told Mr. Ahmad that he would have to
return for a
polygraph examination.(4)  The FBI agent also instructed Mr. Ahmad that he
should not leave his
home without informing the FBI of his whereabouts.  After another half hour
or forty-five minutes
of delay, the agents drove Mr. Ahmad to his home.  For the first time in
three days he was not in
government custody.
</p>

<p>     While all of the above was happening directly to Mr. Ahmad, a number of
additional
tortious acts were being committed out of his presence.  These include the
following:
</p>

<p>     First, as already discussed, his checked baggage was searched without
his permission.
</p>

<p>     Second, some unknown employee of the Justice Department apparently
obtained a
warrant for Mr. Ahmad's detention as a material witness in connection with
the explosion at the
Murrah Building.  Given that there was absolutely no information linking Mr.
Ahmad in any way
to the bombing, this warrant could not have been supported by probable cause.
A knowing
application for a warrant without valid probable cause would constitute an
abuse of process and
represent an additional tortious act committed against Mr. Ahmad.
</p>

<p>     Third, FBI agents came to the Ahmad home and questioned Martina Ahmad
extensively
on April 19 and 20.  The agents tried to convince Mrs. Ahmad that her husband
had hidden
information from her and misled her about his plans by telling her that Mr.
Ahmad had flown to
London rather than to Jordan.  Although Mrs. Ahmad's brother was present for
much of this
interrogation, some of the questioning was conducted by a male agent without
the presence of any male relative.  This violated Mrs. Ahmad's religious
beliefs, under which a Muslim woman is
forbidden  to be in the presence of an unrelated male, unless her husband,
father, or brother is also present.  Both for this reason and because of the
nature of the interrogation, Mrs. Ahmad was extremely upset by this
questioning.
</p>

<p>     Finally, on information and belief, one or more unknown federal
employees, revealed
information about Mr. Ahmad's detention and his purported link to the bombing
to the press and
or the public.  These false comments and improper release of information led
to a rash of
defamatory press reports, a tidal wave of press harassment of the other
members of the Ahmad
family, and hostile and abusive behavior by the Ahmads' neighbors and other
local residents. 
Reporters started to show up at the Ahmad house on Thursday in such numbers
that Martina
Ahmad had to call the police to remove them from the yard.  People drove by
shouting obscenities and threw trash in the Ahmads' yard.  Eventually, Mrs.
Ahmad had to take her daughters to a friend's apartment to escape the media
and public onslaught.  This invasion of privacy has had consequences for the
mental health of the Ahmad family that continue to this day.
</p>

<p>     Mr. Ahmad eventually made the trip to Jordan that had been prevented by
his unlawful
detention in April.  He brought his daughter Sanna with him to shield her
from lingering hostility
in Oklahoma City.  She remains there today.  When Mr. Ahmad returned to the
United States on
September 16, he was stopped by two or three Customs officers in Chicago,
including one who
had questioned him in April.  The Customs officers took him aside for an
intensive search of his
luggage.  For twenty or thirty minutes, they combed through his belongings
piece by piece.  They
found nothing.
</p>


<h4>Property Loss and Economic Injuries
</h4>

<p>     Mr. Ahmad experienced a number of losses of property and instances of
economic damage
as a result of the foregoing misconduct, for some of which he has already
received compensation from the government (as noted below).  These economic
injuries include the following:
</p>

<p><b>1.  Lost value of plane ticket for round-trip travel to Amman, Jordan and
incidental air-travel
expenses:</b> compensation received.  (Mr. Ahmad has received reimbursement for
the cost of a new one-way ticket to Amman, plus the fee for changing the date
of his return flight, as well as
reimbursement for the fee he had paid for excessive checked baggage.)
</p>

<p><b>2.  Loss of use of contents of checked luggage:</b> estimated value of $700
(because Mr. Ahmad had been planning a two month trip to Jordan, he had
packed virtually all of his clothes in his three checked suitcases.  The
government did not return these suitcases to him until early July, two and a
half months after the bombing.  Because of the delay in the return of his
luggage, Mr. Ahmad had to buy replacement items for use during the interim.)
</p>

<p><b>3. Loss of earnings:</b> estimated value of $4,000 (Mr. Ahmad had to leave his
job in order to travel
to Jordan to deal with family matters.  Because his trip was postponed for
two and a half months
as a result of his detention, his return to the workforce has been delayed by
a comparable amount of time.  The estimate is based upon his wage rate at his
last place of employment, but will be adjusted once Mr. Ahmad establishes a
wage rate in a new position.)
</p>

<p><b>4. Increased telephone bills resulting from Mr. Ahmad's detention and the
postponement and
rescheduling of his trip to Jordan:</b> estimated value of $1,000.
</p>

<p><b>5. Cost of travel to Mexico and Jordan for Ahmad children:</b> estimated value of
$1,800  (In order
to escape some of the harassment and attention and to relieve some of their
elder daughter's
anxiety and fear (discussed below), Mr. and Mrs. Ahmad took their daughters
to stay with Mrs.
Ahmad's family in Juarez, Mexico for a period of time following Mr. Ahmad's
detention.  Then
Mr. Ahmad took his oldest daughter, Sanna, with him on his delayed trip to
Jordan, where she
remains at the present time.)
</p>

<p><b>6. Loss of three videotapes:</b> substantial sentimental value (As noted above,
the FBI has never
returned three videotapes taken from Mr. Ahmad's luggage.  Each is the only
copy of an Ahmad
family home movie.  While these tapes have only a nominal economic value,
they have substantial sentimental value which must be factored into the
calculation of personal injuries.)
</p>


<h4>Personal Injuries 
</h4>

<p>     All four members of the Ahmad family(5) sustained personal injuries and
experienced
substantial pain and suffering as a result of the tortious conduct described
above.  Mr. Ahmad is
entitled to compensation for his loss of liberty during his three days of
unlawful detention, as well
as for the injury to his reputation resulting from his unjustified linkage to
a heinous crime.  In
addition, each member of the Ahmad family is entitled to compensation for the
cost of present and future treatment for the psychological effects of their
experiences, as well as compensation for the pain and suffering and extreme
emotional distress they experienced as a result of the actions of federal
government employees.  These injuries are briefly described in this section.
No amount of money could fully compensate Abraham Ahmad and his family for
these injuries.  Nevertheless, an overall value for these claims is given in
the &quot;Amount of Claim&quot; section below.
</p>

<p>     <b>Loss of Liberty:</b>  For three days, Mr. Abraham Ahmad was effectively held
in government
custody.  At no time was he free to leave or go someplace other than where
government agents
wished him to go.  At all times (except possibly for the flight from Chicago
to London) he was
accompanied by government agents or under their active surveillance.  He was
deprived of food
and sleep, was periodically handcuffed, and was forced to submit to a
complete strip search and
visual body inspection.  
</p>

<p>    <b> Injury to Reputation:</b> Mr. Ahmad's reputation was severely damaged when
his name was
associated with the bombing of the Murrah building.  Prejudice against Arab
Americans is already great in this country without having one's name
associated with a vicious terrorist act.  Millions of Americans watched
television reports concerning Mr. Ahmad's detention in Chicago and London.
This image meshed neatly with many Americans preconceptions, encouraged by
many commentators, that the bombing had the markings of a Middle Eastern
terrorist attack.  The Ahmads' neighbors were encouraged to find suspicion in
Mr. Ahmad's past behavior, including even his contribution to the local Heart
Fund.  Presumably based on information provided by United States government
employees, Mr. Ahmad was denied admission to the United Kingdom as an
undesirable person, which may have repercussions for his future travel to
that country or elsewhere in the European Community.  While the dignity and
graciousness Mr. Ahmad exhibited during the period immediately following his
detention did much to restore his reputation, the damage to his good name was
substantial and tragic.
</p>

<p>    <b> Pain and Suffering and Emotional Distress:</b> All four members of the Ahmad
family have
experienced substantial pain and suffering and emotional trauma as a result
of their mistreatment.  It would be impossible to describe fully the
emotional consequences they have experienced.  Mr. Ahmad experienced extreme
feelings of fear during his detention, as well as intense embarrassment and
humiliation during his strip search, when he was forced to appear in public
in handcuffs, and when he learned that he had been publicly identified with
the bombing.  Martina Ahmad was traumatized when, as a result of her
husband's initial detention, she was questioned extensively at her home by
male FBI agents, in violation of her religious principles that prohibit her
from being alone with a man without the presence of a male relative.  In
addition, Mrs. Ahmad and the two girls feared for the well-being of their
husband and father.  They also feared for their own safety when they were
hounded by the press and passersby at their home.  Both Abraham and Martina
Ahmad have found that they have had difficulty eating and sleeping since this
experience.  Abraham Ahmad has experienced nightmares and Martina Ahmad now
feels unsafe in Oklahoma City and wants to move.  Their elder daughter,
Sanna, continues to fear that the police are going to come back and take her
daddy away.  Finally, all members of the family are experiencing the pain of
family separation, because Sanna is now living with relatives in Jordan to
shield her from continuing public attention and hostility.
</p>

<p>   <b>  Medical Treatment and Counseling:</b>Because Mr. Ahmad is currently
unemployed, the
Ahmad family has not been able to afford private medical treatment or
counseling.  They have
received some preliminary counseling from a licensed professional counselor
at Project Heartland, a state agency set up to assist the victims of the
Murrah building explosion.  The counselor, Gary Flynn, believes that all four
members of the Ahmad family have been traumatized by this experience.  He
observed the symptomatology of Post Traumatic Stress in each member of the
family and recommends a minimum of six months to a year or more of weekly
individual, family and relationship counseling.  A second counselor, who
accompanied Mr. Flynn on his visit to the Ahmad family, concurs in his
diagnosis and recommended course of treatment and recently has begun to
provide counseling to the Ahmad family.  A full year of the recommended
counseling would cost approximately $23,400 for the entire family, or $5,850
for each family member.
</p>

<h4>Witnesses
</h4>

<p>     Apart from the Ahmad family itself, the principal witnesses to the
events described above
are the unknown federal government employees who were responsible for Mr.
Ahmad's
mistreatment, as well as any British or Italian authorities who participated
in these activities.  Mr.
Ahmad and his family do not have names and addresses for these employees.  In
addition,
numerous media reports concerning Mr. Ahmad's detention should be available.
Finally, friends
of the Ahmad family, as well as doctors and counselors can provide
information concerning the
injuries suffered by the family as a result of these events.  Names of such
witnesses can be
provided upon request.
</p>


<h4>Amount of Claims
</h4>

<p>     The Ahmad family has not attempted to apportion their claims among the
various federal
agencies involved, because they believe that these agencies are jointly and
severally responsible for their injuries.  In addition to the amounts
identified in the previous sections, Mr. Ahmad seeks $1,000,000 for his loss
of liberty, injury to reputation, and pain and suffering, while the other
members of the Ahmad family seek $300,000 each for the pain and suffering and
emotional distress they experienced.  The following table summarizes the
total sum certain sought by each claimant:
</p>

<center>
<table border=10>
<tr>
<th>Claimant</th> <th> Property Damage</th>    <th> Personal Injury</th>    <th> Total Claim</th>
</tr>
<tr><td>Abraham Ahmad</td>  <td>$ 7,500</td>    <td>  $1,005,850 </td><td> $ 1,013,350 </td>
</tr>
<tr><td>Martina Ahmad</td>  <td>$0</td>    <td>  $305,850 </td><td>$305,850  </td>
</tr>
<tr><td>Sanna Ahmad</td>  <td>$0</td>    <td>  $305,850 </td><td>$305,850  </td>
</tr>
<tr><td>Nesreen Ahmad</td>  <td>$0</td>    <td>  $305,850 </td><td>$305,850  </td>
</tr>
<tr><td><b>Total Claims</b></td>  <td>$7500</td>    <td>$1,923,400</td><td>$1,930,900</td>
</tr>
</table>
</center>
<p>     On behalf of my clients, I certify that the amount of claim covers only
damages and
injuries caused by the accident above and agree to accept said amount in full
satisfaction and final settlement of their respective claims.
</p>

<h4>Date of Claim: November 9, 1995         
</h4>

<h4>Louis M. Bograd<br>
American Civil Liberties Union Foundation<br>
</h4>


<p>     The Ahmad family has no insurance coverage applicable to the events
described above.
</p>


<h4>Conclusion
</h4>

<p>     The Ahmad family is interested in obtaining a prompt and fair resolution
of their claims, so
that they can put this unfortunate incident behind them.  To that end, we
stand ready to provide
any additional information we can to assist in the investigation of these
claims.  Similarly, it would assist us in evaluating any settlement offer if
you would identify for us the various government employees involved in these
events and share with us the fruits of your investigation into these claims.
We would be happy to meet with representatives of any or all of the federal
agencies involved to discuss an amicable resolution of this matter.
</p>

<h4>Sincerely,
</h4>

<h4>Louis M. Bograd, Counsel to the Ahmad Family
</h4>
<center>
<hr width=60%>
</center>
