<h4>ENDNOTES:
</h4>

<p>1 - Although defamation is not actionable under the Federal Tor Claims Act
(FTCA), Mr. Ahmad
may recover up to $50,000 from the Attorney General for injury caused by an
investigative or law enforcement officer employed by the Department of
Justice pursuant to 31 U.S.C. section 3724. Mr. Ahmad asks that this claim be
considered along with his claims pursuant to the FTCA.
</p>


<p>2 - In addition, these same unknown employees of the aforementioned federal
agencies violated
Mr. Ahmad's constitutional rights to due process, to equal protection, and to
be free form
unlawful searches and seizures, under the Fourth and Fifth Amendments to the
United States
Constitution.  If it becomes necessary to initiate litigation to resolve the
Ahmad family's tort
claims, Mr. Ahmad may also seek relief for these constitutional violations
through a Bivens action against the responsible federal employees.
</p>


<p>3 - Mr. Ahmad's checked bags had been sent to Rome, the second connection
point on his
original itinerary.  It is unclear whether the search of his checked baggage
occurred in Italy or the
United States and whether it was physically carried out by American or
Italian authorities. 
Nevertheless, on information and belief, the search of these bags was carried
out under
instructions from and at the behest of federal employees in the United States
and thus is actionable under the Federal Tort Claims Act.
</p>


<p>4 - Later, after Timothy McVeigh had been identified as the principal suspect
in the bombing, the
FBI decided not to conduct the polygraph examination of Mr. Ahmad.
</p>


<p>5 - Mr. Ahmad's relatives in Jordan also experienced severe emotional
distress and pain and
suffering as a result of his detention.  When they learned that their
son/brother had been detained by government authorities for three days, they
feared that he had been beaten and tortured.
</p>
</blockquote>
