<head>
<title>Aclu in the Court</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">
<h1><i> Summary of Argument in ACLU amicus brief </i></h1>
<br>
<center>
<font color="#ff0033">No. 93-1636<br></font>
<h2><font color="3300ff">SWINT et al. <br>
v. <br>
CHAMBERS COUNTY
COMMISSION et al.</font></h2>
<br>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
</center>
<br>
<blockquote>
<h4>SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT
</h4>
<p>The court of appeals decided that Chambers County, Alabama, lacks
any &quot;general law enforcement authority.&quot;  Pet. App. 34a.  Because the
County has no law enforcement authority, the court reasoned, it was
impossible for Sheriff James Morgan to be the final law enforcement
official of the County.  Id.  By so holding, the court effectively
immunized Chambers County from the consequences of Sheriff Morgan's
actions. 
</p>
<p>The court of appeals was able to reach its conclusion only by
ignoring the county-based law enforcement scheme that is clearly
established under Alabama law.  Although the court of appeals held that
state law provides instruction on the scope of Section 1983 liability, it
failed to consider whether county sheriffs actually function as state or
county officials.  When Alabama law is examined with respect to its system
of law enforcement, it is clear that Chambers County provides law
enforcement for the county and that Sheriff Morgan is the final
policymaker for law enforcement in that county. 
</p>
</blockquote>
<center>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
<p>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
