<html>
<head>
<title>ACLU in the Courts</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">
<h1><i> Summary of Argument in ACLU amicus brief </i></h1>
<p>
<center>
<font color="#ff0033">Criminal No. 95-80106<br></font>
<h2><font color="3300ff">UNITED STATES OF AMERICA,<br>
Plaintiff,<br>
v.<br>					
JAKE BAKER and ARTHUR GONDA,<br>Defendants.<br></font></h2>
<br>
<br>
</center>
</p>
<blockquote>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
<h4>	Statement of the Case
</h4>

<p>	The superseding indictment is in five counts.  Each charges the defendant Jake Baker with having violated 18 U.S.C. 875(c) by transmitting in interstate and foreign commerce communications containing a threat to injure (or, in one instance, to kidnap) another person.  All of the communications referred to in the superseding indictment are e-mail (electronic mail) messages exchanged early in December 1994 with the pseudonymous Arthur Gonda at an address in Toronto.  E-mail is an electronic transmission system through which persons can privately communicate with each other via desktop computers.
</p>
<p>  	The original charge against Mr. Baker was based in part on pornographic fiction that he openly posted on a portion of the Internet called &quot;alt.sex.stories.&quot;  The superseding indictment is based entirely on private messages exchanged with Gonda, copies of which were obtained from Mr. Baker (or with his cooperation) once he was under investigation. 
</p>
<p>	In these messages, Mr. Baker confided to Gonda that he increasingly thought about acting out his sadistic sexual fantasies.  Taken in context, as defendant's brief indicates, these thoughts themselves may have been mostly fantasy.  In any event, the first four counts of the indictment are based in effect on Mr. Baker's saying to Gonda that he has thought (or, in count four, dreamed) about perpetrating abduction, rape, mutilation, and murder.  The fifth count relies on an exchange in which Gonda and Mr. Baker talk about getting together, perhaps to enact their fantasies, &quot;[i]f not next week, or in January, then defin[ite]ly sometime in the Summer.&quot;
</p>
<p>	Thus the indictment depends on reading the word &quot;threat&quot; in 875(c) to include any expression to anyone of an apparent desire to commit a particular type of crime, without regard to whether there is an imminent danger that the crime actually will be committed.  This is not what the term &quot;threat&quot; usually means. Moreover, this reading of the statute is incompatible with the principle of free speech incorporated in the First Amendment.  

<h4>	Argument
</h4>
<h4>I.   THE STATEMENTS ATTRIBUTED TO THE DEFENDANT IN THE INDICTMENT DO NOT CONSTITUTE &quot;THREATS&quot; INDICTABLE UNDER 18 U.S.C. 875(c).
</h4>
<blockquote>
<p>	(a)<i> The Meaning of &quot;Threat&quot;</i>
</p>
<p>	Ordinarily, in legal usage, the term &quot;threat&quot; refers to the expression of a real or apparent intent to injure which operates either (1) to compel someone to act or abstain from a particular act, or (2) otherwise to induce fear on the part of the auditor or those to whom the immediate auditor can be expected to relay the threat. See, generally, &quot;Threats &amp; Unlawful Communications,&quot; 86 C.J.S. 1 et seq.; &quot;Extortion, Blackmail, and Threats,&quot; 31A Am.Jur.2d 3,  49-73. On 18 U.S.C. 875(c), in particular, see Anno., 34 A.L.R. Fed. 785. 
</p>
<p>
	General dictionaries sometimes define &quot;threat&quot; to refer in a figurative sense to any &quot;indication of impending evil&quot; (Oxford English Dictionary); but doom-saying as such is not usually prohibited by law, and threats typically have been the object of legal restraint only insofar as they are apt unjustifiably to coerce or to create apprehension on the part of auditors.  Thus, &quot;[t]here are two basic types of threat statutes....  The first type punishes threats to compel action or inaction by a person against his or her will.   The second... punishes threats used to frighten rather than coerce.&quot;  31A Am.Jur.2d 49, at 619.
</p><p>
	Both kinds of threats involve immediate harm.  The first kind of coercive manipulative threat interferes with the freedom of choice or autonomy of the person to whom the threat is directed. The second kind of fear-inducing or terroristic threat creates anxiety and disruption.
</p><p>
	(b)<i> The Meaning of &quot;Threat&quot; in 18 U.S.C. 875(c)</i>
</p>
<p>	When first enacted in 1934, the statute now codified at 18 U.S.C. 875 punished only interstate transmission of threats designed to extort money or other things of value.  The statute was amended in 1939 to include threats to injure the person of another without an intent to extort.  See United States v. Heller, 579 F.2d 990, 995-98 (6th Cir. 1978); United States v. Pennell, 144 F.Supp. 317, 318-19 (N.D. Calif. 1956).  Thus, under the present statute, the threat need not be coercive; it is sufficient that it induces apprehension.  The harm that is the touchstone of whether a threat in the sense of 875(c) exists is &quot;fear of violence&quot; and &quot;the disruption that fear engenders.&quot;  R.A.V. v. City of St. Paul, 112 S.Ct. 2538, 2546, 120 L.Ed.2d 305, 321 (1992).  In this respect, for purposes of 875(c), &quot;a threat is not a state of mind in the threatener; it is an appearance to the victim.&quot;  United States v. Cox, 957 F.2d 264, 266 (6th Cir. 1992), quoting United States v. Holzer, 816 F.2d 304, 310 (7th Cir.), vacated on other grounds, 484 U.S. 807 (1987).
</p>
<p>	This emphasis on the auditor's response accounts for certain odd features of the law relating to threats under 875(c), on which the Government's proposed jury instruction in the present case relies: 
<blockquote>
<p>	1. Neither an actual intent nor the present ability to carry out the threat are said to be required. United States v. Holder, 302 F.Supp. 296, 300 (D. Mont. 1969), aff'd per curiam, 427 F.2d 715 (9th Cir. 1970).  Threatening to kill a non-existent hostage would constitute a sufficient threat if the context made it credible.  See United States v. Cooper, 523 F.2d 8 (6th Cir. 1975), although actually a case under 18 U.S.C. 875(b).
</p>
<p>	2. In most circuits, the accused does not even have to intend that the recipient fear that the threat will be carried out.  The Ninth Circuit requires &quot;specific intent.&quot; United States v. Twine, 853 F.2d 676, 679-81 (9th Cir. 1988).  Elsewhere, including the Sixth Circuit, the question is whether the defendant reasonably should have known that his statement would be perceived as a serious expression of an intent to injure.  It is sufficient, in other words, that a defendant who should have known better created the apprehension of injury.  United States v. DeAndino, 958 U.S. 146 (6th Cir. 1992), cert. denied, 112 S.Ct. 2997, 120 L.Ed.2d 874 (1992).  Accord, United States v. Darby, 37 F.3d 1059 (4th Cir, 1994).  For a similar interpretation of cognate statutes, see United States v. Smith, 928 F.2d 740 (6th Cir. 1991); United States v. Vincent, 681 F.2d 462, 464 (6th Cir. 1982).  Thus, it can be said of 875(c), as it has been said of 18 U.S.C. 786, which prohibits mailing communications containing threats, that the &quot;true gravamen of the offense&quot; is not the defendant's &quot;subjective intent,&quot; but rather the making of a threat which disrupts &quot;the recipient's sense of personal safety and well-being.&quot;  United States v. Bellrichard, 994 F.2d 1319, 1323-24 (8th Cir. 1993), quoting United States v. Manning, 923 F.2d 83, 86 (8th Cir.), cert. denied, 111 S.Ct. 2860, 115 L.Ed 2d 1027 (1991).
</p>
</p>	3. It is not required that the defendant induce fear on the part of the person he proposes to injure.  That person need not know of the threat.  The threat does not have to reach the person threatened.  See Seeber v. United States, 329 F.2d 572 (9th Cir. 1964).  It is said to be sufficient to show that the threat was likely to induce fear that the defendant would act according to its tenor.  United States v. Holder, supra, 302 F.Supp. at 301.  This has been said, however, in cases in which the defendant was more or less open about the threat.  In Holder, for instance, the defendant phoned the F.B.I., threatening to cut off someone's head.   Similarly, in United States v. Schroeder, 902 F.2d 1469 (10th Cir.), cert. denied, 498 U.S. 867 (1990), a threat conveyed through an Assistant U.S. Attorney was held to be sufficient.
</p></blockquote>
<p>	In Schroeder, moreover, the defendant threatened a whole class of people.  The court held that a specific individual does not have to be the target of the threat: a threat focused on a class of people at a particular location may suffice.  See also United States v. Cox, 957 F.2d 264, 266 (6th Cir. 1992), where the threat also was to hurt a &quot;lot of people&quot; at a defined location.  Besides prompting possible fear on the part of people who are the target of the treat, such open threats (like those against public officials) provoke the employment of substantial governmental resources to prevent their fulfillment and, even before that, to ascertain whether a genuine danger indeed exists.  See Kent Greenawalt, Speech, Crime, &amp; the Uses of Language 91, 291 (Oxford University Press 1989).
</p>
<p>	These rules make sense only insofar as threats are the type that provoke anxiety and disruption and so have immediate social costs.  They make no sense at all applied to a case like the present in which the alleged &quot;threat&quot; takes the form of the private confidential communication of morbid fantasies and desires.  Mr. Baker's messages amounted to an ongoing personal conversation -- intimate, secret, and undivulged -- the antithesis of the open threats at issue in prior case law.  They were communications the intended and likely effect of which was to gratify the recipient, not to disquiet.
<p>
	(c)<i> The Meaning of &quot;Threat&quot; in the Indictment</i>
</p>
<p>	The Government's case against Mr. Baker depends on taking out of context rules meant to be applied to certain kinds of threats and applying them mechanically to a very different type of statement. In this respect, the indictment goes beyond existing law.  It assumes that the expression of sadistic thoughts constitutes a threat, no matter what the context in which uttered.   The notion of &quot;threat&quot; underlying the indictment differs from that in previous reported cases under 875(c), which uniformly assume that a threat is supposed to intimidate or induce apprehension in the minds of persons who can be expected to become aware of it.  Here, in contrast, the messages in question served only to titillate their intended audience. </p>

<p>	Without a coercive or anxiety-inducing threat, there is no immediate harm.  The only conceivable harm is the possibility that the speaker will act on his desires.  If anything, such a &quot;threat&quot; constitutes a form of inchoate preparatory crime, but without the requirements of firmness of purpose and of a specific act or agreement that are supposed to prevent other inchoate crimes (such as attempt and conspiracy) from amounting purely to thought-crimes. As shown in the next section of this brief, treating such a declaration of intention or desire as criminal per se would violate the First Amendment.  The statute should not be construed to do so: it is a &quot;cardinal principle&quot; that a statute should be interpreted, where possible, to avoid questions about its constitutional validity.  Ashwander v. Tennessee Valley Authority, 297 U.S. 288, 348 (1936)(Brandeis J., concurring). 
</p></blockquote>
<h4>II.  READING 18 U.S.C. 875(c) TO COVER THE STATEMENTS ATTRIBUTED TO THE DEFENDANT IN THE INDICTMENT WOULD BE INCOMPATIBLE WITH THE GUARANTEE OF FREE SPEECH CONTAINED IN THE FIRST AMENDMENT.</h4>
<p>	Threats often are communicated through forms of expression normally protected by the First Amendment.  Nevertheless, at least certain kinds of threats are not regarded as the sort of speech which the First Amendment renders immune from proscription.  See Doe v. University of Michigan, 721 F.Supp. 852, 862 (E.D.Mich. 1989); see also John T. Nockleby, &quot;Hate Speech in Context: The Case of Verbal Threats,&quot; 42 Buff. L. Rev. 653, 661 (1994). 
</p><p>	There is disagreement about why this is so, about whether such threats should be regarded as speech at all (as opposed to constitutionally unprotected conduct), or whether they are speech, but nonetheless so harmful or valueless as to be subject to legal restriction.  Thus, Professor Kent Greenawalt has proposed a taxonomy of threats, at least some of which (such as &quot;manipulative&quot; as opposed to &quot;unconditional threats&quot; and &quot;warning inducements&quot;) would fall outside the scope of the First Amendment because they are ways of doing things, not asserting things. See K. Greenawalt, Speech, Crime, &amp; the Uses of Language, esp. at 66-68, 90-109, 249-59, 290-92 (Oxford University Press 1989); see also Greenawalt, &quot;Criminal Coercion and Freedom of Speech,&quot; 78 Nw.U. L. Rev. 1081 (1984); Greenawalt, &quot;Speech and Crime,&quot; 1980 Am. B. Found. Research J. 645. On the other hand, this way of classifying threats has been criticized on the ground that the First Amendment applies to all forms of speech; in certain circumstances speech may be harmful and therefore subject to regulation because of its unacceptable results, but not because it constitutes &quot;conduct&quot; or a &quot;performative utterance&quot; entirely beyond the purview of the First Amendment. See, especially, Franklyn S. Haiman, &quot;Speech Acts&quot; and the First Amendment 10-20 (Southern Illinois University Press 1993); see also F.S. Haiman, Speech and Law in a Free Society (University of Chicago Press 1981), and Haiman's &quot;Comments&quot; on Greenawalt in 78 Nw.U. L. Rev. 1125 (1984); cf. C. Edwin Baker, Human Liberty and Freedom of Speech 62-65 (Oxford University Press 1989).
</p><p>	As a practical matter, either view requires distinguishing genuine (unprotected) threats from constitutionally protected utterances that may be labeled &quot;threats&quot; by a misguided prosecutor. See Watts v. United States, 394 U.S. 705, 707 (1969): &quot;a statute such as this one, which makes criminal a form of pure speech, must be interpreted with the commands of the First Amendment clearly in mind.  What is a threat must be distinguished from what is constitutionally protected speech.&quot;  And how the distinction is drawn will depend in turn on the reasons certain types of threats are unprotected despite the fact that they involve &quot;pure speech.&quot;
</p><p>	In R.A.V. v. City of St. Paul, 112 S.Ct. 2538, 120 L.Ed.2d 305 (1992), Justice Scalia's majority opinion gives as &quot;the reasons why threats of violence are outside the First Amendment&quot; the countervailing objectives of &quot;protecting individuals from the fear of violence, from the disruption that fear engenders, and from the possibility that the threatened violence will occur.&quot;  112 S.Ct. at 2546, 120 L.Ed.2d at 321. 
</p><p>	These potential harms are not talismanic: the extent to which they actually warrant restricting speech requires careful analysis.   But the opinion in R.A.V. at least provides an authoritative sketch or checklist of possibly relevant factors.
</p><p>	Neither of the first two reasons mentioned in R.A.V. obtains where, as in the present case, the allegedly threatening statements were made in private communications under circumstances extremely unlikely to produce either fear or disruption.  The only conceivable basis for treating Mr. Baker's statements as subject to prosecution is the objective of protecting individuals &quot;from the possibility that the threatened violence will occur.&quot;  112 S.Ct. at 2546, 120 L.Ed 2d at 321. 
</p><p>	This is a case of &quot;pure speech.&quot;  No immediate harm results from the expression of a desire to commit a crime.  The only warrant for proscribing such expression is the possibility that it will produce harm, should the speaker act on his desire, in the future.  An assertion of intent or desire unattended by any immediate harm is an utterance falling within the broad range of communications to which the First Amendment applies.  Cf. K. Greenawalt, Speech, Crime, &amp; The Uses of Language, supra, at 91.  This conclusion is confirmed by Watts v. United States, supra, which treated expression of an intent to harm the president as an utterance falling, at least prima facie, within the scope of the First Amendment.
</p><p>	In United States v. Kelner, supra, the Second Circuit held that, in order to satisfy First Amendment concerns, the word &quot;threat&quot; in 18 U.S.C. 875(c) must be read to require a threat that &quot;on its face and in the circumstances in which it is made is so unequivocal, unconditional, immediate and specific as to the person threatened, as to convey a gravity of purpose and imminent prospect of execution....&quot; 534 F.2d at 1027.  Application of this test to the &quot;threats&quot; Mr. Baker is alleged to have made would require dismissing the indictment, even if they had been made openly under circumstances apt to induce disquiet and disruption.  It clearly requires dismissing the indictment, given the context in which his supposititious &quot;threats&quot; were uttered.
</p><p>	In Schenck v. United States, 249 U.S. 47 (1919), the Supreme Court held that restrictions on speech cannot be justified merely on the basis that speech may have adverse consequences in the future.  That speech may produce some future harm is not in itself sufficient to warrant its suppression.  It is precisely in such cases, where the harm is not immediate, that regulation of speech is limited to utterances presenting an imminent danger of substantive evil.  &quot;Fear of serious injury cannot alone justify suppression of free speech....  To justify suppression of free speech there must be reasonable ground to fear that serious evil will result if free speech is practiced.  There must be reasonable ground to believe that the danger apprehended is imminent.&quot;  Whitney v. California, 274 U.S. 357, 376-77 (1927) (Brandeis J., concurring). 
</p><p>	In a case where a speaker urges others to violate the law, the constitutional guarantee of free speech will not permit proscription of such advocacy except where it &quot;is directed to inciting or producing imminent lawless action and is likely to induce or produce such action.&quot;  Brandenburg v. Ohio, 395 U.S. 444, 447 (1969).  The danger must be clear.  It must be present.  It must be immediately likely to be realized.  It must be imminent.  
</p><p>	Whatever danger the messages in the present case even arguably embody does not approximate what is required to justify criminal prosecution.  The conversation at issue consisted primarily of general references to the thoughts and ideas of each participant.  The limited discussion of future deeds -- besides appearing to constitute an attempt to further arouse rather than to impart sincere intentions -- in any event described actions that were decidedly nonspecific and expressly not imminent.  Mr. Baker discussed, for example, what he &quot;want[s] to do,&quot; what he &quot;need[s] to do,&quot; what he would &quot;love to&quot; do, and what the two might consider doing &quot;[i]f not next week, or in January, then defin[ite]ly sometime in the Summer.&quot;  To glean from this conversation reasonable grounds to expect imminent danger is wholly unfounded.
</p>
<p>	Cases like Brandenburg deal with encouraging others to violate the law.  But the principles enunciated therein also are applicable a fortiori to the expression of a desire or intent to violate the law oneself.  Otherwise, there would be punishment for mere thought or, more precisely, for giving voice to one's thoughts.   Punishment for the expression of thought without the imminence of further harm is incompatible with the first principles of a free society.  It is punishment for the expression of a distasteful idea.  Without immediate harm or the imminent likelihood of some further harm of proper concern to government, punishing the expression of distasteful ideas amounts to the proscription of thought.  &quot;The notion of thought-crimes is not consistent with that of a free society.&quot; P.J. Fitzgerald, Criminal Law and Punishment 97 (Oxford: Clarendon Press 1962).
 </p><h4>	Conclusion
</h4>
<p>	The indictment in this case extends the term &quot;threat&quot; in 18 U.S.C. 875(c) beyond its generally accepted meaning and represents an effort to penalize thought and expression protected by the First Amendment.  Amicus therefore urges that the indictment be dismissed.
</p>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
</blockquote>
<center>
<p>
