<h1><i> Summary of Argument in ACLU amicus brief </i></h1>
<br>
<center>
<font color="#ff0033">No. 94-1039<br>
 No. 94-6649<br></font>
<h3><font color="3300ff">ROY ROMER,<br>
 AS GOVERNOR OF THE STATE<br>
 OF COLORADO, AND THE STATE<br>
 OF COLORADO,<br>
Petitioners,<br>
- v. -<br>
RICHARD G. EVANS,et al.,<br>
Respondents.<br></font></h3>
<br>
<br>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
</center><blockquote>	
<h4>	INTEREST OF THE <i>AMICI</i>
</h4>
<p>	Amici are a variety of bar associations and other organizations from across the country that are deeply concerned with and affected by Colorado's Amendment 2.  Amici include the State Bar of Arizona, Colorado Bar Association, Connecticut Bar Association, Delaware State Bar Association, The Florida Association of Women Lawyers, Illinois State Bar Association, Kansas Bar Association, Maine State Bar Association, Massachusetts Bar Association, Minnesota Women Lawyers, State Bar of Montana, Women's Law Section, New Jersey State Bar Association, The New Mexico Women's Bar Association, New York County Lawyers' Association, Oregon State Bar, Vermont Bar Association, and the State Bar of Wisconsin, Individual Rights Section.  Each bar association amicus has a strong interest in ensuring its ability to adopt and enforce, or to support the adoption and enforcement of, ethical canons and codes of professional conduct prohibiting discrimination of all kinds in the judicial process and in the provision of legal services.  The discriminatory effects of enactments like Colorado's Amendment 2 directly threaten these interests by prohibiting bar associations and their members from adopting and enforcing anti-discrimination provisions in their respective states and, in the case of integrated bar associations, from adopting and enforcing such measures within the associations themselves. 
</p>
<p>	Amici also include several national organizations dedicated to the preservation of open and effective government, the protection of civil and constitutional rights, and the adoption and enforcement of laws prohibiting arbitrary discrimination, including discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation.  The national amicus organizations include the Society of American Law Teachers, Common Cause and People for the American Way.
</p>
<p>	Amici have the consent of the parties to file this brief.  Letters of consent have been filed separately in this Court.  A complete list of amici and their statements of interest are set forth in Appendix A.  
</p>
<h4>	INTRODUCTION
</h4>
<p>	Blacks and Jews, along with farmers, smokers, joggers and redheads, can seek protection against discrimination from the Colorado legislature, executive departments, courts and the many state and local &quot;agencies, branches, subdivisions and departments&quot; that exercise governmental power.  As a result of Amendment 2, lesbians and gay men cannot.  The question presented by this case is whether it is constitutional for Colorado to reconfigure the process of government in this fashion.
</p>
<p>	For petitioners that is an easy question:  States possess the power to organize their political system in any manner a majority of their citizens support on any issue, provided only that no one is denied the vote and that the rights of certain constitutionally recognized &quot;suspect classes&quot; are protected.  Any other result, say petitioners, would not only infringe upon a state's prerogatives in our federal system, but would propel the process of popular government down a hopelessly slippery slope of special interest challenges to majority rights.
</p>
<p>	Amici submit that this argument is fundamentally misdirected.  This lawsuit is not about slippery slopes, but about level playing fields.  It is not about the right of the people of Colorado, acting through established channels of political expression and representation, to enact or refuse to enact legislation on particular issues.  Rather, it is about their asserted right to place roadblocks in the path of particular individuals in order to impede their ability to participate on even terms in the process by which political issues are adjudicated.
</p>
<p>	No &quot;breathtaking&quot;  or &quot;revolutionary&quot;  principles need be established to protect the right to a fair political process.  Nor does its recognition do &quot;profound violence&quot;  to the majority's right to allocate governmental power and to prevail after a fair fight.  To the contrary, equality of participation in the political process is inherent in the concept of equal protection and should be far less controversial than the often divisive &quot;class&quot;-based analysis that is central to much equal protection jurisprudence.
</p>
<h4>	SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT
</h4>
<p>	1.	The political branches ordinarily control the division and exercise of governmental power and resources.  So long as the process of government is not compromised, courts rarely have a role to play in second-guessing the judgments of the people or their elected representatives.  However, where the process itself &quot;malfunctions,&quot; the basic premise of political legitimacy is called into question and a more active form of judicial review is necessary.  See John H. Ely, Democracy and Distrust 103 (1980).
</p>
<p>	2.	There are two principal situations in which such a malfunction occurs.  The first is where laws disadvantage &quot;discrete and insular minorities.&quot;  The second is where legislation &quot;restricts [the] political process[]&quot; itself.  United States v. Carolene Products Co., 304 U.S. 144, 152 n.4 (1938).  The former may be a more familiar aspect of equal protection jurisprudence, but it is no more important on that account.  Indeed, if anything can be said to be inherent in the concept of equal protection, it is that the ordinary channels for seeking &quot;protection of the laws&quot; should remain open to all on an equal basis.  Specifically, amici submit that under the Equal Protection Clause states may not deny particular individuals equal access to the regularly-established, ongoing processes of government.  
</p>
<p>	3.	The right of citizens to participate in those processes on an equal footing  the right to vote, the right to be represented in a republican form of government, the right to seek legislation or petition the government for redress of grievances  is a core democratic value that has been &quot;inferred&quot; from the structure and traditions of our democratic system.  See, e.g., Reynolds v. Sims, 377 U.S. 533, 562 (1964).  That right is not defined, but effectuated, by the right to cast an effective ballot.  Id. at 565.  
</p>
<p>	4.	Equal political participation can be denied not only by interference with the right to vote, but also by interference with the structure of the legislative process.  Creating a two-tier system in which a class of people is singled out and subjected to a more onerous process for seeking to protect their interests violates those individuals' rights to equal protection to the same extent as laws diluting the effectiveness of particular citizens' votes.  Hunter v. Erickson, 393 U.S. 385, 391 (1969); Reynolds, 377 U.S. at 568.
</p>
<p>	5.	The right to a fair political process is entirely separate from the outcome of that process.  Government action typically benefits some people while burdening others.  It is precisely because this is so that states are prohibited from disabling any particular group of people from equal access to the process by which the political distribution of such burdens and benefits is resolved.  Laws dealing with a particular issue (e.g., fair housing or trout fishing) do not raise an equal protection issue merely because they disproportionately affect particular individuals.  On the other hand, a law which on its face simply makes it harder for a certain identified class of people to participate in the process of day-to-day government stands on a very different constitutional footing.  Such an arrangement offends equal protection of the laws regardless of whether those whom it subordinates are a so-called &quot;suspect class.&quot;  
</p>
<p>	6.	The right of individuals to equal participation in the political process is not at stake where the disadvantaged class can be identified only by reference to its position on a particular matter.  The concept of an &quot;independently identifiable group&quot; neatly captures the notion that equal protection extends to individuals who are identifiable apart from their views on a particular issue.  Thus, a law making employment rights generally a matter of state, rather than local, concern would not deny equal protection, whereas a law making the employment rights of smokers or people with blue eyes a matter of exclusive state concern would.
</p>
<p>	7.	Petitioners err in asserting that the right to equal process is excessively broad, or that recognizing it would fundamentally reorder the relationship between majority and minority rights.  To the contrary, recognizing that everyone has a claim to participate on equal terms in seeking the protection of the laws will have no effect upon the vast majority of legislation (and other governmental action) which has nothing to do with process.  Moreover, nothing prohibits a state from allocating power as it sees fit so long as it does not do so in a manner that singles out particular citizens and makes it more difficult for them, alone, to achieve political success. 
</p>
<h4>	ARGUMENT
</h4>
<h4>I. EQUAL ACCESS TO THE POLITICAL PROCESS IS FUNDAMENTAL TO OUR CONSTITUTIONAL SYSTEM.
</h4>
<p>	Amici and petitioners begin at a common point:  Our constitutional system relies principally upon the electorate and the political branches of government to make decisions and determine policy  to allocate benefits and impose burdens.  Within broad limits, the courts have only a minimal role to play in superintending the decisions of these political branches.  The fact that the government &quot;sometimes generates outcomes with which we disagree&quot; does not give rise to a claim for judicial intervention.  See Ely, supra, at 103.
</p>
<p>	However, the assumption on which this &quot;default system&quot; operates is that the institutions of government are structured and function &quot;so as to represent fairly all of the people.&quot;  Id. at 117 (quoting Kramer v. Union Free School Dist. No. 15, 395 U.S. 621, 627-28 (1969)).  When that assumption does not hold, i.e., &quot;when the challenge . . . is in effect a challenge [to] this basic assumption&quot; itself, the &quot;assumption can no longer serve as the basis for presuming constitutionality.&quot;  Id.
</p>
<p>	There are essentially two such situations.  They are the ones identified by Justice Stone in his famous footnote four in Carolene Products:
</p>
<p><blockquote>	It is unnecessary to consider now whether legislation which restricts those political processes which can ordinarily be expected to bring about repeal of undesirable legislation, is to be subjected to more exacting judicial scrutiny under the general prohibitions of the Fourteenth Amendment than are most other types of legislation. . . .
</p>
<p>	Nor need we enquire whether similar considerations enter into the review of statutes directed at particular religious . . . or national . . . or racial minorities . . . whether prejudice against discrete and insular minorities may be a special condition, which tends seriously to curtail the operation of those political processes ordinarily to be relied upon to protect minorities, and which may call for a correspondingly more searching judicial inquiry.</blockquote></p>
<p>
304 U.S. at 152 n.4 (citations omitted).
</p>
<p>	Stone's concern with laws that disadvantage &quot;discrete and insular minorities&quot;  what are now more commonly referred to as &quot;suspect classes&quot;  has become a primary focus of equal protection jurisprudence.  However, his concern about &quot;legislation which restricts the political processes&quot; is equally important. 
</p>
<p>	The notion that constitutional government rests on the fairness of the political process is scarcely novel, or recent.  In fact, the particular genius of James Madison and the other architects of the Constitution was to focus intently upon the process by which successive governments would be selected and, once chosen, how they would represent the people who elected them.  See Ely, supra, at 77-82.
</p>
<p>	The cornerstone of the system created by the framers, of course, is the principle of majority rule.  Indeed, one of the driving factors behind the American Revolution was the perceived tyranny of English rule in which power was exercised by a few, from afar.  However, the framers also recognized that tyranny could be imposed on minorities by the majority.  As Hamilton put it succinctly in the ratification debates:  &quot;Give all power to the many, they will oppress the few.  Give all power to the few, they will oppress the many.&quot;   See also The Federalist No. 51, at 323 (James Madison) (Mentor ed., 1961) (&quot;It is of great importance . . . not only to guard the society against the oppression of its rulers, but to guard one part of the society against the injustice of the other part.&quot;).
</p>
<p>	The framers understood that unfettered exercise of majority will, especially at the point of fashioning constitutive arrangements governing day-to-day affairs,  would not only jeopardize the rights of minorities, it would threaten the integrity and stability of our constitutional system.  Obviously, a majority could use its numerical power to grant unequal benefits to itself or impose unequal burdens on a minority.  Even more dangerous, however, was the possibility that a majority would fix the very process of government to ensure its own perpetual dominance or at least the perpetual subordination of a disfavored minority.  See Robert Dahl, A Preface to Democratic Theory 11-17 (1956). 
</p>
<p>	Hence, a central preoccupation of the constitutional debates was how to prevent these temporary majorities from restricting or foreclosing the political prospects of minorities.  See The Federalist No. 10 (James Madison).  The solution has been described as &quot;a compromise between the power of majorities and the power of minorities, between the political equality of all adult citizens on the one side and the desire to limit their sovereignty on the other.&quot;  Dahl, supra, at 4.  
</p>
<p>	One of the most important means used by the framers to mediate between majority and minority interests was to structure a political process that would be duly responsive to each.  As Dean Ely describes the outcome of that compromise, the Constitution leaves</p>
<p><blockquote> the selection and accommodation of substantive values . . . almost entirely to the political process . . . . [T]he document is overwhelmingly concerned, on the one hand, with procedural fairness in the resolution of individual disputes (process writ small), and on the other, with . . . process writ large  with ensuring broad participation in the processes and distributions of government.</blockquote></p>
<p>Ely, supra, at 87 (citations omitted).
</p>
<p>	The framers also believed that they could keep majorities from abusing minorities by assuring that the tools of power were both indirect and decentralized.  A decentralized, representative system would protect minorities because majorities would be coalitions of various smaller groups that would be apt to change often as different issues took on relatively greater importance.  The need to build coalitions also would lead to compromise as groups would agree to make concessions on one issue in order to gain support for another.  
</p>
<p>	However clear the framers' goals may have been, implementing them was another matter.  Id. at 80-81.  By the mid-nineteenth century, it had become increasingly evident that these mechanisms were not sufficient to protect minority interests since majorities tended to endure and representatives often failed to represent minority interests.  Therefore, some greater measure of protection was necessary to ensure that government would not simply ignore minority rights.
</p>
<p>	The Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment reflects the most important attempt to resolve this continuing dilemma.  At its most basic level, the Clause commands the States to represent the interests of minorities (as well as majorities) by extending to all persons the equal protection of the laws.  As Justice Jackson put it in his famous concurrence in Railway Express Agency v. New York, 336 U.S. 106, 112 (1949), &quot;there is no more effective guaranty against arbitrary and unreasonable government than to require that the principles of law which officials would impose upon a minority must be imposed generally.&quot;  See also Cruzan v. Director, Mo. Dep't of Health, 497 U.S. 261, 300 (1990) (&quot;the Equal Protection Clause . . . requires the democratic majority to accept for themselves and their loved ones what they impose on you and me.&quot;) (Scalia, J., concurring).  These formulations suggest  as does the very language of the clause, &quot;equal protection of the laws,&quot; not &quot;protection of equal laws&quot;  a concern with process and structure at least as much as with substance or outcomes.
</p>
<p>	This case, also, is about process rather than outcomes.  The central vice of Amendment 2 is that it creates a permanent structural alteration of the process of government in Colorado for gay men, lesbians and bisexuals.  Only they must clear a unique hurdle  a constitutional amendment  to secure protection against discrimination.  
</p>
<p>	That is a &quot;malfunction&quot; of government which undermines the &quot;basic assumption&quot; upon which deference to the political process rests.  In Dean Ely's words, the political process is &quot;undeserving of trust&quot; when </p>
<p><blockquote>
(1) the ins are choking off the channels of 
political change to ensure that they will stay in and the outs will stay out, or (2) though no one is actually denied a voice or a vote, representatives beholden to an effective majority are systematically disadvantaging some minority out of simple hostility or a prejudiced refusal to recognize commonalities of interest, and thereby denying that minority the protection afforded other groups by a representative system.</blockquote></p>
<p>
Ely, supra, at 103.  In such a circumstance, a &quot;more searching&quot; judicial review is not merely appropriate, it is necessary.  In fact, such review is not only a function well-suited &quot;to the capabilities of the courts,&quot; but is also one &quot;which will not likely be performed elsewhere if the courts do not assume it.&quot;  Alexander Bickel, The Least Dangerous Branch 24 (1962).
</p>
<h4>II. THIS COURT HAS RECOGNIZED A RIGHT OF EQUAL POLITICAL PARTICIPATION WHICH INCLUDES, BUT IS NOT LIMITED TO, THE RIGHT TO VOTE.
</h4>
<p> 	The right to vote has been identified as a critical aspect of the right to effective political participation.  This Court has considered various aspects of that right, including vote dilution,  ballot access restrictions,  gerrymandering,  and voter qualifications,  among others.  However, the Court also has expressed unmistakable concern with efforts to corrupt the political process by creating a two-tier legislative structure in which certain individuals must traverse a more burdensome path to advance or protect their interests.  See, e.g., Hunter, 393 U.S. at 389-91; Washington v. Seattle Sch. Dist. No. 1, 458 U.S. 457, 474 75 (1982).
</p>
<blockquote><h4>A. 	The Right to Vote Is Part of a Broader Right.
</h4></blockquote>
<p>	Petitioners contend that the Colorado Supreme Court erred in concluding that there is a right of political participation that extends beyond the &quot;right to vote,&quot; as such.  (Pet. Br. at 25-28.)  But that excessively narrow reading simply is not sustainable.  It ignores not only the language and holdings of specific cases, but also the articulated premises on which they rest.
</p>
<p>	If the right to vote were the only aspect of political participation protected by the Equal Protection Clause, it would have been sufficient to stop with cases like Harper v. Virginia State Board of Elections, 383 U.S. 663 (1966), Carrington v. Rash, 380 U.S. 89 (1965), and Kramer, 395 U.S. 621 (1969), in which certain individuals literally were &quot;fenced out&quot; of the political process by being denied the franchise.  The Court, however, has made it clear that equal protection in the political process demands more than mere access to a voting booth.  Indeed, as the Colorado Supreme Court observed, in cases such as Reynolds v. Sims no one was denied the vote.  Evans v. Romer, 854 P.2d 1270, 1277-78 (Colo. 1993) (en banc).  Rather, the equal protection issue was presented by the inability of certain citizens to have an equal and effective opportunity to influence the outcome of the legislative process because of the way electoral districts were drawn.   Reynolds, 377 U.S. at 561-68.  
</p>
<p>	In fact, Reynolds directly refutes petitioners' claim that &quot;voting&quot; is the end-point right, rather than being supportive of a broader right to effective participation through equal process.  The Court scarcely could have been more explicit:
</p>
<p><blockquote>	[E]ach and every citizen has an inalienable right to full and effective participation in the political processes of his State's legislative bodies.  Most citizens can achieve this participation only as qualified voters . . . . Full and effective participation by all citizens in state government requires, therefore, that each citizen have an equally effective voice in the election of members of his state legislature.</blockquote></p>
<p>
377 U.S. at 565 (emphasis added); see also Board of Estimate v. Morris, 489 U.S. 688, 701 (1989) (aim of equal protection is to provide fair and effective representation for all citizens); Williams v. Rhodes, 393 U.S. 23, 30 (1968) (all qualified voters have the right &quot;to cast their votes effectively&quot;); Whitcomb v. Chavis, 403 U.S. 124, 141-42 (1971). 
</p>
<p>	Not only are petitioners mistaken about the existence (and dimension) of a political participation right, they overlook the fact that this right is rooted in the very majoritarian principles upon which they rely.  In fact, assuring effective participation by all citizens in the process of government makes true majority rule possible and reinforces its legitimacy. 
</p>
<p>	In short, voting is not merely an end in itself, but is one of the means by which the broader right to fair process is effectuated.  There is no principled reason why &quot;all people, one process&quot; is not as much a part of equal protection as &quot;one person, one vote.&quot;
</p>
<blockquote><b>B. 	Principles Recognized by This Court in Hunter, Seattle School District and Gordon Support the Existence of a Right to Equal Participation in the Political Process.
</b></blockquote>
<p>	Amendment 2 violates the Equal Protection Clause because it purposefully restricts effective access by gays, lesbians and bisexuals to the regular channels through which anti-discrimination and other political interests normally are pursued in our republican system of government.  It does that in much the same way that malapportioned state legislatures once created a &quot;legislative straight jacket&quot;  for residents of more populous districts:  by jiggering the process and thereby, in Judge Leventhal's words, &quot;keeping the 'ins' in and the 'outs' out.&quot;  Harold Leventhal, Courts and Political Thickets, 77 Colum. L. Rev. 345, 380 (1977).
</p>
<p>	Colorado seemingly does not take issue with this characterization.  In fact, its brief all but concedes that if Asians or Catholics were substituted for homosexuals, lesbians and bisexuals in Amendment 2 it would be unconstitutional, without more, under cases such as Hunter and Seattle School District.  The difference, say petitioners, is that the Fourteenth Amendment has a special solicitude for, e.g., Asians and Catholics that it does not extend to other socially-identified groups, such as gays and lesbians, the elderly or the disabled.
</p>
<p>	We believe that this argument should be rejected as applied to the right to participate equally in the political process.  The proposition that government may not place extra obstacles in the path of any particular group of citizens in seeking to advance their political interests is hardly a radical notion.  To the contrary, it appeals to the very idea of equality of opportunity  not outcome  that democratic government and equal protection of the laws embody.  See supra pp. ____.  It should be far less controversial than Justice Stone's alternative paradigm of &quot;discrete and insular&quot; minorities, which can invite the type of resentment that often accompanies such class-based differentiation.  See, e.g., Michael J. Klarman, The Puzzling Resistance to Political Process Theory, 77 Va. L. Rev. 747, 748, 783 (1991) (a political process theory that relies solely on the &quot;access&quot; prong of Carolene Products &quot;can avoid controversial value choices in identifying appropriate occasions for judicial review&quot;).
</p>
<p>	The decision below does not represent a radical departure from established constitutional principles.  To the contrary, it is a legitimate heir to Justice Harlan's concurrence in Hunter v. Erickson, in which he identified the absence of a &quot;neutral principle&quot; for affording access to the political process as the critical vice which rendered Akron's city charter amendment constitutionally infirm under the Equal Protection Clause.  Petitioners' bald assertions notwithstanding, both Hunter and Seattle School District are explicable in process, as well as &quot;suspect class,&quot; terms, as the decision below properly points out.  Evans, 854 P.2d at 1279-81.  Thus, for example, Hunter focused substantial attention on Akron's selective deviation from neutral principles in its city charter amendment by &quot;plac[ing] special burdens on racial minorities within the governmental process.&quot;  393 U.S. at 391. 
</p>
<p>	The same observations can be made about Amendment 2.  It places &quot;special burdens&quot; upon a particular group of individuals (&quot;minorit[y]&quot;) in the &quot;governmental process.&quot;  Thus, the sole question is whether the racial character of the group singled out in Hunter was critical to the result.  While some parts of the opinion undeniably focus on that fact, petitioners unfairly denigrate this Court's articulation of a broader principle that, if applied here without the slightest alteration, would be dispositive of this case.  As Justice White stated for the Court, while Akron unquestionably was free to require plebiscites generally it could</p>
<blockquote><p> no more disadvantage any particular group 
by making it more difficult to enact legislation in its behalf than it may dilute any person's vote or give any group a smaller representation than another of comparable size.</p></blockquote>
<p>
Hunter, 393 U.S. at 393 (citations omitted).
</p>
<p>	That observation is particularly significant in light of Justice Harlan's concurrence.  His opinion carefully delineated the broad latitude enjoyed by state and local governments to disadvantage particular groups (even specially protected &quot;suspect&quot; ones) with regard to the outcome of the legislative process.  Id. at 393-95.  The Akron charter amendment, however, was not directed at outcomes.  More fundamentally, it was not grounded in the kind of &quot;neutral principles&quot; that alone ensure &quot;a just framework within which the diverse political groups in our society may fairly compete.&quot;  Id. at 393.  Instead, the Akron law simply disadvantaged certain citizens seeking to protect their basic political interests against discrimination.
</p>
<p>	Nearly fifteen years later, in the Seattle School District case, the Court identified Justice Harlan's &quot;neutral principles&quot; formulation as the &quot;simple but central principle&quot; underlying Hunter.  458 U.S. at 469-70.  The initiative at issue in that case also was directed at racial minorities and the Court discussed that fact at length.  However, as it did in Hunter, the Court described the vice of the law in more general terms.  Specifically, the opinion noted that laws which &quot;make it more difficult for every group in the community to enact comparable laws . . . 'provid[e] a just framework within which the diverse political groups in our society may fairly compete.'&quot;  Id. at 470.  Washington's initiative, however, did &quot;'not attemp[t] to allocate governmental power on the basis of any general principle'&quot; but, rather, simply burdened the rights of specific citizens.  Id. (quoting Hunter, 393 U.S. at 395 (Harlan, J., concurring)).  
</p>
<p>	Two additional cases, decided within six weeks of each other, further illuminate these issues.  In James v. Valtierra, 402 U.S. 137 (1971), the Court upheld a California referendum that required local voters to approve new low-income public housing projects.  In so doing, the Court declined to extend the category of suspect classes to encompass low-income people pursuing their political interest in taxpayer-financed housing.  Shortly thereafter, in Gordon v. Lance, 403 U.S. 1 (1971), the Court upheld constitutional and statutory provisions requiring super-majority approval of increases in bonded indebtedness after concluding that  unlike Hunter  the West Virginia provisions &quot;applied equally to all bond issues for any purpose&quot; and did not burden the rights of any &quot;independently identifiable group.&quot;  Id. at 5.  The majority in the Colorado Supreme Court interpreted Gordon as having adopted a neutral principles view of Hunter.  Evans, 854 P.2d at 1281-82.  By contrast, both the dissent and petitioners claim that James is controlling, whereas Gordon is irrelevant.  See Pet. Br. at 21-22, 23 n.13; Evans, 854 P.2d at 1298-99 (Erickson, J., dissenting).
</p>
<p>	Plainly, James approached Hunter as a &quot;suspect class&quot; case and declined appellee's invitation to apply heightened scrutiny to a &quot;class&quot; of low-income residents.  That was how the parties briefed and presented the issue to the Court.   The Court was not asked to consider the application of any political process right.  Thus, the invitation which amici ask the Court to accept here  to embrace Hunter's concern with process-based discrimination  simply was not extended in James.
</p>
<p>	Gordon involved no race, or other suspect class, issue.  In fact, it was decided by the West Virginia Supreme Court solely as a voting case controlled by decisions such as Reynolds, Kramer, and Wesberry v. Sanders, 376 U.S. 1 (1964).  See Lance v. Board of Educ., 170 S.E.2d 783, 786-90 (W. Va. 1969).  Hunter was not even mentioned.
</p>
<p>	This Court found the voting cases unpersuasive.  See Gordon, 403 U.S. at 4-5.  Instead, the Court analyzed the issues under Hunter. That would have been peculiar if petitioners' characterization of James were correct since, under their approach, Hunter would have been utterly irrelevant.   Thus, the Court's focus on Hunter, at a minimum, acknowledges that Hunter and Gordon are part of the same &quot;family&quot; of cases.  Since Gordon plainly had nothing to do with race, the perceived relationship must turn on the right of political participation.
</p>
<p>	The Court distinguished Hunter on the ground that the West Virginia law, unlike Akron's city charter amendment, &quot;applie[d] equally to all bond issues for any purpose&quot; and did not &quot;single[] out&quot; any particular group for unique disadvantages in the political process.  Id. at 5.  Thus, the Court observed that it could &quot;discern no independently identifiable group or category that favors bonded indebtedness over other forms of financing.  Consequently, no sector of the population may be said to be 'fenced out' from the franchise because of the way they will vote.&quot;  Id. (emphasis added).  Under those circumstances, the Court held that equal protection was not violated.
</p>
<p>	While Gordon referred to the fact that the ordinance in Hunter involved a racial classification, nothing in its analysis turned on that observation.  Rather, the Court's suggestion that the West Virginia provisions would have been held unconstitutional if there had been some &quot;independently identifiable group&quot; that &quot;favor[ed] bonded indebtedness&quot; strongly implies that the critical issue for constitutional purposes was the existence vel non of discrimination against a particular group, not whether the group discriminated against was entitled to special consideration under the Equal Protection Clause.  See id.  That implication was made manifest two pages later in the Court's statement of the controlling constitutional principle:  &quot;We conclude that so long as [laws] do not discriminate against or authorize discrimination against any identifiable class they do not violate the Equal Protection Clause.&quot;  Id. at 7 (emphasis added). 
</p>
<p>	Amici do not claim that Gordon is controlling here.  What we contend is that this Court has recognized the importance of maintaining equal access to the process of government and that this case falls squarely within the category of constitutional wrongs  identified by the Court in Hunter and confirmed by it in Gordon and Seattle School District  in which the fatal vice is the absence of a &quot;neutral principle&quot; for configuring access to the political process. 
</p>
<h4>III. AMENDMENT 2 VIOLATES THE EQUAL PROTECTION CLAUSE BY DEPRIVING AN INDEPENDENTLY IDENTIFIABLE GROUP OF CITIZENS OF EQUAL PARTICIPATION IN THE PROCESSES OF GOVERNMENT.
</h4>
<p>	In addition to denying the existence of a right of political participation, petitioners contend that states are free to allocate governmental authority and jurisdiction as they see fit with respect to any &quot;issue.&quot;  Pet. Br. at 11, 26, 27.  Thus, for example, petitioners suggest that the Constitution does not prevent a state from making such issues as education or employment rights matters of statewide, as opposed to local, jurisdiction.  Pet. Br. at 28, 31.  Similarly, on their view, a law banning smoking or hunting is not subject to constitutional challenge merely because it disadvantages individuals who wish to smoke or hunt.
</p>
<p>	Amici do not quarrel with those propositions.  However, Amendment 2 is not about issues and it is not about outcomes.  It is about the rights of people, to wit, gay men, lesbians and bisexuals, and about erecting obstacles which selectively disable them from effectively protecting their legal interests through the process of government.  That is a far different, and narrower, right than petitioners' unhelpful caricature of the decision below suggests. 
</p>
<p>	Specifically, amici submit that Amendment 2 is constitutionally infirm because it singles out one group from among the many that might seek protection against discrimination in, e.g., housing, employment or public accommodation and alters, for that group alone, the process for obtaining such protection.  While states surely are free to allocate legal authority and jurisdiction as they see fit with respect to issues such as fair housing (or, for that matter, farming, smoking or trout fishing), it is another matter to selectively disable a particular group of citizens from seeking to protect their rights in the same forums and manner in which such issues are addressable by everyone else. 
</p>
<h4>A. 	Individuals, Not Issues
</h4>
<p>	The &quot;political process&quot; cases  from Harper to Reynolds to Hunter to Gordon  speak in terms of individuals, not issues.  For purposes of their analysis it makes no difference whether the challenged inhibition rests on military status,  property ownership  or race.   It is the fact that the political and legal access of particular people has been discriminatorily restricted that is critical.
</p>
<p>	Petitioners and their amici attempt to depict this case as if the issue were the allocation of governmental authority among state and local officials and courts, or the power of the people to legislate directly through initiatives or referenda.  Pet. Br. at 27-28, 31; see also ER/NSR Br. at 8-11.  But that argument is simply miscast.  There is no doubt that the people of Colorado could, if they chose, make non-discrimination in housing a subject of statewide concern, repealing all contrary local ordinances in the process.  What they may not do, however, is allow local jurisdictions (or the state legislature and executive) to create, and courts to apply, laws protecting the housing rights of parents, truck drivers, veterans and the disabled, while foreclosing the ability of gay men, lesbians and bisexuals to seek the same protections in the same forums.  See Seattle School District, 458 U.S. at 478-79.  Petitioners' repeated use of the term &quot;group right&quot; (although intended pejoratively) suggests that they understand this important distinction.  See Pet. Br. at, e.g., 10, 25, 28. 
</p>
<p>	Petitioners and ER/NSR also assert that the appropriate question to be considered is simply whether those who oppose a piece of legislation and those who favor it are treated equally.  (Pet. Br. at 27.)  However, that argument misses the heart of what is unconstitutional about Amendment 2.  The pertinent issue is not whether groups seeking competing outcomes or holding opposing opinions must travel along identical routes in the political process, but whether all groups seeking the same kind of legislative protections must travel along identical routes.  Contrary to petitioners' argument, it is only when a state treats some people differently from others in the process of seeking identical kinds of legislative benefits that the state targets people, rather than issues or outcomes, and thereby violates the Fourteenth Amendment.  If disabled people or truck drivers or heterosexuals in Colorado want to be protected by non-discrimination laws, they may go to some court (if applicable anti-discrimination laws already exist) or to some state or local legislative body (if they do not) and seek that protection.  Gay men, lesbians and bisexuals  and they alone  may not.  That distinction violates their right to equal protection of the laws in the most direct sense.   
</p>
<h4>B. 	&quot;Independently&quot; Identifiable
</h4>
<p>	Gordon refers to &quot;independently identifiable group[s]&quot; as the proper touchstone for determining whether a law affecting process denies equal protection.  That is a useful formulation since it captures both the nature and the limits of the right in question.
</p>
<p>	Gordon's reference to a group that is &quot;independently&quot; identifiable is striking and cannot have been accidental.  A group is independently identifiable where it can be described without reference to any particular issue.  Thus, for example, in  Gordon, people who favored bonded indebtedness demonstrably were disadvantaged by West Virginia's super majority voting requirement.  Yet, as the Court explained, that fact did not make them a protectable class for equal protection purposes since (a) the same voting requirements applied to all forms of bonded indebtedness for any &quot;purpose&quot; (&quot;whether for schools, sewers or highways&quot;) and (b) the affected group was not identifiable except by reference to its position on that issue.  403 U.S. at 5.  
</p>
<p>	By contrast, gay men and lesbians  like Hispanics, Army officers, skiers and smokers  are identifiable apart from particular issues that affect their rights.  Thus, for example, it is perfectly comprehensible to speak of &quot;Hispanics&quot; or &quot;veterans,&quot; as such, without relating that identity to any underlying issue, such as housing, jobs or bonded indebtedness.  
</p>
<p>	Some groups, of course, are defined in whole or in part by a specific activity.  Thus, unlike blacks or redheads, &quot;farmers&quot; are a class defined by an occupation, &quot;poker players&quot; by a certain recreational activity and &quot;vegetarians&quot; by their diet.  Many laws make it harder for such groups to protect their interests in the activity which defines the class  a law repealing municipal option legislation for poker clubs, for example.  If such laws go no further than to regulate the &quot;definitional&quot; activity there is no basis for special equal protection concern.  Put otherwise, a class defined by an activity is not  as to regulation of that activity   independently identifiable.
</p>
<p>	This distinction is important.  As noted previously, were Colorado to adopt a constitutional amendment prohibiting cities from regulating smoking, the mere fact that smokers thereby would be disadvantaged in seeking to protect their desire to smoke does not, in our view, raise special concerns under the Equal Protection clause.  However, if the people of Colorado, in a fit of anti smoker hysteria, went further and precluded smokers from seeking legislation to protect them from arbitrary or malicious discrimination in housing, education or employment, such concern would be appropriate since the affected class (&quot;smokers&quot;) is unrelated to (i.e., is  independent of) the subject matter of the prohibition (i.e., housing, jobs or education).
</p>
<p>	That is, of course, the vice of Amendment 2.  Unlike all of the other groups (e.g., blacks, or veterans, or hunters or the elderly) who may seek anti discrimination legislation from local or statewide lawmaking bodies in Colorado, gay men and lesbians may not.  Moreover, even assuming arguendo that the group identified by Amendment 2 is a class defined by a particular activity  as opposed to being merely descriptive of a personal trait, such as being Hispanic or left-handed or deaf  the referendum is not limited to the activity (love and physical intimacy among people of the same gender) that defines the class but, instead,  flatly disables gays and lesbians from seeking any form of anti discrimination protection from any branch or agency of Colorado's state or local government.
</p>
<h4>C. 	Process, Not Outcome
</h4>
<p>	Petitioners say that this case is about slippery slopes.  See Pet. Br. at, e.g., 12, 36-37.  Amici submit that it is about level playing fields.  Far from involving any extraordinary redefinition of our federal system or limiting the rights of majorities to prevail, the result below and the principle on which it rests are quite narrow.  Only process, not outcome, is at issue. 
</p>
<p>	It is, instead, Amendment 2 that is &quot;extraordinary.&quot;  Pet. Br. at 9.  The Amendment creates a system in which gays, lesbians and bisexuals are singled out and subjected to a special and more onerous process in seeking to protect their political interests.  Moreover, the preclusion is permanent.  Put simply, Amendment 2 is a process-based obstacle course that only gays, lesbians and bisexuals are required to negotiate. 
</p>
<p>	There may, of course, be close cases.  Constitutional issues are rarely clear-cut and lawyers tend to be both creative and tenacious.  But tomorrow's difficult case is no justification for failing to deal correctly with today's easy one.  See Keller v. State Bar, 496 U.S. 1, 15-16 (1990).  Amendment 2 is, to borrow Justice Frankfurter's phrase, an &quot;uncouth&quot;  law.  The idea of placing obstacles in the path of particular citizens in order to deprive them of an equal opportunity to protect their interests through the political process is a particularly pernicious form of discrimination because it contradicts the idea that we all ought to play by the same rules and &quot;may the best person win.&quot;  When one group must run farther or surmount higher barricades to reach the same point, the contest itself is unacceptably corrupted.
</p>
<p>	Ending the debate now and for the future by taking certain people's rights off the table of political discourse is not merely poor practice  it denies those people the ability to obtain &quot;equal protection of the laws.&quot;  Well-settled principles recognize that equal protection is violated when certain people are &quot;fenced out&quot; of the process.  Carrington, 380 U.S. at 94.  The same is true when their political effectiveness is &quot;diluted.&quot;  Reynolds, 377 U.S. at 555.  The result should not be different merely because the &quot;fencing out&quot; and &quot;dilution&quot; take place at a different point in the process.  Amendment 2 is the ultimate exercise in group gerrymandering.  As such, it goes too far and is unconstitutional.
</p>
<h4>  	CONCLUSION
</h4>
<p>	For the foregoing reasons, the judgment of the Colorado Supreme Court should be affirmed.
</p>
</blockquote>
<center>
