<html>
<head>
<title>ACLU in the Courts</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">
<center>
<p><b>IN THE
               SUPREME COURT OF THE UNITED STATES
<p>                         
OCTOBER TERM, 1970
<p>                      
No. 299
<p>                          
PAUL ROBERT COHEN,
<p>                          
v.
<p>                                              
CALIFORNIA,
     Appellant,
 <p>        
APPEAL FROM THE COURT OF APPEAL OF
CALIFORNIA SECOND APPELLATE DISTRICT
</b></center><br>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=100%><br><p>
BRIEF FOR APPELLANT
<p>
INTRODUCTION
<p>                   
          Appellant appeals from a judgment of the Court of Appeal, Second Appellate District, State of California, entered October 22, 1969 (A. 26), affirming a judgment of conviction entered by the Municipal Court of the Los Angeles Judicial District, State of California, on September 27, 1968 (A. 8). Appellant was charged with "engaging in tumultuous and offensive conduct" in violation of the California disturbing-the-peace statute, section 415 of the California Penal Code (A. 1). The said Municipal Court, sitting without a jury, found Appellant guilty, and sentenced Appellant to thirty days in county jail (A. 8).
<p>         
          Upon appeal to the Appellate Department of the Superior Court the judgment was reversed on January 20, 1969 (A. 10). Thereafter State petitioned for rehearing or certification to the Court of Appeal. The Appellate Department granted rehearing (A. 12), and the matter was orally argued for a second time. On May 23, 1969, the Appellate Department once again reversed the judgment of conviction (A. 13). The State again petitioned for certification to the Court of Appeal. The Appellate Department granted the petition and issued an order certifying the cause to be transferred to the California Court of Appeal (A. 23). The Court of Appeal, Second Appellate District, ordered such transfer (A. 25), heard the case on appeal, and affirmed the judgment of conviction (A. 26). Appellant filed a Petition for Rehearing before the Court of Appeal, and said Petition was denied on November 13, 1969 (A. 36). Appellant then filed a Petition for Hearing before the California Supreme Court, and said Petition was denied on December 17, 1969 (A. 36). It is of some significance to note that the Petition for Hearing was denied by the California Supreme Court by a 4-to-3 vote, with Chief Justice Traynor, and Justices Peters and Tobriner dissenting (A. 36).
<p>         
<b>OPINIONS BELOW</b>
<p>                 
          The trial judge in the Municipal Court did not render a written opinion. The Appellate Department of the Superior Court in reversing the judgment of conviction rendered an unreported Memorandum Opinion and Judgment on January 20, 1969 (A. 10). Upon rehearing, the Appellate Department of the Superior Court on May 23, 1969, in once again reversing the judgment of conviction, rendered a second unreported  Memorandum Opinion and Judgment (A. 13). The Court of Appeal, in affirming the judgment of conviction, rendered an opinion (A. 26), which has been reported in 1 Cal. App. 3d 94, 81 Cal. Rptr. 503 (1969).
<p>         
<b>JURISDICTIONAL GROUNDS</b>
<p>                   
Appellant was convicted of violation of section 415 of the California Penal Code. After reversal by the Appellate Department of the Superior Court (see Introduction), the conviction was ultimately affirmed by the Court of Appeal, Second Appellate District, State of California, on October 22, 1969. Petition for Rehearing before the Court of Appeal was denied on November 13, 1969 (A. 36). In view of the fact that the California Supreme Court thereafter declined to hear the case by denying Appellant's Petition for Hearing (A. 36), the judgment of the said Court of
Appeal constitutes a judgment rendered by the highest court of the State of California in which a decision can be had within the meaning of 28 U.S.C. section 1257. (American Railway Express Co. v. Levee, 263 U.S. 19, 68 L. Ed. 140 (1923).) The California Supreme Court denied Appellant's Petition for Hearing on December 17, 1969 (A. 36), and the time for bringing this appeal is measured from the date of such denial. (American Railway Express Co. v. Levee, supra.) The validity of section 415 of the Califomia Penal Code was drawn in question on the ground of its
being repugnant to the First and Fourteenth Amendments of the United States Constitution, and both the trial court (A. 21) and the Court of Appeal (A. 30) rendered decision in favor of the validity of said section 415. It follows, therefore, that an appeal will lie before this Court pursuant to 28 U.S.C. section 1257(2). Notice of Appeal to this Court was filed in the Court of Appeal, Second Appellate District, State of California, on February 20, 1970. The case was docketed in this Court on March 5, 1970 (see Appendix, cover). Jurisdiction was postponed to the hearing of the case on the merits, and the case was transferred to the appellate docket and placed on the summary calendar on June 22, 1970 (A. 37).
<p>          
<b>CONSTITUTIONAL AND STATUTORY
PROVISIONS INVOLVED</b>
<p>        
The constitutional provisions involved are the First and Fourteenth Amendments, U.S. Const., Amend. I, Amend. XIV, Sec. 1.
<p>         
The statutory provision involved is that portion of section 415, California Penal Code, relating to "offensive conduct." Section 415 reads in its entirety as follows:
<p><blockquote>         
        "Disturbing the peace; noise; use of public streets of unincorporated town for offensive conduct, horse racing, or shooting; indecent language; punishment
<p>         
 "Every person who maliciously and willfully disturbs the peace or quiet of any neighborhood or
person, by loud or unusual noise, or by tumultuous or offensive conduct, or threatening, traducing, quarreling, challenging to fight, or fighting, or who, on the public streets of any unincorporated town, or upon the public highways in such unincorporated town, run any horse race, either for a wager or for amusement, or fire any gun or pistol in such unincorporated town, or use any vulgar, profane, or indecent language within the presence or hearing of women or children, in a loud and boisterous manner, is guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction by
any Court of competent jurisdiction shall be punished by fine not exceeding two hundred dollars, or by imprisonment in the County Jail for not more than ninety days, or by both fine and imprisonment, or either, at the discretion of the Court." (Enacted 1872. As amended Code Am. 1877-8, c. 299, p. 117,  1.)
</blockquote><p>
<b>QUESTIONS PRESENTED</b>
<p>
 1. Can one who publicly exhibits in writing the words "Fuck the Draft" be denied the guarantees of freedom of speech under the First and Fourteenth Amendments on the ground that the exhibition of such writing "had a tendency to incite others to violent behavior or to disturb the peace" (A. 29) where the trial court found that: "No evidence was offered by the People indicating or tending to indicate that Defendant either engaged in or threatened any acts of violence, or was about to engage in any such acts, or that Defendant by his conduct incited anyone else to any acts of violence, or that any persons observing Defendant engaged in or threatened, or were about to engage in acts of violence " (A. 19) ?
<p>         
 2. Is it a denial of liberty without due process of law in violation of the Fourteenth Amendment to sentence the Appellant to 30 days in jail on the ground that his exhibition in writing of the words "Fuck the Draft" "had a tendency to incite others to violent behavior or to disturb the
peace" (A. 29) in view of the finding of the trial court that there was no evidence "that any persons observing Defendant engaged in or threatened, or were about to engage in acts of violence" (A. 19)?
<p>
 3. Can the expression of words stating a political opinion be punished, notwithstanding the First and Fourteenth Amendments, on the ground that such expression creates a tendency that others will respond with violent behavior, where there is an absence of any evidence of a likelihood that such a violent response would in fact occur?
<p>
 4. Does the so-called "fighting words" exception to First Amendment protection apply where the words expressed are critical of a political institution ( i.e., the Selective Service System) and not of any individual persons to whom the expression may be addressed, or to any other individual persons?
<p><blockquote>
   a. Can such words be considered to be "likely to provoke the average person to retaliation, and thereby cause a breach of the peace"?
<p>
   b. Even if violent retaliation by persons viewing the words were likely, does this justify silencing the speaker in the absence of proof that the police are incapable of controlling such violent retaliation?
</blockquote><p>
 5. Are the words "Fuck the Draft" obscene in a constitutional sense?
<blockquote><p>
   a. Does the dominant theme of these words taken as a whole appeal to a prurient interest in sex?
<p>
   b. Are these words patently offensive because they affront community standards relating to the description or representation of sexual matters?
<p>
   c. Are these words utterly without redeeming social value?
<p>
   d. Can these words be regarded as obscene if the answer to either a, b or c of this Question 5 is "No"?
<p></blockquote>
 6. If the words "Fuck the Draft" are not obscene in a constitutional sense, may their expression nevertheless be punished, despite the First and Fourteenth Amendments, on the ground that non-obscene profanity is offensive to others?
<p>
 7. Can non-obscene speech (and particularly speech expressing a political point of view) ever be abridged simply because others find the expression offensive?
<p>
 8. Is there a "non-speech element" which justifies abridging Appellant's freedom of speech by reason of the fact that he expressed himself in the corridor of a public building when his physical presence and demeanor in such corridor (as distinguished from the words he expressed) was neither illegal, nor objected to by any authorities?
<p>
 9. Is a criminal statute which punishes speech as a form of "offensive conduct" without specifying which forms of speech will constitute such "offensive conduct" unconstitutionally overbroad in its chilling effect on freedom of speech?
<p>
 10. If the answer to Question 9 is "yes," is the statute rendered constitutionally valid by a judicial construction which limits its application to speech where there is a tendency that the audience for such speech might so object to the speech as to resort to violence, but under such construction speech may be punished even though there is no likelihood that such violence will in fact occur?
<p>
 11. Is a statute as described in Questions 9 and 10 unconstitutionally vague?
<p>
<b>STATEMENT OF THE CASE</b>
<p>
 While in the courthouse corridor outside Division 20 of the Los Angeles Municipal Court, Appellant wore a jacket upon which were inscribed the words "Fuck the Draft" (A. 18). Also inscribed on the jacket were the words "Stop War" and two "peace symbols" (A. 19). Women and children were present in said corridor (A. 18). Appellant neither engaged in, threatened, nor incited any acts of violence (A. 19), nor were any other persons in the said corridor engaged in, threatening, or about to engage in acts of violence (A. 19). Appellant at no time caused the emission of any loud or unusual noises (A. 19). Appellant testified that by wearing the jacket as thus inscribed the public was made aware of the depth of feeling against the draft shared by himself and his friends (A. 19-20), and that he had no wish to vex, annoy, or injure others (A. 20).
<p>
 Appellant was charged with "engaging in tumultuous and offensive conduct" in violation of section 415 of the Penal Code. He was convicted, and sentenced to 30 days in county jail (A. 8).
<p>
 The constitutional issues here raised were first raised at trial on Appellant's motion to suppress evidence on constitutional grounds (A. 4). They were raised once again after the evidence was admitted on Appellant's motion for entry of judgment of acquittal under California Penal Code section 1118 (A. 7). In each instance the trial court expressly held that Appellant could be convicted of violation of Penal Code section 415 without abridging his rights under the First and Fourteenth Amendments (A. 20-21), and that section 415 is not invalid on its face in that it is neither unconstitutionally vague (A. 21) nor unconstitutionally overbroad (A. 21). In addition, the trial court held that the words "Fuck the Draft" are "obscene" within the constitutional meaning of that word (A. 20).
<p>
The same constitutional issues were briefed and argued at each succeeding proceeding in this case. See generally the Court of Appeal's discussion of Appellant's position (A. 26-35).
<p>
<b>SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT</b>
<p>
Appellant was clearly engaging in speech, and such speech is entitled to First and Fourteenth Amendment protection because it neither contained nor was it accompanied by any of the elements which this Court has heretofore recognized as justifying abridgment of freedom of speech.
 <p>
There was no threat of violence such as to justify abridgment of Appellant's speech. The Settled Statement makes clear that there was no likelihood of violence either from Appellant or from anyone viewing his words. The trial court erroneously held that no violence potential need be
shown in order to convict for the use of words which constitute "offensive conduct." This in itself requires reversal. But even under the construction adopted by the Court of Appeal it is clear that a mere "tendency" that violence might result from some unidentified bystanders is too remote a danger to justify abridgment of speech (Argument I A (1)).
<p>
Even if there were a likelihood of violence by those opposing Appellant's speech, this in itself would not justify vitiating Appellant's First Amendment rights, at least in the absence of a showing that the police were unable to restrain those who would resort to violence (Argument I A (2)).
<p>
The so-called "fighting words" doctrine is not here applicable because there was no showing of a likelihood that a breach of the peace would result from Appellant's words, and further because Appellant's words were not "fighting words" in the sense of attacking or criticizing those to whom the words were being addressed (Argument I A (3)).
<p>
Appellant's words were not "obscene" in the constitutional sense as this Court has defined obscenity in that the dominant theme of the words "Fuck the Draft" does not appeal to a prurient interest in sex, the words are not patently offensive by reason of affronting contemporary community standards relating to the description or representation of sexual matters, and the words are not utterly without redeeming social value (Argument I B).
<p>
There were no time, place or manner "non-speech" elements justifying the denial of First and Fourteenth Amendment protection for Appellant's speech. Appellant had every right to be where he was, his manner was neither loud nor unruly, and the only objection by the authorities was to Appellant's speech itself (Argument I C).
<p>
The fact that Appellant's speech may have been offensive to some persons does not justify the abridgment of his speech. The First Amendment is equally applicable to offensive and non-offensive speech (Argument II A).
<p>
Fundamental First Amendment theory requires protection for speech such as that employed by Appellant. A free marketplace of ideas, or democratic dialogue, is essential for a self-governing people to be able to make informed decisions (Argument II B (1) (a)).
<p>
The democratic dialogue would not function properly if the state could censor the form ( i.e., particular words chosen to express an idea) of speech even if there were no censorship of the ideas conveyed. In this case if Appellant had expressed himself in a more polite manner the self-
governing people would not have been apprised of the depth of feeling against the draft shared by Appellant and his friends. More fundamentally, if the state could censor the emotive content of speech, even though it did not censor the intellectual content, the state could thereby to
a large extent determine to which members of the public a given speech will appeal, and could thus largely influence whether a particular idea will prevail in the marketplace. For this reason it is clear that speech to be protected by the First and Fourteenth Amendments need not be "polite"
(Argument II B (I) (b)).
<p>
 Profanity has become a vital ingredient in the language of dissent as used by many young people, and by many members of minority groups. If the use of such words were to be legally proscribed, the language of dissent, and hence the democratic dialogue, would be severely inhibited (Argument II B ( I ) (c)).
<p>
 Furthermore, society at large now tolerates and even rewards the use of the word "fuck" in the arts and in motion pictures. It would be ludicrous to jail Appellant for the use of a word which appears in seven out of the ten best-selling works of fiction, and which is generally accept-
able to a large segment of society (Argument II B (1) (d)).
<p>
 It may not be argued that those who viewed Appellant's words constituted a "captive audience" since at most they were required to fleetingly glance at such words. If such a casual and fleeting contact by an unwilling audience justifies abridgment of speech, then street-corner speakers, radio and television broadcasters and many others whose statements may be offensive to some listeners could be silenced, and the democratic dialogue would be stultified. In this regard, it adds nothing analytically to refer to the "shock" effect of Appellant's words, since this is but a different label for highly offensive words, and offensiveness per se does not vitiate First Amendment rights (Argument II B (I) (e)).
<p>
Freedom of speech is also important as an end in itself, in that it serves the function of self-fulfillment. This is true of four-letter words both for literary and psychological reasons (Argument II B (2)).
<p>
Finally, freedom of speech serves a safety-value function, as men are less inclined to resort to violence to achieve given ends if they can freely express themselves verbally with respect to such ends. The cathartic effect of four-letter-word speech is confirmed by psychological authorities (Argument II B (3)).
<p>
Section 415 of the California Penal Code, as construed by the California courts, is unconstitutionally vague and overbroad. Under the Court of Appeal's construction, if there is a mere possibility that someone might be offended by given words and might therefore resort to violence, such words may constitute "offensive conduct" within the meaning of the statute. This is both overly vague and overbroad in applying an impermissible standard. The construction of section 415 by the California Supreme Court in a subsequent case does not save the statute from vulnerability both on grounds of vagueness and overbreadth (Argument III).
<P>
