<HEAD>
<TITLE>Scott Brief</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/graphics/courthdr.gif"></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>THIS COMPLAINT HAS BEEN REDACTED TO DELETE THE NAMES OF THE MINORS. 
REDACTIONS ARE INDICATED BY BRACKETS.</B></P>
<HR>
<P>CONNIE SCOTT and CARL (BUD) UNITED STATES <BR>SCOTT, individually, and on
behalf of and DISTRICT COURT<BR>as guardians and next friends of   FOR THE
DISTRICT<BR>[the young woman], a minor,  OF NEBRASKA<BR>Plaintiffs,</P>
<P>vs.</P>
<P>JOHN E. SAMSON, County Attorney for<BR>Washington County, in his individual
andCIVIL ACTION NO. 4:95CV-3319<BR>official capacities; WASHINGTON<BR>COUNTY;
WAYNE FLORA, as former<BR>Sheriff for Washington County, in his individual and
official capacities;<BR>ARNIE SVENNINGSEN, as Sheriff for<BR>Washington
County, in his official capacity; DARRELL<BR>HOWARD, KEVIN WILLIS, JAMES THIRD
AMENDED<BR>DEEMER, RICHARD HILLMAN, and   COMPLAINT AND<BR>JULIE EMSWILER, as
members of the DEMAND FOR JURY TRIAL<BR>Washington County Sheriff's Department,
<BR>in their individual and official capacities; <BR>the CITY OF BLAIR; MARVIN
DOEDEN, <BR>as Chief of Police for the City of Blair, <BR>in his individual
and official capacities;<BR>JOSEPH LAGER, NICHOLAS THALLAS <BR>and BERND
SCHERER, as members of the <BR>City of Blair Police Department, in their <BR>individual
and official capacities; [the<BR>boyfriend], a minor, by and through his <BR>guardian
and next friend; KATHY TULL, <BR>individually and as guardian and next <BR>friend
of [the boyfriend]; JOHN TULL; <BR>DR. K.C. BAGBY and JAMES JORDAN, <BR>in
their individual capacities, <BR>Defendants.</P>
<HR>
<P>INTRODUCTORY STATEMENT</P>
<P>1.  This is an action under 42 U.S.C. &#167;&#167; 1983 and 1988, 18 U.S.C. &#167;
248, and Nebraska law seeking damages and other appropriate relief from public
officials, and others acting in concert with them, for the unconstitutional and
tortious interference with plaintiff [the young woman]'s right to reproductive
choice and the plaintiffs' right to family integrity effected when the
defendants assaulted the plaintiffs in their home, illegally seized plaintiff
[the young woman], and removed her from her family in order to prevent her from
making a free choice about whether to carry her pregnancy to term.  </P>
<P><B>JURISDICTION AND PARTIES </B></P>
<P>2.  Jurisdiction of this action is based on 28 U.S.C. &#167;&#167; 1331 and
1343.  The plaintiffs further invoke the supplemental jurisdiction of this Court
with respect to claims arising under state law pursuant to 28 U.S.C. &#167;
1367.</P>
<P>3.  Plaintiff [the young woman] is a woman under the age of 18.  [The young
woman] resided in Blair, Nebraska during the times relevant to this complaint. 
In July 1995, [the young woman] moved from Blair with her parents, Connie and
Carl Scott.  [The young woman] appears in this action by and through her general
guardians and next friends Connie and Carl Scott.  </P>
<P>4.  Plaintiff Connie Scott is [the young woman]'s mother.  Connie Scott
resided in Blair, Nebraska during the times relevant to this complaint.  In July
1995, she moved from Blair with Carl and [the young woman].  Connie Scott files
on her own behalf and as a general guardian and next friend of [the young
woman].  </P>
<P>5.  Plaintiff Carl (Bud) Scott is [the young woman]'s father.  During the
times relevant to this complaint, Carl Scott lived in Blair, Nebraska in the
same house as Connie and [the young woman].  In July 1995, he moved from Blair
with Connie and [the young woman].  Carl and Connie Scott have not yet sold the
family home in Blair.  Carl Scott files on his own behalf and as a general
guardian and next friend of [the young woman].</P>
<P>6.  Defendant John E. Samson is the County Attorney for Washington County,
Nebraska and, as such, is responsible for making county policies and determining
county practices and customs for the enforcement of the Nebraska child
protection laws, and for investigating, initiating, and litigating actions under
those laws.  At all times relevant to this complaint, Samson was acting under
color of state law.  He is sued in both his individual and official capacities.</P>
<P>7.  Defendants Darrell Howard, Kevin Willis, James Deemer, Richard Hillman,
and Julie Emswiler were, at all times relevant to this complaint, members of the
Washington County Sheriff's Department and, as such, were responsible for
enforcement of the laws, including the Nebraska child protection laws.  At all
times relevant to this complaint, the defendant officers were acting under color
of state law.  They are sued in both their individual and official capacities. 
</P>
<P>8.  Defendant Wayne Flora was the Sheriff of Washington County in, and prior
to, September 1994.  Defendant Arnie Svenningsen is the current Sheriff of
Washington County.  The Sheriff is responsible for making county policies and
determining county practices and customs for the training and supervision of
members of the Washington County Sheriff's Department in the enforcement of the
laws of Nebraska, including the child protection laws.  Defendant Flora is sued
in both his individual and official capacities.  Defendant Svenningsen is sued
in his official capacity.  At all times relevant to this complaint, Flora and
Svenningsen were acting under color of state law.</P>
<P>9.  Defendant Washington County is located in the State of Nebraska.   At
all times relevant to this complaint, defendant Washington County acted under
color of state law.  Through defendant John E. Samson and others, defendant
Washington County makes county policies and determines county practices and
customs for the enforcement of the Nebraska child protection laws, including the
investigation, initiation, and litigation of actions under those laws.  Through
the Sheriff of Washington County, Washington County makes county policies and
determines county practices and customs for the enforcement of Nebraska child
protection laws, including the training and supervision of officers in their
investigation and enforcement of these laws.  Through defendants Darrell Howard,
Kevin Willis, James Deemer, Richard Hillman, Julie Emswiler, and others unknown,
defendant Washington County implements its policies, practices and customs
relating to the enforcement of the Nebraska child protection laws.  </P>
<P>10.  Officers Joseph Lager, Nicholas Thallas, and Bernd Scherer are members
of the City of Blair Police Department and, as such, are responsible for the
enforcement of the laws, including the Nebraska child protection laws.  At all
times relevant to this complaint, the defendant officers were acting under color
of state law.  They are sued in both their individual and official capacities.</P>
<P>11.  Defendant Marvin Doeden is the Chief of Police for the City of Blair

and, as such, is responsible for making city policies and determining city
practices and customs for the training and supervision of City of Blair police
in the enforcement of the laws of Nebraska, including the child protection laws.
 At all times relevant to this complaint, defendant Doeden was acting under
color of state law.  He is sued in his individual and official capacities.</P>
<P>12.  The City of Blair is a municipality located in Washington County,
Nebraska.  Through defendant Marvin Doeden, defendant City of Blair makes city
policies and determines city practices and customs for the enforcement of the
Nebraska child protection laws, including the training and supervision of
officers in their investigation and enforcement of these laws.  Through
defendants Joseph Lager, Nicholas Thallas, Bernd Scherer, and others unknown,
defendant City of Blair implements its polices, practices and customs relating
to the enforcement of the Nebraska child protection laws.  At all times relevant
to this complaint, defendant City of Blair was acting under color of state law.</P>
<P>13.  Defendant [the boyfriend] is a man under the age of 18 who resides in
Blair, Nebraska.</P>
<P>14.  Defendant Kathy Tull resides in Blair, Nebraska and is the mother of
[the boyfriend].</P>
<P>15.  Defendant John Tull resides in Blair, Nebraska and is the stepfather of
[the boyfriend]. </P>
<P>16.  Defendant K.C. Bagby is a physician and defendant James Jordan is a
physician's assistant who, at all times relevant to this complaint, were
practicing at the Blair Medical Group in Blair, Nebraska.</P>
<P>17.  At all times relevant to this complaint, defendants [the boyfriend],
Kathy Tull, John Tull, K.C. Bagby and James Jordan were acting in concert with
defendant public officials and thereby acting under color of state law.</P>
<P><B>FACTS</B></P>
<P>18.  In September 1994, plaintiff [the young woman], who at the time was 15
years old, became aware that she was pregnant.  [The young woman] had not
questioned the absence of her menstrual period immediately, because her periods
were consistently irregular.  On Monday, September 26, she informed her parents,
plaintiffs Connie and Carl Scott, that she was pregnant as a result of sexual
relations with her boyfriend [the boyfriend].  Together the plaintiffs decided
to have [the young woman] consult a physician and to consider her options. </P>
<P>19.  Defendants [the boyfriend] and his mother and stepfather Kathy and John
Tull had become aware of the pregnancy on the afternoon of September 26 because
Kathy had [the young woman] take two home pregnancy tests at the Tulls' house. 
Later that evening, Kathy and John Tull made an unsolicited visit to the Scotts'
home.  The Tulls informed the Scotts of their desire to help raise [the young
woman]'s child, even though [the young woman] had not yet decided whether or not
she would carry her pregnancy to term.  </P>
<P>20.  On Tuesday, September 27, plaintiff [the young woman] was examined by
Dr. Carol Weckmuller at the Blair Medical Group.  The family's regular doctor
was on vacation at the time.  [The young woman] was accompanied by her mother
Connie Scott.  Based on a physical examination, Dr. Weckmuller informed [the
young woman] and Connie Scott that she estimated that [the young woman] was

twenty-three weeks pregnant.  Dr. Weckmuller advised [the young woman] where she
could get an abortion, should that be her choice.  [The young woman] informed
defendant Kathy Tull, by telephone, of the developments that day.</P>
<P>21.  On Wednesday, September 28, [the young woman] spoke at length with her
family about her options.  After extensive deliberation, [the young woman]
decided to seek an abortion.</P>
<P>22.  On Wednesday, September 28, [the young woman] made an appointment by
telephone for an abortion.  During the phone call, [the young woman] spoke to a
clinic employee, who asked her a series of questions and then explained the
abortion procedure to her.  Connie Scott also talked to the employee and gave
her additional information.  [The young woman] then spoke again with the clinic
employee, who asked again whether [the young woman] really wanted an abortion. 
[The young woman] replied yes, and scheduled an appointment.</P>
<P>23.  Early that evening, [the boyfriend] came over to [the young woman]'s
house.  [The young woman] told him that she planned to have an abortion.  He was
upset, saying she was killing a baby.  Mid-evening, Kathy Tull called the

Scotts, screaming and saying such upsetting things that Connie Scott hung up the
telephone. </P>
<P>24.  Shortly thereafter someone pounded on the Scotts' door.  Carl Scott
went to answer the door, but before he could open it, defendant [the boyfriend]
kicked the door, causing it to hit Carl in the eye and [the young woman] across
the face.  Present with [the boyfriend] at the Scott home were, among others,
Kathy and John Tull, another Tull family member, and several of [the
boyfriend]'s friends. They were screaming, calling the Scotts &quot;baby killers&quot;
and other derogatory names, pulling [the young woman], and hitting Carl.  Connie
Scott called the police to the house because of the violence against her family.
 When the police arrived, including defendants Willis, Lager, Thallas, and
Scherer, [the boyfriend] struck Officer Lager and was arrested.  Kathy Tull
assaulted Connie Scott by kicking her in the stomach.  Kathy Tull was not
arrested.  Two officers asked [the young woman] if she had made an appointment
for an abortion, to which she responded, yes. </P>
<P>25.  At least one deputy from the Sheriff's Department, defendant Officer
Darrell Howard, arrived at the scene separately.  He tried to give [the young
woman] a manila envelope containing anti-abortion literature.  Earlier that day,
Officer Howard, who is active in the anti-choice movement in Blair, had met with
the Tulls at their home apparently for the purpose of preventing [the young
woman] from obtaining an abortion.  </P>
<P>26.  After the altercation, the plaintiffs and [the young woman]'s younger
brother went to their cousins' house for the night.  The plaintiffs had earlier
told the police that they would be staying at their cousins' home in Blair that
night and had given the officers their cousins' address.  </P>
<P>27.  That same day, September 28, without [the young woman]s' consent,
defendant Kathy Tull discussed [the young woman]'s pregnancy and abortion plans

with defendants Bagby and Jordan apparently for the purpose of preventing [the

young woman] from obtaining an abortion.  Defendants Bagby and Jordan
cooperated, by writing a letter stating that &quot;any elective abortion could
potentially cause medical and emotional damage to the mother at any stage of
pregnancy&quot; and that an abortion at twenty-three weeks &quot;could be
harmful&quot; to [the young woman].  (Emphasis added.)  Neither Bagby nor Jordan
had ever examined or spoken with [the young woman].  The letter did not state
that an abortion at twenty-three weeks is legal and is accepted medical
practice, nor did it note that carrying to term and delivering a child could
also be harmful to [the young woman].  Kathy Tull then took the letter to the
Blair police station.  Attached as Exhibit A is a copy of that letter.</P>
<P>28.  At around 12:30 a.m. on Thursday, September 29, the plaintiffs were
awakened by police at their cousins' house.  More than ten law enforcement
vehicles surrounded the house.  Present were members of the City of Blair Police
Department, including defendants Lager, Thallas, and Scherer, as well as county
officers, including defendants Deemer, Hillman, and Emswiler.  The police took
[the young woman] into custody.  They did so for the purpose of preventing [the
young woman] from obtaining an abortion.  </P>
<P>29.  The Scotts were told that [the young woman] was being taken into
protective custody.  The police offered the Scotts little explanation as to why
[the young woman] was being taken into custody except to show them the letter
from defendants Bagby and Jordan, and to say that defendant John E. Samson, the
County Attorney, had directed them to take [the young woman] into custody.  The
police told the Scotts there would be a hearing at 9 a.m. that morning, and
advised them to get an attorney.  They did not inform the plaintiffs where they
were taking [the young woman] or what they would do with her.  The plaintiffs
were extremely frightened and confused by the police removing [the young woman]
in the middle of the night to an undisclosed place for an undefined purpose.</P>
<P>30.  [the young woman] was taken by the police to the Blair police station. 
[The young woman] was at the police station for several hours.  During this
time, the police did not give her written notice of the reasons she was taken
into custody.  During this time, [the young woman] also noticed anti-choice
materials on one of the lockers in the station.  </P>
<P>31.  After several hours at the police station, [the young woman] was
transported to the home of a foster family who were strangers to her.  At
approximately 3:30 a.m., plaintiffs Connie and Carl Scott received a call from
Deborah Bales, whom they did not know, but who identified herself as being with
the Nebraska Department of Social Services.  Ms. Bales informed the Scotts that
[the young woman] was safe and urged them to get an attorney.</P>
<P>32.  Early Thursday morning, September 29, plaintiffs Connie and Carl Scott
sought and obtained counsel.  Their attorney was informed by defendant County
Attorney Samson that no hearing would be held that day because there were no
judges in town.  Plaintiffs Connie and Carl Scott were not told when a hearing
would be held, nor were they given the option of going to another town to appear
before a judge in order to avoid further delay.</P>
<P>33.  On Thursday morning, defendant County Attorney John Samson interrogated
[the young woman].  [The young woman] was alone throughout the questioning, even
though defendant Samson knew that she was under eighteen years of age and that
her parents were available.  Defendant Samson further knew that the Scotts had
retained counsel.  Defendant Samson also refused Deborah Bales' requests that he
release [the young woman].  Instead, he filed a baseless petition with the
Washington County Juvenile Court under the child protection law, alleging that
[the young woman] was in a situation dangerous to life or limb or injurious to
her health.  The only stated reasons for the petition were that plaintiffs
Connie and Carl Scott &quot;had made arrangements&quot; for [the young woman] to
obtain an abortion and that defendant Bagby had provided a letter to law
enforcement officials stating that an elective abortion could be harmful to [the
young woman].  A copy of the petition is attached as Exhibit B.</P>
<P>34.  On Thursday, September 29, the Scotts discovered that fliers had been
posted all over Blair stating that plaintiffs Carl and Connie Scott were &quot;murderers.&quot;
 Members of [the boyfriend]'s family and his friends were responsible for
posting the fliers.</P>
<P>35.  On Friday morning, September 30, another physical examination was
scheduled for [the young woman] in Omaha.  Connie and Carl Scott were permitted
to accompany [the young woman] to this appointment.  Deborah Bales drove the
Scotts to the appointment.  Upon completion of the examination, the doctor
informed the Scotts that he believed [the young woman] was in her twenty-seventh
week of pregnancy.</P>
<P>36.  On Friday afternoon, September 30, the Honorable F.A. Gossett, III, of
Juvenile Court of Washington County held a hearing regarding [the young woman]. 
No guardian ad litem or attorney was ever appointed to represent [the young
woman]'s interests. </P>
<P>37.  At the hearing, County Attorney Samson filed an Amended Petition
alleging that [the young woman] was in a situation dangerous or injurious to her
health or morals and that she was being neglected by her parents.  The only
evidence offered by defendant Samson to support [the young woman]'s detention
was the letter from defendants Bagby and Jordan (Ex. A), who had never examined
or spoken to [the young woman], stating that they believed an abortion at
twenty-three weeks could be harmful to [the young woman], and information given
to law enforcement that [the young woman] and her parents were going to leave on
Thursday, September 29, to explore the possibility of an abortion.  A copy of
the Amended Petition is attached as Exhibit C.  A copy of the transcript of the
hearing is attached as Exhibit D.  </P>
<P>38.  At the hearing, counsel for Connie and Carl Scott stated that, in light
of the morning examination, his clients now believed that an abortion was no
longer an option for [the young woman].</P>
<P>39.  The petition filed by defendant County Attorney Samson stated that the
allegations against plaintiffs Connie and Carl Scott were based on reports to &quot;Law
Enforcement.&quot;  The Scotts did not, however, receive written notification of
the investigation from the state Department of Social Services.  Nor were any of
the other procedures typically associated with a child abuse or neglect
investigation followed, such as the appointment of a guardian ad litem for [the
young woman].</P>
<P>40.  Upon consideration of the Amended Petition, Judge Gossett stated that
[the young woman] should not have been removed from the Scotts' custody.  Judge
Gossett ordered that the temporary placement of [the young woman] with the
Department of Social Services be terminated, and further ordered that [the young
woman] be released to the custody of her parents &quot;on the condition that no
abortion shall be performed on the subject's unborn child without further order
of the Court.&quot;  The order provides that any violation of its terms is
punishable as contempt.   A copy of the Order is attached as Exhibit E.  In
light of their impression that an abortion was no longer a possibility, Connie,
Carl and [the young woman] stipulated to the order.  At no time did [the young
woman] have independent counsel, although the decision whether or not to
continue the pregnancy was [the young woman]'s alone.</P>
<P>41.  Subsequent to the hearing, [the young woman] obtained protective orders
from the District Court of Washington County against Kathy Tull and [the
boyfriend] prohibiting them from harassing [the young woman] and entering the
Scott home.  These orders became permanent on October 14, 1994, and are still in
effect.</P>
<P>42.  After the incident, [the boyfriend] tried repeatedly to contact [the
young woman].  His friends followed [the young woman] when she left the house in
Blair.  [The young woman] was threatened with assault.  [The young woman] became
afraid to leave the house alone.  School in Blair became so threatening that
[the young woman] was tutored at home.  [The young woman] was so upset by the
events that she had to seek the advice and support of a counselor.  Connie and
Carl Scott were also harassed.  Because of the trauma to their family caused by
these events and the ongoing harassment, Connie and Carl Scott decided to move
from Blair.  They wanted [the young woman] to be able to return to school and
again be with peers.  Despite the move and passage of time, [the young woman]
continues to have nightmares.</P>
<P>43.  Subsequent to the events, [the boyfriend] pleaded guilty to assaulting
a police officer at the Scotts' house and was placed on probation for one year.</P>
<P>44.  In December 1994, [the young woman] gave birth to a baby, whom she is
raising in [the young woman]'s parents' home.</P>
<P>45.  On September 22, 1995, the plaintiffs served upon defendants Washington
County, John E. Samson, Darrell Howard, Kevin Willis, City of Blair, Joseph
Lager, Nicholas Thallas, Bernd Scherer, and John Doe I-VII tort claim notices in
the form required and provided in such cases by the laws of the State of
Nebraska concerning claims of trespass, intentional infliction of emotional
distress, invasion of privacy and interference with the rights to reproductive
choice, family integrity, due process, and freedom from illegal search and
seizure as guaranteed by the Nebraska Constitution.  </P>
<P>46.  Pursuant to the laws of the State of Nebraska, on April 24, 1996, after
having received no response to the tort claim notices, plaintiffs served the
relevant governing bodies with a notice withdrawing the tort claims from their
consideration.</P>
<P>47.  The risk of mortality from abortions performed after twenty weeks
gestation is no greater than that from childbirth.  Abortions performed up to
twenty weeks gestation are safer than childbirth.</P>
<P>48.  Law enforcement officers have a duty to a juvenile and her family,
before removing a juvenile from her home and family without a warrant or order
of the court, to determine that the juvenile is seriously endangered in her
surroundings and that immediate removal appears to be necessary for the juvenile
protection.</P>
<P>49.  At all times relevant to this complaint, officers of the Washington
County Sheriff's Department received inadequate training or no training at all
with regard to investigations of allegations of child abuse or neglect and the
legal requirements and procedures for removing juveniles from their homes.</P>
<P>50.  At all times relevant to this complaint, officers of the City of Blair
Police Department received inadequate training or no training at all with regard
to investigations of allegations of child abuse or neglect and the legal
requirements and procedures for removing juveniles from their homes.</P>
<P>51.  Upon information and belief, neither Wayne Flora nor Arnie Svenningsen,
although having knowledge of his officers' involvement in the seizure of [the
young woman], did not discipline any of such officers for their involvement.</P>
<P>52.  Upon information and belief, Chief of Police Marvin Doeden, although
having knowledge of his officers' involvement in the seizure of [the young
woman], did not discipline any of such officers for their involvement.</P>
<P><B>CLAIMS FOR RELIEF</B></P>
<P>53.  The allegations set forth in paragraphs 1 through 52, inclusive, are
repeated as if again set forth at length.</P>
<P>54.  By, among other things, violently trespassing into the plaintiffs'
home, assaulting [the young woman], Connie, and Carl Scott, obtaining and
providing a letter to law enforcement officials misrepresenting the danger of
abortion to [the young woman], awakening and taking [the young woman] into
custody in the middle of the night, removing her from her parents, holding her
in a police station and placing her with total strangers for over 36 hours,
interrogating [the young woman], then fifteen years of age, without counsel or
her parents present, delaying the appearance before a judge for over 29 hours
while refusing to release [the young woman], filing and pursuing a petition and
amended petition alleging that [the young woman]'s consideration of her
constitutional right to have an abortion was injurious to her and reflective of
parental neglect and lacking any evidence of abuse or neglect under Nebraska
law, prohibiting [the young woman] from attending her pre-scheduled and urgent
appointment for an abortion, and through ongoing harassment, the defendants,
willfully participating in joint activity, have interfered with and infringed
and continue to interfere with and infringe plaintiff [the young woman]'s right
to reproductive choice in violation of the Fourteenth Amendment to the United
States Constitution.</P>
<P>55.  By, among other things, violently trespassing into the plaintiffs'
home, assaulting [the young woman] and Carl Scott, obtaining and providing a
letter to law enforcement officials misrepresenting the danger of abortion to
[the young woman], awakening and taking [the young woman] into custody in the
middle of the night, removing her from her parents, holding her in a police
station and placing her with total strangers for over 36 hours, interrogating
[the young woman], then fifteen years of age, without counsel or her parents
present, delaying the appearance before a judge for over 29 hours, while
refusing to release [the young woman], filing and pursuing a petition and
amended petition alleging that [the young woman]'s consideration of her
constitutional right to have an abortion was injurious to her and reflective of
parental neglect and lacking any evidence of abuse or neglect under Nebraska
law, prohibiting [the young woman] from attending her pre-scheduled and urgent
appointment for an abortion, and through ongoing harassment, the defendants,
willfully participating in joint activity, have interfered with and infringed
and continue to interfere with and infringe the plaintiffs' right of family
integrity in violation of the Fourteenth Amendment to the United States
Constitution.</P>
<P>56.  By, among other things, taking [the young woman] into custody in the
middle of the night, removing her from her parents, holding her in a police
station and placing her with total strangers for over 36 hours, interrogating
[the young woman], then fifteen years of age, without counsel or her parents
present, filing and pursuing a petition and amended petition alleging that [the
young woman]'s consideration of her constitutional right to have an abortion was
injurious to her and reflective of parental neglect and lacking any evidence of
abuse or neglect under Nebraska law, delaying the appearance before a judge for
over 29 hours, while refusing to release [the young woman], the defendants,
willfully participating in joint activity, deprived the plaintiffs of their
liberty without due process of law in violation of the Fourteenth Amendment to
the United States Constitution.</P>
<P>57.  By, among other things, forcibly and without consent, entering the
Scotts' residence, entering the residence where the plaintiffs were staying,
taking [the young woman] into custody, forcibly removing her from home and her
parents without a judicial warrant or order, probable cause, or any exigent
circumstances excusing the absence of a warrant, the defendants, willfully
participating in joint activity, violated the plaintiffs' rights in violation of
the Fourth and Fourteenth Amendments to the United States Constitution.</P>
<P>58.  By, among other things, establishing a custom, policy and practice of
failing to train police officers about the investigations of allegations of
child abuse or neglect and the legal requirements and procedures for removing
juveniles from their homes, in deliberate indifference to the likely resulting
violations of family integrity and liberty, Washington County, through its
Sheriff, and the City of Blair, through its Chief of Police, caused [the young
woman] to be removed from her family in violation of the Fourth and Fourteenth
Amendments to the United States Constitution.  </P>
<P>59.  By, among other things, removing [the young woman] from her family in
the middle of the night and detaining her, based only on a letter of a physician
and his assistant who had never seen [the young woman] which misrepresented the
danger of abortion to [the young woman], and in disregard of her constitutional
right to decide whether to have an abortion, and for the purpose of preventing
her from having an abortion, defendants John Samson, Darrell Howard, Kevin
Willis, James Deemer, Richard Hillman, Julie Emswiler, Joseph Lager, Nicholas
Thallas, and Bernd Scherer, acting in concert and outside the scope of their
official authority, subjected [the young woman] to false arrest and
imprisonment.</P>
<P>60.  By, among other things, removing [the young woman], then fifteen years
old, from her family in the middle of the night and by detaining her, based only
on a letter of a physician and his assistant who had never seen [the young
woman] which misrepresented the danger of abortion to [the young woman], and in
disregard of her constitutional right to decide whether to have an abortion, and
for the purpose of preventing [the young woman] from having an abortion and from
conferring with her family, all of which has lead to humiliating, disabling and
debilitating emotional injury for the Scott family, defendants John Samson,
James Deemer, Julie Emswiler, Richard Hillman, Darrell Howard, Joseph Lager,
Nicholas Thallas, Bernd Scherer, and Kevin Willis, acting in concert and outside
the scope of their official authority, intentionally inflicted emotional
distress upon plaintiffs.</P>

<P>61.  By, among other things, removing [the young woman] from her family in
the middle of the night and detaining her, based only on a letter of a physician
and his assistant who had never seen [the young woman] which misrepresented the
danger of abortion to [the young woman], and in disregard of her constitutional
right to decide whether to have an abortion, and for the purpose of preventing
[the young woman] from having an abortion and from conferring with her family,
defendants John Samson, Darrell Howard, Kevin Willis, James Deemer, Richard

Hillman, Julie Emswiler, Joseph Lager, Nicholas Thallas, and Bernd Scherer,
acting in concert and outside the scope of their official authority,
substantially interfered with the Scotts' seclusion, in a manner that would be
highly offensive to a reasonable person, and thus intruded upon plaintiffs'
privacy.</P>
<P>62.  By, among other things, removing [the young woman] from her family in
the middle of the night and detaining her, based only on a letter of a physician
and his assistant who had never seen [the young woman] which misrepresented the

dangers of abortion to [the young woman], in disregard of [the young woman]'s
constitutional right to an abortion, and without an allegation of immediate
harm, defendants John Samson, Darrell Howard, Kevin Willis, James Deemer,
Richard Hillman, Julie Emswiler, Joseph Lager, Nicholas Thallas, and Bernd
Scherer breached their affirmative duty to [the young woman] and her family to
disrupt the family only after ensuring the juvenile is seriously endangered and
to address any allegations of abuse with the least restraint on [the young
woman]'s freedom, thereby causing [the young woman] to suffer harm to her rights
of reproductive choice and causing violations of the Scotts' rights of family
integrity and liberty, and emotional injury, and thus rendering defendants
liable in negligence.</P>
<P>63.  By, among other things, violently trespassing into the plaintiffs' home
and assaulting and battering [the young woman], Connie, and Carl Scott,
defendants [the boyfriend], Kathy Tull and John Tull intentionally injured,
intimidated and interfered with [the young woman] because she sought to obtain
services in a facility that provides reproductive health services, including
counseling about abortion, in violation of the Freedom of Access to Clinic
Entrances Act, 18 U.S.C. &#167; 248.</P>
<P>64.  By, among other things, forcibly taking [the young woman] into custody
on September 29, and holding her for more than 36 hours, defendants John Samson,
Joseph Lager, Nicholas Thallas, Bernd Scherer, James Deemer, Richard Hillman and
Julie Emswiler intentionally interfered with [the young woman] because she
sought to obtain services in a facility that provides reproductive health
services, including counseling about abortion, in violation of the Freedom of
Access to Clinic Entrances Act, 18 U.S.C. &#167; 248.</P>
<P>65.  By, among other things, intentionally kicking in the door of the
Scotts' home, causing it to hit Carl Scott in the eye and [the young woman]
across the face, and pulling, hitting, kicking and injuring [the young woman],
Carl Scott and Connie Scott, defendants [the boyfriend] and Kathy Tull assaulted
and battered the plaintiffs.</P>
<P>66.  By, among other things, willfully, forcibly, and without consent,
entering upon the Scotts' property and kicking in their door on the night of
September 28, 1994, defendants [the boyfriend], Kathy Tull and John Tull
trespassed upon the Plaintiffs' property.</P>
<P>67.  By, among other things, obtaining and providing the above letter and
making other statements to law enforcement officials, which caused such law
enforcement officials to take [the young woman] into custody unlawfully in the
middle of the night, remove her from her parents, hold her in a police station
and place her with total strangers for over 36 hours, defendant Kathy Tull is
liable for the false arrest and imprisonment of plaintiff [the young woman].</P>
<P>68.  By, among other things, willfully, forcibly, and without consent,
entering upon the Scotts' property and kicking in their door on the night of
September 28, 1994, providing confidential medical information to third parties,
obtaining and providing a letter to law enforcement officials that
misrepresented the danger of abortion to [the young woman] and caused law
enforcement to intrude upon the home where [the young woman] was staying and
remove her from her family, and by interfering with [the young woman]'s right to
bodily integrity and autonomy with respect to her childbearing decisions and the
Scott family's right to family privacy and integrity, defendants [the
boyfriend], Kathy Tull and John Tull intruded upon plaintiffs' solitude.</P>
<P>69.  By, among other things, misusing information about [the young woman],
without ever examining her or speaking to her, to provide a misleading letter to
law enforcement officials, which caused such law enforcement officials to take
[the young woman] into custody unlawfully in the middle of the night, remove her
from her parents, hold her in a police station and place her with total
strangers for over 36 hours, defendants K.C. Bagby and James Jordan are liable
for the false arrest and imprisonment of plaintiff [the young woman].</P>
<P>70.  By, among other things, violently trespassing onto plaintiffs'
property, assaulting [the young woman], Carl and Connie Scott, calling them &quot;baby
killers,&quot; obtaining and providing a letter to law enforcement officials
that  misrepresented the danger of abortion to [the young woman] and caused such
law enforcement officials to take [the young woman] into custody in the middle
of the night, remove her from her parents, hold her in a police station and
place her with total strangers for over 36 hours, all of which, in addition to
continuing harassment, has resulted in injury to all plaintiffs including
interference with [the young woman]'s bodily autonomy regarding her decision
whether to continue her pregnancy, and all of which has led to humiliating,
disabling and debilitating emotional injury for the Scott family including, but
not limited to, [the young woman]'s inability to leave her house alone and to
continue her education at Blair High School, and the Scott family's decision to
move out of town, defendants [the boyfriend], Kathy Tull, John Tull, K.C. Bagby,
and James Jordan have intentionally inflicted emotional distress upon
plaintiffs.</P>
<P>71.  As a direct and proximate result of the foregoing actions by the
Defendants, the plaintiffs have suffered and continue to suffer damages.</P>
<P>WHEREFORE, plaintiffs pray that this Honorable Court:</P>
<P>I.  Declare that the seizure of plaintiff [the young woman], removal from
her family, placement in police and foster custody and interference with her
right to reproductive choice and plaintiffs' right of family integrity were
unconstitutional and tortious;</P>
<P>II.  Award plaintiffs compensatory and punitive damages, including but not
limited to damages available pursuant to 18 U.S.C. &#167; 248(c)(1)(B);</P>
<P>III.  Award plaintiffs reasonable attorneys' fees and the costs of this
action, pursuant to 42 U.S.C. &#167; 1988, 18 U.S.C. &#167; 248(c)(1)(B), and
any other applicable law; and </P>
<P>IV.  Award such further or other relief as the Court deems just and proper.</P>
<P>DEMAND FOR JURY TRIAL</P>
<P>Plaintiffs demand trial by jury of all issues triable by jury in Lincoln,
Nebraska.  </P>
