<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">
<h1><i> Summary of Argument in ACLU amicus brief </i></h1>
<br>
<center>
<font color="#ff0033">Civil Action No. 95-0618<br></font>
<h2><font color="3300ff">MUMIA ABU-JAMAL,			Plaintiff,			<br>
		v.<br>		
JAMES PRICE, et al., <br>
Defendants.<br>	</font></h2>
<br>
</center>
<blockquote>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>		
<p>MEMORANDUM OF LAW SUBMITTED BY AMICUS CURIAE,
 AMERICAN CIVIL LIBERTIES UNION OF PENNSYLVANIA,
 IN SUPPORT OF PLAINTIFF'S MOTION FOR PRELIMINARY INJUNCTION
</p>
<p>	The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) is a national, non-profit organization dedicated exclusively to the preservation and promotion of civil rights and civil liberties.  The organization numbers about 300,000 members nationwide, approximately 10,000 of whom reside in Pennsylvania.  The ACLU has appeared in hundreds of cases before the United States Supreme Court in both representational and amicus curiae capacities.  The ACLU is presently involved in countless  civil liberties cases throughout the United States.  
</p>
<p>	Mr. Abu-Jamal's Motion For Preliminary Injunction claims that he has been and is being punished for publishing a book, Live From Death Row, that is highly critical of the Pennsylvania Department of Corrections ("DOC").  Plaintiff asserts that since the publication of his book, the DOC has retaliated against him by prohibiting contact with the media and placing him on disciplinary segregation.  The latter sanction was imposed ostensibly for violating a policy forbidding "private businesses."  The DOC is interpreting the policy as a prohibition on any fee-for-publication arrangement.
</p>
<p>	Mr. Abu-Jamal's allegations against the Pennsylvania Department of Corrections (hereafter "DOC") raise serious issues relating to freedom of expression.  As an organization dedicated not only to protecting First Amendment freedoms, but also opposed to the death penalty, ACLU members have a keen interest in reading accounts of the conditions on death row, such as Mr. Abu-Jamal's book, Live From Death Row.  If Mr. Abu-Jamal's allegations are true, the DOC's policy of prohibiting receipt of fees for any publication and prison officials' punishment of the Plaintiff as a result of the book severely chills free expression.  Such a chill works to the great disadvantage of the general public by suppressing prisoners' artistic expressions, as well as valuable information about the operation of Pennsylvania's prisons.  
</p>
<p>	A statement of the ACLU's views may be of aid to the Court in considering the Plaintiff's motion for preliminary injunction.  The ACLU argues below that prohibiting financial compensation  for the publication of  Live From Death Row, and punishing Mr. Abu-Jamal with disciplinary segregation for receiving compensation, violates the First Amendment to the U. S. Constitution.  This is so even in the absence of evidence that the policy or the punishment were retaliatory.  If a retaliatory motive can be proven, the constitutional violation is simply compounded.  Furthermore, although prison officials have some leeway in restricting contact with the media, uneven application of such a policy or a retaliatory motive render any consequential restrictions unconstitutional.
</p>

<h4>I.	THE FIRST AMENDMENT RIGHT OF THE GENERAL PUBLIC TO ACQUIRE INFORMATION ABOUT PRISON LIFE PRECLUDES CORRECTIONS' OFFICIALS FROM RESTRICTING A PRISONER'S RIGHT TO PUBLISH BOOKS AND COMMUNICATE WITH THE MEDIA ABSENT A SUBSTANTIAL SECURITY INTEREST THAT IS CONTENT-NEUTRAL.
</h4>
<p>	Plaintiff's Motion For Preliminary Injunction asserts claims which, if proven, raise serious concerns not only about Mr. Abu-Jamal's free speech rights, but also about the First Amendment rights of the public to receive information about Pennsylvania's prisons.  The potential recipients of expression, like the general public and news media, have a legally cognizable interest in receiving the written works of prisoners in order to learn about conditions within the Commonwealth's prisons.  Virginia State Bd. of Pharmacy v. Virginia Citizens Consumer Council, Inc., 425 U.S. 728 (1976).    The Supreme Court recently reaffirmed the First Amendment right of the public to "read and hear" information.  Treasury Union Employees. ___ U.S. ___, ___, 115 S. Ct 1003, 1020 (1995).  Receiving information about prison life is important to ACLU members.
</p>
<p>	The public typically knows very little about life behind prison walls.  What happens behind those walls, however, is of vital public interest:
</p>
<blockquote>
<p>                                 		[T]he conditions in the nation's prisons are a matter that is both newsworthy and of great public importance.  As THE CHIEF JUSTICE has commented, we cannot "continue ... to brush under the rug the problems of those who are found guilty and subject to criminal sentence . . . .  It is a melancholy truth that it has taken the tragic prison outbreaks of the past three years to focus widespread public attention on this problem."  Burger, Our Options are Limited, 18 Vill. L. Rev. 165, 167 (1972).
</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Pell v. Procunier, 417 U.S. 817, 831 n.7 (1974).   Today, as corrections budgets swallow larger and larger chunks of the public treasury, general knowledge about what actually happens behind those walls becomes increasingly important.
</p>
<p>	The public acquires information about prison life through media reports, interpersonal communications with prisoners, and accounts written, sung and drawn by inmates themselves.  Additionally, many great works of music, art and literature, and some not so great, have been created by people behind bars.  In the field of literature, Martin Luther King's Letter From Birmingham Jail, Henri Charriere's Papillon and the works of Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn stand out.  Many of the famous southern blues artists spent time in jail.  Not only have these musicians and writers enriched our culture, but they have helped to inform public debate about corrections and the criminal justice system. 
</p>
<p>	The First Amendment right of the public to receive information from prisoners precludes prison officials from interfering unduly with outgoing correspondence and access to the media.  Vigorous enforcement of this right by the courts is essential to guarantee that the voices of future King's, Charriere's and Solzhenitsyn's will be heard, and that the taxpayers of Pennsylvania have information about the operation of the Commonwealth's prisons.
</p>

<h4>	A. 	Restrictions on Outgoing Prisoner Mail Are Subject to a Higher Level of Scrutiny than Other Infringements on Prisoners' Rights.
</h4>

<p>	Prisoners have a constitutional right to communicate with the outside world by mail.  Thornburgh v. Abbott, 490 U.S. 401 (1989); Procunier v. Martinez, 416 U.S. 396 (1974). 
While the Supreme Court has curtailed many prisoners' rights in recent years, see, e.g., Turner v. Safley, 482 U.S. 78 (1987) (applying "reasonableness standard" to correspondence between inmates), the right of prisoners to send mail to the outside world has retained greater respect and protection.  In Thornburgh v. Abbott, the Court extended Turner's "reasonableness" standard of review to incoming general mail.  The Court expressly left in place, however, a higher standard for outgoing correspondence: 
<blockquote>		
                                [T]he logic of our analyses in [Procunier v.]Martinez [416 U.S. 396 (1974)] and Turner requires that Martinez be limited to regulations concerning outgoing correspondence. . . .  The implications of outgoing correspondence for prison security are of a categorically lesser magnitude than the implications of incoming materials.  490 U.S. at 413 (italics added).  Accord, Bieregu v. Reno, No. 94-5719, Slip Op. at 18 (3d Cir. July 11, 1995)  (opening and reading legal mail "chills protected expression and may inhibit the inmate's ability to speak, protest and complain openly, directly and without reservation with the court"). 
</blockquote>
<p>	In the context of cases involving the right of media access, the Supreme Court has recognized the importance of protecting this right of prisoners to send out information about life in prison.  In  Houchins v. KQED, Inc., 438 U.S. 1 (1978) , the Court stated as follows:
</p>
<blockquote>		[The government] cannot prevent respondents from learning about jail conditions in a variety of ways, albeit not as conveniently as they might prefer. [The news media and public] have a First Amendment right to receive letters from inmates criticizing jail officials and reporting on conditions.
</blockquote>
<p>Id. at 15.  Similarly, in Pell the Court held that it is clear that the medium of written correspondence affords inmates an open and substantially unimpeded channel for communication with persons outside the prison, including representatives of the news media.
</p>
<p>417 U.S. at 824.  Writing and sending a book manuscript or a demo tape of songs to a publisher is a form of constitutionally protected expression.  Such communication is practically and legally indistinguishable from other outgoing correspondence.  Although the Third Circuit has not ruled on the issue, some courts have accorded communication with the media the same confidentiality and protection as is given to legal mail.  Guajardo, 580 F.2d at 759; Taylor v. Sterrett, 532 F.2d 462, 481-82 (5th Cir. 1976); Travis v. Lockhart, 607 F. Supp. 1082 (E.D. Ark. 1985); Burton v. Foltz, 599 F. Supp. 114 (E.D. Mich. 1984).  These courts have held that mail to the media is essential to protect not only the interests of the inmates, but also the interest of the public in learning about prison conditions.  Restrictions on such outgoing correspondence are more difficult to justify because the dangers "of [such] outgoing correspondence for prison security are of a categorically lesser magnitude" than the dangers posed by other prisoner contacts with the outside world.  Thornburgh, 490 U.S. at 413.  
</p>
<p>	Even if the heightened standard applied to legal mail is not extended to media contacts, prison officials can justify restrictions on prisoners' First Amendment right to communicate by mail with the media and publishing houses only if they satisfy the Martinez test: the restrictions must  (1) "further an important or substantial governmental interest [in security, order or rehabilitation] unrelated to the suppression of expression"; and (2) "the limitation of First Amendment freedoms [must be] no greater than is necessary or essential to the protection of the particular governmental interest involved."  416 U.S. at 413.
<h4>	
	B.	Restrictions on a Prisoner's Access to the Media Cannot Be Imposed Discriminatorily or Be Motivated by a Desire to Suppress the Contents of Inmate Communication Simply Because it Is Critical of Prison Officials.
</h4>
<p>	Prisoners also have a First Amendment right of access to the media.  Pell, 417 U.S. at 822.  The Court has permitted some reasonable restrictions on this right.  See, e.g., Houchins, 438 U.S. 1 (1978) (news media have no special right of access to prisons over and above that of other persons); Pell, 417 U.S. 817 (1974) (upholding constitutionality of rule prohibiting press from interviewing "specific individual inmates"); Saxbe v. Washington Post Co., 417 U.S. 843 (1974) (upholding constitutionality of regulation prohibiting some face-to-face press interviews).    At a minimum, however, any restrictions must be imposed in a non-discriminatory and content neutral manner, and must provide alternative channels of communication if face-to-face press interviews are restricted.  Pell, 417 U.S. at 827-28.
</p>
<p>	"Content-neutrality" has a peculiar meaning in prisoners' rights law.  Regulations and practices in prison generally must "further an important governmental interest unrelated to the suppression of expression."   Turner, 482 U.S. at 413 (emphasis added).  Although the Court repeatedly speaks of the need for regulation of First Amendment rights "without regard to the content of the expression," Thornburgh, 490 U.S. at 415, quoting Turner, 482 U.S. at 90, drawing "distinctions between publications on the basis of their potential implications for prison security" is considered "neutral" and, therefore,  permissible content-based censorship.  Thornburgh, 490 U.S. at  415.  
</p>
<p>	Impermissible "content-based" censorship in the prison setting entails suppression or discouragement of "unflattering or unwelcome opinions."  Martinez, 416 U.S. at 413; Andolina, 826 F.2d at 1268.  The Thornburgh Court elaborated on this impermissible type of censorship: 
</p>
<p>		In Martinez, the regulations barred writings that "unduly complain" or "magnify grievances," express "inflammatory political, racial, religious or other views," or are "defamatory" or "otherwise inappropriate."  We found in Martinez that "[t]hese regulations fairly invited prison officials and employees to apply their own personal prejudices and opinions as standards for prisoner mail censorship," and that the purpose of the regulations had not been found "unrelated to the suppression of expression."  The regulations at issue in Martinez , therefore, were decidedly not "neutral" in the relevant sense.
</p>
<p>Thornburgh, 490 U.S. at 416 n.14 (citations omitted).  In other words, disapproval of expression in the absence of any significant governmental interest in security, order or rehabilitation is prohibited.
</p>
<h4>II.	THE DOC'S POLICY OF PROHIBITING PRISONERS FROM RECEIVING PAYMENT FOR THE PUBLICATION OF BOOKS VIOLATES THE FIRST AMENDMENT.
</h4>
<p>	The DOC's placement of Mr. Abu-Jamal on disciplinary segregation because publication of his book for profit violated a DOC policy against operating "private businesses" is unconstitutional.  The DOC may, consistent with the U.S. Constitution,  prohibit inmates from engaging in a business or profession, French v. Butterworth, 614 F.2d 23, 24 (1st Cir. 1980), but it may not extend that policy to encompass the publication of a book, such as Live From Death Row, about matters of public concern.
</p>
<p>	Regardless whether the DOC's motivation was illicit,  Simon &amp; Schuster, Inc. v.  Members of N. Y. State Crime Victims Bd., 502 U.S. 105, ___, 112 S. Ct. 501. 509 (1991) ("[i]llicit legislative intent is not the sina quo non of a violation of the First Amendment"), application of the policy prohibiting "private businesses" to prevent  inmates from receiving financial remuneration for the publication of written materials is unconstitutional.  The DOC's overbroad application of the policy effectively penalizes inmates for publishing constitutionally protected material. 
</p>
<p>	Even though the DOC did not (nor could it) actually prohibit Mr. Abu-Jamal from publishing the book, penalizing him for receiving financial remuneration from the publisher is similarly unconstitutional.   United States v. National Treasury Employees Union, ___ U. S. ___, 115 S. Ct. 1003 (1995);   Simon &amp; Schuster, supra; Andolina, 826 F.2d at 868.  In National Treasury Employees Union the Court held unconstitutional a law that prohibited federal employees from accepting any compensation for making speeches or writing articles.  Id.  Even though the law neither prohibited speech, per se, nor drew content-based distinctions, the financial penalty was ruled unconstitutional:
<blockquote>
		[The law's] prohibition on compensation unquestionably imposes a significant burden on expressive activity.  See Simon &amp; Schuster, Inc. v.  Members of N. Y. State Crime Victims Bd., 502 U.S. 105 (1991); see also Arkansas Writers' Project , Inc. v. Ragland, 481 U.S. 221, 227-231 (1987); Minneapolis Star &amp; Tribune Co. v. Minnesota Commissioner of Revenue, 460 U.S. 575 (1983).  Publishers compensate authors because compensation provides a significant incentive toward more expression.  By denying respondents that incentive, the honoraria ban induces them to curtail their expression if they wish to continue working for the Government.
</blockquote>
<p>___ U. S. at ___, 115 S. Ct. at 1014 (citations in original) (footnote omitted).  See also, id. at 1020 (O'Connor, concurring) (recognizing that imposition of financial burdens has a direct effect on incentives to speak).  
</p><p>	Likewise, in striking down New York's "Son of Sam law," which escrowed the profits of publications by criminals, the Court recognized that financial burdens "operate as a disincentive to speak" and are, therefore, constitutionally suspect. Simon &amp; Schuster, 502 U.S. at ___, 112 S. Ct. at 508 - 09.  
</p><p>	
In this case, the DOC's application of a policy against private businesses to prohibit prisoners from receiving remuneration for publishing books is unconstitutional under both National Treasury Employees Union and Simon &amp; Schuster.  Similarly, punishing inmates for receiving such payment is also unconstitutional.  As the Third Circuit stated in holding unconstitutional the punishment of an inmate who wrote a letter critical of the prison,  it is immaterial that the officials did not interfere directly with the mailing of the letter.  If prison officials cannot censor unflattering statements made in letters to outsiders, they also may not punish an inmate for the contents of such letters.
</p>
<p>Andolina, 826 F.2d at 1268.  Punishing an inmate for profiting from a publication can no more be tolerated than interfering directly with the dissemination of constitutionally protected expression.
</p>
<p>	An injunction against continued application of the policy will not affect the DOC's security interests.  If the introduction of currency into the prison is a security concern, a more narrowly tailored policy can be implemented restricting the amount of money that may actually enter the prison.  Although it is difficult to conceive of a situation whereby prison officials could show a compelling interest in security to justify prohibiting profits, they could still do so on a case by case basis.  Application of the policy to all prisoner publications is, however, unjustifiable and unconstitutional.
</p>
<p>	Accordingly, this court should enjoin the DOC's application of the policy prohibiting private business to publication for profit and declare that Mr. Abu-Jamal's thirty day sentence to disciplinary segregation for violating the policy was unconstitutional.
</p>
<h4>III.	ANY DOC ACTIONS AGAINST MR. ABU-JAMAL THAT WERE TAKEN IN RETALIATION FOR THE PUBLICATION OF LIVE FROM DEATH ROW ARE UNCONSTITUTIONAL.
</h4>
<p>	If Plaintiff proves that the DOC disapproved of Live From Death Row and retaliated against him because of it, both the segregation sentence and the prohibition on access to media are unconstitutional.  White v. Napoleon, 897 F.2d 103, 111-12 (3d Cir. 1990) ("Retaliation for the exercise of constitutionally protected rights is itself a violation of rights secured by the Constitution. . . ."); Millhouse v. Carlson, 652 F.2d 371, 373 (3d Cir. 1981).  Even the withdrawal of privileges that enjoy no independent constitutional protection, such as housing in general population, Sandin v. Connor, 63 U.S.L.W. 4601 (U.S. June 19, 1995) (30 day disciplinary segregation sentence does not raise due process claim), become unconstitutional when inflicted in retaliation for the exercise of a constitutionally protected right.  White, 897 F.2d at 106 (institution of disciplinary process); Andolina, 826 F.2d at 1267 (30 days disciplinary segregation); Millhouse, 652 F.2d at 372 (transfer to less desirable housing); Flanagan v. Shively, 783 F. Supp. 922, 931 (M.D. Pa. 1992) ("Transfer to another institution is a violation of plaintiff's rights only if ordered in retaliation for his exercise of constitutional rights") (citations omitted). 
</p>
<p>	Similarly, if defendants' conduct was motivated by a disapproval of the book, any relatively disadvantageous treatment of Mr. Abu-Jamal is unconstitutional.  Andolina v. Brooks, 826 F.2d 1266, 1268 (3d Cir. 1987) ("may not punish inmates for statements made in letters to outsiders, even if the same statement would be grounds for punishment if made orally to prison guards"), quoting McNamara v. Moody, 606 F.2d 621, 624 (5th Cir. 1979).  In Main Road v. Aytch, the Third Circuit ruled that the First Amendment prohibits prison officials from granting or denying a prisoner's interviews with the press based on the expected content of that interview.  522 F.2d 1080 (3d Cir. 1975).  The court stated, in relevant part, that the
</p>
<p>		First Amendment precludes [a prison official] from regulating, through the grant or denial of permission for prisoners to talk with reporters, the content of speech which reaches the news media, unless the restriction bears a substantial relationship to a significant governmental interest.
</p>
<p>Id. at 1086-87.  See also,   Kimberlin v. Quinlan, 774 F. Supp. 1 (D.D.C. 1991) ("if [prison] officials were motivated by a purpose to keep Kimberlin from speaking to the press because of the content of his expected communications [e.g., about vice presidential candidate Dan Quayle's alleged marijuana use], their conduct violated a well established right...."), rev'd on other grounds, 6 F.3d 789 (D.C. Cir. 1993) (plaintiff failed to meet heightened pleading standard that is applicable whenever officials' state of mind at issue), vacated and remanded in light of Johnson v. Jones, 67 U.S.L.W. 4556 (U.S. June 12, 1995) (No. 93-2068). 
</p>
<p>	Therefore, evidence that the defendants' actions were motivated either by a desire to punish Mr. Abu-Jamal for writing Live From Death Row or by an effort to suppress the criticism contained therein renders the prohibition on media contact unconstitutional.  If that is the case, this Court should enjoin the ban on media contact.  Moreover, unless such illicit conduct is penalized appropriately, the chill on future expression by Mr. Abu-Jamal and other prison writers will be palpable.
</p>
<h4>IV.	CONCLUSION
</h4>
<p>	Regardless whether Mr. Abu-Jamal can prove that DOC officials acted with the illicit purpose of retaliating against him for writing Live From Death Row or in an effort to suppress the criticism contained in the book, the DOC policy prohibiting financial remuneration for publishing a book is unconstitutional.  If Mr. Abu-Jamal proves that DOC officials retaliated against him for publishing the book, or to suppress discussion of it, then the prohibition on media interviews also is unconstitutional.  
</p>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%><br>
</blockquote>
<center>
