<html>
<head>
<title>ACLU in the Courts</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">
<center>
<p><b>IN THE 15th JUDICIAL CIRCUIT COURT
	PALM BEACH COUNTY, FLORIDA
                                                
<P>
  Dr. CECIL McIVER, M.D.; C.B. ("CHUCK") CASTONGUAY; ROBERT G. CRON; and CHARLES E. HALL,
	Plaintiffs,              
<p>
v.
<P>
BARRY KRISCHER, in his official capacity as State Attorney of the 15th Judicial Circuit, et al.
<P>

</b></center>
<br>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=100%><br>
<p>
	The plaintiffs, Dr. CECIL McIVER, M.D., C.B. ("CHUCK") CASTONGUAY, ROBERT G. CRON and CHARLES E. HALL, sue the defendants, BARRY KRISCHER, in his official capacity as State Attorney of the 15th Judicial Circuit; BRAD KING, in his official capacity as State Attorney of the 5th Judicial Circuit; BERNIE McCABE, in his official capacity as State Attorney of the 6th Judicial Circuit; STEVE ALEXANDER, in his official capacity as State Attorney of the 7th Judicial Circuit; and Dr. Fuad S. Ashkar, M.D., Dr. James Cerda, M.D., Dr. Edward A. Dauer, M.D., Becky Cherney, Dr. Emilio Echevarria, M.D., Dr. Georges A. El-Bahri, M.D., Dr. Martin J. Fenwick, M.D., Dr. Mary Kathryn Garrett, M.D., Dr. John W. Glotfelty, M.D., Dr. Louis C. Murray, M.D., Dr. Margaret C.S. Skinner, M.D., Cecile M. Scoon, Esq., H. Fred Varn, Dr. Gary E. Winchester, M.D., and Dr. Abraham L. Woods, M.D., each in his or her official capacity as a member of the Board of Medicine of the State of Florida, Agency for Health Care Administration, and allege:
<blockquote>
<p> 	1.	This action challenges whether Fla. Stat.  782.08, which makes it a crime for one to assist another in suicide, is unconstitutional as applied to prevent an adult, who is mentally competent, terminally ill, and acting under no undue influence, from hastening his own death by taking a lethal dose of drugs prescribed by his doctor; and whether the state medical regulatory authorities may discipline a physician for providing such assistance.
<p>	2.	The plaintiffs seek a temporary injunction, a declaratory judgment and permanent injunctive relief pursuant to the United States Constitution; Article I, Section 23 of the Florida Constitution, the Privacy Amendment; 42 U.S.C.  1983, the Civil Rights Act of 1879; and Section 86.011 et seq., Florida Statutes.
<p>	3.	The plaintiff Dr. Cecil McIver, M.D., is a physician duly licensed to practice medicine in the State of Florida and practicing in Jupiter, Palm Beach County, Florida.  Venue lies in Palm Beach County pursuant to Florida Statutes  47.011.  Dr. McIver seeks direct judicial protection from the defendants' unlawful invasion of his fundamental constitutional rights, and the constitutional rights he asserts on behalf of his patients.
<p>	4.	Moreover, the Court should dispense with any home venue privilege, if one exists for any or all defendants, because fairness, justice, and convenience would be furthered in view of the circumstances presented and the interests of all parties.
<p>	5.	The defendants' unlawful action is imminently threatened in Palm Beach County, where Dr. McIver's practice is located, within the jurisdiction of Barry Krischer, the State Attorney of the 15th Judicial Circuit.
<p>	6.	The plaintiff C.B. ("Chuck") Castonguay is a resident of Edgewater, in Volusia County, Florida, within the jurisdiction of Steve Alexander, the State Attorney of the 7th Judicial Circuit.
<p>	7.	The plaintiff Robert G. Cron is a resident of Oldsmar, in Pinellas County, Florida, within the jurisdiction of Bernie McCabe, the State Attorney of the 6th Judicial Circuit.
<p>	8.	The plaintiff Charles E. Hall is a resident of Beverly Hills, in Citrus County, Florida, within the jurisdiction of Brad King, the State Attorney of the 5th Judicial Circuit.
<p>	9.	The defendants, Barry Krischer, Brad King, Bernie McCabe and Steve Alexander (hereinafter the "State Attorneys"), act under color of state law when acting in their official capacities.  Each is vested with the sole authority to determine whom to prosecute within his territorial jurisdiction under Florida Statutes Section 782.08, entitled "assisting self murder," which provides:
<p>
			Every person deliberately assisting another in the commission of self-murder shall be guilty of manslaughter, a felony of the second degree ... 
<p>	10.	Dr. McIver is actually threatened with imminent prosecution by any one of the State Attorneys for a violation of Section 782.08 if he provides the treatment that his patients seek and that he, in the exercise of his best professional judgment, believes is appropriate.  The declaratory and injunctive relief sought in this action therefore would affect his rights and the rights he asserts on behalf of his patients.
<p>	11.	The defendants, Dr. Fuad S. Ashkar, M.D., Dr. James Cerda, M.D., Dr. Edward A. Dauer, M.D., Becky Cherney, Dr. Emilio Echevarra, M.D., Dr. Georges A. El-Bahri, M.D., Dr. Martin J. Fenwick, M.D., Dr. Mary Kathryn Garrett, M.D., Dr. John W. Glotfelty, M.D., Dr. Louis C. Murray, M.D., Dr. Margaret C.S. Skinner, M.D., Cecile M. Scoon, Esq., H. Fred Varn, Dr. Gary E. Winchester, M.D., and Dr. Abraham L. Woods, M.D. (collectively, the "Board"), are members of the Board of Medicine of the State of Florida, Agency for Health Care Administration.
<p>	12.	Each member of the Board is sued in his or her official capacity.  The Board is created by Fla. Stat.  458.301 et seq. and vested with the authority to grant, deny, revoke, and otherwise regulate a physician's license to practice medicine in Florida.  The Board is additionally authorized to investigate physicians and impose a wide range of sanctions for misconduct.
<p>	13.	The Board acts under color of state law in all these activities.
<p>	14.	Dr. McIver is actually threatened with imminent disciplinary action by the Board if he provides the treatment that his patient seeks and that he, in the exercise of his best professional judgment, believes is appropriate.  The declaratory and injunctive relief sought in this action therefore would affect his fundamental constitutional rights and the rights he asserts on behalf of his patients.
<p>	15.	The State Attorneys and the Board are additionally authorized by Florida Statutes to take other actions prejudicial to Dr. McIver if he enables the plaintiffs Castonguay, Cron and Hall to terminate their own suffering, including, but not limited to:
<blockquote>	<p>	(a)	A conviction under the assisted suicide statute could lead to disciplinary action by the Board.  See Fla. Stat.  458.331(1)(c) (creating the disciplinary violation of "[b]eing convicted ... of ... a crime ... which directly relates to the practice of medicine").
	<p>	(b)	The assistance sought by the plaintiffs Castonguay, Cron and Hall could be construed to violate Fla. Stat.  458.326(4) ("Nothing in this section shall be construed to condone, authorize, or approve mercy killing or euthanasia, and no treatment authorized by this section may be used for such purpose.").  In turn, such a violation could lead to Dr. McIver's prosecution for a crime pursuant to Fla. Stat.  458.327(2)(a) (creating a second-degree misdemeanor for "[k]nowingly concealing information relating to violations of this chapter").
	<p>	(c)	The assistance Dr. McIver seeks to provide to the plaintiffs Castonguay, Cron and Hall could also be construed to be prohibited by Section 765.309, which states that nothing in the chapter on the lawful withholding or withdrawal of life-prolonging procedures "shall be construed to condone, authorize, or approve mercy killing or euthanasia, or to permit any affirmative or deliberate act or omission to end life other than to permit the natural process of dying."</blockquote>
<p>
	<b>Castonguay</b>
<p>	16.	Castonguay, a writer, suffers from cancer of the esophagus, which has spread into his chest.  He is also a childhood polio victim.  He is 65.
<p>	17.	His cancer was diagnosed in April 1995.  Informed that medical science could offer no curative measures, he declined therapy that he felt would only prolong his illness.  He had previously, at age 53, survived a malignant melanoma.
<p>	18.	Castonguay is under the care of Hospice and is provided with morphine to control the pain in his right side.  His weight has fallen from 145 pounds to 112.
<p>	19.	He moves with great difficulty because of general weakness from his cancer coupled with the lifelong weakness in his legs caused by his childhood polio.  He has difficulty speaking and swallowing.
<p>	20.	He recognizes that his condition is deteriorating and he wishes to control the terminal stages of his inevitable decline.  His major concern is a progressive erosion in the quality of his life.  Describing himself as a "planner," he wants to "keep one jump ahead" and control the circumstances of his death.  
<p>	<b>Cron</b>
<p>	21.	Cron, the retired owner of a Clearwater printing business, suffers from mesothelioma, a cancer of the lining of the chest cavity.  He is 72.
<p>	22.	Cron took ill in September 1994, complaining of shortness of breath.  He was experiencing fluid buildup on the pleural space surrounding the lungs.  Upon diagnosis of his cancer, he underwent treatment which consisted of obliterating the pleural space, which prevented the possibility of further fluid buildup in his chest, and chemotherapy.
<p>	23.	At the end of his treatment his physician informed him that no known therapy was likely to benefit him and that his condition was terminal.  There is no reasonable doubt about his prognosis.
<p>	24.	Cron's wife and family fully understand and support his decision.  Indeed, his decision is motivated in part by a desire to minimize the emotional trauma his death will cause to them.
<p>	<b>Hall</b>
<p>	25.	Hall, a restaurateur when he last was able to work, is a victim of Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome, or AIDS.  He is 40.
<p>	26.	In 1981 Hall had back surgery to correct a problem that had developed as a result of a fall and had a blood transfusion during the surgery.  In 1993, while he was being treated for hepatitis, his doctors discovered he had contracted the AIDS virus from the transfusions twelve years earlier.
<p>	27.	Hall's health is deteriorating rapidly.  He has lost 40 pounds.  He is confined to a wheelchair because of the pain in his legs and the weakness of his leg muscles.  He suffers from severe headaches and has had some seizures.
<p>	28.	He is taking a large number of medications.  His T-cell count has fallen to approximately 110.  His prognosis in the present state of medical knowledge is hopeless and he is terminal.
<p>	29.	Hall is clearly mentally competent at this time and in fact is using his last days to develop an AIDS support group in his local community. 
<p>	*  *  *
<p>	30.	Each of the three patients whose rights Dr. McIver is asserting is mentally competent and emotionally stable.  Each is able to comprehend the ethical and moral implications of his decision to terminate his suffering. 
<p>	31.	Each recognizes that a point is likely to come at which he will experience only useless suffering, a point at which he will no longer feel the solace of knowing that his suffering will be followed by, and justified by, a period of renewed health.
<p>	32.	Each of the three patient plaintiffs, Castonguay, Cron and Hall, has a prognosis that is certainly hopeless and each is terminally ill.  Each can foresee the situation when, if natural death does not terminate his life, his best and most logical option will be to cut his suffering short and terminate life.
<p>	33.	Not having the expertise to terminate life painlessly and with certainty, Castonguay, Cron and Hall each requires the assistance of a physician.
<p>	34.	Each would prefer to die at home, in the company of those who accept his invitation to be present, having administered a substance which will induce immediate loss of consciousness and certain death shortly thereafter.
<p>	35.	Castonguay, Cron and Hall have sought the services of Dr. McIver, who is willing to exercise his professional skill and judgment to provide Castonguay, Cron and Hall with the assistance they need to end their suffering.  Without Dr. McIver's assistance, each man would confront the alternative of attempting to terminate his life in a manner that could fail and leave him in a worse condition than before his attempt, as often happens with such terminal patients.
<p>	36.	Dr. McIver has consulted with Castonguay, Cron and Hall and concluded that each is fully competent at this time to make the request he is making, and that his decision is not a result of mental illness or undue influence by others.  Dr. McIver's professional judgment is that it would be medically appropriate and ethical to provide Castonguay, Cron and Hall with the assistance they request.
<p>	37.	Absent a declaratory judgment that Castonguay, Cron and Hall each has a constitutional right to exercise the informed choice he has made, and injunctive relief to protect Dr. McIver from being punished therefore, Dr. McIver will not prescribe the drugs that his patients seek and that he believes would be appropriately and ethically prescribed under the circumstances.
<p>	38.	The decision of Castonguay, Cron and Hall whether to terminate their own suffering before nature takes its full course is one of the most intimate, personal choices they will make in their lifetime.  No decision is closer to the heart of personal liberty.  Each man's ability to make this decision without undue governmental interference is central to his personal dignity and autonomy.
<p>	39.	Accordingly, Castonguay, Cron and Hall, as mentally competent, terminally ill adults with no chance of recovery, have a right under the Florida Privacy Amendment to take their own lives with their physician's assistance and without undue interference by the state government.  By prohibiting Castonguay, Cron and Hall from making their own free choice, the government has entered a realm of individual liberty that it is not entitled to enter.
<p>	40.	Dr. McIver, as a physician duly licensed by the state of Florida, has third-party standing to assert his patients' privacy rights and additionally has a privacy right of his own to practice medicine consistent with his best professional judgment.  This privacy right includes the right to assist a competent, terminally ill adult patient such as Castonguay, Cron or Hall to hasten his death by prescribing suitable medication for self-administration by the patient.
<p>	41.	Section 782.08 does not serve a state interest sufficiently compelling to override the rights of Castonguay, Cron and Hall and Dr. McIver to privacy in the facts of this case.  To the extent that Section 782.08 serves a generally compelling state interest, that interest is at its weakest in the facts of this case.
<p>	42.	To the extent that Section 782.08 or other Florida statutes impose criminal sanctions on Dr. McIver for prescribing medication with which Castonguay, Cron or Hall would terminate his own suffering, section 782.08 or such other criminal statute is not the least intrusive means for the state of Florida to accomplish its legitimate goals.
<p>	43.	Under the Privacy Amendment, the right to privacy which Dr. McIver and Castonguay, Cron and Hall seek to vindicate is a right vouchsafed to them by the Florida Constitution.  Yet Dr. McIver and Castonguay, Cron and Hall have been deprived of these rights without due process of law, in contravention of their rights under the Fourteenth Amendment.
<p>	44.	The plaintiffs have no adequate remedy at law and face imminent and irreparable loss of their rights.  Absent expedited consideration and prompt injunction, the plaintiffs will continue to suffer substantial and irreparable harm and their rights will finally and fully be denied before this Court can rule.
<p>	45.	The State Attorneys and the Board are acting under color of state law in depriving Dr. McIver, Castonguay, Cron and Hall of these state-created rights without due process of law.
<p>	46.	Dr. McIver, Castonguay, Cron and Hall have been forced to retain the undersigned counsel to vindicate their right to privacy in the actions they propose to take.  They have been forced to incur court costs and a reasonable attorneys' fee in connection with this action.
<p>	47.	The plaintiffs are entitled to recover all costs and a reasonable attorneys' fee pursuant to 42 U.S.C.  1988 and Florida common law.
<p>	WHEREFORE, the plaintiffs, Dr. McIver, Castonguay, Cron and Hall, pray that the Court take jurisdiction over these parties and this action, enter such orders as are appropriate to expedite consideration of this action, and:
<blockquote>	<p>	(a)	Enter a declaratory judgment that Castonguay, Cron and Hall each has a constitutional right under the Privacy Amendment to make the decision to terminate his own suffering, and to seek his physician's assistance to do so, under the circumstances of this case;
	<p>	(b)	Enter a declaratory judgment that Dr. McIver is entitled to assert the rights of Castonguay, Cron and Hall and his own right to provide Castonguay, Cron and Hall with the assistance they request;
	<p>	(c)	Enter a temporary and permanent injunction prohibiting the State Attorneys from prosecuting Dr. McIver under Section 782.08, or any other Florida criminal statute, for engaging in the conduct specifically found by the Court's declaratory judgment to be constitutionally protected;
	<p>	(d)	Enter a temporary and permanent injunction prohibiting the State Attorneys from prosecuting, under Section 782.08, or any other Florida criminal statute, anyone who is present or who assists Castonguay, Cron or Hall, at the patient's request, in the administration of his prescription;
	<p>	(e)	Enter a temporary and permanent injunction prohibiting the Board from investigating or convening a probable cause panel to investigate or to make a probable cause determination against Dr. McIver pursuant to Fla. Stat.  455.255(1)-(4) and 458.307(b) for engaging in the conduct specifically found by the Court's declaratory judgment to be constitutionally protected, from finding probable cause therefore, and from imposing or attempting to impose on Dr. McIver any disciplinary action therefore, pursuant to Fla. Stat.  458.333, including, but not limited to, revocation or suspension of license, restriction of practice, probation, the imposition of conditions on continued licensure, fines, or the issuance of a letter of concern or other type of public or private reprimand.
	<p>	(f)	Awarding the plaintiffs all costs and a reasonable attorneys' fee for the prosecution of this action pursuant to 42 U.S.C.  1988 and Florida common law.
<p></blockquote></blockquote>		Dated this 16th day of February, 1996.
			<p>			Respectfully submitted,
<p>
						HOLLAND & KNIGHT<br>
						Counsel for Plaintiffs<br>
						625 N. Flagler Dr., Suite 700<br>
						West Palm Beach, FL   33401<br>
						Tel: (407) 833-2000<br>
						Fax: (407) 650-8399<br>
<p>


						By:<br>
							Robert Rivas<br>
							 Florida Bar No. 896969<br>
<p>

 		Cooperating Attorneys for the American Civil Liberties Union Foundation of Florida, Inc.

