          4.   The Commission's Reports and Orders      <br>
          5.   The Proceedings Below    <br>
     <a href="#sum">SUMMARY OF THE ARGUMENT</a><br>
    <a href="#arg"> THE ARGUMENT</a>   
</blockquote>
<p>
     <a name="qp"><b>QUESTIONS PRESENTED</b></a>
<p>
     Sections 10(a) and 10(b) of the 1992 Cable Act establish a comprehensive scheme for
censorship of "indecent" programming on leased access channels.  Congress authorized cable
operators to prohibit programming that they "reasonably believe" to be indecent and, in the
alternative, required such protected speech to be placed on segregated channels that must be
blocked until the subscriber requests access in writing and for up to thirty days thereafter. 
Section 10(c) authorized cable operators to prohibit programming on public, educational, and
governmental access channels that is "sexually explicit" or "solicits or promotes unlawful
conduct."
<br>
     1.   Is section 10's explicitly content- and speaker-based censorship scheme subject to
First Amendment scrutiny?<br>
     2.   Is section 10 unconstitutional because it authorizes and requires censorship under
vague standards and lacks essential procedural safeguards?<br>
     3.   Is section 10's content- and speaker-based censorship scheme   which regulates
"indecent" speech on only access channels and is not the least restrictive means of accomplishing
a compelling governmental interest   unconstitutional under the First Amendment?     
<p>
<a name="list"><b>LIST OF PARTIES</b></a>
<p>
     The judgment here reviewed was rendered in a proceeding in the United States Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit addressing four petitions for review of orders of the
Federal Communications Commission.
  <p>   In addition to those listed on the cover, respondents include Alliance for Community
Media, Alliance for Communications Democracy, People For the American Way, New York
Citizens Committee for Responsible Media, Media Access New York, Brooklyn Producers'
Group, and David Channon.  The foregoing respondents are petitioners in no. 95-227, which has
been consolidated with the present action, and their interests are aligned with those of petitioners
here.
<p>     Respondents also include National Cable Television Association, Inc., which was an
intervenor in all four proceedings before the court of appeals.
<p>
     RULE 29.6 NOTATION<br>
     Petitioners have no parent companies or subsidiaries.     
 <p>
     I.   All of Section 10 Is Impermissibly Content-Based, and No Part Can Be
Immunized from Constitutional Review by the State Action Doctrine     13
<blockquote>      
 <p>    A.   The Court Must Determine the Validity of Section 10 and Cannot Do That
Without Reaching and Deciding the First Amendment Challenge 14
     <p>      B.   The Issue Is Whether Section 10 Violates the Constitution, Not Whether
Particular Censorship Decisions of Cable Operators Would Be State Action   19
<blockquote>     <p>           1.   The state action doctrine is inapposite 19
     <p>           2.   Section 10 does not "restore" rights to cable operators, and a partial
restoration is constitutionally reviewable in any event     21
     <p>           3.   Section 10 cannot escape constitutional scrutiny, because it
preempts contrary state law, significantly encourages content-based censorship, and embroils the
Commission as a joint participant in the censorship scheme  23
</blockquote></blockquote>  
<p>    II.  Section 10 Is Unconstitutional Because It Authorizes and Requires Censorship
under Vague Standards and Lacks Essential Procedural Safeguards  25
<blockquote><p>        A.   Section 10 Is Completely Vague     25
     <p>      B.   Pacifica Is Not Controlling   32
    <p>       C.   Section 10 Lacks Essential Procedural Safeguards  36
</blockquote>
     <p> III. Section 10's Content-Based Direct Burdens on Free Speech Rights Violate the
First Amendment     38
<blockquote>      <p>     A.   Sections 10(a) and 10(c) Are Not Narrowly Tailored     41
       <p>    B.   Section 10(b) Is Not Narrowly Tailored  42
<blockquote>          <p>      1.   Section 10(b) is impermissibly overinclusive, because its
restrictions on speech do not advance the government's goals     42
          <p>      2.   Section 10(b) imposes unnecessary burdens on speech    43
          <p>      3.   Section 10(b) is impermissibly underinclusive, because it blocks
speech only by leased access programmers     47
 </blockquote></blockquote><p>
 CONCLUSION     49
