<p>
     <a name="ob"><b>OPINIONS BELOW</b></a>
<p>
     The en banc opinion of the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia
Circuit is reported at 56 F.3d 105 and reprinted in the appendix to the petition for writ of
certiorari ("Pet. __a") at 2a.  The en banc per curiam order vacating the panel decision is reported
at 15 F.3d 186 and reprinted at Pet. 89a.  The panel decision is reported at 10 F.3d 812 and
reprinted at Pet. 90a.
<p>
     <a name="jur"><b>JURISDICTION</b></a>
<p>
     The court of appeals issued its decision on June 6, 1995 and stayed issuance of the
mandate on July 10, 1995.  Pet. 1a.  The Court docketed the timely petition for writ of certiorari
on July 21, 1995 and granted the petition on November 13, 1995.  The Court has jurisdiction
under 28 U.S.C.    1254(1) and 2350(a).
<p>
<a name="con"><b>CONSTITUTIONAL PROVISIONS, STATUTES, AND REGULATIONS INVOLVED</b></a>
<p>
     The First Amendment to the Constitution provides, in pertinent part, that "Congress shall
make no law . . . abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press."  The Fifth Amendment to the
Constitution to the United States provides, in pertinent part, that "No person shall . . . be deprived
of life, liberty, or property, without due process of law."
<p>
     Section 10 of the Cable Television Consumer Protection and Competition Act of 1992,
Pub. L. No. 102-385,   10, 106 Stat. 1460, 1486 (codified at 47 U.S.C.    531, 532(h), 532(j),
and 558) ("section 10" or "  10") is reproduced at Pet. 126a.  See also Statutory Addendum
below ("Stat. __a") (relevant provisions governing leased access and PEG access channels).
<p>
     The implementing regulations of the Federal Communications Commission (the
"Commission") are the First Report and Order in the Matter of Implementation of Section 10 of
the Cable Consumer Protection and Competition Act of 1992, 8 FCC Rcd 998 (1993) (codified at
47 C.F.R.   76.701) ("First Report"), reproduced at Pet. 128a, and the Second Report and Order
in the Matter of Implementation of Section 10 of the Cable Consumer Protection and
Competition Act of 1992, 8 FCC Rcd 2638 (1993) (codified at 47 C.F.R.   76.702) ("Second
Report"), reproduced at Pet. 178a.
<p>
     <a name="sc"><b>STATEMENT OF THE CASE</b></a>
<p>
     1.   Local Regulation and the 1984 Cable Act.  Cable access channels were first
created in the 1960s, as cable operators received franchises from local authorities.  Local
governments provided "use of public rights-of-way and easements" essential to the cable
system's "physical infrastructure," Turner Broadcasting Sys., Inc. v. FCC, 114 S. Ct. 2445, 2452
(1994), and, in turn, generally required cable operators to act as conduits and set aside some
portion of their channel capacity for the public, thereby providing a "direct right of access to the
video media" through access channels, the content of which cable operators were generally
prohibited from controlling, Daniel L. Brenner et al., Cable Television and Other Nonbroadcast
Video   6.04[1], at 6-31 (1995); cf. Turner, 114 S. Ct. at 2465 (cable operators are also conduits
for broadcast signals).
<p>
     In 1972, the Commission promulgated mandatory access rules, requiring the largest cable
operators to offer, by 1977, access to the public on a first-come, nondiscriminatory basis, with
operators having no control over content.  36 F.C.C.2d 143 (1972).  In 1976, the Commission
revised and reissued its mandatory access rules, applying them to more cable systems and
extending the compliance date for most systems to 1986.  59 F.C.C.2d 294 (1976).  On review of
these rules, this Court held them statutorily unauthorized.  FCC v. Midwest Video Corp., 440
U.S. 689 (1979).
<p>
     Although the Commission lacked authority to mandate cable access channels, local
franchising authorities were free to do so, and, in the wake of Midwest Video, almost all
franchise agreements continued to provide for access by community groups over public access
channels, where operators functioned simply as conduits, and prohibited operator control of
content.  See H.R. Rep. No. 934, 98th Cong., 2d Sess. 30 (1984).
<p>
     Then, in 1984, to "assure that cable communications provide . . . the widest possible
diversity of information sources and services to the public," Congress passed the Cable
Communication Policy Act of 1984, Pub. L. No. 98-549, 98 Stat. 2780.  47 U.S.C.   521.  This
Act required cable operators to set aside channels for leased access programming that the
operators were forbidden to censor.  Id.   532(b), (c)(2).  It also prohibited them from censoring
programming on the public, educational, and governmental ("PEG") access channels required
under cable franchise agreements.  Id.   531(e).  Because cable operators were barred from
exercising editorial control over these access channels, Congress explicitly shielded cable
operators from liability for access programming.  Id.   558.  In another provision of the Act,
Congress required operators to provide "lockboxes" that enable a subscriber to block any cable
channel during selected periods, id.   544(d)(2); this provision remains in effect.
<p>
     2.   The 1992 Cable Act.  In 1992, Congress again focused on the cable industry   this
time primarily to promote diversity through temporary rate re-regulation, address customer
service practices, and implement "must-carry" broadcast rules   and enacted the Cable Television
Consumer Protection and Competition Act of 1992, Pub. L. No. 102-385, 106 Stat. 1460.  On the
last legislative day before the Senate approved its bill, Senator Helms offered two floor
amendments and then-Senator Fowler offered a third that collectively became   10, entitled
"Children's Protection from Indecent Programming on Leased Access Channels."  Senator Helms
plainly stated the purpose of   10's liability provision:  to "put an end to the kind of things going
on" on access channels.  138 Cong. Rec. S652 (daily ed. Jan. 30, 1992).  No other provision in
the lengthy Senate or House bills even remotely treated "indecency" or protection of children. 
Section 10 was never sent to a committee and was never the subject of any congressional
hearings or findings.
<p>
     Section 10 established a censorship scheme with four interlocking parts.  Section 10(a)
authorized cable operators to ban from leased access channels what they "reasonably believe[]
describes or depicts sexual or excretory activities or organs in a patently offensive manner as
measured by contemporary community standards."  Pet. 126a.  Cable operators were given, and
have, no other "editorial discretion" to regulate the content of leased access programming.  Pet.
126a; Stat. 2a-4a.
<p>
     Section 10(b), the stated purpose of which is "to limit the access of children to indecent
programming," required the Commission to prescribe rules requiring cable operators that have
not "voluntarily prohibited" programming under   10(a) to segregate all "indecent" leased access
programming on channels that must remain blocked until a subscriber requests access in writing;
Congress mandated no time period within which such requests must be satisfied.  Pet. 126a-27a. 
Section 10(b) also required the Commission to prescribe rules requiring leased access
programmers to identify for cable operators any of their programs that "would be indecent as
defined by Commission regulations."  Pet. 126a.
<p>
     Section 10(c) applied to PEG access channels and authorized cable operators to ban "any
programming which contains obscene material, sexually explicit conduct, or material soliciting
or promoting unlawful conduct."  Pet. 127a.  However, if a cable operator does not ban particular
"indecent" PEG programming, it may cablecast that programming without blocking, just as it
may cablecast "indecent" programming on its commercial channels without blocking (where it
functions as publisher rather than simply as conduit) and must cablecast such broadcast
programming without blocking.  See Pet. 127a.
<p>
     Section 10(d) eliminates cable operators' statutory immunity from liability for access
programming that "involves obscene material."  Pet. 127a.  Taken together with   10's other
provisions,   10(d) virtually compels cable operators to censor "indecency."
<p>
     3.   Comments to the Rule Making.  On November 10, 1992, the Commission issued a
notice of proposed rule making to implement   10 and requested comments.  Petitioners Denver
Area Educational Telecommunications Consortium, Inc. ("DAETC"), which is a nonprofit leased
access cable programmer, and American Civil Liberties Union ("ACLU"), whose members
include leased and PEG access viewers (also collectively "petitioners"), submitted comments to
the Commission challenging the constitutionality of   10 and describing its impact on a wide
variety of access programming of serious journalistic or artistic value.
<p>
     Petitioners noted their concern with   10's capacious definition of "indecent
programming" as "describ[ing] or depict[ing] sexual or excretory activities or organs in a
patently offensive manner as measured by contemporary community standards."  Pet. 126a. 
Because this definition has no substantive content except to subject all programming that
contains any mention of human reproduction or sexuality, regardless of its value, to a
retrospective assessment of "community standards" of "offensiveness," it encompasses a far
wider, but uncertain, range of programming than Senator Helms evidently envisioned from the
anecdotal examples he offered on the Senate floor.  Comments of DAETC, JA 203-04.  Even if
one could identify programming that actually contains "indecent" material,   10(a) exacerbates
the overbreadth of that definition by granting cable operators authority to prohibit programs that
they "reasonably believe" contain indecent material.  Reply Comments of DAETC, JA 330-31;
see Acton Corp., JA 1-2.
<p>
     Indeed, much of DAETC's socially useful programming would be swept up in   10's
broad definition of "indecency."  DAETC's cable access service, which is known as "The 90's
Channel" and is offered in a block of programming reaching approximately 500,000 households,
presents in a verit style a wide variety of material.  Its programming is often controversial and
otherwise unavailable and discusses topics including the Persian Gulf war, environmental
contamination, AIDS, racism, US-Cuba relations, art censorship, union organizing, the status of
recent immigrants, gay rights, the Palestinian uprising, issues of concern to Native Americans,
prostitution, and prison conditions.  Comments of DAETC, JA 199-201.  An important part of
DAETC's programming on many of these topics inextricably deals with sexuality, such as the
program segments about an organization that seeks to demystify gynecology and teach women
how to perform their own pelvic exams, the controversy surrounding a Robert Mapplethorpe art
exhibit, a pro-choice performance artist, and an annual Japanese fertility festival   all of which
might well fall within   10's broad regulatory definition of "indecency" or cable operators'
"reasonable beliefs" about "indecency."  Program Segments Carried by The 90's Channel Dealing
with Sexuality, JA 224-25; see Pet. 44a-45a (Wald, J., dissenting).
<p>
     In their comments to the Commission, cable operators expressed their concern that   10
offended the First Amendment.  Many commented that Congress' existing requirement of
lockboxes already satisfies the government's asserted interest in protecting  children from
"indecency," particularly in light of cable's status as an invitee in the home for which the
subscriber voluntarily pays a monthly fee.  Some commented that, although the bans authorized
by    10(a) and 10(c) are in form voluntary, the impact of   10 in many instances is likely to be a
de facto ban on the targeted, yet protected, speech.
<p>
     Local cable authorities complained that the proposed rules would deprive them of their
state-law rights to prohibit cable operators from controlling the content of cable access
programming, which many of them had exercised even before the Commission attempted to
mandate access channels in the 1970s.  City of St. Paul, JA 318-26; National Ass'n of
Telecommunications Officers & Advisors, JA 345; see Continental Cablevision, Inc., JA 181,
186-87 (requesting clarification that agreements prohibiting operator control of access channels
are preempted).
<p>
     4.   The Commission's Reports and Orders.  On February 3, 1993, the Commission
released its First Report, which adopted regulations to implement    10(a) and 10(b) relating to
leased access channels.  Pet. 128a.  Despite petitioners' and other comments, the Commission
defined "indecent" programming almost identically to the language used in   10(a), authorized a
cable operator to adopt and enforce a policy of banning leased access programming that it
"reasonably believes" contains indecency, and, if a cable operator does not voluntarily adopt and
enforce such a policy, required it to block all leased access programming that falls within the
Commission's definition of "indecency."  47 C.F.R.   76.701, Pet. 171a-72a.  Cable operators are
also allowed to delay for up to thirty days satisfying a subscriber's written request to receive
blocked programming.  Id.   76.701(c), Pet. 171a.
<p>
     The First Report's regulations further required leased access programmers to identify
whether any of their programming is indecent and to certify at the operator's request whether any
or all of their programming is indecent or obscene.  If a programmer fails to provide this
identification or certification in a timely fashion, the cable operator may cut off access to that
programmer altogether.  Id.   76.701(f), Pet. 172a.  If a cable operator (or a subscriber) disagrees
with a programmer's certification, the Commission "will entertain special relief petitions."  Pet.
167a-68a.  In order to exercise the censorship power delegated to them, cable operators are
further authorized to "pre-screen" all leased access programming.  Pet. 151a n.39.
<p>
     The Commission's Second Report adopted regulations to implement   10(c) relating to
PEG access channels.  Pet. 178a.  The Commission interpreted   10(c) to authorize cable
operators to prohibit obscene material, indecent material (defined as in the First Report, rather
than as   10(c)'s "sexually explicit material"), and material soliciting or promoting unlawful
conduct (interpreted by the Commission as "material that is otherwise proscribed by law").  47
C.F.R.   76.702, Pet. 197a-98a.  To further facilitate censorship of access programming, the
regulations provided that a cable operator may require a PEG access programmer "to certify that
its programming does not contain any of the materials" subject to   10(c) prohibition.  Id., Pet.
198a.  Additionally, the Commission stated that it would not consider disputes from subscribers
or PEG programmers complaining of undue censorship.  Pet. 194a.
<p>
     The Commission also determined in each of the reports and orders that   10 and its
implementing regulations preempt contrary state or local law and contrary provisions in cable
franchise agreements.  Pet. 157 n.44, 183a n.7.
<p>
     5.   The Proceedings Below.  Petitioners petitioned the Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia Circuit for review pursuant to 28 U.S.C.   2342(1).  These petitions were
consolidated with others, and the Commission and the United States (collectively the
Commission or the "government") were respondents in each.
<p>
     After oral argument during which the government conceded that, if    10(a) and 10(c)
involved "state action," they would violate the First Amendment, Pet. 104a n.9, a panel of the
court unanimously struck down    10(a) and 10(c).  As to   10(b) and its implementing
regulations, the panel found such serious constitutional questions due to their apparent
underinclusiveness that it remanded them to the Commission for reconsideration.  Pet. 112a-25a.
<p>
     The full court vacated the panel's judgment, reheard the case en banc, and sustained   10
and the regulations over the dissent in whole or in part of four of the court's eleven judges.  Pet.
4a-5a.  The majority concluded   in an unprecedented holding   that the court could avoid
reaching petitioners' constitutional challenges to a content-based statute regulating protected
speech and the implementing regulations because they only authorize, rather than command,
private parties to ban the targeted speech and because those private acts cannot be attributed to
the government.  Pet. 11a-27a.  As to   10(b), which compels blocking in the absence of banning
on leased access channels, the majority held, despite the absence of legislative or administrative
support, that it is the least restrictive means to serve the "compelling" interest in shielding minors
from "indecent" speech, Pet. 32a-36a, and cursorily determined that   10 is not impermissibly
vague, Pet. 42a-43a.
<p>
     In her dissenting opinion joined in full by Judge Tatel, Judge Wald pointed out that   
10(a) and 10(b) must be considered together as part of one scheme regulating leased access
programming, which, rather than "restore" editorial control to cable operators, requires them
either to ban or block "indecent programming" and, as such, is clearly subject to First
Amendment scrutiny.  Pet. 46a-53a.  Now also joined by Judge Rogers, Judge Wald concluded
that    10(a) and 10(b) unconstitutionally cause a deprivation of First Amendment rights because
of their undue burden on both speakers and listeners, Pet. 54a-58a, and are not the least
restrictive means of achieving the asserted compelling interest because of the ready availability
of less restrictive means, such as the existing lockbox requirement, Pet. 66a-71a.  Additionally,
Judge Wald found that   10(c), with its governmentally imposed definitions of disfavored speech
and its erection of a separate statutory scheme to regulate such speech, clearly constitutes
governmental action and is not the least restrictive means of achieving the asserted compelling
interest.  Pet. 71a-75a.
<p>
     Chief Judge Edwards dissented in part and found that    10(a) and 10(b), which must be
read together, involve government action (while   10(c) does not) and that they work in tandem
to produce an impermissible ban on protected speech.  Pet. 77a-81a.  Chief Judge Edwards also
questioned whether the government's asserted interest in shielding minors from "indecency" was
compelling.  Pet. 82a-84a.  Judge Rogers, concurring in part and dissenting in part, agreed that  
10(b) is unconstitutional, but argued that it is severable from    10(a) and 10(c).  Pet. 85a-88a.
<p>
<a name="sum"><b>SUMMARY OF THE ARGUMENT</b></a>
<p>
     Section 10 and its implementing regulations cannot escape constitutional scrutiny
because laws regulating speech and discriminating on the basis of content and speaker identity
are subject to review regardless of whether every action taken under them is state action. 
Congress, through 28 U.S.C.     2342-49, directed the courts to "determine the validity" of all
Commission regulations, which necessarily requires resolution of constitutional challenges. 
Moreover,  10 preempts state laws banning operator censorship of access channels and
establishes the Commission as a joint participant in the censorship scheme.  (Point I.)
<p>
     Section 10 and its implementing regulations are invalid because they authorize operators
to ban disfavored speech under impermissibly vague standards and without the procedural
safeguards required of all laws that authorize the prohibition of speech based on its content.  FCC
v. Pacifica Found., 438 U.S. 726 (1978), is not to the contrary, because, in an adjudicative (rather
than facial) challenge, it narrowly addressed the permissibility of an "indecent language"
standard and did so only in the context of channeling.  Here, however, private delegates are
ordered to segregate and block a completely vague category of "patently offensive"
"programming" (not merely "language") if they do not prohibit it outright on a "reasonable
belief" that it is "indecent," all without administrative or judicial superintendence.  (Point II.)
<p>
     Finally,    10 is invalid because it imposes new censorship and other substantial burdens
on protected speech due to its content and the identity of its speakers.  Moreover, assuming
further scrutiny is necessary,    10's application to far more speech than might be harmful to
minors, the underinclusiveness of the blocking requirement (cable operators are free to continue
cablecasting identical speech on PEG and commercial channels without blocking), and the
availability of less restrictive but equally effective alternatives (such as lockboxes and blocking
on request) doom the censorship system that    10 created for access channels.  (Point III.)
<p>
     <a name="arg"><b>ARGUMENT</b></a>
<p>
     Cable programmers "engage in and transmit speech, and they are entitled to the
protection of the speech and press provisions of the First Amendment" when they create and
disseminate " original programming . . . on a wide variety of topics and in a wide variety of
formats.'"  Turner, 114 S. Ct. at 2456 (citation omitted).
<p>
     Their speech is no less protected when it touches on sex.  As this Court held in Roth v.
United States, 354 U.S. 476, 487 (1957), "[t]he portrayal of sex, e.g., in art, literature and
scientific works, is not itself sufficient reason to deny material the constitutional protection of
freedom of speech and press.  Sex, a great and mysterious motive force in human life, has
indisputably been a subject of absorbing interest to mankind through the ages; it is one of the
vital problems of human interest and public concern."
<p>
     Given    10's extraordinarily sweeping definition of "indecency" and authorization to
censor speech upon a "reasonable belief" that that broad definition is met (see Point II below),
this case must be decided in full recognition that    10 imperils the presentation of speech of
substantial artistic, literary, scientific, medical, educational, and social importance:  speech that is
protected not only for adults, but for teenagers as well.  The measure of the threatened speech is
the capacious, subjective language of    10 and the unsuperintended discretion it affords, not the
anecdotal allegations with which sponsors regaled Congress during the brief hours that    10 was
considered.  Cf. Estate of Cowart v. Nicklos Drilling, 505 U.S. 469, 475 (1992); West Virginia
Univ. Hosps., Inc. v. Casey, 499 U.S. 83, 97-98 (1991).
<p>
I.  All of Section 10 Is Impermissibly Content-Based, and No Part Can Be Immunized from
Constitutional Review by the State Action Doctrine.
<p>
     Recognizing (indeed conceding at oral argument below, Pet. 104a n.9) that      10(a) and
10(c) could not pass muster under the First Amendment, the government attempts to avoid
constitutional scrutiny altogether.  Remarkably, the en banc majority decided that it need "not
reach petitioners' First Amendment attack on sections 10(a) and 10(c)," because "a private cable
operator may refuse to carry indecent programming without having its decision tested by First
Amendment principles applicable to the government alone."  Pet. 31a; see Pet. 11a-12a. 
However, because a cable operator may censor only under the authority and to the limited extent
Congress devised in      10(a) and 10(c), the court's holding is indefensible, and its reasoning is a
non sequitur.
<p>
     All statutes are subject to constitutional constraint and, therefore, necessarily to
constitutional review.  Properly analyzed, this case presents no state action issue at all, and    10
is subject, in its entirety, to strict scrutiny.
<p><blockquote>
A.   The Court Must Determine the Validity of Section 10.
<p></blockquote>
     The First Amendment provides that "Congress shall make no law . . . abridging the
freedom of speech, or of the press."  Section 10 is plainly such a law and, thus, is subject to "the
most exacting scrutiny," according to a long line of cases concerning "regulations that suppress,
disadvantage, or impose differential burdens upon speech because of its content," Turner, 114 S.
Ct. at 2459 (emphasis added), as well as cases concerning laws that directly burden expression.
<p>
     Before    10's enactment, federal law and many state and local laws and agreements
prohibited cable operators from interfering in any manner with programming on access channels,
regardless of content, because access channels' very raison d'tre is to establish a forum in which
persons other than large media companies can speak to the public in one of the Nation's most
important mediums of communication.  Now, however,
<p><blockquote>
     section 10(a) authorizes and encourages cable operators to ban speech depending on its
content  i.e., programming that the operator "reasonably believes" to be "indecent" (a term
Congress and the Commission defined)  and only if such programming is offered by a leased
access cable programmer;
<p>
     section 10(c) authorizes and encourages cable operators to ban speech depending on its
content  i.e., programming that is "sexually explicit" or "solicits or promotes unlawful conduct"
 and only if such programming is offered by a PEG access cable programmer;
<p>
     sections 10(a) and 10(b) require cable operators either to promulgate and enforce written
policies banning speech believed to be indecent on leased access channels or to block such
programming pursuant to Commission regulations;
<p>
     sections 10(a) and 10(c) authorize cable operators to pre-screen access programming for
the sole purpose of ferreting out material that either they believe to be "indecent" or that
"promotes" unlawful conduct; and
<p>
     sections 10(a), 10(b), and 10(c) preempt all state and local laws, and all franchise or other
agreements entered into pursuant to those laws, that prohibit cable operators from pre-screening,
banning, blocking, or otherwise interfering with speech on access channels.
Given those provisions, the content- and speaker-based lines they embody, and the stated
purposes of the bill's sponsors,      10(a) and 10(c) are core candidates for the exacting First
Amendment review required by Turner and the cases cited above at 14 n.15.  
<p></blockquote>
     The court of appeals' contrary conclusion was premised on the fact that the actor directly
undertaking the newly authorized censorship decisions would be a private party, thereby
rendering successful Senator Helms' attempt to craft anti-"indecency" legislation that would
escape First Amendment scrutiny.  But it has long been the rule, both in cases challenging
Commission action, see Columbia Broadcasting Sys., Inc. v. United States, 316 U.S. 407, 415-17
(1942), and elsewhere, that courts consider the harm that laws and rules are likely to cause,
regardless of who "directly" causes the harm.
<p>
     "[I]n passing upon constitutional questions the court has regard to substance and not to
mere matters of form, and . . . the statute must be tested by its operation and effect."  Near v.
Minnesota, 283 U.S. 697, 708 (1931); accord Federal Election Comm'n v. Massachusetts
Citizens for Life, Inc., 479 U.S. 238, 255 (1986) (plurality opinion) ("The fact that the statute's
practical effect may be to discourage protected speech is sufficient to characterize [it] as an
infringement on First Amendment activities").
<p>
     Nothing in Turner or in any other case delineating the kinds of laws subject to exacting
scrutiny suggests that a properly presented constitutional challenge can be not reached simply
because the harms flowing from statutory implementation flow through private parties.
<p>
     Cases in other constitutional contexts make the same point and have subjected statutes to
scrutiny even where no harm would have occurred unless a third party did something that it was
authorized (but not compelled) to do.  For example, this Court invalidated a statute authorizing
cable operators to invade apartment buildings, even though the statute did not direct any entry
whatsoever and merely "adjusted" property rights, leaving cable operators free to enter or not. 
Loretto v. Teleprompter Manhattan CATV Corp., 458 U.S. 419 (1982).  Similarly, this Court
struck under the Establishment Clause a statute authorizing churches and schools to veto
applications for certain liquor licenses, even though churches are not state actors and were free to
use the veto or not.  Larkin v. Grendel's Den, Inc., 459 U.S. 116 (1982).
<p>
     The court of appeals' decision to "not reach" petitioners' First Amendment challenge, Pet.
31a, disregards the very provisions pursuant to which this action is brought.  Congress directed
the courts of appeals, in 28 U.S.C.      2342, 2344, and 2349, to "determine the validity of . . . all
final orders of the Federal Communications Commission," 28 U.S.C.    2342(1), and "make and
enter . . . a judgment determining the validity of . . . the order of the agency," id.    2349(a).
<p>
     The courts could not "determine the validity" of the Commission's final rules, however,
without considering properly presented constitutional challenges.  See Marbury v. Madison, 5
U.S. (1 Cranch) 137 (1803).  Indeed, it is axiomatic that in every proper case it is the court's duty
"to say what the law is" and to refuse to give effect to a statute or regulation that violates the
Constitution.  Id. at 177.  That is why this Court has routinely considered constitutional
challenges in cases brought pursuant to 28 U.S.C.    2342 (or its predecessor), without ever
pausing to see "whether state action is present."  See, e.g., Midwest Video, 440 U.S. 689; FCC v.
National Citizens Comm. for Broadcasting, 436 U.S. 775 (1978); Columbia Broadcasting Sys.,
Inc. v. Democratic Nat'l Comm., 412 U.S. 94 (1973); National Broadcasting Co. v. United
States, 319 U.S. 190, 226 (1943).
<p>
     For the court of appeals not to "reach" the challenge to      10(a) and 10(c)  not even to
decide whether the First Amendment forbids Congress from delegating to private parties the
authority that they had theretofore lacked to censor speech depending on its content  violates
both    2342 and the obligation to say "what the law is" in a proper case.
<p>
     The en banc court asserted that    10 was not subject to review under the First
Amendment because "it simply adjusted editorial authority between two private groups."  Pet.
15a (emphasis added).  So characterizing    10 does not support an abdication of judicial review. 
Just the contrary, a legislative "adjustment" of who will have the right to speak would seem to
provide a core occasion for review.  See PruneYard Shopping Ctr. v. Robins, 447 U.S. 74 (1980)
(rejecting on the merits a claim that state's adjustment of right to speak on private property
violated the Fifth and Fourteenth Amendments); Miami Herald Publishing Co. v. Tornillo, 418
U.S. 241 (1974) (upholding on the merits a challenge to state adjustment of right to speak in print
publication); Columbia Broadcasting Sys. v. Democratic Nat'l Comm., 412 U.S. 94 (rejecting on
the merits a claim that the First Amendment required change in the existing distribution of
speech rights on public airwaves).
<p>
     This Court has insisted that "where legislative abridgment of [First Amendment] rights is
asserted, the courts should be astute to examine the effect of the challenged legislation" and
decide its constitutionality in "every case."  Schneider v. State, 308 U.S. 147, 161 (1939)
(emphasis added).  The court of appeals disobeyed that mandate here when it chose to "not
reach" petitioners' First Amendment attack on sections 10(a) and 10(c).  Pet. 31a.
<p><blockquote>
B.   The Issue Is Whether Section 10 Violates the Constitution, Not Whether Particular
Censorship Decisions of Cable Operators Would Be State Action.
<blockquote>
     1.   The state action doctrine is inapposite.
<p></blockquote>
     Petitioners' challenge to the constitutionality of    10 poses no state action question, and
none need be resolved.  The state action doctrine arises when a private party's actions are claimed
to be subject to constitutional constraint, an issue this case does not raise.  It has no relevance to
any question of whether particular statutes are somehow insulated from constitutional review.
<p>
     Neither the court of appeals' lengthy discussion, nor any brief that the Commission
submitted, cites any case refusing to reach a properly presented constitutional challenge to a
statute or regulation upon a determination that actions taken pursuant thereto would not be "state
action."  Petitioners have not found a single case holding that a constitutional challenge to a
statute need not be reached on state action grounds.
<p>
     The court seemed to believe Reitman v. Mulkey, 387 U.S. 369 (1967), supported its
decision, Pet. 16a-17a, but it does just the opposite.  Reitman's relevant teaching is not so much
the 5-4 decision on the merits, but the Court's unanimous decision to reach the constitutionality
of the state constitutional amendment repealing fair housing statutes and making future ones
more difficult to enact.  Although on the merits the four dissenting justices disagreed sharply,
they found "no question that the adoption of    26 . . . constituted  state action' within the meaning
of the Fourteenth Amendment.  The only issue is whether this provision impermissibly deprives
any person of equal protection of the laws."  387 U.S. at 392 (Harlan, J., dissenting) (emphasis
added).
<p>
     To the same effect is San Francisco Arts & Athletics, Inc. v. United States Olympic
Comm., 483 U.S. 522 (1987), another decision on which the government inexplicably relied. 
The relevant portion of that case is the disposition on the merits of the facial challenge to a
statute as violative of free speech rights, even though no speech would have even been arguably
impaired unless a private party took the action that the statute authorized but did not compel. 
Because the constitutionality of a federal statute was challenged, the Court was obliged to reach
and decide the merits of the First Amendment attack, and every member of the Court did.
<p>
     This Court has insisted on "careful attention to the gravamen of the plaintiff's complaint"
in considering state action issues.  Blum v. Yaretsky, 457 U.S. 991, 1003 (1982).  Here, the
petitions for review challenged the validity of    10 and its implementing regulations under   
2342 and did not raise the question whether "the operators' exercise of . . . discretion [is] state
action subject to the First Amendment," Pet. 15a (as posed by the en banc court).
<p>
     2.   Section 10 does not "restore" rights to cable operators, and a partial restoration is
constitutionally reviewable in any event.
<p>
     The court of appeals' decision to "not reach" petitioners' challenge to      10(a) and 10(c)
rested largely on its assumption that Congress had merely "restored" to cable operators some
"editorial control" that they supposedly had over access channels prior to the 1984 Act.  Pet.
13a-17a.  That assumption is factually wrong and would not, in any event, justify letting    10
escape judicial review.
<p>
     Access channels are creatures of state or federal law or local franchise agreement, for
which cable operators function simply as conduits and over which they never had editorial
control.  Even prior to 1984, state law (the source of property rights) and franchise agreements
generally required access channels and prohibited cable operator censorship thereof, even before
any given system was even constructed.  See above at 2, 3.  The Commission's early regulations
carving out an exception to this no-censorship rule for "obscene or indecent" programming were
a mandate, not a grant of editorial discretion, and never even went into effect, having been
recognized as flatly unconstitutional.  See above at 3 n.1.  Judge Randolph was therefore
mistaken when he relied on a supposed pre-1984 state-of-nature where operators had editorial
control over alleged indecency on cable access.  Pet. 14a.  Moreover, as to leased access,    10
cannot fairly be characterized as restoring "editorial control"; rather, it permits only a highly
constrained choice between two speech-limiting alternatives.  Pet. 47a (Wald, J., dissenting).
<p>
     But even assuming arguendo that Congress could grant cable operators full editorial
control over locally created PEG access channels and over leased access channels without
violating the First Amendment, it may not partially and selectively grant editorial control in a
way that suppresses, disadvantages, or imposes differential burdens on speech because of its
content.  Turner, 114 S. Ct. at 2459.  "[E]ven a traffic regulation cannot discriminate on the basis
of content . . . ."  Erznoznik, 422 U.S. at 215; e.g., Simon & Schuster, 502 U.S. at 116 ("the
government's ability to impose content-based burdens on speech raises the specter that the
government may effectively drive certain ideas or viewpoints from the marketplace"); Leathers
v. Medlock, 499 U.S. 439, 448-49 (1991).
<p>
     If the constitutional rule were otherwise, no court could consider and decide a First
Amendment challenge to a statute selectively "restoring" the rights of cable operators to censor
on access channels the speech of African-Americans or socialists or speech opposing reduction
of welfare grants.  Actions taken under the authorization of such a statute would be merely
"restoration," not state action, and the statute itself would (under the court's reasoning) be
"immunized" from constitutional challenge.  But such statutes are, of course, facially
unconstitutional and subject to judicial review in a proper challenge, regardless of whether the
cable operator's censorship as authorized by statute would itself violate the Constitution.
<p>
     In short, as Judge Wald observed (Pet. 50a n.4), the court of appeals erred in supposing
that whether a law is subject to review under the Constitution, and whether all action taken under
its cloak is state action, are the same question.
<p>
     3.   Section 10 cannot escape constitutional scrutiny, because it preempts contrary
state law, significantly encourages content-based censorship, and embroils the Commission as a
joint participant in the censorship scheme.
<p>
     Additional factors confirm beyond doubt that    10 is subject to constitutional scrutiny. 
First,    10 is subject to review (or, in the court of appeals' imprecise formulation, "state action is
present") because it preempts contrary state law.  Railway Employes' Dep't v. Hanson, 351 U.S.
225 (1956).
<p>
     In Hanson, a group of employees, who chose not to join a union in reliance on the
Nebraska "right-to-work" law, sued their company and its union over the inclusion of a
closed-shop agreement in the labor contract, which they claimed violated their First Amendment
rights.  Even though the Railway Labor Act had merely authorized, but in no way required, the
challenged closed-shop agreement, and even though the decision to require one was made by the
union and company alone, this Court unanimously agreed that the constitutional question
tendered had to be decided.  "If private rights are being invaded, it is by force of an agreement
made pursuant to federal law which expressly declares that state law is superseded."  351 U.S. at
232.
<p>
     Section 10 is subject to review under Hanson, because it is similarly preempting and
subjects programmers to censorship despite otherwise enforceable state law rights (including
municipal franchises) to be free from such censorship.  Second Report, Pet. 183a n.7.
<p>
     Second, the reviewability of      10(a) and 10(c) follows a fortiori from Skinner v.
Railway Labor Executives' Ass'n, 489 U.S. 602 (1989).  Skinner subjected to constitutional
scrutiny a statute that permitted (but did not compel) private drug testing, noting that "the
Government did more than adopt a passive position towards the underlying private conduct."  Id.
at 615; see also Blum v. Yaretsky, 457 U.S. at 1004 (government's "significant encouragement"
of private conduct creates state action); Norwood v. Harrison, 413 U.S. 455, 465 (1973) (" a state
may not induce, encourage or promote private persons to accomplish what it is constitutionally
forbidden to accomplish'") (citation omitted).  As in Skinner, the government has in    10 adopted
more than a passive position, for it has imposed definitions of disfavored speech and erected a
separate statutory scheme to regulate such speech.
<p>
     Finally,      10(a) and 10(b) establish a comprehensive scheme to censor "indecency" on
leased access channels with private cable operators and the Commission playing interlocking
roles:  the Commission defines indecency, resolves certain disputes over its application, and
prescribes blocking and segregation requirements, while the cable operators determine what
programming falls within their "reasonable belief" of indecency and decide whether to ban or
block such programming pursuant to the choice Congress has imposed.  Such a joint enterprise
between government and private actors is subject to constitutional scrutiny.  See Skinner, 489
U.S. at 615; Dennis v. Sparks, 449 U.S. 24, 27-28 (1980); Adickes v. S.H. Kress & Co., 398 U.S.
144, 152 (1970).
<p></blockquote>
II. Section 10 Is Unconstitutional Because It Authorizes and Requires Censorship under Vague
Standards and Lacks Essential Procedural Safeguards.
<p>
     To ensure the "[p]recision of regulation" that "must be the touchstone" when free
expression is concerned, NAACP v. Button, 371 U.S. 415, 438 (1963), laws regulating speech
must not be vague and must include procedural safeguards to secure the prompt restoration of
protected speech when it has been improperly censored.  Section 10 fails both requirements.
<p><blockquote>
A.   Section 10 Is Completely Vague.
<blockquote><p>
     1.  Laws that inhibit free speech are subject to the most "stringent" standards of precision. 
Village of Hoffman Estates v. Flipside, Hoffman Estates, Inc., 455 U.S. 489, 499 (1982); Cramp
v. Board of Pub. Instruction, 368 U.S. 278, 287 (1961).  Vague laws touching speech invite
over-censorship and viewpoint-based enforcement by granting censors "unbridled discretion." 
See, e.g., Forsyth County v. Nationalist Movement, 505 U.S. 123, 132 (1992); Southeastern
Promotions, Ltd. v. Conrad, 420 U.S. 546, 553 (1975) (condemning denial of access to a
municipal theater where "the exercise of such authority was not bounded by precise and clear
standards"); Smith v. Goguen, 415 U.S. 566, 574-75 (1974).
<p>
     Vague laws also pose an unacceptable risk of self-censorship, because speakers who
cannot discern clear lines will " steer far wider of the unlawful zone' than they would if the
boundaries of the forbidden areas were clearly marked."  Baggett v. Bullitt, 377 U.S. 360, 372
(1964) (quoting Speiser v. Randall, 357 U.S. 513, 526 (1958)); see Grayned v. City of Rockford,
408 U.S. 104, 108 (1972) (vague laws fail to "give the person of ordinary intelligence a
reasonable opportunity to know what is prohibited, so that he may act accordingly"); see also
Gentile v. State Bar of Nev., 501 U.S. 1030, 1051 (1991).
<p>
     Thus, vague laws attempting to regulate or suppress non-obscene speech have been
repeatedly struck down, even when enacted to protect minors.  Illustrative is Interstate Circuit,
Inc. v. City of Dallas, 390 U.S. 676 (1968), where this Court invalidated an ordinance requiring
film classification and prohibiting attendance by youths under 16 at films classified "not suitable
for young persons."  Although the "not suitable" standard had been fleshed out   defined as
"describing or portraying nudity beyond the customary limits of candor in the community, or
sexual promiscuity or extra-marital or abnormal sexual relations in such a manner as to be, in the
judgment of the Board, likely to incite or encourage delinquency or sexual promiscuity on the
part of young persons or to appeal to their prurient interest," id. at 681   eight members of the
Court concluded that, in the end, " [t]he only limits on the censor's discretion is his
understanding of what is included within the term "desirable, acceptable or proper."  This is
nothing less than a roving commission.'"  Id. at 688 (citation omitted).
<p>
     Interstate Circuit rejected the argument that a vague standard was permissible so long as
"it was adopted for the salutary purpose of protecting children."  Id. at 689.  "The permissible
extent of vagueness is not directly proportional to, or a function of, the extent of the power to
regulate or control expression with respect to children."  Id.  Rather, it depends on the harm to
free expression, regardless of an assertedly narrow interest in protecting children.
<p>
     [A] local exhibitor who cannot afford to risk losing the youthful audience . . . may
contract to show only the totally inane.  The vast wasteland that some have described in reference
to another medium might be a verdant paradise in comparison.  The First Amendment interests
here are, therefore, broader than merely those of the film maker, distributor, and exhibitor, and
certainly broader than those of youths under 16.
Id. at 684.
<p>
     2.  Section 10's fulcrum is the phrase "indecent programming," defined as "any
programming that describes or depicts sexual or excretory activities or organs in a patently
offensive manner as measured by contemporary community standards for the cable medium."  47
C.F.R.    76.701(g), Pet. 172a.  Programmers must identify "any programming that is indecent"
on pain of a damoclean array of sanctions and remedies that include censorship of individual
programs, financial penalties, and denial of access to a program provider in the future.  Id.   
76.701(f), Pet. 172a; see also First Report, Pet. 168a.  Operators are given wide discretion to
require more, including certifications that particular programming (or all programming) is not
"indecent" or that "reasonable efforts" will be undertaken to "insure" that indecent live
programming will be prevented.  Id.    76.701(e), Pet. 172a; id.    76.702, Pet. 197a-98a. 
Operators may suppress or must block "indecent programming" and may pre-screen in order to
do so.  Id.    76.701(a), Pet. 171a; id.    76.702, Pet. 197a-98a; First Report, Pet. 151a n.39.
<p>
     The definition of "indecent" under    10 is substantially more vague than the familiar
three-part test upheld against a vagueness challenge by a 5-4 decision in Miller v. California, 413
U.S. 15 (1973), because it utterly dispenses with two parts of that triangulated test. 
Programmers, operators, and indeed the Commission and courts are deprived of the substantial
instruction and constraint that Miller affords by restricting obscenity to "hard-core pornography,"
and then to only those patently offensive works that, "as a whole, appeal to the prurient interest"
and, "taken as a whole, do not have serious literary, artistic, political, or scientific value."  Id. at
24.  Unlike the hard-core pornography to which Miller restricted itself, a category that Justice
Stewart memorably described with the phrase "I know it when I see it," Jacobellis v. Ohio, 378
U.S. 184, 197 (1964) (concurring opinion), "indecency" encompasses a broad and undefined
category that appears to extend far beyond even "soft-core" pornography and that no member of
this Court has ever suggested is recognizable on sight.
<p>
     Just as there is no telling how a stool with two of its three legs sawed off will land, no one
can know what may be proscribed when "indecency" means only what is "patently offensive" by
"contemporary community standards":  terms that prescribe no ascertainable standard of conduct
at all and are, therefore, "perfectly vague."  See, e.g., Smith v. Goguen, 415 U.S. at 573
(invalidating a law barring "contemptuous" treatment of the flag, because " [w]hat is
contemptuous to one man may be a work of art to another'") (citation omitted); Coates v.
Cincinnati, 402 U.S. 611, 614 (1971) (ordinance barring "annoying" conduct is "vague, not in the
sense that it requires a person to conform his conduct to an imprecise but comprehensible
normative standard, but rather in the sense that no standard of conduct is specified at all").
<p>
     Moreover,    10 regulates speech exclusively on a basis ("offensiveness") that this Court
has repeatedly said is constitutionally impermissible.  See, e.g., Texas v. Johnson, 491 U.S. at
414 (government "may not prohibit the expression of an idea simply because society finds the
idea itself offensive or disagreeable"); Cohen v. California, 403 U.S. 15, 25 (1971) ("the State
has no right to cleanse public debate" of certain "offensive" words); Bolger, 463 U.S. at 71
("offensiveness" is not a justification for suppressing expression).
<p>
     Comments from cable operators show precisely how widely these delegate censors will
steer, untethered by any clear and ascertainable standard.  E.g., Acton Corp., JA 1-2; Community
Antenna Television Ass'n, Inc., JA 175-76; NYNEX Tel. Cos., JA 377, 383-84; see also
Goldstein v. Manhattan Cable Television, Inc., No. 90 Civ. 4750, 1995 WL 562182 (S.D.N.Y.
Sept. 20, 1995).  The wages of imprecision will be the routine suppression of fully protected
speech   not just "obscenity lite," but speech of substantial value, Pet. 44a-45a & n.1 (Wald, J.,
dissenting)   and the contraction of what is available to "the totally inane."  Interstate Circuit, 390
U.S. at 684.  The opportunity for cable access channels to offer viewers some relief from the
"vast wasteland" on broadcast and most operator-programmed channels   to see the works of
artists such as Courbet or Rodin or Picasso (some of which depict sexual organs), or films like
Putney Swope (with a classic scene at the urinal) or Carnal Knowledge (found protected in
Jenkins v. Georgia, 418 U.S. 153 (1974)), or educational works on breast or testicular
self-examination   would be further diminished, or dashed.
<p>
     Section 10's self-certification requirements magnify the chilling effect, as this Court's
prior cases invalidating oaths disclaiming certain kinds of speech attest.  Baggett v. Bullitt, 377
U.S. at 372 ("uncertain meanings of . . . oaths require the oath-taker . . . to  steer far wider of the
unlawful zone'") (citation omitted); Cramp v. Board, 368 U.S. at 286; see also Bella Lewitzky
Dance Found. v. Frohnmayer, 754 F. Supp. 774, 782-83 (C.D. Cal. 1991).
<p>
     The consequence of the over-aggressive deployment of the operator's or the
Commission's imprecise censorial power, or even a programmer's wrong guess, is not merely
channeling certain language to a later hour, as in Pacifica, 438 U.S. 726, or even a stay of
cablecasting pending prompt judicial review.  Rather, the consequence is a final restraint of
protected speech for adults as well as children:  speech that the programmer has a constitutional
right to present and viewers to receive.  Such DAETC programs as a cinema verit self-help
gynecological exam, a documentary on arts censorship, or a traditional Japanese fertility festival
featuring a procession of markers with images of human genitalia (JA 224-25) would surely
court suppression by operators under such a standard, regardless of whether, at the end of years
of litigation (assuming that DAETC had the resources to pursue it), an operator's belief that
programming was "indecent" was found unreasonable.
<p>
     There are still other aspects in which the cable "indecency" standard is patently vague. 
First, and crucially important from the standpoint of vagueness, the "reasonable belief" standard
in    10(a) substantially exacerbates the statute's imprecision and potential for discriminatory
enforcement.  Unlike the Commission's broadcast indecency standard, which is at least applied
by one agency,    10(a)'s invitation is to censor not only the "indecent" (as it might be measured
judicially) but also what an operator "reasonably believes" is indecent:  a far bigger kettle of fish. 
Imprecision and self-censorship are therefore multiplied.  See Schwartz Decl., JA 390, 392-94. 
Doubly subjective judgments are particularly indeterminate.  Big Mama Rag, 631 F.2d at
1037-38; Stanton v. Brunswick Sch. Dep't, 577 F. Supp. 1560, 1574 (D. Me. 1984).  Thus, this
Court in Interstate Circuit, striking down as vague a movie classification ordinance, pointed
particularly to the ordinance's relegation of decision-making to "the judgment of the
[classification] Board."  390 U.S. at 681.  Likewise, in Bella Lewitzky, 754 F. Supp. at 781-82,
the court invalidated as vague the NEA's obscenity oath because it relied on the agency's
unreviewable "judgment" as to what is obscene.
<p>
     The cable "indecency" standard is "based on the  average cable subscriber' . . . not
confined to a specific geographical area or specific cable system."  First Report, Pet. 148a-49a. 
This Court has recognized, however, that "our Nation is simply too big and too diverse for this
Court to reasonably expect that such standards [as  patently offensive'] could be articulated for all
50 States in a single formulation, even assuming the prerequisite consensus exists."  Miller v.
California, 413 U.S. at 30.  Both cable operators and programmers are left wholly without
guidance as to who such an "average cable subscriber" is and how the standard relates to current
cable programming in Los Angeles, Kalamazoo, New York, or Salt Lake City.
<p>
     Finally, the dangers of arbitrary action, and indeed self-censorship, are magnified because
under    10 operators need not prohibit or block comparably "indecent" programs on their own
channels, and, thus, access programmers cannot gain any useful guidance or comfort from
comparing their own programming to other programs carried on the system.  The presence of any
comparable or even more sexually explicit program is absolutely no assurance that a cable
operator or the Commission would not find an access program to be "indecent."
<p></blockquote>
B.   Pacifica Is Not Controlling.
<blockquote><p>
     1.   FCC v. Pacifica Found., 438 U.S. 726 (1978), does not foreclose petitioners'
vagueness challenge to    10's definition of "indecency."  Its "emphatically narrow" holding
addressed only the facts of that particular adjudication (the monologue "as broadcast"), stressed
that the seven words at issue were at the very core of the statutory proscription, and expressly
disclaimed any opinion on the facial validity of the "indecency" standard of 18 U.S.C.    1464. 
The Court noted that no sanctions had been imposed or would be "without warning."  Id. at 743. 
The Court narrowed its decision even further by expressly limiting its fact-specific ruling to the
broadcast medium and to a nuisance (channelling) rationale.  Id. at 750; see Sable, 492 U.S. at
127-28 (Pacifica was "an emphatically narrow holding"); Bolger, 463 U.S. at 74.
  <p>
   Pacifica did not purport to overrule the vagueness cases cited above at 25-26.  It did not
consider a "reasonably believes" standard heaped onto an "indecency" standard or the
authorization of a total ban.  Nor did it consider "indecency" under the shadow of the
Commission's since-greatly expanded sense of what falls within that rubric: not just dirty words,
but, as the record shows here, speech of serious value, whose very merit will [often] be inseparable from its seminal "offensiveness."  A bowdlerized documentary on the Mapplethorpe exhibit which did not include some description or depiction of Mapplethorpe's sexually explicit photographs themselves, for example, would hardly be an
informative statement on the artistic and political debate the exhibit engendered.
Pet. 45a (Wald, J., dissenting).  By contrast, Justice Stevens' plurality opinion in Pacifica reveals
time and again that it was considering "indecent language"; not, as    10 and its regulations do,
"indecent programming."
<p>
     In short, Pacifica simply did not decide whether "indecency" as defined here by Congress
and the Commission is sufficiently definite for a scheme of delegated censorship under a
"reasonable belief" standard that escapes judicial and even administrative superintendence.
<p>
     2.   If Pacifica were found to have decided the vagueness question, it should be
reconsidered and overruled.  Whatever national consensus might have permitted anyone to find
seven dirty words patently offensive as broadcast in the mid-afternoon 20 years ago cannot
render the Commission's    10 indecency standard sufficiently precise for now and beyond. 
Times and mores have changed.  Ask any ten Americans from different communities what is
patently offensive to the average cable subscriber, and you will have ten answers.  Those in their
20's would give vastly different answers than their grandparents.
<p>
     Sexual politics, i.e., discussions of relationships between and among the sexes, have
become a major issue for public debate.  Public proceedings concerning sexual harassment and
"date rape" are broadcast or cablecast on television.  Depiction of "sexual organs" are
commonplace, not only in "adult" materials, but in mainstream magazines, advertisements, and
motion pictures.  The Simpsons, enjoyed by millions of children and adults on broadcast TV,
recently (December 3) showed each family member in the buff and Bart engaging in an
"excretory activity."  In the film ET, which millions of young children watch on video cassette in
the home, one child calls another "penis-breath."  The speech of artists and journalists, and of
many from all walks of life whose voices are not otherwise heard on broadcast and most cable
systems, also frequently embraces such politically sexual issues as rape and domestic violence,
safe sex, and, indeed, the nature of sexuality itself.  See David Cole, Playing by Pornography's
Rules:  The Regulation of Sexual Expression, 143 U. Pa. L. Rev. 111, 125 (1994).
<p>
     The rationales underlying the plurality opinion in Pacifica have substantially weakened
since 1978.  The current viability of the "pig in the parlor" rationale is questionable in light of the
availability of lockboxes and other parental control mechanisms.  Moreover, in contrast to the
plurality's relegation of "indecent" language to diminished constitutional status, the Court's
subsequent majority decision in Sable establishes that indecent but not obscene expression has
full First Amendment protection.
<p>
     Petitioners see no occasion here for reconsidering Pacifica, but if the Court concludes that
that case controls this vagueness challenge, then Pacifica should be limited to its facts or
overruled.
<p></blockquote>
C.   Section 10 Lacks Essential Procedural Safeguards.
<p>
     The immediate, intended, and direct impact of a cable operator's exercise of the
censorship power created by    10 is to restrain protected speech permanently and in advance of
its communication.  In      10(a) and 10(c), Congress authorized cable operators to censor outright
protected speech:  not only speech that is asserted (but has never been judicially found) to be
"indecent," but also the substantially broader category of speech that the operator "reasonably
believes" to be indecent.  Congress and the Commission did precisely what this Court has
repeatedly condemned:  they gave censors "wide discretion" to restrain speech depending on
their predilections.
<p>
     Thus, "[c]able operators may, if they choose, pre-screen programming as a means to
enforce any cable operator policies adopted under the authority of section 10(a)."  Second
Report, Pet. 151a n.39.  This is the classic form of prior restraint, under a long line of cases
condemning the power to pre-screen and prohibit absent specific procedures, which are entirely
unavailable here.
<p>
     Less bluntly but just as surely,    10(b), too, interdicts speech that willing viewers would
otherwise access.  To the extent that cable operators do not prohibit all indecent speech on leased
access channels, they must withhold it from every subscriber unless the subscriber requests the
speech, and even then for an additional thirty days.  47 C.F.R.    76.701(d), Pet. 171a.
<p>
     Because this system of content-based prohibitions, restraints, and delays is
"indistinguishable in its censoring effect from the official actions consistently identified as prior
restraints in a long line of this Court's decisions," it " avoids constitutional infirmity only if it
takes place under procedural safeguards designed to obviate the dangers of a censorship system.'" 
Southeastern Promotions, 420 U.S. at 552, 559 (quoting Freedman v. Maryland, 380 U.S. at 58).
<p>
     First, the burden of instituting judicial proceedings, and of proving that the material is
unprotected, must rest on the censor.  Second, any restraint prior to judicial review can be
imposed only for a specialized brief period and only for the purpose of preserving the status quo. 
Third, a prompt final judicial determination must be assured.
Id. at 560 (discussing Freedman v. Maryland, 380 U.S. 51).
<p>
     Section 10's censorship scheme lacks each of those requirements.  The censor bears no
burden of promptly instituting judicial (or any other) proceedings.  Under    10, a cable operator,
having pre-screened or obtained information about a program, simply censors it, thereby
suppressing it to all viewers, or blocks it, thereby suppressing it to all blocked viewers unless
they learn of the program and request it at least thirty days in advance.  The viewer or
programmer, not the operator, must "assume the burden of instituting judicial proceedings and of
persuading the courts that the [program] is protected expression," Freedman v. Maryland, 380
U.S. at 59-60, assuming arguendo that there is a cause of action to challenge particular acts of
censorship.  The operator's censorship is thus final, not provisional or brief, expressly so under
     10(a) and 10(c) and as a practical matter under    10(b).  Given the absence of any provision
for "judicial superintendence" at all, there is naturally no provision for prompt judicial review to
restore free speech rights when they have been "erroneously denied."
<p>
     In sum,    10 is unconstitutional because it provides for censorship without required
procedural protections.
<p></blockquote>
III.Section 10's Content-Based Direct Burdens on Free Speech Rights Violate the First Amendment.
   <blockquote><p>
  1.   Section 10 "amounts to raw censorship based on content, censorship forbidden by
the text of the First Amendment and well-settled principles protecting speech and the press.  That
ought to end the matter."  Simon & Schuster, 502 U.S. at 128 (Kennedy, J., concurring).  As
Justice Kennedy pointed out, the strict scrutiny test was imported from equal protection
jurisprudence and "has no real or legitimate place when the Court considers the straightforward
question whether the State may enact a burdensome restriction of speech based on content only." 
Id. at 124.  Because    10 authorizes the prohibition of speech based solely on its content, it
should be invalidated without further inquiry into whether this plain First Amendment violation
also narrowly advances compelling government interests.  Id. at 124-128.
<p>
     2.   Even assuming arguendo that a content-based authorization to prohibit a huge
amount of protected speech (when engaged in only by certain speakers) is not invalid per se,    10
cannot survive the "the most exacting scrutiny" to which it is, at a minimum, subject. Turner, 114
S. Ct. at 2459.  Under strict scrutiny the government must prove (not merely assert) that the
regulations are necessary and narrowly tailored to achieve compelling governmental interests that
cannot be otherwise achieved.  Id. at 2469 (requiring such proof even under intermediate
review); see, e.g., Sable, 492 U.S. at 126; Simon & Schuster, 502 U.S. at 118.
<p>
     A challenged regulation is not "narrowly tailored" if it is significantly overinclusive,
burdening speech that need not be burdened to achieve the government's compelling interest. 
See id. at 121-22 (invalidating New York's Son-of-Sam law because it burdened "a wide range of
literature" whose burdening could not be defended by the asserted justification); see also NTEU,
115 S. Ct. at 1012-15 (well-intended but overbroad honoraria ban would have prohibited
payment for works by Hawthorne, Melville, Whitman, and Harte); Texas v. Johnson, 491 U.S. at
407-10 (statute reached far more speech than necessary to advance interest in preserving order).
<p>
     A challenged law will also fail strict scrutiny if it is significantly underinclusive, failing
to reach other conduct and speech that poses the same harm.  Florida Star v. BJF, 491 U.S. 524,
541-42 (1989) (Scalia, J., concurring in part and in judgment) ("a law cannot be regarded as
protecting an interest  of the highest order,' and thus as justifying a restriction upon truthful
speech, when it leaves appreciable damage to that supposedly vital interest unprohibited")
(citation omitted); see also Simon & Schuster, 502 U.S. at 123 (Blackmun, J., concurring);
Arkansas Writers' Project, Inc. v. Ragland, 481 U.S. 221, 230 (1987); Carey v. Brown, 447 U.S.
455, 465 & n.9 (1980).  Thus, the government must prove the necessity not only for    10 as a
whole, but also for the content- and speaker-based distinctions embodied in    10:  here, that it is
necessary to restrict only the "indecent" speech of access programmers.  Minneapolis Star, 460
U.S. 575; Leathers v. Medlock, 499 U.S. at 447.
<p>
     The government has an interest in enabling parents to protect their children from harm
and, one may assume, in directly protecting children from harm in circumstances where parental
supervision is likely to be systematically or structurally impracticable.  Even so, however,    10 is
far from the least restrictive means available to achieve it.
<p></blockquote>
A.   Sections 10(a) and 10(c) Are Not Narrowly Tailored.
<p>
     The government's concession that      10(a) and 10(c) are invalid if they are subject to
constitutional review is dispositive and, in view of Sable, inevitable.  It is apparent from
examining the "likely" and "practical" effect that    10 will have, as is required (see above at 16),
that it will suppress a wide range of protected and valuable speech from a vital avenue of
communication, cable television.  Speech that would otherwise be communicated and eagerly
received will be prohibited across the board, rendered unavailable not only to young children, but
also to older teenagers and adults.  " Surely this is to burn the house to roast the pig.'"  Sable, 492
U.S. at 127 (quoting Butler v. Michigan, 352 U.S. 380, 383 (1957)); see also Sable, at 127
("Pacifica is readily distinguishable from this case, most obviously because it did not involve a
total ban on broadcasting indecent material"); Pacifica, 438 U.S. at 750 & n.28 (implying that
prohibition of broadcasting indecent language would violate the First Amendment).
<p>
B.   Section 10(b) Is Not Narrowly Tailored.
<p>
     Assuming that      10(a) and 10(c) are invalid and severable, the remaining portion of the
regulatory framework  requiring the blocking of unprohibited "indecent" speech from only
leased access channels, but not PEG channels or any other channels  also imposes burdens on
speech that are neither necessary nor narrowly tailored to advance the government's goals.
<p><blockquote>
     1.   Section 10(b) is impermissibly overinclusive, because its restrictions on speech do
not advance the government's goals.
<p>
     Section 10(b)'s blocking scheme is invalid for the same reason that the Son-of-Sam law
was struck down: however laudable the goal to be served, the regulatory scheme is so carelessly
constructed (and in such derogation of basic First Amendment principles) that it burdens
substantial and valuable speech that need not be burdened to achieve its legitimate goals, and in
any event imposes far greater burdens on speech than are necessary given available alternatives
that are far less oppressive.
<p>
     As in Simon & Schuster, 502 U.S. at 122, and NTEU, 115 S. Ct. at 1013, a substantial
portion of the burden on speech does not serve to advance the government's content-neutral goal. 
See above at 7 & n.6.  Instead of targeting speech that would be harmful to children, as in
Ginsberg v. New York, 390 U.S. at 639,    10's touchstone is any reference to sexual activity or
body parts that operators might believe the "average cable subscriber" would consider
"offensive," even if those materials undeniably have serious literary, artistic, scientific, or
educational value.  Offensiveness is surely not a proxy for harm.  See above at 29.  Regardless of
whether the hypothetical "average cable subscriber" might consider Picasso's drawings,
Shakespeare's double entendres, film of a Japanese village fertility festival, or an illustrated
discussion of the importance of and techniques for breast self-examination to be offensive, such
content is not harmful to all those under 18 (indeed, it is probably not harmful to any of them).
<p>
     2.   Section 10(b) imposes unnecessary burdens on speech.
<p>
     Petitioners begin by identifying the burdens imposed by    10(b), even in the absence of
     10(a) and 10(c), and then turn to the available alternatives that advance the relevant interests
equally as well with far less restriction on First Amendment interests.
<p>
     Section 10(b) requires suppression of speech unless viewers perform "an official act" as a
prerequisite to receiving constitutionally protected programming.  But, as this Court held in
Lamont v. Postmaster General, 381 U.S. 301, 305 (1965), requiring "an official act (viz.,
returning the reply card) as a limitation on the unfettered exercise of the addressee's First
Amendment rights" is unconstitutional.  Requiring a written request   thereby placing one's name
on a list of those desiring "bad" speech and exposing oneself to subpoena, leak, or gossip   is "an
affirmative obligation which we do not think the Government may impose . . . [and] is almost
certain to have a deterrent effect."  Id. at 307; see also Fabulous Assocs., Inc. v. Pennsylvania
Pub. Util. Comm'n, 896 F.2d 780, 785 (3d Cir. 1990) ("An identification requirement exerts an
inhibitory effect, and such deterrence raises First Amendment issues comparable to those raised
by direct state imposed burdens or restrictions") (citing Talley v. California, 362 U.S. 60, 64-65
(1960)).
<p>
     Blocking under 10(b) is indistinguishable from a total prohibition for viewers who, not
yet having requested access, would have seen  a (now-blocked) program while changing
channels and decided to watch it.  The same is true for every subscriber who promptly asks for
access to a program she learns about   from a friend who calls and says "turn to channel 36,"
from a listing in a daily newspaper or weekly TV Guide, or from a community group telephone
call or mailing   but will be denied because of the 30-day delay in unblocking.  Advisories about
such programs (which could prompt an unblocking request) are rarely available with more than 7
days notice, and virtually never with more than 30.
<p>
     Yet, in a sterile analysis at odds with this Court's First Amendment jurisprudence and
Lamont, the court of appeals held that the practical loss of speech was of no constitutional
concern, because speakers are not forbidden "from speaking" and viewers could have obtained all
indecent speech had they previously sent in their postcards asking to be put on the "indecent
speech" list.  Compare Pet. 42a with, e.g., Lamont, 381 U.S. at 306-07.  Judge Wald's response is
compelling.
<p>
     The blocking scheme is "almost certain to have a deterrent effect" on those who would
otherwise seek to obtain the speech by requiring virtually any speech with a sexual reference to
be "certified" with the denigrating term "indecent," authorizing operators to divert speech they
"believe" to be "indecent" onto a channel for "indecent" speech, and prohibiting access except
upon a written request for the "indecent" channel.  Lamont, 381 U.S. at 307; Thornburgh v.
American College of Obstetricians & Gynecologists, 476 U.S. 747, 766-67 (1986).
<p>
     The government entirely failed to show that any of these burdens was necessary, and the
record and reason demonstrate that there are a number of available, less restrictive alternatives 
including lockboxes already required by law, or the even less restrictive and equally effective
blocking-on-request  by which the government could advance its legitimate interests.
<p>
     Since 1984, Congress has mandated that cable operators provide a "lockbox" to every
subscriber, 47 U.S.C.    544(d)(2), having found during lengthy committee hearings and floor
discussions that lockboxes are a very effective and efficient means of individually regulating
what is viewable in one's own home, e.g., H.R. Rep. No. 934, 98th Cong., 2d Sess. 70 (1984). 
There is no demonstration in    10's legislative history   indeed, there are no congressional
findings as to    10 at all   that lockboxes are no longer a sufficient means of meeting any asserted
compelling governmental interest underlying    10 or otherwise.  Before the Commission,
operators, programmers, and viewers noted without contradiction that lockboxes are an effective
way of achieving the government's aims.  See above at 7-8.
<p>
     The court of appeals' contrary conclusion (Pet. 33a-36a) lacks any foundation in the
record (or in anything before Congress) and applies a version of strict scrutiny so relaxed that it
bears no semblance to the test that this Court deploys.  Compare Sable, 492 U.S. at 128-129, and
id. at 131 (Scalia, J., concurring) (available technological alternatives render statute invalid, even
though some children "would manage to secure access") with Pet. 35a (lockbox alternative not
effective because adults would have to "continually activate and deactivate their lockboxes,
inevitably risking a slip up or a lapse"); see also NTEU, 115 S. Ct. at 1017 (individual
determinations less restrictive than wholesale prophylactic rule).
<p>
     Another obvious alternative that puts decision-making in the hands of parents instead of
the state is reverse central blocking, under which an operator would block specific channels on a
subscriber's request to do so.  Blocking on subscriber request would be equally effective at
facilitating parental protection of children and, with respect to each of the burdens imposed by   
10(b), far less restrictive than the present system.  Notably, the telecommunications restructuring
bill passed in the Senate and, at this writing, in conference recognizes the practicability of such a
system, and would require scrambling "upon subscriber request."
<p>
     Further, there is no merit to the government's attempt to cure the absence of findings by
the Commission or Congress regarding the necessity for    10(b)'s blocking scheme by focussing
on findings regarding a completely different medium, telephones.  This Court has repeatedly
insisted that each medium of communication requires individual treatment, e.g., Pacifica, 438
U.S. at 748, Burstyn, 343 U.S. at 503, and findings from one medium cannot simply be imported
to another where the basic structures differ in important relevant respects.  Here, it is self-evident
that the telephone has highly relevant technological capabilities (and limitations) and practical
configurations wholly different from cable.  See Regulations Concerning Indecent
Communications by Telephone, 5 FCC Rcd 4926 (1990).
<p>
     For example, it is not technologically practical to use voluntary blocking for telephones
because of the extremely large number of dial-a-porn numbers and the ease of creating or
switching to new numbers.  By contrast, lockboxes present a practical means of voluntary
blocking on cable, because televisions are not available on street corners and cable operators only
rarely reallocate channel numbers.  Cf. Bolger, 463 U.S. at 73 ("We can reasonably assume that
parents already exercise substantial control over the disposition of mail once it enters their
mailboxes").
<p>
     The government has not cited any evidence or congressional findings as to the necessity
for automatic central blocking limited to leased access, such as it presented to the courts in the
"dial-a-porn" cases, nor any findings that the situations are analogous.  And the evidence is to the
contrary.  For these reasons   and because    10 will effectively prohibit and deny adults and
minors access to valuable speech that they would have otherwise accessed and have a right to
receive, id., whereas the effect of the dial-a-porn measures was entirely less restrictive for adults  
the cases upholding the final version of the dial-a-porn regulations are inapposite here.
<p>
     3.   Section 10(b) is impermissibly underinclusive, because it blocks only speech by
leased access programmers.
<p>
     Finally,    10(b) and its implementing regulations require the blocking of "indecent"
speech on leased access channels, but not on PEG channels and not on the channels over which a
cable operator has editorial discretion.  Irrationally, even though a cable operator is required to
block on a leased access channel a program that is identified as (or which it believes to be)
"indecent," the operator is entirely free to cablecast that same program (or any other program
with comparably "indecent" content) on any other cable channel.  See above at 32 n.44.  Of
course, given the strong antipathy that many cable operators have for access programmers and
their desire to exclude them from their systems, the likelihood that blocking will be used to
disadvantage leased access programmers, rather than to protect children, is substantial.
<p>
     "One step at a time" is not a justification for content- or speaker-based distinctions where
First Amendment rights are concerned, regardless of the en banc court's unsupported assertion to
the contrary, Pet. 39a-40a.  See Minneapolis Star, 460 U.S. at 585; Arkansas Writers' Project,
481 U.S. at 231-32.  But even if it were, no factual predicate for such a justification has been
demonstrated here, and none exists.  Speech apparently within the "indecent" definition can be,
and indeed is, cablecast across every portion of cable systems without legal restraint (and can be
broadcast, as well, during the safe harbor hours).  Absent any demonstrated compelling necessity
for blocking only access channels,   10(b) violates the First Amendment.
<p></blockquote>
<a name="con"><b>CONCLUSION</b></a>
<p>
     For all the foregoing reasons, section 10 and its implementing regulations are
unconstitutional and the judgment below should be reversed.
<p>
Respectfully submitted,
<p>
Counsel for Petitioners<br>
Steven R. Shapiro<br>
Marjorie Heins<br>
