1.    Despite their general prohibition of editorial control by cable operators over access channels,
the Commission's 1972 access rules required cable operators to "establish" rules prohibiting
transmission of obscene or indecent matter, but delayed their compliance date until 1977.  47
C.F.R. Section 76.256(d)(1)-(3).  in 1976, the Commission revised these provisions to clarify
that they were mandatory, but again delayed compliance.  59 F.C.C.2d 984, 986 (1976). These
provisions as revised were challenged as an unconstitutional imposition of censorship obligations
on cable operators, and the Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit stayed their
effect.  American Civil Liberties Union v. FCC, No. 76-1695 (D.C. Cir. Aug. 26,
1977)(referenced in Midwest Video, 571 F.2d at 1056, 1057.  In its Midwest Video decision, the
Eighth Circuit found that "the Commission appears to have created a corps of involuntary
government surrogates, but without providing the procedural safeguards respecting 'prior
restraint' required of the government," and flagged several other constitutional concerns.  571
F.2d at 1056, 1057.  This Court noted the District of Columbia Circuit's stay and the Eighth
Circuit's disapproval of the indecency provisions, but, finding the entire regulatory scheme
unauthorized by Congress, did not itself reach those issues.  440 U.S. at 693 n.4, 695-96.
