<p>
48.       Thus, faced with a statute that on its face reached only "obscene, indecent, or profane
language," 18 U.S.C.   1464 (emphasis added), and with the Carlin monologue, the Court wrote
that there are "few, if any, thoughts that cannot be expressed by the use of less offensive
language."  438 U.S. at 743 n.18.  But the Commission's focus has moved well beyond "dirty
words," and its regulation of "indecent programming" sets at risk a host of valuable programs on
such subjects as artists, reproductive health, breast or testicular cancer, and anthropology, which
would be entirely unviable, or rendered far less effective, if stripped of all depiction or
description of "sexual or excretory activities or organs."
<p>
49.       In addition, as Justice Stewart and three other dissenters in Pacifica persuasively argued,
the term "indecent" in 18 U.S.C.   1464 is most reasonably read to be simply a synonym for
"obscene," particularly in view of the constitutional difficulties created by a more expansive
definition.  438 U.S. at 777-80; see 47 U.S.C.   532(h) (referring to cable service that is
"obscene, or . . . indecent or is otherwise unprotected by the Constitution") (emphasis added).
<p>
