53.       The Commission found procedural safeguards unnecessary on the theory that any
censorship under    10(a) and (c) would be private action, even though the government defines
the speech to be censored and prescribes regulations (  10(c)) or written policy requirements ( 
10(a)) under which the censorship takes place.  See Second Report, Pet. 193a n.17.  Delegation
of censorship to private decision-makers is of course no answer to the insurmountable due
process problems that result.  See National Ass'n of Theatre Owners, Inc. v. Motion Picture
Comm'n, 328 F. Supp. 6 (E.D. Wis. 1971); Engdahl v. City of Kenosha, 317 F. Supp. 1133 (E.D.
Wis. 1970); Motion Picture Ass'n of Am. v. Specter, 315 F. Supp. 824 (E.D. Pa. 1970).

<p>54.       See Interstate Circuit, 390 U.S. at 686 (citing cases).
<p>
55.       See above at 14.  Neither the Commission nor the court of appeals doubted that   10 is
subject to strict scrutiny to whatever extent it is subject to constitutional review at all.  See Pet.
32a-34a; Pet. 131a-40a.  Until this case, the courts had unanimously held that restrictions on
"indecent" cable programming violate the First Amendment  E.g., Wilkinson v. Jones, 480 U.S.
926 (1987) (mem.), aff'g 800 F.2d 989 (10th Cir. 1986), aff'g 611 F. Supp. 1099 (D. Utah 1985). 
See also Goldstein v. Manhattan Cable Television Inc., No. 90 Civ. 4750,
1995 WL 562182 (S.D.N.Y. Sept. 20, 1995); Altmann v. Television Signal Corp., 849 F. Supp.
1335 (N.D. Cal. 1994); Cruz v. Ferre, 755 F.2d 1415 (11th Cir. 1985); Community Television of
Utah, Inc. v. Roy City, 555 F. Supp. 1164 (D. Utah 1982); Home Box Office, Inc. v. Wilkinson,
531 F. Supp. 987 (D. Utah 1982).
<p>
56.       The many cases recognizing a strong interest in enabling parents to control their
upbringing of their children are inconsistent with an independent governmental interest in
protecting children from non-obscene speech contrary to parental wishes, as Chief Judge
Edwards observed, Pet. 77a.  See, e.g., Bolger, 463 U.S. at 73, 75 (right of parent to provide
children with materials government deems harmful); Wisconsin v. Yoder, 406 U.S. 205, 213-14
(1972); Ginsberg v. New York, 390 U.S. 629, 639 (1968) ("the prohibition against sales to
minors does not bar parents who so desire from purchasing the magazines for their children");
Meyer v. Nebraska, 262 U.S. 390, 401 (1923) (striking law as interfering with "the power of
parents to control the education of their own"); see also Pacifica, 438 U.S. at 769-70 (Brennan,
Marshall, JJ., dissenting); Pet. 59a-61a (Wald, J., dissenting).
<p>     Assuming, however, that the government has an independent interest in protecting children
from non-obscene speech in those circumstances where parental control is likely to be
structurally impracticable, cable television is decidedly not a context where such circumstances
exist, and hence that additional interest cannot support restrictions on speech in this case beyond
those supportable under the interest in enabling parents.  Cable television is exclusively
accessible in homes (there are no pay-cable sets on street corners), where it is an invited (and
paid-for) guest.  In sharp contrast to telephones, cable television is highly susceptible to parental
control, as the family mailbox was found to be in Bolger, 463 U.S. at 73.
<p>
57.       See McIntyre v. Ohio Elections Comm'n, 115 S. Ct. 1511, 1516-17 (1994) (recognizing
First Amendment and privacy interests served by anonymity).  
<p>
58.            "Many viewers] probably do not want to be perceived (even by their cable operator,
much less anyone who might later acquire such information by subpoena or otherwise) as the
kind of people who [want indecent speech].  They therefore will not
affirmatively write for access . . . .  Yet given a free choice in the matter, they might prefer to
have unimpeded, selective access to some but not all programs that fall within that broad
umbrella designation.  Not only aficionados of the arts or of politics but also the mildly curious
might well decide to watch an "unvarnished" documentary on the Mapplethorpe exhibit if it is
readily available, for example, but may not write to request an entire channel of indecency on the
chance that this and similar programs will be included.  They may want to shield their children
from most "indecent" programming, yet may occasionally find it appropriate to expose older
children to frank, even graphic discussions of sexuality and the AIDS epidemic, including some
programs that might fall within the FCC's definition of "indecency" (or at any rate are close
enough to the line that cable operators will ban them altogether or relegate them to the "indecent"
channel).  Whether they are "channel surfers" who like to browse before settling on a program, or
"appointment viewers" who prefer to study a program guide and watch pre-selected programs,
this regulation [deprives viewers of speech that they would otherwise obtain]."Pet. 57a (Wald, J.,
dissenting).
<p>
59.       The privacy provisions of 47 U.S.C.   551 do not resolve these concerns, for they are
entirely dependent upon cable operators and the penalties for violation thereof are minimal.
<p>
60.       Lockboxes allow a subscriber to block and unblock any channel at any time, generally by
programming her lockbox and using a numerical code or mechanical lock that the subscriber
controls.  Pet. 36a; see also Lockbox Manuals, JA 95-100, 126-30, 147-51.
<p>
61.       S. 652, 104th Cong., 1st Sess.   407 (1995); see also S. Con. 652, 104th Cong., 1st Sess.
  504 (draft of Dec. 17, 1995, 5:33 p.m.).
<p>
62.  In its opposition to the petitions for certiorari at 18, the government asserted that   10(b) is
"based on similar blocking requirements used to control children's access to dial-a-porn" and that
"Congress could reasonably draw upon the knowledge gained in constructing that analogous
legislation" (emphasis added).
<p>
63.  See, e.g., S. Rep. No. 92, 102d Cong., 1st Sess. 31 (1991) ("The cable operator is almost
certain to have interests that clash with that of the programmer seeking to use leased access
channels . . . .  For example, the operator may believe that the programmer might compete with
programming that the [operator] owns or controls"); H.R. Rep. No. 934, 98th Cong., 2d Sess. 48
(1984) (access channels may "represent[] a social or political viewpoint that a cable operator
does not wish to disseminate" and may "compete[] with a program service already being
provided by that cable system"); see also Comments of DAETC, JA 202; NYNEX Tel. Cos., JA
377.
<p>
64.  See Action for Children's Television v. FCC, 58 F.3d 654 (D.C. Cir.), pet. for cert. filed, 64
U.S.L.W. 3271 (Sept. 26, 1995); New York Citizens Comm. for Responsible Media, JA 365-74;
Schwartz Decl., JA 393.
